<html><head><title>CES: Publications: Research: SEP: SEP No. 8</title></head><body><hr><center><h1>Sustaining School Change</h1><h3>Case Studies from the Coalition of Essential Schools</h3><p>DONNA E. MUNCEY<br>and PATRICK J. McQUILLAN<p>THE SCHOOL ETHNOGRAPHY PROJECT (No. 8)<p>October 1992<hr><p><h4>ACKNOWLEDGMENTS</h4></center>An earlier version of this paper was presented at the Ninetieth Annual Meeting of the American Anthropological Association in Chicago, Illinois, November 1991. The authors thank Exxon Education Foundation for supporting our work and Martha Gardner, who provided assistance and critical feedback on drafts of this paper. The authors also wish to thank the faculty and administrators from the three study schools for their cooperation and feedback, even though confidentiality agreements preclude mentioning them by name. We alone are responsible for the contents of this paper.<p><a name="contents"><hr><p><h2>Table of Contents:</h2><p><ul><li><a href="#intr">Introduction</a>	<ul>	<li><a href="#tcoe">The Coaltion of Essential Schools</a>	<li><a href="#tsep">The School Ethnography Project</a>	</ul><li><a href="#cs1">Case Study I: Lewis High School</a>	<ul>	<li><a href="#fltt">Factors Leading to the Expansion of the SWAS</a>	<li><a href="#cots">Criticisms of the SWAS</a>	</ul><li><a href="#cs2">Case Study II: Green Vally Junior/Senior High School</a>	<ul>	<li><a href="#kaot">Key Aspects of the Reform Efforts</a>	<li><a href="#fltt2">Factors Leading to the Expansion of Reform</a>	<li><a href="#pfre">Problems Facing Reform Efforts</a>	</ul><li><a href="#cs3">Case Study III: The Wade School</a>	<ul>	<li><a href="#agdo">A General Description of Wade</a>	<li><a href="#cwtc">Connections with the Coalition's Philosophy</a>	<li><a href="#ofsr">Other Factors Supporting Reform</a>	</ul><li><a href="#cp">Comparative Perspectives</a>	<ul>	<li><a href="#char">Characteristics</a>	<li><a href="#impl">Implications</a>	</ul><li><a href="#note">Notes</a><li><a href="#refe">References</a></ul><p><a name="intr"><hr><center><h2>Introduction</h2></center><hr>In this paper we take a micro- look at school reform in the United States by examining three case studies of schools that are members in one national school reform effort, the Coalition of Essential Schools (CES). <p>	While the Coalition represents but one of many reform efforts in the United States, we feel nonetheless that a case study approach focused on three schools identified by the Coalition as having sustained their reform efforts over time offers a useful perspective on school reform for three reasons. <p>	First, these three schools provide a perspective on school change with substantial depth. As members of the Coalition, these schools have been working to implement change since at least 1985. <p>	Second, as these schools' restructuring agendas have evolved, they have incorporated many aspects of reform common to several current change efforts -- for instance, restructuring their schools into teams of students and teachers, reorganizing their school days into extended time blocks, promoting school-site management, initiating their own professional development activities, experimenting with alternative assessment methods, and promoting pedagogies to make students active learners. <p>	Finally, and again mirroring developments in the larger educational arena, these schools' reform efforts have encountered problems and resistance (Firestone et al. 1989; Fiske 1991; Futrell 1989; Muncey and McQuillan 1993; McQuillan and Muncey n.d.). <p>	Through these case studies, we will examine multiple dimensions of the Coalition of Essential Schools' reform effort. We begin by providing a brief overview of the Coalition's philosophy, formation, and growth. We next discuss our research project, the School Ethnography Project. Then we turn to our three case study schools, each of which adopted a different approach to Coalition reform: a school-within-a-school (SWAS) program that has continued to expand and include more and more of the school; a whole-school effort that approached reform in multiple ways and made both change and professional development the focus of many of its daily activities; and a new school created and designed to honor and embody Coalition ideas. <p>	Because the Coalition offers no model for school change nor even one required starting point for change, looking at three different approaches to school change offers a rich understanding of the processes of school reform experienced by this restructuring movement. <p>	We focused on these three schools because, although these schools were not problem-free,1 of our eight study sites, these were selected by the Coalition as those showing the most concerted and sustained efforts to experiment with reform ideas. In addition, the Coalition of Essential Schools has identified these as "second-step" schools, schools that are deepening reform schoolwide and that might reasonably be expected to be "more fully articulated Coalition schools" within the next few years. <p>	In the final section of this chapter, we draw shared characteristics from these three case studies that seemed to foster, sustain, and deepen efforts to change schools, discussing also some of the implications of these shared characteristics for school reform. <p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="tcoe"><h3>The Coalition of Essential Schools </h3>The Coalition of Essential Schools was founded in 1984 by Theodore Sizer, former Dean of the Harvard Graduate School of Education and former Headmaster at Phillips Academy, Andover, Massachusetts. Coalition philosophy is the product of thinking, research, and writing that emerged from a five-year, multisite study of American secondary schools, A Study of High Schools.2 <p>	Drawing on his experiences in schools and the general shortcomings he perceived in American education, Sizer wrote a narrative about his findings, <i>Horace's Compromise</i>, and devised a philosophy, codified in the Common Principles (see Appendix A), that has formed the basis of the Coalition. Prior to and at the time of his book's publication, Sizer and his associates promoted his philosophy in many contexts. Based on what he perceived as an enthusiastic reception for his ideas among the teachers and school administrators he met, Sizer recruited schools willing to experiment with his ideas, and he put together a small, university-based staff to assist this effort. <p>	From its inception the Coalition has envisioned itself as a partnership in which a university-based Central Staff (and increasingly a regional Coalition staff) and school personnel benefit from their mutual areas of expertise. As a self-defined grassroots reform movement focused on helping students to "use their minds well" and on improving classroom teaching and learning, the Coalition differs from many reform efforts in that it rejects centralized and standardized solutions to school problems. <p>	While the Coalition of Essential Schools is founded on the nine Common Principles, how these principles are implemented in the daily business of school life is determined by the needs and understandings of individual schools. The Central and Regional Staff assist restructuring schools through professional development activities and through the development, refinement, and dissemination of information about school-based projects aimed at improving schooling and creating more thoughtful practitioners and students. From an initial membership of twelve charter schools in December of 1985 and a Central Staff of three persons, the Coalition has grown to include over 400 schools and a Central Staff that now numbers nearly forty persons. <p>	In part, this expansion resulted from a partnership called Re:Learning that the Coalition initiated with the Education Commission of the States (ECS), a "non-profit, nationwide interstate compact formed to help governors, state legislators, state education officials and others develop policies to improve education" (Re:Learning 1989). While the Coalition focuses on school-site reform, ECS works with state and local governmental agencies to create a policy environment conducive to school-site change. Most of the newest Coalition member schools have joined through states that are part of the Re:Learning partnership. All of the study schools described in this paper were charter-member schools, and none are located in a Re:Learning state.<p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="tsep"><h3>The School Ethnography Project </h3>The School Ethnography Project began a five-year ethnographic study of the Coalition's Central Staff, eight charter member schools, and the professional development activities offered by the Central Staff for member (and potential member) schools in the summer of 1986, when the first member schools were still in the initial stages of their restructuring efforts. <p>	While we feel that our research offers a valuable perspective on school change and has implications for future restructuring efforts, our work was not a formal educational evaluation of the Coalition of Essential Schools. Rather, we sought to document broadly what occurred as a consequence of the Coalition's reform efforts by focusing on two general questions about the Common Principles: How are the Principles interpreted by individ-ual schools? And, how do teachers, administrators, and students in Coalition schools develop and implement the principles in each setting?<p>	In our research we sought to include an array of perspectives -- including those of supporters and opponents of Coalition philosophy and practices, Central Staff members and school personnel, and students, teachers, and administrators. Specifically, we spent substantial amounts of time in each of our eight study sites observing classes, after-school activities, planning meetings, and so forth. We also interviewed students, teachers, and administrators about school life as well as any proposed or implemented changes and their future plans. In addition, we read the Coalition Central Staff's archival collection on each of our study schools, which included reports of work done with or by the school prior to the start of our research. We concluded our research in June 1990. <p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="cs1"><hr><center><h2>Case Study I:Lewis High School </h2></center><hr><p>Located in a mid-Atlantic city of 750,000 residents, Lewis High is a "zoned" or neighborhood, comprehensive school that enrolls an entirely African-American student population of about 1,100. About three-quarters of the faculty are also African-American. The city school system consists of seventeen high schools. There are five "academic" high schools and three vocational/technical schools, all designated as magnet schools for which students must apply and meet entrance requirements in order to enroll. The nine remaining schools are neighborhood comprehensive high schools. The top students in the city generally attend the academic or vocational/technical schools; the remaining students enter the comprehensive high schools. As one foundation report observed, "Of all the high schools, the lowest attendance, worst scores, and the highest dropout rates are found in the comprehensive high schools."3 <p>	In some ways Lewis fits the typical conception of an urban high school. Many school doors are locked or chained closed to restrict the flow of outsiders into the school. Students take public transportation to school and are greeted in the morning by teachers and administrators who check their ID's and make certain that they have "regulation" book bags -- they must be mesh so that students cannot conceal weapons. Lewis's dress code restricts students from wearing baseball caps, leather jackets, or gold jewelry -- in part, to avoid having valuable items stolen and in part, to distinguish Lewis students from outsiders who wander into the building. Security guards and administrators carry walkie-talkies. Classes are generally large; most enroll over thirty students. <p>	Yet, Lewis has a comfortable, "small school" feel as well. In the classrooms and hallways students, teachers, and administrators seem at ease with one another. The school offers an array of extracur-ricular activities, and participating students and faculty appear enthusiastic about them. Most members of the Lewis "family," a common description of the school by those associated with it, freely acknowledge pride in their school. Reflecting something of this pride, the school is clean and relatively litter-free. <p>	Although Lewis relocated for building renovations from the fall of 1988 through the spring of 1991, in its permanent location the school is unquestionably a "neighborhood school," with many families choosing to send more than one child to the school.<p>	When Lewis began its Coalition involvement in 1985, the school enrolled nearly 2,000 students. While being renovated, Lewis shared a building with another high school. At this time, enrollment decreased by approximately 900 students, precipitating a concern with job security by some faculty.<p>	In terms of our research sample, Lewis High is an interesting case: while there were four school-within-a-school (SWAS) reform efforts in our sample of study schools, Lewis was the only one that expanded its SWAS program throughout the five years of our research -- adding more students as well as faculty members to the program every year. <p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="fltt"><h3>Factors Leading to the Expansion of the SWAS </h3>A variety of interrelated factors appear to have allowed Lewis to experience this continued growth -- one being the program's structure. <p><h4>Flexible Scheduling</h4>One of the first objectives of the SWAS was to create a flexible schedule that would allow SWAS faculty to adjust time segments to meet their educational needs. To do this, the team created two extended time blocks for SWAS classes -- one double-period in the morning and one triple-period block in the afternoon. These time slots were then subdivided to match ongoing educational priorities. For instance, since the teachers decided to focus their efforts on getting 75 percent of all SWAS students to pass the required state competency exams in reading, writing, math, and citizenship in their sophomore years, they scheduled students to meet and prepare intensively in the appropriate discipline the weeks prior to each exam.<p><h4>Personalization</h4>A second key aspect of Lewis's SWAS program was the personalization SWAS teachers tried to create for their students. As one SWAS member explained: "We're closer to our students simply because we have fewer. Also, we know more about individual students because we can have more parental contact and individualized instruction. We know what students really can do." <p>	At a Coalition-sponsored symposium a SWAS student concurred with his teacher's perspective:<p><blockquote>I hadn't experienced education that was this personalized before. In the larger school, classes were so large that teachers could only lecture. In the Essential School we're able to develop a real relationship with our teachers. We're almost like a family. . . . [And] teachers not only teach us "facts." . . . We learn to be leaders, we learn to work in groups, and I, personally, have come to realize that learning is a constant process, not something that just takes place in classrooms. </blockquote>	This more personalized school environment has taken many forms at Lewis. Besides having a lower student/teacher ratio than the larger school, the SWAS has sponsored activities intended to address more than traditional, classroom academic concerns: inviting speakers to talk with students about being young, African-American, and growing up in an urban environment; making field trips to college campuses to give students a glimpse of college life; and arranging to have all SWAS students take PSAT exams. The manner in which the SWAS used the Coalition idea of exhibitions represented an effort to incorporate a more personalized dimension into the curriculum. Either at the end of a course or prior to graduation, exhibitions -- which are selected by individual students based on their particular interests and strengths -- serve as multidisciplinary, culminating activities where students <i>exhibit </i>the abilities developed through their studies before faculty and community members. <p><h4>Multiple Support Mechanisms</h4>Another factor that appears to have played a pivotal role in the program's continued expansion was the multiple support mechanisms that existed for the program, perhaps the most prominent being program leadership. Although the city superintendent who sought Coalition membership resigned two years into Lewis's Coalition affiliation and her replacement had an uncertain commitment to Coalition philosophy, administrative support for Lewis's SWAS at the school site remained consistent. Throughout the program's existence, Lewis's principal, David Johnson, has been a vocal propo-nent of this effort, within the city as well as nationally. As principal, he provided the program with forceful administrative support -- recruiting teachers, securing foundation grants, assigning uninterested teachers elsewhere, and reallocating staff positions to support the SWAS. The program coordinator for Lewis's Essential School -- a full-time administrative position4 -- has also been in that position since the school joined the Coalition. She, too, has overseen the program's implementation and development, has assisted SWAS fundraising efforts, and has participated in professional development efforts within Lewis and nationally as a representative of a Coalition school.<p>	Lewis's SWAS efforts have also been supported by foundation grants. These supplemental funds have allowed SWAS faculty to attend professional development activities (often Coalition-sponsored), to sponsor their own professional development activities, and to purchase equipment for the SWAS. They have also offset the cost of field trips taken by SWAS faculty and students.<p>	In addition to school-site and foundation support, the Coalition of Essential Schools' Central Staff have been very involved with Lewis High. As a charter member of the Coalition, David Johnson and the program coordinator attended semiannual or annual meetings of the Principals' and Coordinators' Council to discuss program developments and consider ways to further their reform efforts. Since Lewis consistently expanded the size of its Essential School and continued to restructure its program -- for example, by making schoolwide exhibitions a prerequisite for graduation from their program -- the Central Staff selected Lewis High for the Five Schools Project and focused a portion of its expertise and funding on helping these second-step schools promote change. The Central Staff also selected Lewis for the IBM Project which offered participating schools an opportunity to utilize computer databases and networking to promote school-site reform. <p>	As well as schoolwide involvement with these Coalition projects, individual Lewis faculty and administrators have participated in other Coali-tion-related efforts. David Johnson, for example, has been a Thomson Fellow. In this role, the city school department releases him from time to time to attend conferences, symposia, and workshops and discuss aspects of Lewis's Coalition program. Two Lewis teachers serve as Citibank Faculty members, receiving training in how to promote school-site change and serving as consultants to restructuring schools. Furthermore, Lewis faculty and administrators are often asked by Central Staff to make presentations at Coalition-sponsored work-shops and symposia. <p><h4>Early Success Leading to Growth</h4>Early evidence of success in the Lewis SWAS has also contributed to the program's growth and visibility. One indicator of success cited by Lewis's SWAS has been their students' performance on the state-mandated competency exams. Between 1986 and 1989, SWAS students did better than their "large school" counterparts in all four subject areas, and they did better than the system-wide average in all but one exam, where they equaled the systemwide score.5 Moreover, in terms of atten-dance, dropout rates, and college acceptances, the SWAS has had an impressive record. During the 1988-89 school year the SWAS program had an attendance rate of 92 percent, whereas in the larger school the rate was 74 percent, and citywide it was slightly more than 80 percent. And, during the 1988-89 school year, the SWAS dropout rate was less than 2 percent;6 for non-SWAS students it was 23 percent, and for the city it was over 11 percent. Lewis's SWAS has also been relatively successful in terms of college acceptances -- in its first graduating class (in 1988-89), three-quarters of its graduates went on to two- or four-year colleges or vocational education compared with 42 percent for non-SWAS students and 11 percent for the city overall. <p>	It may also have been important that these signs of success were widely touted. Lewis's SWAS has been the focus of articles in local papers and national publications. As a Thomson Fellow, David Johnson has traveled widely to discuss his program. In recognition of Lewis's efforts, the Coalition Central Staff have featured the school in workshops as well as public presentations. This positive exposure has helped to reassure parents and persuade them to enroll their children in the SWAS. Students, too, have been impressed by these figures and have joined the SWAS without parental urging. Lewis's administration has also used these figures to convince the superintendent's office of the program's effectiveness and need for continued support. These measures of success have also proved persuasive in reports to funders. <p><h4>Professional Development Activities</h4>Another factor that seems to have helped sustain the growth of the program was that Lewis's SWAS sponsored its own professional development activities -- ranging from week-long summer institutes to half-day workshops -- designed to develop aspects of their program and introduce new faculty to Coalition philosophy. Often, Coalition Central Staff members participated in these workshops. Commenting on the first summer institute, the program coordinator discussed some workshop activities:<p><blockquote>We looked at different teaching styles. We looked at different curricula. We looked at coaching. We looked at how we would implement student-as-worker. We did critical thinking skills. We did interdisciplinary curri-cula. And each morning we would have a work session. Then that evening, we would try to implement . . . what we said we were going to do that morning. We would coach each other. We did curriculum development and we did practical applications of what it was we were doing. In the final weeks we had a laboratory school . . . [where] we used the integrated curriculum approach. We combined math and science, and we did humanities in which we included foreign language, English, and social studies. </blockquote><h4>Few Constraints for Change</h4>At Lewis, there were few existing school structures that may have restricted SWAS expansion.7 Although Lewis High offers Communication Arts and Naval Junior Reserve Officer Training Corps programs, there were no serious conflicts between these programs and the SWAS. One program, the Business Department, did express reservations with SWAS expansion. Their main concern stemmed from the SWAS's curriculum, which -- because of its increased requirements in math, social studies, foreign language, and science -- restricted the number of electives Lewis SWAS students could take. Consequently, with the advent of the SWAS program, their department's size steadily decreased -- from eleven to four faculty members. Nonetheless, these teachers never mobilized significant resistance to the program's expansion. <p>	Furthermore, although grievances related to SWAS expansion were filed by the teachers' union, these actions did not deter program expansion. When Lewis faculty "grieved" their assignments to other city schools on the basis of building seniority, the transfers stood since the Coalition SWAS had "special program" status which allowed relatively inexperienced SWAS faculty to maintain their building tenure over teachers with departmental seniority. <p><h4>Hiring Flexibility</h4>A final factor that promoted the continued expansion of Lewis's SWAS was the hiring flexibility created by the reassignment of over thirty Lewis teachers due to decreased enrollment, a consequence of moving to a new building, combined with citywide demographic shifts. When this occurred and reassignment became apparent, the SWAS held "interest meetings" to determine which faculty wanted to join the program. As Johnson commented in anticipation of that shift:<p><blockquote>Some teachers probably won't buy Coalition philosophy. But I can help them relocate. I couldn't do that before, but I can now [because of having fewer students]. So those staying here will use Essential School ideas -- such as lecturing less, more group work. I hope it will be voluntary.</blockquote><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="cots"><h3>Criticisms of the SWAS</h3>Although Lewis's SWAS expanded consistently, the program did encounter skepticism and resistance from some uninvolved faculty. One common criticism was that SWAS students received preferential treatment. Uninvolved faculty maintained that SWAS students were provided privileges and opportunities unavailable to other Lewis students -- such as taking overnight field trips (some non-SWAS faculty inaccurately thought overnight trips were banned), having more opportunities to study a foreign language (most foreign language teachers were SWAS faculty), and being able to make-up incomplete work over holidays and the summer (rather than failing or attending summer school). <p>	Additionally, some noninvolved faculty felt that SWAS teachers received preferential treatment. As was common with noninvolved teachers' reactions to other SWAS programs, these teachers cited the SWAS teachers' reduced student load and additional planning time as signs of this preferred treatment. They also cited the number of professional development activities SWAS faculty attended because of their grants and what they saw as the disproportionate dispersal of school funds for the SWAS. <p>	Intra-faculty tensions also emerged from concerns with job security. As discussed earlier, some Lewis faculty were upset by how decisions to transfer faculty to other city schools were made. Also, some uninvolved faculty argued that Coalition philosophy was not appropriate for all Lewis students -- specifically because of its college-oriented curriculum. In the words of one non-SWAS teacher:<p><blockquote>My concern is that every child in Lewis High School is not going to college. We know this. And yet the program is set up [as] strictly academic, with little or no room for electives. [The neighborhoods] where our students come from, most of these students go to work. They're looking for immediate employment. We would like to see them do something other than fast food, which is fine to a point, but, once they graduate, it hurts to see them slinging hamburgers when they could be operating a computer. But they must be proficient in those areas. They must have marketable skills.</blockquote>	While Lewis's SWAS was the only one of four SWAS programs in our study sample that consistently expanded and simultaneously appeared to deepen its efforts to restructure the school and implement CES reform, we are not asserting that Lewis has solved the problems of urban education. In fact, other researchers have questioned the extent to which SWAS teachers have deepened their understandings of Coalition philosophy and the quality of their students' work. 	Nevertheless, the Lewis program has continued to expand, and it has struggled with exhibitions and other manifestations of a deepening of Coalition ideas, an impressive feat given that it encountered many of the same problems that beset the other SWAS programs. <p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="cs2"><hr><center><h2>Case Study II:Green Valley Junior/Senior High School</h2></center><hr><p>Green Valley Junior/Senior High School is located in the northeastern quadrant of the country. The town of Green Valley has the second lowest per-capita income in an Appalachian state that provides little support for local education. According to 1980 census figures, much of the town lives below the poverty level and many families receive welfare assistance. The school is small, with roughly 350 students enrolled in grades seven through twelve and a staff of slightly more than thirty. While the physical plant is sparse, there is a sense of community, life, and excitement about the school. A Green Valley teacher described this sense of community when reflecting on her first year of teaching:<p><blockquote>I was taught [in college] that the first year of teaching is hell because you're so alone. But that's not true here. In [college], doing my student teaching, I only had one mentor. Here, I have thirty-three. . . . The atmosphere is honest and open. There's lots of help available. I can go to anyone and count on them.</blockquote><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="kaot"><h3>Key Aspects of the Reform Efforts</h3>Much of what occurs at Green Valley Junior/Senior High emanates from its principal, Stuart Tucker. He came to the school in 1981 after leaving a similar position at a relatively prominent middle school. The school that Stuart Tucker took over in 1981 had a troubled recent history. While many local residents had memories of a positive and successful past, in the late seventies the school faced many problems. School funding -- on both the state and local level -- was very tight. Teacher salaries were low, with the salary scale for first-year teachers just slightly over $10,000 and the top end for veteran teachers under $20,000. Furthermore, the school had one of the higher dropout rates in the state -- 20 percent -- and sent only 8 percent of its graduates to college. The absentee rate was nearly 20 percent. The school building was plagued by vandalism and neglect. <p><h4>An Innovative Structure</h4>When Stuart Tucker began working at Green Valley, the school had a very traditional structure -- a seven-period day, a faculty divided into discrete departments, and students who were each scheduled individually. Over time, Tucker and the faculty redesigned the school's structure. First, one period from the school day was eliminated and periods were lengthened. Study halls were eliminated. Teachers willing to team were recruited, and these experimental teams were assigned a set group of students and encouraged to schedule their classes as they considered appropriate for their course goals and students. This schedule allowed teamed teachers the flexibility to have their classes conduct an archaeological excavation of a colonial settlement, map out a "depth chart" of a local lake, and test the water in a local river and run-off brooks and streams for various pollutants. <p>	To promote active learning and teamed teaching among the faculty, Green Valley instituted their "two-week thing." Once a year, during the two-week thing, the school breaks from business-as-usual and organizes itself into interdisciplinary teams of teachers and students. Each year, the school selects a different theme, and teachers develop plans to address that theme. One year the home economics teacher secured an $8,000 grant to underwrite the school's effort to examine the question of "sustainability" -- how can the world be organized so that it doesn't slowly self-destruct? Beyond allowing students to address a topic in depth and from various disciplinary perspectives, during this two-week experience, everyday teaching was a potential source of professional development as teachers experienced team teach-ing, interdisciplinary courses, group learning, and a more flexible schedule. <p><h4>Personalization</h4>Another key aspect of Green Valley's reform efforts involved personalizing students' educational experience. For instance, to provide each student with an adult advocate on the faculty, the school instituted an advisory system. All staff, including the principal, are assigned approximately fifteen advisees with whom they meet every day during what most schools call homeroom. During this time, teachers can discuss students' academic work, problems students may be experiencing, issues that arise at the school, and so on. Commenting on the program, Stuart Tucker wrote in a paper presented at an educational conference: <p><blockquote>The structure is . . . there for the student to talk seriously and openly to an adult. The structure doesn't make any demands on the student to develop a deep interpersonal relationship with an advisor, it simply gives the student assurance that there is an adult who will listen. The point is that without the structure that put this in place, communication is limited and therefore, so is understanding and trust. In a crisis, two people cannot suddenly develop trust. It must be built beforehand. The advisory system makes that possible. </blockquote>	Another way in which Green Valley has attempted to personalize students' educational experiences is through the "Life After Green Valley" class. A required course for all seniors, these single-sex classes expose students to concerns involved with such practical life choices as interviewing for and finding a job, managing a budget. Students also have the opportunity to discuss health and social issues. In one class, for example, a teacher discussed AIDS, herpes, and various myths about birth control, showed the class of boys how to wear condoms properly, and stressed the implications of having unprotected sex ("We have a name for people who have sex without contraception -- we call them parents"). <p><h4>Apprenticeship Program</h4>Another Green Valley innovation directed at making school relevant for students is the Apprenticeship Program. For part of each day this program sends about fifty students to work in the community. Before being assigned a work site, students meet with the program director to determine what jobs interest them. They must then produce a resume and initiate the interview process. The program is intended to engage students in actively learning about relevant professional skills as well as offering them an opportunity to develop socially and intellectually outside the school setting. As part of this program, students have worked as newspaper reporters, as teacher aides in a local grammar school, as auto mechanics, and as secretaries for town businesses. <p><h4>Streamlined Discipline Policy</h4>Along with these structural and curricular changes, Tucker streamlined the school's discipline policy by implementing a series of simple rules: students are suspended for fighting, using drugs or alcohol, swearing at teachers, stealing, and destroying property. Reflecting on this policy at one Coalition-sponsored symposium, Tucker remarked: "We wanted to teach students to respect other students, to respect the faculty, to respect property, and to respect themselves and their own well-being."<p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="fltt2"><h3>Factors Leading to the Expansion of Reform</h3>A variety of interrelated factors appear to have contributed to the sustained expansion and refinement of Green Valley's restructuring efforts.<p><h4>Leadership</h4>As was true at Lewis High, leadership seems to have played an integral role. Unlike most Coalition programs that we studied, Green Valley has no program coordinator -- either part- or full-time. Prior to Green Valley's membership, Tucker had been the impetus for most change and he continued in that role after the school joined the Coalition. As one faculty member explained:<p><blockquote>Stuart is concerned about all the faculty, both professionally and personally. I always thought of the principal as a figurehead. I never even met the principal at the school where I did my student teaching. But I see Stuart every day. He's very much a part of my day. He's involved with everything at the school, and that's important to the teachers and the kids.</blockquote>	Much of Tucker's enthusiasm has carried over to his staff, some of whom were at first skeptical. For instance, one Green Valley veteran was put off by Tucker's touting of the success the school experienced after his arrival because of the implicit criticism of previous efforts. Later, she came to support his efforts. Commenting on this shift she said: <p><blockquote>Stuart is a great persuader. . . . He can convince you to do anything. He told me that the program <i>needed </i>me. . . . He's the reason behind much of my professional change because he's been encouraging me to do more. </blockquote>	While Tucker's leadership and vision are widely regarded as key to the changes the school has experienced, Tucker's efforts have been complemented by grassroots support and commitment from his faculty that have allowed these changes to take root. The teams of teachers, for instance, have had virtually total freedom to develop curricula, design schedules, and organize student groups.<p><h4>Professional Development</h4>To help teachers remain professionally active, Stuart Tucker constantly promotes professional development. Indeed, much of what transpires in the course of normal school routine at Green Valley might constitute professional development. For instance, every Wednesday, the school holds faculty meetings where, along with addressing administrative matters, teachers discuss pedagogical, curricular, and assessment issues. Tucker also encourages faculty to keep journals to reflect on various aspects of their work. At the end of each week, Tucker collects these journals and reads each twice, once for understanding and a second time to respond to what teachers have written. He also tries to visit teachers' classes regularly. Describing his role in her professional development, one new teacher commented:<p><blockquote>He plays a big role on our team because the three teachers on my team are new to Green Valley. . . . Stuart helps to direct my thinking, and I have no hesitation to say, "I'm stuck." He never lets me rest and I like that. He meets with us as a team at least once a month. Sometimes, he'll just stop in when we're working together. He's helped us adjust to teaching seventh grade and establishing an exciting and worthwhile curriculum. . . . I've really had to relearn how to plan and teach, to decide what's important in my class. </blockquote>	Tucker also uses summer as a time to help teachers develop professionally by finding funds to allow teaching teams to meet for a week or two to discuss such matters as goals and curricula for the coming school year. Moreover, Tucker has been attentive to his teachers' concerns and uses multiple professional development forums to discuss them. Besides signaling an interest in and respect for teachers' ideas, providing faculty with these multiple forums seems to have had an additional positive effect: the Green Valley staff has evolved a sense of a shared philosophy. <p><h4>Outside Supports </h4>A third apparent reason why change at Green Valley has continued to encompass more of the school is connected to the outside support the school has received. As a "charter" member of the Coalition, for instance, the school has collectively discussed school restructuring at meetings of the Principals' and Coordinators' Council, which are annual CES-sponsored meetings held for all charter members. In addition, like Lewis, Green Valley has participated in the Five School Project. This involvement has provided the school with funding for travel, release time for staff members, and assistance to help the school assess its current efforts and plan for the next steps. <p>	Tucker has also spent a great deal of time and effort seeking grant monies to underwrite his faculty's work. One grant, for example, funded an effort by five Green Valley teachers to develop a flexible schedule that would allow the school to integrate critical thinking skills across the curriculum and develop individual education plans for all students. One summer Green Valley received funding that allowed ten teachers to "define in measurable, performance terms, both entry- and exit-level academic requirements." The following summer Green Valley faculty directed a three-week professional development session on the West Coast aimed at helping teaching teams from other schools jointly develop curricula -- using essential questions8 as the overarching framework. <p>	Moreover, Green Valley teachers frequently serve in this capacity at CES-sponsored activities as well as at other schools' professional development activities. These professional opportunities have played a critical role in the school's restructuring efforts, in part because through the processes of articulating their educational goals, developing materials, organizing workshops, and instructing other teachers, Green Valley teachers have fine-tuned their own abilities and develop deeper insights into their own work.<p><h4>Success Leading to Sustained Reform</h4>The school's relative success at reform may be another reason why changes are being sustained at Green. By 1986, after five years of Tucker and school reform, Green Valley's dropout rate sank to 3 percent and daily attendance rose to over 95 percent. In addition, the number of students who attended college tripled. Three years later, half of Green Valley's graduating class went on to college -- the most ever for Green Valley. Not only could Green Valley offer these signs of relative success, but their success has received wide exposure. The schools' efforts were featured in regional magazines and prominent newspapers, and Tucker was featured in a PBS special.<p><h4>Few External Constraints</h4>Another reason that Green Valley has sustained change appears connected to the lack of resistance these efforts have encountered. In a historically non-union state, for instance, the local teachers' union has had little influence at the school. While at other schools unions have sought a clear delineation of teachers' work responsibilities, the limited union influence at Green Valley has helped Tucker, as he puts it, to "encourage and cajole" his teachers into going beyond the normal eight-to-three routine in providing service to the school and students. The school also had no special programs, such as magnet programs or advanced placement offerings. Departmental ties were weak at Green Valley and have been further weakened as many teachers developed stronger interdisciplinary ties with team members. In changing institutional structures, therefore, there was less likelihood of violating existing interests. <p>	Somewhat related to the fact that there were few entrenched interests at Green Valley was the fact that Stuart Tucker was also able to hire many staff members according to his interests. Because few faculty had tenure (in part, due to Green Valley's difficult recent history combined with a low pay scale), as of the 1991 school year, approximately two-thirds of Green Valley faculty had been hired by Tucker. <p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="pfre"><h3>Problems Facing Reform Efforts</h3>While the Coalition views Green Valley High as one of its more successful second-step schools, foundations have supported the school's efforts, and the media have generally presented Green Valley's efforts in a positive light, the school has encountered problems in implementing change. Green Valley is a conservative town, and these difficulties have arisen, in part, because some local residents disliked Stuart Tucker's appearance, demeanor, and approach toward education. At school, he never wears a coat and tie, instead preferring flannel shirts. As he had two doctorates, he was considered an intellectual in a town where some residents were skeptical of such "experts." Moreover, some programs implemented during Tucker's tenure were viewed skeptically. Commenting on the tensions stirred up by the school's efforts to alter its previous structure, one faculty member from Green Valley remarked:<p><blockquote>Some people in town . . . feel that doing something different in the school means that we are treating the kids like guinea pigs. Some feel that the high cost of education is tied to our reform-minded teachers. Some school board members have commented that they think the journals that we use in some classes are intrusive into the private life of students.</blockquote>	Eventually, lingering tensions came to a head. In his third year as principal, the school board decided not to renew Tucker's contract. When he challenged their right to do so in court, the reservations that some community members held toward him surfaced. His detractors maintained that Tucker was too liberal and too lenient. For instance, when a junior girl became pregnant and was asked to leave her apprenticeship assignment at a local beauty parlor, Tucker offered her an alternative assignment -- to study community attitudes toward teen pregnancy. <p>	Green Valley's membership in the Coalition of Essential Schools was also viewed with disfavor by those who saw it as a liberal, university-based experiment. After a bitter court battle that ruled in Tucker's favor and a highly contested school board election in which board members supportive of Tucker's ideals were elected, Tucker returned to Green Valley Junior/Senior High as principal. At present, his position appears secure.<p>	One final point: while many of the changes implemented at Green Valley reflect Coalition philosophy, and while the school was among the first to join the Coalition in 1984, this was three years after Tucker had arrived and after many of the reforms discussed here were already under way. In many respects, Coalition membership offered Tucker a means to further his own ideas.<p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="cs3"><hr><center><h2>Case Study III:The Wade School</h2></center><hr><p>A growing number of schools are being designed and founded using the nine Common Principles as their underlying philosophy. The first, and one of the most well-known of these schools, the Wade School, is the subject of the final case. The school was founded by Helen Markham, an educator and innovator with a history of involvement in alternative elementary school education. Beginning with approximately 80 seventh-graders in 1985, the school added one grade per year for six years until it reached its present size of approximately 450 students. Wade graduated its first senior class in 1991.<p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="agdo"><h3>A General Description of Wade</h3>Wade is located in a large urban system which spent, on average, about $6,500 annually per-pupil in the mid-1980s. However, district per-pupil expenditures vary widely, with schools in poorer sections of the city generally receiving less funding. As with Lewis High, this urban system is hier-archical. Nevertheless, a growing range of alternative and magnet programs are available to meet differing needs and to serve specialized populations. While situated in an area of poverty, violence, and joblessness, Wade is part of a subdistrict that is widely acknowledged to favor innovation. The district has supported Wade's administrators, for instance, by assisting with fundraising and providing political support for the fledgling school. <p>	While Wade is an alternative public school and students are selected for admission, Markham has sought to maintain several balances in selecting students.<p><blockquote>We made an early decision that we should be designing a program for every kind of kid. . . . And that the school ought to be mixed: we didn't want all high achievers or all low achievers. The next criteria was that any kid coming out of our elementary schools ought to be allowed to come here because we wanted that continuity. Next, we have a strong focus on families, so we ought to give first preference to the siblings of kids who are already here. . . . Then we have some decisions to make because . . . we want it to be representative of the [city's] population, ethnically, economically, and so forth, but we also wanted to make sure we had enough kids [from this neighborhood].</blockquote>	The Wade School's admissions process is respectful of the criteria Markham outlined. Additionally, prospective students and at least one parent and  must visit the school before the child can enroll. Another balance the school maintains is that 20 percent of the student body are special ed students.<p>	Throughout our research period, the racial and ethnic mix at Wade was approximately 40 percent African-American, 35 percent Hispanic, 9 percent White, 6 percent Asian, and 10 percent biracial. The administration and staff were committed to building a multicultural faculty: approximately one-third of the faculty was African-American. Hispanic teachers represented a growing presence in the school. One source of faculty recruitment has been interns and student teachers from city colleges and universities who volunteer at Wade.<p>	Teachers, administrators, and students frequently use family-like metaphors to characterize the school community. Most stressed the supportiveness, caring, and sense of shared purpose among staff and students. This was perhaps most obvious when talking with Wade's students, who seemed to "own" the Coalition's reform rhetoric and who infused it with an active and pragmatic sense of purpose. Students described themselves as "workers," preparing "exhibitions," and discussed topics that derived from "essential questions" they were studying individually and in groups. <p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="cwtc"><h3>Connections with the Coalition's Philosophy</h3>The school's structure, curriculum, and dominant pedagogical techniques reflect the central aims of Coalition philosophy. Five essential questions guide inquiry in the school in general: How do we know what we know? What's the evidence? Whose viewpoint is represented? How else might it be viewed, seen, considered? and What difference does it make?<p> <p><h4>Innovative Structure</h4>Students are not strictly age-graded, but are taught in classes containing at least two grades. The six years of education offered at Wade are divided into three administrative divisions: what are traditionally seventh and eighth grades are Division One, ninth and tenth grades are Division Two, and the final two years of school are termed the Senior Institute. Each division's curriculum is based on specific essential questions, which, in Divisions One and Two, alternate every two years. <p>	In Divisions One and Two, students have three classes per day: a two-hour humanities blocked class, a two-hour period of math-science (in some instances instruction is interdisciplinary; in most, each subject is taught for one hour during the block), and an advisory period. Students must also demonstrate foreign language competency before graduation and may attend optional Spanish classes before school officially begins each day to help them prepare for the tests. Students in Divisions One and Two perform community service once each week in a three-hour time block. A one-hour lunch break where students can eat and play intramural sports rounds out the formal school day. The building is open for numerous after-school options every day. In addition to de-emphasizing age-grading, organizing the curriculum around essential questions, and stressing active student learning, Wade School emphasizes the Coalition ideas of personalization, "Less is more," staff as generalist, and exhibitions. (See Appendix A.) <p><h4>Personalization</h4>In terms of personalization, no teacher is responsible for more than eighty students and each student is part of an advisory group of ten to fifteen that meets daily with a faculty advisor. The advisor schedules at least two parent-student-teacher conferences per year. To promote continuity in this relationship, students keep their advisors throughout their stay in the division, increasing the knowledge base upon which advice and assessment are based. Further evidence of personalization is the house system: each division includes two houses, each with approximately eighty students and a team of teachers that includes one math, one science, and at least two humanities teachers. These teachers see each student daily in classes that are rarely larger than twenty students. Because teams have the same students for two years, teachers come to know students well and encounter only forty new students in any given year. The house teams meet regularly to discuss students' progress.<p><h4>"Less Is More"</h4>The entire school's philosophy corresponds to the principle of "Less is more." The curriculum has been pared down, students take only a handful of subjects, and each is organized around essential questions. Students do not study all of American history, for instance -- they examine aspects of it in studying revolutions or what it means to be an American. In the Senior Institute they may further specialize in such aspects of American history as the labor movement or Puerto Rican history. <p><h4>Staff as Generalists</h4>The entire staff is expected to function as generalists. While the school offers some psychological and social services, including one full-time school/family coordinator (a trained social worker), classroom teachers fill many guidance roles, and most have studied conflict mediation to help students resolve problems among themselves. All administrators also have advisories and teach when possible. These decisions allow the school to maintain a low student/teacher ratio, while still fulfilling traditional school functions. This generalist principle also functions in the Senior Institute where, through the advisory process, teachers help students find internships that will be appropriate to their planned post-secondary school experiences and help them select colleges or technical schools that will challenge, but not overwhelm, them. <p><h4>Exhibitions </h4>In all aspects of their schooling, students are expected to demonstrate mastery through exhibitions. Students prepare oral and/or written exhibitions for each subject or unit. Some are done individually, others in groups. For their end-of-the year exhibitions, students often present their research findings and draw implications for a team of teachers, parents, or other adults. By the time they enter the Senior Institute, the students have had much practice in the oral and written defense of ideas. <p>	The Senior Institute is designed to provide opportunities for individual students to explore their interests and plan their futures. Senior Institute students may attend classes at Wade, city colleges and universities, and wherever their internships lead them. To complete the Senior Institute students must prepare and defend a set of portfolios which include tasks thatreflect competencies ranging from math, writing, foreign language, and literature to preparing an autobiographical narrative and completing an internship in an area of potential employment interest.<p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="ofsr"><h3>Other Factors Supporting Reform</h3>Several factors have contributed to the ongoing strength of the reform effort at Wade.<p><h4>Leadership</h4>The school owes much to the leadership of its founder, Helen Markham. Her reputation as an educator and her adeptness at building coalitions of supporters and "protectors" is widely acknow-ledged. Markham's style of leadership includes both sharing decision making and protecting her staff from the whims and bureaucracy of city and state educational offices. Teachers often expressed their gratitude for the efforts that Markham exerts to protect the school. One teacher, for instance, said, "She really goes to bat for us downtown; she'll push as hard as she needs to to get us what we want." Further, they often noted with pride the success that Markham has had raising additional funds for the school. <p>	The staff and administration at Wade have allocated tasks to balance the top-down administrative decision making with more grassroots, faculty decision making. For example, curriculum, pedagogical approaches, and methods of assessment are discussed and decided at all levels of the school among teachers and administrators. And while Markham hand-picked the original Wade staff (who spent one year planning and designing the school before it opened), teacher hiring has since been done by teams of teachers. <p><h4>Support from the Coalition</h4>Another source of support for Wade has been the Coalition of Essential School's Central Staff. For several reasons, Ted Sizer and others have spent much time visiting and working at Wade. Wade was the first school designed in terms of Coalition ideas. In addition, the staff regularly requested assistance from the Coalition and attended many Coalition-sponsored professional development activities, including working parties at Brown University, meetings of the Principals' and Coordinators' Council, conferences, and week-long workshops. Third, Wade staff experimented with Coalition ideas and were open about discussing early successes and failures. The staff at Brown valued the Wade faculty's honesty and kept close track of their experiences. Wade was also chosen to participate in the Five Schools Project. Wade teachers and administrators frequently make presentations at the Coalition and other conferences, and the school's new co-director was recently selected to be a Thomson Fellow. Finally, the Coalition has assisted Wade in its efforts to raise funds, and together Helen Markham and Ted Sizer have presented a formidable front when meeting with educators or potential funders. <p><h4>Professional Development</h4>When the Coalition made Wade's state part of a Coalition region, additional local support and professional development activities were created. This regional center is now housed at the school. Wade also received support from the network of elementary schools that Markham had founded and from a growing network of alternative Coalition schools in the city. Teacher education programs from various local institutions have also established working relationships with Wade. <p>	Wade's faculty also runs its own professional development activities -- at least twice a year they have two-day retreats (sometimes with the elementary schools), house teams meet for three hours of curriculum development per week, and half of the weekly faculty meetings are spent discussing pedagogical and curricular issues.<p><h4>Lack of Entrenched Interests</h4>The flexibility of the school's structure results in part from a lack of entrenched interests -- one consequence of being a new school. The few interests defended in early faculty meetings -- community service, the library, and foreign language instruction (Spanish) -- were clearly connected to the school's overarching goals. Additionally, through negotiating with the district and state, many requirements that were viewed as potentially divisive to the school's aims were waived. Finally, because there is a strong sense of shared purpose at the school, teachers who are uncomfortable with the school's structure and/or pedagogical and curricular emphases generally self-select out. <p><h4>A Reputation for Success</h4>Since the school's inception, Wade has enjoyed a highly favorable reputation, in part a consequence of Markham's successful elementary school network. Staff members have taken advantage of the many opportunities offered them to discuss and dis-seminate their philosophy and the program's highlights. They have made presentations (often at Coalition-sponsored activities) and have written articles that describe their work. The school produces a monthly newsletter for parents and interested others. Wade is also very open about allowing researchers and others interested in educational change to visit the school and provides an orientation (staffed by teachers and students) to all visitors.<p>	The more recent successes of its students have also been widely disseminated: All but one member of the first graduating class pursued higher education. While some fifteen or so students did not graduate "on schedule" -- using a traditional definition of schooling --  all persevered in pursuing their degree to completion. Dropout rates at Wade are very low (a total of approximately 5 percent over the four years). Most students who leave Wade continue at other schools; they have not left school altogether. <p><h4>Collaborative Reflection</h4>Faculty and administrators stress that Wade is still "evolving" and that the staff use their time together to reflect upon and reconsider their current activities and future plans. <p>	One example illustrates the work of collective and collaborative reflection and decision making that permeates the school. In an urban environment filled with overt and subtle racial confrontation and innuendo, racial tensions among the faculty and between the faculty and students at Wade seemed ever present and occasionally became the focus of much anger. One of the earliest faculty retreats was devoted to confronting issues related to race and ethnicity. Markham described some reasons for addressing racism head-on and some consequences for the school.<p><blockquote>Last spring we had a retreat in which we tried to frontally discuss the racial tensions among the staff members, and we brought in someone to serve as a moderator. We wanted to discuss resentments and feelings people had about whether white teachers could really teach black kids and other unspoken questions among the faculty. And I just felt with the secondary school you absolutely have to. The kids themselves are going to face it in the world they're going into: dealing with colleges and jobs. And if we can't talk to kids about race we're leaving out too large a dimension. If teachers can't talk to each other about it, how are they going to talk to the kids about it? If white teachers don't know what black teachers feel about things then they're missing a lot. How do we talk about what black parents feel? What's happening when they're having a conference if they're not discussing how that parent is feeling about them as a white teacher. It was important. </blockquote><blockquote>We had an extraordinarily explosive meeting. On the other hand, it broke the ice. There was enough desire of people in the school to make this school succeed so that it wasn't a disaster. If we had done this two years earlier it could have ended the school. </blockquote><blockquote>Well, we followed it up really by taking a step back and approaching it a different way. And we decided to approach it by bringing a conflict resolution program into the school for students, parents, and faculty. To talk more about how you talk about conflict -- how you deal with things that are hard to talk about. And hoping to then move back into [the issue of] racism. For the first whole series of meetings with the staff it was just about conflict and how to position yourself in a conversation when it's difficult. How to talk about things that are difficult. And the last two meetings have been on race. So we are coming into it the back way, and I hope we will be able to get back to the conversation we had last spring.</blockquote>	An important point about this example is how student-centered, responsive, and in many ways daring this retreat was. Tensions ran <i>very </i>high as people of varied backgrounds addressed feelings and reactions they had both in their personal lives and in the Wade School setting. Team members argued about incidents between teachers and students and what they implied about the teacher's racial beliefs. Despite the high levels of stress (and occasional animosity) at the retreat, there was consensus among the faculty that direct, open discussions were a necessary prelude to more "genuine" and "responsive" interactions with students and to a better handling of race and ethnicity in the curriculum. While tensions among individual faculty members have persisted, most felt the school took an enormous risk -- that paid off -- in trying to face racial tensions directly and respectfully. <p>	Unlike our other sites, there were few concerns about preferential treatment or job security at Wade. At most, accusations of preferential treatment were directed at faculty who were the earliest spokespersons for the school in public presentations. Any job security issues, like so many problems Wade faces, result from budget deficits in the citywide system. They never threatened people's loyalty to Wade -- rather the problems often increased people's commitment to the school's efforts.<p><h4>Criticisms of Wade</h4>Of course the school has its detractors. One of the more commonly heard criticisms is that because foundation grants supplement the citywide per pupil allocation, it cannot serve as a general model for schools wishing to restructure. Others are skeptical of its serving as a general model because of its admission requirements -- most notably the agreement of students to be active participants in the life of the school with their parents agreeing to actively participate on their child's behalf. <p>	The school, by its faculty and administration's own admissions, struggles with many difficult problems -- but one difference between this school and many others is that problems usually become the object of serious reflection by the whole staff, not simply of idle gossip in the faculty room. Further, the sense of student involvement in schoolwork, the school's mission, and their ownership of the reform language at Wade results from the close and careful articulation of Coalition philosophy with all aspects of the school's design and approach to curriculum, instruction, and assessment. <p>	One gets the sense at this school that everyone -- administrators, teachers, students, and parents -- is pulling together for all community members and that there is a commitment to ongoing reflection that will be a continuing part of the school's overall "evolution."<p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="cp"><hr><center><h2>Comparative Perspectives</h2></center><hr><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="char"><h3>Characteristics</h3>The three schools described in the preceding cases share eight characteristics in terms of their reform efforts:<p><h4>Characteristic #1</h4>The principals are strong leaders who are vocally supportive of the restructuring efforts. For instance, principals at these three schools have taken advantage of faculty hiring opportunities, turn-over, and loss of staff due to declining enrollments to retain and hire those faculty members who expressed interest in pursuing reform goals. They are also respected by most faculty members. While at other schools faculty often resisted change efforts because of the principal's close association with these efforts, these principals have persuaded faculty to participate in the reforms. <p>	Furthermore, these principals were committed to change even before their formal affiliation with the Coalition. In many respects, the Coalition provided them with an avenue to realize their pre-existing ideas about school restructuring. In addition, these principals have been at their schools through-out the period of restructuring. Our five other study schools all experienced some administrative turnover. <p><h4>Characteristic #2 </h4>There were few pre-existing interests in place at these schools prior to the reform. These schools had no magnet programs, no extensive advanced placement offerings, no powerful union presence, nor did they have other special interests that might have felt threatened and/or resisted efforts to restructure. <p><h4>Characteristic #3 </h4>None of these schools had a reputation for academic excellence. Two schools had substantial at-risk populations, relatively high dropout rates, and few students who went on to college. The third school, since it was new and built grade-by-grade, had no prior reputation, but was located in a city with a poor reputation for public schooling. It is important to keep these conditions in mind when considering each school's reports of success. While both pre-existing schools have reported impressive gains or comparisons in student attendance and college attendance, these should be viewed in the context of the conditions at the schools and/or their troubled school systems prior to Coalition membership. <p><h4>Characteristic #4 </h4>The Central Staff invested in these schools far more than most member schools -- possibly because these schools reported regularly on their efforts and specifically requested Central Staff assistance. In supporting these schools, the Central Staff did not direct the schools' work; rather, they tended to do whatever they could to support the schools' self-initiated efforts, one of the Central Staff's ways of demonstrating respect for local autonomy. Also, because the Coalition Central Staff perceived these schools to be doing some of the more ambitious reform work, they were often "showcased" in CES symposia, workshops, and public relations efforts. Finally, these schools attended many Coalition-sponsored professional development activities. As a result of the interaction between the Central Staff and these particular schools, teachers at these schools generally viewed Central Staff members positively, as persons with something to offer them and as encouraging of their efforts -- almost as mentors. <p><h4>Characteristic #5 </h4>These three schools sponsored and ran their own professional development activities which built on aspects of Coalition philosophy and promoted a sense of common purpose among all staff members.<p><h4>Characteristic #6</h4>Each of the three schools took steps to support the efforts of teachers directly involved in their restructuring efforts. These included creating common planning time for involved faculty to meet jointly and securing funds so participants could attend Coalition-sponsored workshops. Further, these schools took advantage of multiple opportunities -- faculty meetings, professional development activities, and team meetings, for example -- to develop and promote a shared vision or common philosophy among the staff and other members of the school community. <p><h4>Characteristic #7</h4>Each of these schools raised extra funds from foundations to support their restructuring efforts and received funds from the Coalition to encourage their own school-based change efforts and to work with like-minded school personnel.<p><h4>Characteristic #8</h4>Each school used mounting evidence of its success to build further support for its work.<p>	Abstracting from these common characteristics, four points are worth noting. First, school reform at these three sites was multidimensional and provided many different opportunities for school personnel to become involved.9 Second, there were both external (e.g., Central Staff expertise) and internal (e.g., planning time, school-based professional development, etc.) supports for these change efforts. Third, these schools invested substantial time in allowing all school personnel to rethink many previously unchallenged assumptions about schools throughout the restructuring process -- in planning for change, in monitoring the effectiveness of their efforts at change, and in re-envisioning what it might take to deepen their efforts. Finally, the three schools all allocated significant amounts of time, money, and effort toward helping teachers acquire the skills needed to sustain and deepen their work -- not only as it applied to their classroom, but also as it applied to collaboration with colleagues, interactions with parents, and to their expanded roles as advisors. <p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="impl"><h3>Implications</h3>We briefly discuss three implications of these cases. First, if as the Coalition states these schools are exemplary in their active commitment to change, systemic school change efforts may be more likely to endure and deepen. By <i>systemic </i>we mean moving on many fronts at once  -- the classroom, the school, the district -- and involving multiple actors -- teachers, students, administrators, and parents -- in sizable numbers as these schools have each attempted to do. A simultaneously top-down and grassroots approach built on a shared vision has seemed to yield continuity in dealing with students, less reform-minded others, and the local community. Additionally, while structural and attitudinal constraints can make it difficult for students to be active participants in the change process, where this has been nurtured, it too has seemed to sustain and deepen classroom and schoolwide changes. In each of these three schools, there appeared to be at least an implicit acknowledgment of the importance of three factors that contribute to systemic change: the schools have created structures that would support school reform, i.e., the <i>actions </i>supportive of change; they focused on discussing and defining the philosophical and pedagogical assumptions that undergird these actions, i.e., the <i>beliefs </i>that underlie the specific reforms and the goals of change; and they have created opportunities, often in conjunction with the Coalition, to help faculty and administrators develop the <i>skills </i>that will help them implement their philosophy. <p>	Second, where professional development has been made a part of the life of the school itself, rather than a one-shot deal every twelve or fourteen weeks, it has appeared to contribute to deepening the school's reform efforts. This seems particularly true when professional development has been closely tied to schoolwide goals. <p>	Finally, because of the difficulties of school change, it seems critical to seek outside perspectives while developing, implementing, and assessing a school's efforts at change. It is sometimes difficult for school personnel to distance themselves from the effects of change and the political climate within which they act. Outsiders can offer a distanced perspectives on events and their likely effects.<p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="note"><hr><center><h3>Notes</h3></center><hr><ol><p><li> Difficulties faced by the Coalition schools whose reform efforts have proven more problematic are discussed in Muncey and McQuillan (1992).<p><li> A Study of High Schools generated three books: <i>Horace's Compromise </i>(1984) by Sizer; <i>The Shopping Mall High School </i>(1985) by Arthur Powell, Eleanor Farrar, and David Cohen; and <i>The Last Little Citadel </i>(1986) by Robert Hampel.<p><li> We provide no specific reference for this citation (and others throughout the case studies) because it might jeopardize the confidentiality we promised our study schools. <p><li> This contrasts with most of our study schools where program coordinators generally had teaching responsibilities in addition to their administrative work. <p><li> Although Lewis's SWAS students have done relatively well on these exams, the school's flexible schedule allows them to prepare students intensively for these exams, an opportunity non-SWAS students at Lewis and other city students do not have. In addition, Lewis's SWAS students, especially the first cohort, were not an "average" group of Lewis students. An independent study of Lewis's SWAS found: <blockquote>The evidence shows that <i>going </i>in the students begin with sizable advantages over other Lewis students; they are younger, thus more likely to have been promoted on time at each earlier grade in their respective histories; and second, the students turn out to have had much better attendance rates his-torically than their non-Coalition counterparts at Lewis have had. An objective observer might argue then that the Coalition students are in fact the most likely students to succeed anyway -- in whatever enrichment environment they are in or not in.</blockquote>	While voicing these caveats, the report added that, after controlling for differences in student characteristics, <blockquote>the thrust of the evidence is that participation in the SWAS program at Lewis increases a student's school attendance and promotion rates, which are important behaviors linked to school academic achievement and graduation.</blockquote><p><li> Although the SWAS has cited these figures as a sign of success, other faculty members contend that the SWAS manipulates these figures by first enrolling SWAS dropouts in the larger school before they are discharged.<p><li> The problems four SWAS Coalition schools encountered when they tried to expand are compared in McQuillan and Muncey (1991).<p><li> "Essential questions" are a curricular framework promoted by the Coalition (see Wiggins 1987). In contrast to the common curricular focus on coverage, essential questions are intended to focus curriculum on a specific topic in depth. In part, essential questions represent an effort to strike a balance between process and content in curricular organization -- that is, acknowledging that teachers cannot cover everything but also acknowledging that focusing purely on process is equally inadequate. <p><li> Cusick (1991) for instance, argues that most effective efforts at school change have been systemic and multidimensional.<p></ol><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="refe"><hr><center><h2>References</h2></center><hr>Cusick, Philip. 1991. <i>The Educational System, Its Nature and Logic. </i>New York: McGraw-Hill.<p>Firestone, William, Susan Fuhrman, and Michael Kirst. 1989. <i>The Progress of Reform: An Appraisal of State Educational Initiatives. </i>New Brunswick, NJ: Center for Policy Research, Rutgers University.<p>Fiske, Edward. 1991.<i> Smart Schools, Smart Kids</i>. New York: Simon and Schuster.<p>Futrell, Mary. 1989. "Mission Not Accomplished: Educational Reform in Retrospect." <i>Phi Delta Kappan </i>71 (1):9-14.<p>Hampel, Robert. 1986. <i>The Last Little Citadel</i>. Boston: Houghton Mifflin Company.<p>McQuillan, Patrick J. and Donna E. Muncey. n.d. "Change Takes Time." Forthcoming in <i>Journal of Curriculum Studies.</i><p>_____. 1992. "School-Within-A-School Restruc-turing and Faculty Divisiveness: Examples from a Study of the Coalition of Essential Schools." W