The Essential Questions</a></b><br>Joseph P. McDonald, Bethany Rogers, and Theodore R. Sizer<p> <li><b><a href="exhibit/steps.htm">Steps In Planning Backwards: Early Lessons From The Schools</a></b><br>Joseph P. McDonald<p><li><b><a href="exhibit/3pic.htm">Three Pictures Of An Exhibition: Warm, Cool And Hard</a></b><br>Joseph P. McDonald<p><li><b><a href="exhibit/visfoes.htm">Vision And Its Foes</a></b><br>Joseph P. McDonald<p></ul><p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><a name="2"><hr><h2>Research papers on School Change:</h2><hr>Patricia A Wasley, Director, Richard W. Clark and Robert L. Hampel<p>The progress of change in five public Essential high schools between 1991 and 1994 was documented by CES research teams working in collaboration with the schools' faculty.  Drawing on the faculties' responses and their own observations, the research teams explore three main themes: how the nine Common Principles are put into practice; how whole-school change occurs; and what factors affect the momentum of change.<p><h4>The "Lincoln" Study:</h4>Robert L. Hampel with Loraine Hong, Neill Wenger and Laura Maxwell<p>"Lincoln High School" is a mid-size, minority-majority suburban high school in a south-central state.  Forty percent of Lincoln's students come from low-income families.  Since joining the Coalition in 1988, Lincoln has implemented several major changes, including teaming, site-based decision making, and authentic assessments.<p><ul><li><b><a href="sc/lincoln1.htm">Lincoln No. 1: The Limits of Caring, the Rigors of Change</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/lincoln2.htm">Lincoln No. 2: Teaming: Working Together for Change</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/lincoln3.htm">Lincoln No. 3: A Student's-eye View of School Change</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/lincoln4.htm">Lincoln No. 4: Priorities and Possibilities: Choices for Change</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/lincoln5.htm">Lincoln No. 5: Rewriting the Roles</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/lincoln6.htm">Lincoln No. 6: Three Views of Lincoln</a></b><p></ul><p><h4>The "Crossroads" Study:</h4>Richard W. Clark with Janey Miller and Vicky Murray<p>"Crossroads High School" is a mid-size school in a multi-ethnic community on the outskirts of a Southwestern city.  In addition to its traditional features, Crossroads has an interdisciplinary, cross-grade program and a governing council in which faculty, students, parents, and administrators share decision making.  Crossroads joined the Coalition in 1991.<p><ul><li><b><a href="sc/cross1.htm">Crossroads No. 1: Challenges and Incongruities</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/cross2.htm">Crossroads No. 2: Consensus-building: Progress and Problems</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/cross3.htm">Crossroads No. 3: A Context for Change</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/cross4.htm">Crossroads No. 4: Possibilities and Realities: Facing the Obstacles to Change</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/cross5.htm">Crossroads No. 5: Some Things Change, Some Things Don't</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/cross6.htm">Crossroads No. 6: Still At The Crossroads</a></b><p></ul><p><h4>The "Oak Hill" Study:</h4>Patricia A. Wasley with Barbara Powell and Donna Hughes<p>"Oak Hill High School" is the pseudonym for a suburban school in the Northeast with a primarily white, college-bound population.  A traditional high school with a history of openness to innovation, Oak Hill joined the Coalition in the 1989-90 school year.<p><ul><li><b><a href="sc/oh1.htm">Oak Hill No. 1: Poised for Change</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/oh2.htm">Oak Hill No. 2: Principles and Practice</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/oh2a.htm">Oak Hill No. 2a: Interpreting the Nine Common Principles</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/oh3.htm">Oak Hill No. 3: A Gathering Momentum: Change and Transition</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/oh4.htm">Oak Hill No. 4: Toward a Reflexive Learning Community</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/oh5.htm">Oak Hill No. 5: Ideals and Realities</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/oh6.htm">Oak Hill No. 6: Looking Back, Looking Ahead</a></b><p></ul><p><h3>The Urban School Studies:</h3>Richard W. Clark, Janet Miller, Neill Wenger and Barara S. Powell<p>Studies of two of the high schools, in a large Eastern city, reveal the particular challenges of attempting change within the inner city.  Underlining the connection between what happens in schools and their larger context, these studies describe districtwide restructuring efforts, as well as school-based initiatives.<p><h4>The "Marshall" Study:</h4>"Marshall High School" enrolls more than 2,000 students from all parts of the city.<ul><li><b><a href="sc/marshal1.htm">Marshall No. 1: On the Road to Renewal</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/marshal2.htm">Marshall No. 2: Thriving in the Midst of Chaos</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/marshal3.htm">Marshall No. 3: Finding Common Vision</a></b><p></ul><p><h4>The "Forest Park" Study:</h4>"Forest Park High School" enrolls 1,000 ninth- through twelfth-graders from a neighborhood filled with the signs of urban decay.<ul><li><b><a href="sc/fp1.htm">Forest Park No. 1: Revitalization in an Urban Setting</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/fp2.htm">Forest Park No. 2: Many Paths to Reform</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sc/fp3.htm">Forest Park No. 3: "Clean, Cool, and Calm": A Haven in the Inner City</a></b><p></ul><p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><p><a name="3"><hr><h2>Research papers on the School Ethnography Proejct:</h2><hr>Donna Muncey and Patrick McQuillan<p>This six-year, independently funded project, begun in 1986, documents the consequences of reform efforts in eight "charter" Essential Schools.  The study attempts to answer two questions: How are the nine Common Principles interpreted by individual schools? and How are they translated into practice in each setting?<p><ul><li><b><a href="sep/sep02.htm">SEP No. 2: Protecting Your School's Interest While Promoting Quality Research</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sep/sep03.htm">SEP No. 3: Findings from the Field: What Happens When Schools Restructure?  A Five-Year Study of Eight Essential Schools</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sep/sep05.htm">SEP No. 5: Empowering Nonentities: Students in Educational Reform</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sep/sep06.htm">SEP No. 6: School-within-a-School Restructuring and Faculty Divisiveness: Examples from a Study of the Coalition of Essential Schools</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sep/sep07.htm">SEP No. 7: Teachers Talk about Coalition Reforms at their Schools</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sep/sep08.htm">SEP No. 8: Sustaining School Change: Case Studies from the Coalition of Essential Schools</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sep/sep09.htm">SEP No. 9: The Dangers of Assuming Consensus for Change: Some Examples from the Coalition of Essential Schools</a></b><p><li><b><a href="sep/sep10.htm">SEP No. 10: Change Takes Time": A Look at the Growth and Development of the Coalition of Essential Schools</a></b><p></ul><p><a href="#contents">[Return to Table of Contents]</a><p><hr><p><a href = "../publicat.htm">Return to the Publications page.</a></b><p><p></body></html>
