 the report.)<p>Zero Tolerance: Status Report on Implementation  (B. Soft/A. Prince) (5 minutes)<p>Administration: Status report on early dismissal  (A. Prince) (5 minutes)<p><b>Old Business  </b>(See attached background information)<p>Future of Block  (Action scheduled for March 17 -- Today participants will have the opportunity to state advantages and disadvantages of current advisory schedule and advantages and disadvantages of current arrangements for 1st and 7th period) (20 minutes)<p>Continuation of Faculty Meetings  (Action scheduled for today -- Motion -- "Faculty meeting shall be continued for the remainder of 1993-94 on Thursdays from 3:30 to 4:30. All faculty not having specific assignment to work with students shall attend.") [Note: approval must be given by two-thirds of faculty. Proxies voted must be worded as support or opposition to the motion stated here.] (10 minutes)<p><b>New Business</b><p>Request for volunteers for pre and spring registration  (A. Juarez) (2 minutes -- if no volunteers, chair will appoint)<p>Request for volunteer facilitator for next meeting  (L. Good) (2 minutes -- if no volunteers, chair will appoint)<p><b>Process Observations:</b>   Comments by observer (A. Goodguy) (5 minutes)<p><b>Announcements and Schedule of Future Items</b><p>Committee Report on In-School Suspension will be presented on March 10.  (Action tentatively scheduled for March 24)<p>Schedule for Semester Exams for Spring 1994 will be discussed by Governing Council on March 7. Recommendation will be presented for information on March 10.  (Action tentatively scheduled for March 17)<p>Committee on closed campus will meet in Room 210 on Tuesday. Contact Mary Wells if you have questions.<p>Background Notes for March 3 Meeting<p><p><center><h4>BACKGROUND INFORMATION FOR THE MARCH 3 MEETING</h4>Future of Block<p>(Contact C. McCarthy if you have questions)</center><p>At last week's meeting we voted to continue the block for this year. Now we need to decide about next year. The curriculum committee has found that there are two big issues which make it hard for us to recommend a particular plan for the schedule for next year: (1) what to do about the period 1 and 7 schedule and (2) what to do about advisory. Concerning the period 1 and 7 schedule, the sports/PE classes seem to be the most frequently mentioned reason for needing daily meetings of these periods. However, there are other arguments. Concerning advisory, we are not sure whether the experiences to date indicate we should continue the program next year. Nor can we tell, if we do, what the frequency of meeting or the length of each advisory session should be. We need to talk about this in depth during our planning period meetings on March 7, 8 and 9. During the March 3 meeting we hope to hear different points of view that will help all of us be aware of the issues as we have these period discussions. Everyone should be aware that we hope to have a vote on the block schedule for 1994-95 during our faculty meeting on March 17. The specific motion on which we will vote will be on the agenda which will be issued on March 14 for that meeting.<p><p><center><h3>Continuation of Faculty Meetings</h3>(Contact A. Prince or M. B. Bryan if you have questions)</center><p>Since January, 1994 our entire faculty has met each Thursday from 3:30 to 4:30. We had hoped to be able to conduct these meetings during early dismissals on Friday. However, we will have to wait until transportation can coordinate our dismissal with ending times for other schools. Meanwhile we believe the meetings should continue for the rest of the year so we can take care of important unfinished business. The motion on this week's agenda has been developed by the administration committee.<p><p><hr><a href="cross6.htm">Return to Crossroads No. 6</a><br><a href="../list.htm#2">Return to Index of School Change Publications</a><p></b