<html><head><title>CES: Membership: The Application Procedure</title></head><body><hr><h1><center>The Application Procedure</center></h1><hr>The Application for Membership in the Coalition of Essential Schools is designed as an opportunity for the applicant school to make an honest self-assessment of past practice, current progress, and future goals.  To be considered for memberhip, a school needs to demonstrate the ability to meet the necessary criteria, and present a "change strategy" that reflects where the school is, where it wants to be, and how it intends to get there.<p>To apply for membership in the Coalition of Essential Schools, your school should submit a letter of interest accompanied by the following documents:<p><ol><li><b>An overview of your school's exploration and planning processes</b> that describes the length and scope of the period of interest and documents the activities undertaken as your school developed its plan of action for translating the <a href = "../principl/principl.htm"> Nine Common Principles</a> into practice.<p>The decision to redesign your school along the nine Common Principles is ambitious, and the process that your school followed as you prepared your Essential school program helps put current and future practice into context.<p><li><b>A description of the parts of your Essential school philosophy that are already in place.</b>  If a visitor were to enter your school today, what would she see?  To apply for membership, a school must have in place at least a prelliminary program that reflects the nine Common Principles in practice.  The opportunity to describe that program helps schools see what is happening, and what adjustments could be made for the benefit of the students.<p><li><b>An action plan for translating the nine Common Principles into practice</b> in your entire school.  The plan should include at least the following:<p><b>A statement of the goals your faculty has agreed on and a description (necessarily preliminary) of the changes you will be making.</b>  Some examples of these <b>goals</b> might be:<p><b>Philosophical</b>, such as:<br><ul><li>The development of a vision of the ideal graduate of your school <li>A clear and unmistakable intellectual emphasis<li>The setting of goals and standards that are clear, few in number, and apply to all students</ul><p><b>Structural</b>, such as:<br><ul><li>A school structure which supports longer periods of time for uninterrupted student work<li>Regular and substantial time for collective planning by teachers who have the same students<li>The development of teacher and student teams<li>A management structure which gives authority to teachers and principals to determine the instructional program and operational details of the school<li>A structure which allows for the active participation of parents, community members, businesses, and universities as supporters and allies for the school<li>The implementation of heterogeneous grouping<li>A reduction in the student load per teacher</ul><p><b>Pedagogical</b>, such as:<br><ul><li>Students actively displaying their knowledge through performances and Exhibitions as a means of earning their diplomas<li>Teachers working as generalists, and as coaches<li>Implementation of ideas to personalize the school environment for the students<li>The setting of a tone of decency and "unanxious expectations," both within individual classrooms and throughout the school</ul><p>b.<b> A description of the strategies your school plans to use</b> in the next year in order to move toward meeting its goals.<p>c.<b>A list of the most pressing impediments</b> (both internal and external) to the changes being made, and possible strategies for overcoming them.<p><li><b>A Letter of Agreement</b> signed by appropriate school authorities.<li><b>A School Profile Form</b> completed in full.</ol><p>Schools applying for membership should submit one copy of their completed application to their state or regional coordinator (where appropriate), and one copy to the Schools Coordinator of the Coalition of Essential Schools.  Where possible, a school visit will be arranged as a part of the evaluation process.  Applications for membership in the Coalition of Essential Schools will be processed in a timely fashion - schools should expect a response within thirty days of the date of receipt of the membership application.<p><a href="membersh.htm">Return to the Membership page.</a><p></body></html>
