<html><head><title>CES: Membership: Membership Statement</title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><hr><h1><center>Membership Statement</center></h1><hr><ul><li><a href = "#statement">Statement</a><li><a href = "#stages">Stages of Membership</a><li><a href = "#criteria">Criteria for Membership</a><li><a href = "#expectations">Expectations for Member Schools</a></ul><p><hr><a name = "statement"></a>The Coalition of Essential Schools is a nationwide effort by teachers,students, administrators and parents in more than 230 member schools -large, medium and small; public, private and parochial; rural, urban andsuburban - to rethink their school's priorities and simplify itsstructure in order to focus on helping students learn to use their mindswell.  The Coalition offers no specific model for changing schoolpractices; rather, each school evolves a plan appropriate to its ownsetting based on a set of nine "common principles."  Each school developsits own programs, suited to its particular students, faculty andcommunity, and member schools serve as examples of a variety ofthoughtfully redesigned schools.  The network offers the opportunity forEssential schools to exchange ideas and strategies for change.  TheCoalition is, at heart, an ongoing "conversation among friends" who agreeupon a critique of schooling and a set of shared ideas that give focus totheir diverse efforts.<p>Essential schools are supported in their work through the Re:Learninginitiative and through regional networks.  The Coalition and theEducation Commission of the States jointly sponsor Re:Learning, designedto help people in all levels of the education system "from school houseto statehouse" work toward the goal of teaching all students to use theirminds well.  Eleven states have so far joined Re:Learning: Arkansas,Colorado, Delaware, Illinois, Indiana, Maine, Missouri, New Mexico,Pennsylvania, Rhode Island and South Carolina.  Regional networks havebeen set up in Northern and Southern California; New York City and State;New England; Jefferson County (Louisville), Kentucky; Greater Houston,Texas; and Broward County (Ft. Lauderdale), Florida.  Each region andRe:Learning state has a full-time coordinator who works with schools asthey rethink their structures and practices in light of the CommonPrinciples.<p>Essential schools have found that successful change efforts require thefollowing:<ul><li>recognition of the need for change<li>commitment<li>a shared vision<li>collaboration among the faculty, leadership, community, and district<li>confidence<li>a sense of humor</ul><br>Those collaborating for change must also be given adequate time andresources to explore and discuss ideas for change.  Because suchbroad-reaching efforts are unlikely to succeed in isolation, theCoalition discourages membership of schools not able to network withcolleagues through a region or Re:Learning state.<p><a name = "stages"><h3><center>The "Stages" of Membership</center></h3></a>Becoming an Essential schools is not the single step of applying formembership in the Coalition but rather a series of stages that begin evenbefore a schools asks for an application and continue long past the timea school officially joins.  Ours is a process whereby schools arecontinually "evolving into" Essential schools.  We recognize that aschool's interest and engagement will vary at different stages in thechange process.  As the Essential schools ideas take shape in the school,the faculty continually broadens its understanding of the <a href = "../principl/principl.htm">Nine Common Principles</a> and their implication forsignificant and substantive change.<p>Prior to membership, a school typically moves through these stages:<p><b>Exploring</b><br>Individuals interested in rethinking their school's priorities and practices initiate a "conversation" among faculty, parents and/or schoolboard members about the nine Common Principles as a way to structurechange.  Faculty members are given the time and resources to attendsymposia and visit Essential schools.  The school works to build thecooperative culture necessary to initiate and sustain on-going change.The school begins to identify obstacles to change and ways to addressthem to determine whether they want to proceed with developing a plan forschool change.<p><b>Planning</b><br>As the conversation among constituencies in the school continues, thewhole school community agrees on a plan of action for the first year ofchanges in the classroom.  The plan should include both a supportingrationale, and an outline of the pedagogical and structural changes to beimplemented.  For example, structural changes might include longerclass-time blocks, smaller students loads for teachers, new criteria for grouping students, common teacher-planning time, teaching teams andperformance-based assessments, while changes in pedagogy and curriculumdevelopment might lead to simplifying curriculum, a focus onstudents-as-workers and teachers-as-coaches, and the fostering of anatmosphere where decency and "unanxious expectation" are emphasized.  Thefaculty begins to work toward consensus on the essential skills and areasof knowledge that students must "exhibit" to earn the school's diploma.The school develops links to colleagues in the regional, state andnational networks.<p>A school may apply for membership in the Coalition of Essential Schoolswhen it has at least an initial program in place with students andteachers and can demonstrate a commitment to the criteria andexpectations outlined below.<p><b>Membership</b><br>When a school joins the Coalition, it is publicly recognized as anEssential school, an active member in a partnership of like-mindedcolleagues committed to improving student learning through the nineCommon Principles.  Evidence of that commitment is visible in the changedpractices of the school.  Member schools serve as exemplars to schoolswithin and outside the Coalition of how the Common Principles may beinterpreted in practice.  They may also work collaboratively withnearby exploring or planning schools.<p>Pivotal points in the continuing evolution of an Essential school are:<p><b>Implementation and Expansion</b><br>With the action plan in effect in classrooms, the school during the firstyear focuses on making needed adjustments as problems arise and onsupporting students through the transition to new learning techniques andresponsibilities.  Plans are developed for the second and subsequentyears of the program.  The faculty continues to develop and refinecriteria and tools for graduation Exhibitions.<p><b>Evaluation and Renewal</b><br>Every two years, member schools assess their own progress and report inwriting on their achievements to date, new or unresolved obstacles tochange and their plans for the next two years.  The specific process forthe self-evaluation might vary by region or state.  In addition, schools are expected to regularly work collaboratively with Essential schoolcolleagues to reflect on the progress of their school, to review andrenew their commitment to Essential school change and to chart a coursefor the future.<p><a name = "criteria"><h3><b><center>The Criteria for Membership</center></b></h3></a><br>The following criteria are considered necessary for acceptance into theCoalition of Essential Schools.  Representatives of the school communityare asked to sign a Letter of Agreement confirming their commitment to these criteria.<p><b>Action Plan</b><br>As part of the application process, school submit a statement of theirlong-term goals, and an action plan for the development of theirEssential school program for at least the next school year.  The planstates the school's new priorities, describes the changes in structures,pedagogy, curriculum and assessment procedures needed to support thosepriorities and represents the faculty's commitment to actively engagestudents in the learning process.<p><b>Consensus</b><br>The Coalition is a school-based reform effort.  Thus, it is essentialthat the faculty of the school demonstrate an understanding of the CommonPrinciples and that a substantial majority agree to work toward theapplication of all nine Common Principles.  Concurrently, the approvalof the governing boards and superintendents is crucial to give the program necessary and continuing support.<p><b>Community Support</b><br>It is vital that the community be involved as a full partner in schoolchange.  Thus, it is expected throughout the planning and membershipprocess that community leaders, parents and other stakeholders take anactive role in the development and implementation of the Essential schoolphilosophy.<p><b>School Coordinator</b><br>To support the ongoing change process, each school identifies aschool-site coordinator to be responsible for exchanging informationbetween the school, the regional or state coordinator and the Coalition and for organizing professional development activities for the faculty.<p><a name = "expectations"><h3><center>Expectations for Member Schools</center></h3></a><b>Commitment</b><br>Any serious effort at change, especially change as ambitious as theCoalition envisions, requires time.  Schools that join the Coalition, therefore, are expected to make at least a four-year commitment.  Thiscommitment reflects the belief that a member school is continually movingtoward the goal of becoming a fully articulated Essential school.<p><b>Whole-School Involvement</b><br>The Coalition is not an "alternative" school program, nor is it a "pilotproject."  Therefore, it is required that every Essential school plan forwhole-school expansion, and expected that the school community at-largebe included in the discussions that shape the program.  While a schoolmay begin its Essential school program with a small portion of its students and staff, the long-term goal is for the Coalition philosophy toshape the entire school.<p><b>Documentation</b><br>Membership in the Coalition carries with it a responsibility tocontribute information to people both involved in and interested in theeffort, including Coalition staff and member schools, regional and statecoordinators, nonmember schools, parents, community groups and thepress.  This documentation will also be used as a tool for reflection inthe two-year self-evaluations, and to establish and further networks among schools.<p><b>Assessment of Progress</b><br>A vital part of the membership process is a periodic "good hard look" atthe amount of progress made and the kinds of difficulties encountered.Both the Coalition staff and member schools feel that self-evaluationsand critical friends' assessments are vital for meaningful dialogue bothwithin the school and between the school and the larger Coalition network.<p><b>Sufficient Funds</b><br>While there is no fee to join the Coalition, a substantial commitment ofdistrict funds over several years is necessary to support the schoolduring the planning and implementation of its Essential school ideas.Coalition-related expenses include on-site professional development andplanning, travel costs and conference fees for participation in Coalitionactivities.  While the specific amount varies from one situation toanother, the school needs to demonstrate that it is likely to havesufficient monies to meet these expenses over the multi-year commitment.<p>Schools interested in membership may contact their local Re:Learning or regional coordinator or the Schools Coordinator at the Coalition.<p><hr><p><a href = "membersh.htm">Return to the Membership page</a><p></body></html>
