<BODY>

<H1><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H1>
<H2><CODE><B>A Rural School Asks More, Gets More</B></CODE> </H2>

<H4><B>November, 1994 - No. 12</B></H4>
<HR>

<H5><B>Noble High School</B></H5>

<P>
46 Cranberry Meadow Road
<P>
Berwick, Maine 03901
<P>
(207) 698-1320
<P>
Pamela Fisher, Principal
<P>
867 students grades 9-12, 75 staff
<P>
99% white students
<P>
14% free or reduced-price lunch
<P>
13% receiving special ed services
<P>
35-40% go on to college
<P>
Rural regional high school<HR>

<H3><EM>Four years of math and science, combined with challenging
new classroom methods, have raised student performance dramatically
in this hard-strapped rural school. </EM></H3>

<P>
Three seniors have taped a couple of yardsticks to the table in
John Nowacki's physics class, slanted so they can roll a small
steel ball down a track onto the floor. &quot;We've got to figure
out exactly where it'll land,&quot; says Tad Barbour, brushing
his blond forelock out of his eyes. &quot;Got to set this cup
on the floor and catch it on the first try.&quot; He catches Nowacki's
eye, gets the go-ahead to see if his group got it right. The ball
plunks into the cup. His teammates cheer, elated. &quot;We did
it with this equation,&quot; says Dawn Ingots, brandishing a graphing
calculator. &quot;Look, I'll show you how.&quot;
<P>
Five years ago, these students would not have been taking physics
at Noble High School. To get to this school you drive through
a landscape of fields, dotted with mobile homes and silos and
the occasional satellite dish or Dairy Queen. You'll see pockets
of quaintness, but this is not vacationland Maine; this inland
southern region suffers low employment and does not expect much
better very soon. Though its high school is bursting at the seams,
housing close to 300 more kids than it was built for, a new building
will have to wait until 1998.
<P>
But four years ago, Noble High School decided it wasn't going
to wait for the success its kids deserved. In a bold and controversial
leap based on the principle of the Coalition of Essential Schools,
the staff agreed to eliminate lower-track courses altogether,
offering the same challenging curriculum to every student. &quot;If
you do not teach watered-down subjects,&quot; principal Pamela
Fisher declares, &quot;kids will not be able to take them.&quot;
<P>
Noble still offers a wide variety of elective courses, from studio
arts to Latin, French, and Spanish. But classes are now taught
in 80-minute blocks that encourage greater depth. In any course,
any student can go for greater challenge by fulfilling the stiffer
requirements of an &quot;honors&quot; option. As many as 100 kids
have signed up for ten Advanced Placement courses, in which anyone
can enroll. Subjects like &quot;consumer math&quot; have vanished.
And by June 1996, every graduate will have taken four years of
math and science, including advanced algebra as well as biology,
chemistry, and physics.
<P>
Down in the Learning Center, where kids and aides and teachers
cluster around computer stations and tables, special education
teacher Betsey Clark muses on the shock waves that accompanied
the change. &quot;You just can't use the same old lecture techniques
on a mixed group of students,&quot; she says. If everyone's going
to get it, teachers have to come up with new strategies.&quot;
<P>
Quite a few Noble teachers were already using those strategies,
Clark and her team pointed out. As new methods took hold, moreover
-- like cooperative learning, hands-on projects, and real-world
applications -- high-achieving youngsters began to benefit as
much as those who needed a boost to make the grade. These days,
the Learning Center bustles with activity across the spectrum
of student talent, providing individual coaching and technological
support.
<H5><B>Taking the Work Personally</B> </H5>

<P>
Today a look into Noble's classrooms offers an unusual glimpse
of teachers given broad latitude to work with students in whatever
ways they think will work. In one of several temporary classrooms
set up to hold the overflow, Jon Appleby teaches English and writing
to five classes, including an &quot;alternative&quot; for those
who have done poorly in previous years. His syllabus for this
last course rivals those of many college seminars in its thoughtfulness
and passion for ideas. Kids choose four out of ten possible ten-week
units that center around &quot;essential questions&quot; like
&quot;Why do human beings seek risk?&quot; Each unit comes with
a selection of provocative readings, writing assignments, and
presentations; each holds out a tantalizing hook to a student
who chooses to be &quot;different.&quot;
<P>
Waylaid in the halls with a bucket in hand, biology teacher Gerry
Crocker is just in from a field research session with a group
of students. The data they collect, about the effects of development
on two nearby rivers, contributes to a long-term state and local
environmental study. &quot;Our goal is to get kids into research
projects that matter,&quot; says Crocker, who brings a background
in Foxfire and other experiential learning programs to her work.
<P>
Quite a few Noble teachers, in fact, have some degree of special
training they share with colleagues (often in their three hours
of weekly common planning time). The &quot;gifted and talented&quot;
specialist, Susan DeVito, moves freely between classrooms, prodding
teachers to extend extra challenges to all students. John Nowacki
and Jim Andrews bring back ideas from Brown University, where
they trained as Math-Science Fellows on the Coalition's National
Re:Learning Faculty. Scott Edelman is designing a school-to-work
internship program based on his alliance with TERC, the Teacher
Education Research Center in Cambridge, Massachusetts. Many other
such connections lead directly into Noble's classrooms, where
kids are &quot;too busy these days,&quot; says Assistant Principal
Peter Meagher, to get in much trouble. Disciplinary incidents
are way down and attendance is up, he says, since the move to
teaming and a tougher academic core.
<P>
By the time the first seniors present their &quot;Senior Celebration&quot;
exhibitions this June, this school will have radically revised
its definition of excellence. New &quot;school learning results,&quot;
based on the Maine Common Core of Learning and demonstrated in
cumulative portfolios of student work, will soon substitute for
Carnegie units graduation requirements. The budget may be shrinking
yearly as Noble faces the challenges of a rural community in transition.
But everything else about this school is expanding - and in this
obscure corner of the nation, a new standard has begun to take
shape.
<H5><B>Noble Progress: Out-Performing State Norms Across the Board</B>
</H5>

<P>
The 1994 results from the Mine Educational Assessment (MEA) tests
were awaited with particular eagerness at Noble High School. Essential
School assessment analysts consider MEA a &quot;good test&quot;
- since its introduction in the late 1980s it has steadily increased
the number of more authentic, &quot;performance-based&quot; questions
that require students to demonstrate higher-order thinking. Moreover,
the Noble class of 1995 had taken the test in spring of 1990,
just as they were leaving a traditional junior high for Noble's
untracked Essential School experience - thus providing a clean
baseline by which to evaluate their progress under the new approach.
Finally, the MEA provides comparisons not only with the state
average scores, but also with comparable students in terms of
demographics - factors like parental employment and education,
which in Noble's case is strikingly low. Little wonder that the
following results brought satisfaction to the school community:
<UL>
<LI>The first class to be completely heterogeneously grouped for
all core academic classes showed a substantial increase across
all subjects in the percentage of students performing in the top
quarter. These percentages leaped from 19 to 31% in mathematics,
from 22 to 26% in science, from 19 to 26% in reading, from 24
to 26% in writing, from 19 to 22% in social studies, and from
22 to 27% in the arts and humanities.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>At the same time, the percentage of students performing in
the lowest quartile dropped dramatically - from 31 to 17% in reading,
from 34 to 13% in writing, from 30 to 20% in mathematics, from
28 to 19% in science, from 30 to 22% in social studies, and from
27 to 20% in the arts and humanities.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>The gender gap in math and science performance was virtually
eliminated, in the first classes ('94 and '95) who were required
to take three years of math including algebra and geometry.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Noble students are significantly out-performing comparison
groups with similar rural, poor, blue-collar demographics. And
MEA data shows their aspirations have doubled in five years: from
35% indicating college plans to 69% in 1994. (A similar rise in
aspirations shows up in the sharp increase of Noble students who
choose to take Advanced Placement courses.)
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>For the first time, students in Noble's class of 1995 scored
above the state average in every category the MEA tests.
</UL>

<H3><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools </B>
<P>
<B>Number 12, November 1994</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing areas in which Essential Schools
are demonstrating significant progress toward change using the
Nine Common Principles.</B> 
<P>
