<HEAD>

<TITLE>PERFORMANCE</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="General Use">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H1>

<H3><B>February, 1995 - No. 15</B></H3>
<HR>

<P>
<B>Rancho San Joaquin Middle School</B>
<P>
4861 Michelson Drive
<P>
Irvine, California 92715
<P>
(714) 786-3005
<P>
Mark Reider, Principal
<P>
812 students grades 7-8
<P>
45 teachers and other staff
<P>
36% minority students
<P>
12.4% free or reduced lunch
<P>
Member of California's 1274 Restructuring Sch. Network<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>Laying a Foundation for Learning Well </B></CODE>
</H2>

<H3><EM>This middle school coaches kids steadily in work habits
so they can handle more demanding thinking tasks in class and
in later life. </EM></H3>

<P>
The school doesn't look so old; it's only been around since 1971.
But here in the planned community of Irvine, California, Rancho
San Joaquin Middle School is positively hoary with age. Like an
extravagant plant in this sunny Orange County climate, its district
has grown exponentially throughout the past two decades, adding
school after school to serve a burgeoning population.
<P>
Rancho got the reputation of being the old place everyone would
leave for the dynamic new start-ups,&quot; says Roger King, who
came here in 1986 to teach and later became the school's in-house
professional development coach. Students arrived with widely different
academic preparations from elementary school scattered around
the district; after Rancho they went on to Irvine's conventional
(and nationally ranked) high schools. In between, King says, &quot;It
was a traditional junior high: isolated teachers in classrooms
with closed doors using 'sit-and-listen' teaching methods, and
little recognition of the special needs of students at this age.&quot;
<P>
But in the last seven years a new philosophy has taken hold at
this school, influenced both by the national middle-school reform
movement and by the ideas of the Coalition of Essential Schools.
&quot;We're no longer a teacher-centered school,&quot; says Erin
Hughes, a resource specialist at Rancho since 1986. &quot;We're
student-centered.&quot; And Rancho students now have such an active
approach to their own education that teachers up and down this
system are feeling its effect. Its graduates arriving at Irvine's
top-ranked high schools come much more prepared to tackle demanding
work - not just because they read, write, and do math better than
they used to, say their teachers, but because their attitude toward
school work has profoundly shifted.
<H5><B>First Target: Work Habits</B> </H5>

<P>
That shift happened, teachers here say, because for its first
several years of reform Rancho explicitly taught, monitored, and
rewarded good work habits. An Effort Honor Roll provides rewards
on a monthly basis to students who consistently come prepared
and participate actively in class, bring materials to class, and
use their time effectively. &quot;You can't learn successfully
if you don't have these habits,&quot; asserts Erin Hughes. Students
seem to agree; most report that the work habits program raised
their sights and often their grades.
<P>
Next, the faculty began a campaign to develop schoolwide &quot;habits
of respectfulness&quot; from keeping orderly spaces to conserving
resources and practicing tolerant and supportive attitudes. The
school climate has improved markedly since, Rancho's yearly student
survey reveals. Students are measurably more comfortable asking
counselors for help with academic problems; many more believe
that most teachers take time to answer their questions in class;
and 83 percent now agree that all student get equal treatment.
<P>
&quot;We agree with the research showing that a supportive classroom
and school climate positively influence student effort and academic
motivation,&quot; says Mark Reider, Rancho's new principal. &quot;That's
why we go to such trouble to document and improve our performance
in this area.&quot; Having launched that effort, he says, the
school could move on to its latest campaign: getting its students
into good intellectual habits.
<H5><B>Shaping Habits of Mind</B> </H5>

<P>
The seventh-grade warlords in Brad Hughes's classroom may not
realize that thinking habits underlie the ritualistic swordplay
and tea ceremonies they are enthusiastically enacting as five-tone
music sets the mood of ancient Japan. Integrating humanities and
the sciences in a three-hour block with 29 students, Hughes and
his colleague Cathy Lovejoy, one door down, are working to engage
these youngsters in serious analytical tasks: comparing perspectives,
analyzing evidence, making projections.
<P>
&quot;Earthquake!&quot; shouts Hughes suddenly, and the students
dive beneath their desks for the requisite drill. Minutes later,
they are gathered around tables of five, using wave theory to
analyze actual earthquake data from Japan and calculate where
the epicenter is. It's all part of the warlord game - they'll
get points for letting the &quot;emperor&quot; know how the quake
or upcoming weather patterns will affect troop movement. But it's
rigorous science curriculum along with the concepts and skills
of social studies, art, and language arts.
<P>
All English and social studies teachers now teach humanities instead,
in two long blocks that have reduced the number of students they
see daily by 30, to an average of 100. At least as important,
the faculty now meets regularly to go over how its work provokes
higher-order thinking in students - perspective, analysis, imagination,
empathy, communication, and commitment. As a recipient of California's
restructuring grant, the school has committed to assessing how
student work stacks up against shared standards of excellence.
<P>
&quot;For the first time, teachers here see their job as not only
creating success in their individual classrooms,&quot; King observes,
&quot;but also reflecting on it and analyzing it schoolwide.&quot;
<P>
Michele Rosenblum's seventh-grade class is busy learning sign
language to accommodate the deaf and autistic classmate who will
soon be joining them. Out on the sports fields, Scott Bowman points
out how kids are designing successful fitness programs for people
of all descriptions. In the technology classroom, former wood
shop teacher Bob Mayfield shows the ways students use robotics,
electronics, pneumatics, and solar power to solve problems. Clearly,
most here speak the same language, care about the same outcomes,
share the same values.
<P>
&quot;I know the standards now,&quot; says eighth-grader Jennifer
Barth. &quot;So I work harder, and my teachers help me, because
they know me.&quot; At Rancho, they call that progress.
<H5><B>How Are We Doing? For a Candid View, Rancho Annually Asks
Its Students</B> </H5>

<UL>
<LI>Almost two-thirds of Rancho students say their work habits
and effort have improved this year, and that the effort has improved
their grades. Many credit the Work Habits program and Effort Honor
Roll (which virtually all say they understand), with half of students
saying it encourages them to work harder.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Almost three-fourths of Rancho students say that at least
half their teachers give them the chance for active learning,
not just sitting and listening.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Almost three-fourths say there are different ways besides
quizzes and tests to show what they know or can do in class.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>More than two-thirds say more than half their teachers help
them see how different subjects are connected to each other.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Almost 3/4 (74%) believe that their Rancho classes will be
useful in their lives, and two-thirds say that in at least half
of their classes they are learning &quot;to solve real problems.&quot;
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>In their humanities classes, conclude roughly three fourths
of Rancho students, they are improving their writing skills; learning
to think about issues and ideas rather than only learning facts;
and learning to identify elements of literature like plot, character,
and theme.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>In math, 81 percent say they're learning math concepts and
skills that will be important later, and 74 percent say they're
learning to communicate about math by writing, explaining, and
demonstrating what they know.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>In science, 73 percent say they're learning to understand
science in the real world, and 60 percent say they're learning
concepts and skills that will be important in their future.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Most Rancho students (73-83%) feel physically safe at school
- evidence that in the context of nationally increasing violence,
the school has maintained a safe environment.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Rancho's efforts toward making a more personal atmosphere
at the school have borne fruit. Students and teachers get along
very well; most (over 70%) believe their teachers like and respect
them, and more than half believe at least one Rancho staff member
knows about their special talents and qualities. But only 36%
believe they get personal attention in class, which has led the
faculty to explore a new student advisement program.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Rancho students say they trust each other (54%) and try to
support and encourage each other (52%). Almost half say they can
share their ideas and opinions without fear of being put down.
Three out of five say most of their teachers are enthusiastic
about teaching.
</UL>

<H3><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools</B>

<P>
<B>Number 15, February 1995</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing areas in which Essential Schools
are demonstrating significant progress toward change using the
Nine Common Principles.</B> 
<P>
<B>Published regularly by the Coalition of Essential Schools,
Box 1969, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912 - </B>
<P>
<B>(401) 863-3384.</B> 
