<HEAD>

<TITLE>PERFORMANCE</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="General Use">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>PERFORMANCE </H1>

<H3>January, 1995 - No. 16</H3>
<HR>

<H5>Oceana High School</H5>

<P>
401 Paloma Avenue
<P>
Pacifica, California 94044
<P>
(415) 355-4131
<P>
Lois Jones, Principal
<P>
550 students grades 9-12
<P>
27 teachers and administrators
<P>
50 percent minority
<P>
13 percent free or reduced lunch
<P>
Member of California's 1274 Restructuring Schools Network
<P>
Working-class community high school near San Francisco<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>A Hard-Pressed School Expects More, Gets More</B></CODE><EM>
</EM></H2>

<H4><EM><B>Once a comprehensive high school, this school halved
its size, trimmed its offerings, revised staff roles, made students
more active, and pushed for more depth across curriculum areas.</B>
</EM></H4>

<P>
Brandee Crowell gave a lesson in Boolean logic this week to the
eighth-graders and their parents who showed up at an open house
to see how they liked Oceana High School here in Pacifica, California.
She had just learned how to mine the Internet for information
on anything from skinheads to smoking laws, and like the rest
of her classmates she was ready to show what she knew. In another
corner, classmate Sudhir Durvasula talked with visitors about
issues in genetic engineering that had come up in science class
recently. Nobody felt much like strangers to each other; through
their community service requirement, Oceana students have become
familiar figures in the hospitals, the day care centers, and the
public library of this working-class suburb of San Francisco.
<P>
That informal evening was just one indicator of how, within this
aging complex of concrete buildings hugging the bare hills against
a sweeping ocean vista, a sea change has begun to take place in
how high school students are regarded by their school, by their
community, and by one another. In the three years since Oceana
adopted the principles of the Coalition of Essential Schools,
this school has not only cut its size in half. It has reexamined
the roles and responsibilities of its teaching staff. It has redefined
what learning looks like in the classroom. And it has broadened
the scope of student work so that real life problems come clearly
into focus under an academic lens.
<P>
&quot;As a freshman, Brandee wanted a more traditional, textbook-driven
experience,&quot; says Lois Jones, who turned a district financial
crisis into an opportunity for reform when she took over as principal
here four years ago. Now, opportunities abound across Oceana's
curriculum for kids to create the process of their own learning
rather than passively receive information from their teachers.
&quot;All you who pass through these portals,&quot; read the signs
over several classroom doors, &quot;prepare to educate yourselves.&quot;
<P>
In Bev Kong's science class, lab groups have just finished separating
a mixture of iron filings, salt, water, and sand into its various
parts and accounting scientifically for how they did it. &quot;In
my old school they would have given us a work sheet with instructions
and we would follow them like a recipe,&quot; says sophomore John
Magee. &quot;Here, they make us figure it out for ourselves.&quot;
The student teacher in Kong's class, a research biologist who
has switched in mid-career to teaching, nods approval. &quot;These
kids are learning to think like real scientists,&quot; he says.
<H5>'Tuning' the Standards </H5>

<P>
The change is coming about partly through painstaking attention
by Oceana's faculty to setting higher standards across the board.
As part of a phalanx of schools restructuring under the state's
1274 legislation, teachers meet regularly for critical discussions
about student work, drawing conclusions about how to shape their
teaching to improve achievement. Humanities teachers bring in
writing samples monthly for these &quot;tuning protocols,&quot;
a method that originated with Essential School researcher Joe
McDonald and which California's reform effort has adopted.
<P>
&quot;We grapple continually with what is acceptable, what is
mastery,&quot; Lois Jones says. &quot;Getting in the habit of
looking at student work pushes our expectations beyond where they
have been.&quot; To help students go deeper, Oceana reshaped its
schedule into 95-minute periods that meet two or three times weekly,
strengthened connections between courses across the curriculum,
and established a midyear &quot;Interim Week&quot; in which students
explore one subject in depth either on or off campus.
<P>
It's not only acceptable but prestigious now to be an achiever
at school,&quot; says librarian Mark Gordon, who coached Brandee
and her classmates on high-tech research techniques. &quot;Critical
thinking and skill mastery are jointly emphasized in every class.&quot;
The exhibition in Gordon's &quot;computer links&quot; course,
for example, asks students to demonstrate individually that they
can log on to the Internet to locate, download, and edit a file
using Gopher technology. More, they must evaluate the factual
validity of the information they retrieve, based on what they
know of the topic. &quot;Do you trust the source? Why?&quot; Gordon
asks them.
<H5>Arts Across the Curriculum </H5>

<P>
One striking area where this school excels is in the arts. Fine
arts teacher Mary Heeb works with every grade's humanities team
to devise an arts component to every unit, then coaches students
as they prepare exhibitions. &quot;The ninth graders were reading
<I>Black Boy</I> in their unit on African Americans,&quot; she
says. &quot;In conjunction with that I introduced a unit on the
blues, where they studied major blues artists and wrote their
own 12-bar blues pieces. Finally each student took a different
section of text from <I>Black Boy</I>, researched its meaning,
and summarized it in the blues call-and-response form. When they
performed the 25 sections together, we had a summary of the book
set in music.&quot; Heeb works with a statewide initiative on
integrating the arts; her experience has helped other Oceana teachers
in developing portfolio assessments across the curriculum.
<P>
That feeling of mutuality extends throughout the Oceana campus,
both students and teachers say. &quot;This school is far more
unified than any I have ever taught in,&quot; says counselor and
veteran teacher Steve North. &quot;Teachers really give students
their trust, and they do not abuse it. You can hand over major
responsibilities to them - in 1993 three freshmen totally organized
our Career Days, for example. Kids and adults all have the sense
that we're in this together.&quot;
<P>
&quot;Ours is one of the poorest districts in California,&quot;
Jones says. &quot;Our budget is in shreds; our classrooms are
bursting. We are hanging on financially by our fingernails.&quot;
Yet because the Oceana staff takes on multiple roles - administrators
are advisors and teachers; classified staff helps in the classroom
- the school has managed to maintain a personal and collaborative
ethos. Meanwhile, the 100 hours of community service every student
performs before graduating has also made new friends in the town.
<P>
On her way into the library with an armload of books, senior Tina
Khatcherian pauses to talk. &quot;I came here in tenth grade with
a 1.6 average, and I'm leaving with a 3.9,&quot; she says. &quot;The
teachers work together to help the students ; the long classes
let us go into things much deeper.&quot; Tina's family never expected
her to go past high school; but now she hosts a cable TV show
for teenagers, she recently led a science class discussion of
race and genetics, and she plans to go on to a four-year college.
&quot;This school totally turned me around,&quot; she says; and
the grin she flashes from the library door is just one success
story among many.
<H5>Aiming Higher, Going Farther: The Numbers </H5>

<P>
Oceana is watching closely as the first students to have experienced
all four years of high school in a restructured environment approach
graduation in June 1995. Compared to the days when Oceana was
a comprehensive high school of twice its present size, the numbers
already look good:
<UL>
<LI><B>TEST SCORES:</B> On the College Board's Scholastic Achievement
Tests (SATs), Oceana students' average verbal scores rose 33 points
between 1991 and 1994; their math scores rose by 25 points.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><B>ADVANCED COURSES:</B> Only 7 percent of students took Oceana's
third-year algebra and trigonometry course in 1990-91; three years
later, 10.26 percent did. The fourth-year college prep math analysis
course doubled the percentage of students who took it over the
same three-year period.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><B>POST-SECONDARY PLANS:</B> In 1990-91, 74 percent of Oceana
students went on to two- or four-year colleges; by 1993-94, that
number had risen to 99 percent. The majority opt for California's
community college system, but the number of those choosing four-year
colleges rose by close to 8 percent in that period.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><B>STUDENT RETENTION:</B> In 1990-91, 4.9 percent of Oceana
students dropped out before graduation; by 1993-1994 that figure
had dropped to .74 percent.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI><B>ATTENDANCE:</B> Oceana has always had high attendance rates,
but they rose from 96 percent in 1990-91 to 98 percent in 1993-94.
</UL>

<H3>PERFORMANCE</H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools</B>

<P>
<B>Number 16, January 1995</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing areas in which Essential Schools
are demonstrating significant progress toward change using the
Nine Common Principles.</B> 
<P>
<B>Published regularly by the Coalition of Essential Schools,
Box 1969, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912 (401) 863-3384.</B>

