<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Salem High School</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="David Allen">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1>PERFORMANCE</H1>

<H3>February, 1995 - No. 18</H3>
<HR>

<H5>Salem High School</H5>

<P>
3551 Underwood Road
<P>
Conyers, Georgia 30208
<P>
(404) 929-0176
<P>
Robert Cresswell, Principal
<P>
1250 students grades 9-12
<P>
75 teachers and other staff
<P>
8% minority students
<P>
11% free or reduced lunch
<P>
Residential suburban community
<P>
Georgia Demonstration School for School Restructuring<HR>

<H3><CODE><B>Higher Achievement via Heterogeneous Grouping</B></CODE>
</H3>

<H3><EM>Though many parents preferred sorting students by prior
achievement level, this school set high-level tasks for all students,
and is winning the gamble.</EM></H3>

<P>
The teacher looks young - barely older than his students. But
Jason Teague takes his task seriously. And it is only after he
finishes working aloud through the reasons one of his students
is falling behind that one realizes this member of the Salem High
School tenth-grade teaching team is only eighteen himself.
<P>
It's just one way this suburban Atlanta school, still wet behind
the ears, breaks out of the conventional mold to match its practice
to its rhetoric. If we value students as active workers, Salem
seems to say, why not take their intellectual contribution seriously
giving due respect to their questions and aspirations?
<P>
In the slick, high-growth corporate culture of this booming New
South town, Salem has stuck its neck out to achieve an intellectual
productivity previously unheard of even in these well groomed
suburbs. As the first Georgia member of the Coalition of Essential
Schools, it has vested ownership of its mission in teams of teachers,
reshaped the school day into long blocks to encourage deeper engagement,
and dramatically redrawn the lines of expected student behavior.
In such a risk-taking environment, Jason's venture into a team-teaching
internship seems almost routine.
<P>
The first class of Salem's seniors graduates in June 1995 from
the school that began in 1990 with sixth through ninth graders
and has since worked its way up to senior high status. Like Jason,
some 45 of 231 graduates will have pioneered the &quot;executive
internship&quot; program in which they serve as helpers two days
a week in Atlanta's professional community, keeping close records
of what they learned along the way.
<P>
But any of these students will tell you what else they have learned
here over four years of an Essential school experience. Salem's
unorthodox mixing of all students in two-hour academic blocks
at first drew protest from parents who thought it would pull down
challenge levels for higher-achieving students. Instead, students
say they are working harder than ever and enjoying it more. Attendance
figures and test scores back them up. Salem students have a higher
attendance rate and a lower failure rate than the other high schools
in the district. And in 1994, as average SAT scores dropped for
seniors in comparable county schools, Salem's juniors outperformed
their older peers by an average of 66 points.
<P>
<B>Teaching to the Top</B> 
<P>
People thought the classes would be dumber, that they would teach
to the lower level,&quot; says senior Rebecca Pitts. &quot;It
didn't turn out that way; it was whatever you made it.&quot; During
the school's first years any Salem student could achieve honors
status by taking on demanding independent projects within a course,
with a mentor and an outside review board.
<P>
&quot;From eighth through tenth grades I did honors projects in
pretty much every class,&quot; says Ruchi Gupta, a junior. &quot;For
my humanities course I interviewed Tom Murphy, the Speaker of
the Georgia House; I talked to his enemies and other State House
people, too. It was a pain - they were always canceling on me.
But I got a lot of help from my mentor here at school.&quot;
<P>
The attitude of excellence spread to embrace all students, even
those who conventionally would have been separated for more basic
classes. &quot;Two of our special needs students built an amazing
scale model of the Globe Theatre as we were studying <I>Romeo
and Juliet</I>,&quot; says language arts teacher Allison Wright.
&quot;If they hadn't been in a mixed group they would never have
done something that required so much outside research!&quot;
<P>
The president of the senior class Hal Loper, grins agreement.
&quot;I am so dyslexic that when I write it is like another language,&quot;
he says. &quot;The help I have gotten from this school is outstanding.
I did an internship at the Secretary of State's office in Atlanta,
and next Saturday I am going to sit in on a class with Newt Gingrich,
who teaches at the college I am going to sit in on a class with
Newt Gingrich, who teaches at the college I am going to.&quot;
A politician already, he shakes his head. &quot;I have a few questions
for him.&quot;
<P>
<B>Waivers? What Waivers?</B> 
<P>
Georgia's Governor Zell Miller came to Salem High in 1993 to sign
into law the state's &quot;charter schools&quot; bill, which allows
schools to apply for blanket waivers from the state. And Salem
is also a demonstration school for the state's high school restructuring
project. But principal Bob Cresswell looks bemused at the mention
of red tape. &quot;Turns out nothing we're doing requires any
waivers,&quot; he shrugs. &quot;Anybody could do it.&quot;
<P>
To encourage flexibility and productivity, Cresswell has turned
over substantial authority over how the school day works to his
staff. Teams of four teachers in Salem's core subject areas work
together with groups of 100 students in ninth and tenth grade,
in a project-rich curriculum that commonly crosses disciplinary
lines. Each team sets up its own schedule within a four and a
half hour block of academic time. Both special education and gifted
education teachers move through all classes to ensure that kids
receive the help and challenge they need.
<P>
<B>The J-Curve to Success</B> 
<P>
In algebra classes, for example, all students are coached to perform
the same demanding tasks. If their final assessments show low
scores their transcript may give credit in &quot;math&quot; instead
of algebra, but they stick with the group. &quot;Two years after
Angie Weekly failed Algebra 1, she finished Algebra 2 with one
of the highest averages in the class,&quot; boasts teacher Lynn
Fore.
<P>
By eleventh grade, teachers team more loosely, as projects demand
and interests warrant. Any student can elect Advanced Placement
courses, and the faculty concedes that some prove more ambitious
than others. Even in the upper grades, though, Salem holds to
its &quot;J-curve' philosophy of continuous improvement, arguing
that any work below a B is not good enough.
<P>
&quot;All kids can learn,&quot; declares tenth grades team member
Frances Freedman. &quot;But some need more time - how much depends
on a lot of different factors. Rather than emphasizing a certain
grade by a certain date, we concentrate on what you must achieve
so you can go on to the next thing. If you can write a complete
sentence only 70 percent of time the state will give you credit
for passing. But you write like a mess - why would you want to
go on to the next grade, much less on to college? With the J-curve,
we say, &quot;Why don't you take it further and get a B?&quot;
<P>
<B>Honors, With a Difference</B> 
<P>
The approach seems to have galvanized these students to new levels
of prowess. Three Salem tenth-graders qualified in 1993 for the
prestigious Governor's Honors Program, usually reserved for eleventh-graders.
The school won second place in the region's literary competition,
with a ninth-grader taking first place in the state. In math competitions,
mock-government simulations, and other such arenas Salem has racked
up a string of awards.
<P>
But these students clearly put most stock in their success when
it pushes past convention to break new ground for all. Salem's
chapter of the national Beta Club honor society, for instance,
found a way to ensure that their special needs peers could be
included in the club.
<P>
&quot;Everybody has their own gifts,&quot; declares eleventh-grader
Kelita Wiley. &quot;Like if I can show this kid something, he
can show me something different.&quot; Salem's peer mediation
program, she says, makes a good example of how her schoolmates
help each other. &quot;The first year we opened, every week there
was some kind of physical fight. They chose a very mixed group
of 20 or 30 kids to be peer mediators, and right from the start
you could see the fighting drop.&quot;
<P>
These students also feel that their work matters, both to the
school and the community. Sophomore J.C. Aevaliotis recalls a
ninth-grade project in which his team designed a stadium and field
house for the high school, and brought it before the school board
for consideration. Rebecca Pitts found herself in court fall term,
helping the district attorney's office fill out plea forms for
defendants who could not read or write. Trained by Atlanta's Alliance
Theater, the student drama group conducts workshops in local elementary
schools.
<P>
&quot;Last year our team did a project called 'Beyond the Year
2000,' where kids had to research and present projections for
some field,&quot; recalls tenth grade teacher Suzanne Gebhart.
&quot;They could do anything from transportation to medicine to
computers - one boy did an amazing project on air transportation.&quot;
Some students, she says, chose to envision the future of education.
&quot;Strange,&quot; Gebhart muses. &quot;A lot of the things
they said would happen some day were already happening here at
Salem High School.&quot;
<H3>PERFORMANCE </H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools </B>
<P>
<B>Number 18, February 1995 </B>
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman </B>
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing areas in which Essential Schools
are demonstrating significant progress toward change using the
Nine Common Principles. </B>
<P>
<B>Published regularly by the Coalition of Essential Schools,
Box 1969, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912 (401) 863-3384.
</B>
</BODY>

