<HEAD>

<TITLE>Oakland Park Elementary School</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="David Allen">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><B>PERFORMANCE </B></H1>

<H3>March, 1995  -  No. 19</H3>
<HR>

<H5>Oakland Park Elementary School</H5>

<P>
936 N.E. 33rd Street
<P>
Oakland Park, FL 33334
<P>
(305)390-0790
<P>
Larry Katz, Principal
<P>
715 students, 37 staff
<P>
50% minority students K-5
<P>
17% limited English proficiency
<P>
52% free and reduced lunch
<P>
36% turnover rate<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>Giant Steps toward Elementary Student Progress</B></CODE>
</H2>

<H3><EM>A climate that emphasizes family connections and celebrates
mastery has driven student achievement at this working-class elementary
school to record heights. </EM></H3>

<P>
Oakland Park Elementary School has a merry air about it, like
a small child bursting with a secret. Though it is the oldest
school in Fort Lauderdale and registered as a national historical
landmark, its graceful cloistered walkways, stucco walls, and
red tiled roofs somehow lose their sober gravity as lines of children
of every color troop through on errands or run up to a teacher
for some pressing exchange of news. Outside its wrought iron gates
the modest cottages go on for blocks, home to the working-class
families whose kids come here; at the nearest corner is the busy
boulevard with its auto shops and fast food joints.
<P>
In the principal's office sits Gay Nichols, a member of the school's
parent advisory council, ready to help wherever she can. Her second-grader
Ashley is the youngest of seven, and this sun-weathered mother
has seen the inside of well over a dozen other schools in Broward
County in her time. &quot;This whole staff really cares about
children,&quot; she says. &quot;You feel like you're part of the
team.&quot;
<P>
Moreover, the school has changed dramatically, she asserts, since
principal Larry Katz arrived in 1990 and brought the ideas of
the Coalition of Essential Schools with him. &quot;The children
really love to come to school now, she says. &quot;And you can
see their marks going up every year.&quot;
<P>
Indeed, Oakland Park's delicious secret does lie in student achievement,
as much as it does in the affectionate partnership the members
of this school community openly display toward each other. Their
pride is well founded; in the last four years these children have
shown unheard-of progress by every measure.
<H5><B>Scores Up, Behavior Better</B> </H5>

<P>
&quot;In 1990, the school had suffered a seven-year downward slide
of test scores,&quot; Katz says. &quot;We began a school-wide
conversation about the Coalition's Nine Common Principles and
how we could improve our performance through practicing them here.&quot;
<P>
Improve they did. On the Stanford Achievement Tests in reading
between 1992 and 1994, last year's fifth graders rose from the
36th percentile to the 52nd percentile, moving from six percentage
points below the district average to seven percentage point above
it. In math, their scores leaped from the 40th percentile to the
63rd, while the district average edged from 55th to 59th. Oakland
Park's rising scores are even more impressive for its minority
students; last year's math scores for Hispanic fourth-graders
skyrocketed from the 27th to the 73rd percentile. And on Florida's
new performance-based writing assessment, schoolwide scores also
rose steadily.
<P>
Student behavior has also shown sharp improvement during the same
period. &quot;In my first spring here I saw at least eight fights
every day at dismissal time,&quot; says Katz. Now, even in the
midst of disruptive construction as the school expands, such fighting
is &quot;almost nonexistent,&quot; he observes. Through a consistent
policy of intervention that includes peer mediation as well as
direct consequences for good and bad behavior, discipline referrals
at the school have dropped in half in the past year.
<P>
Teacher Pam Keel serves not only as the Essential School coordinator
here but also as a behavioral specialist in a new state-funded
program. &quot;I am available to help with any behavior problem
on short notice,&quot; she says. &quot;I go into classrooms regularly
and work with groups, and I can also pull kids out for help when
their behavior is getting in the way of academic progress.&quot;
<P>
Focusing on a schoolwide tone of decency, Keel says, has definitely
helped children academically. &quot;We have more time to teach
now that discipline has improved,&quot; she notes. In addition,
several other changes have made it easier for staff to focus on
helping children learn more effectively.
<H5><B>Cross-Grade &quot;Families&quot;</B> </H5>

<P>
The faculty reorganized classes this year, for example, into multi-grade
&quot;families&quot; that include teachers and students from kindergarten
through fourth grade. &quot;It's not just a social system; we
buddy up for all kinds of things,&quot; says Pam Tindall, who
teaches one of the school's nine mixed-age classes of first and
second graders. &quot;My class regularly goes to read and write
with a third-grade class. I can tell it has a big effect on improving
quality - their work takes on much more importance to them.&quot;
<P>
In Mary Terwilleger's fourth-grade classroom, kids at long tables
work together on analyzing the science of weather in written documents.
When they finish, they will troop over to another of the school's
portable classrooms to teach the information to a younger class.
&quot;We approach reading, writing, and math all through the point
of view of science,&quot; says Terwilleger - a curricular innovation
typical of this faculty's commitment to new ways of learning.
<P>
In another nearby classroom, Tracy Spayd coaches 20 fifth-graders
whose academic performance has put them at the risk of dropping
out. &quot;The state gives us extra funding to work intensively
with these children in grades four and five, and we have extended
the program on our own into the third grade,&quot; says principal
Katz. His concern for remediation also extends to families, especially
because Oakland Park is host to a continual stream of immigrants.
(The school's turnover rate is 36 percent.) At tables in the back
of the school auditorium, a dozen mothers are working on learning
English or studying for the high school equivalency exam with
child care provided for their younger children on the premises.
<P>
It typifies the tone of this school that teachers refer to student
exhibitions as &quot;celebrations.&quot; Children openly share
a stake in each other's success - as peer tutors, for example,
or on the morning closed-circuit television show where kids show
off their latest projects. &quot;We consciously focus on making
things cooperative, not competitive, among the children,&quot;
Pam Tindell says. Physical education teacher Tony DiPierro adds,
&quot;They take responsibility for handling challenges among themselves,
even refereeing their own games.&quot;
<P>
In the small lunchroom, teachers compare notes and trade materials
on ideas ranging from puppet shows to photo journals. The faculty
meets regularly in family groups, grade-level groups, and study
groups that discuss Coalition principles. &quot;There are a lot
of avenues for people to express things and come up with new ideas,&quot;
says Pam Keel. &quot;Every teacher has the freedom to use his
or her own style.&quot;
<P>
The outside community has also joined the effort: local banks
and restaurants share information and resources, and even the
shrubs that line the walkways near a maze of portable classrooms
were planted with the help of a nearby center for handicapped
youth.
<P>
Larry Katz points proudly to a recent questionnaire in which 95
percent of Oakland Park third-graders agreed that they liked going
to this school, and 99 percent of fourth graders said they plan
to graduate from high school. In his office and glad to be there,
Gay Nichols looks back on her time as a mother of seven and shakes
her head; these statistics are by no means par for the course.
&quot;You don't find many schools this good,&quot; she says. &quot;I
haven't seen it any better.&quot;<SAMP>Essential School Principles, Grade School Setting</SAMP>

<P>
On the walls of the teachers' lunchroom at Oakland Park hang several
sheets of newsprint, on which the members of the Coalition study
group have made notes from their latest meeting, about how various
Essential School principles showed up in their classroom practice.
A few samples:
<H5><B>Principle 3 (goals apply to all students, means to goals
vary):</B> </H5>

<UL>
<LI>Share materials between grade levels; dialogue among teachers
<LI>Focus on the process to produce a quality product that reflects
a child's ability
<LI>&quot;Over-teaching,&quot; using a variety of methods and
activities to develop concepts
</UL>

<H4><B>Principle 5 (student as worker):</B> </H4>

<UL>
<LI>Children monitor each other's behavior
<LI>Students generate classroom themes and lists of spelling words
from reading
<LI>Teachers answer questions with questions
<LI>Students serve as teachers and coaches to each other
</UL>

<H5><B>Principle 6</B> <B>(demonstration of mastery):</B></H5>

<UL>
<LI>Alternative assessments - plays, puppet shows, student-made
books, models, dioramas, academic fair, murals, charts
<LI>Portfolios
<LI>Science experiments, concept maps, student-made audiotapes
and videotapes
</UL>

<P>

<H3><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools </B>
<P>
<B>Number 19, March 1995</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing areas in which Essential Schools
are demonstrating significant progress toward change using the
Nine Common Principles.</B> 
<P>
<B>Published regularly by the Coalition of Essential Schools,
Box 1969, Brown University, Providence, RI 02912 </B>
<P>
<B>(401) 863-3384</B> 
