<HEAD>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Word 1.0Z">
<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="General Use">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<H1><B>PERFORMANCE </B></H1>

<H3>June, 1995   -   No. 21</H3>
<HR>

<H5><B>Satellite Academy High School</B></H5>

<P>
Chambers Street site
<P>
49-51 Chambers Street
<P>
New York, NY 10007
<P>
(212) 374-1410
<P>
Alan Dichter, Principal
<P>
Alan Baratz, Chambers Street Site Coordinator
<P>
175 students, 14 teachers at Chambers street
<P>
780 students in four Satellite sites
<P>
99% minority students
<P>
New York City alternative school<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>In Schoolwork and in Life, Revision is Key Here</B></CODE>
</H2>

<H3><EM>Once dropout or truant, these city kids commit to one
more try at high school - and their school fosters their new habits
with both academic and personal attention. </EM></H3>

<P>
It's a shabby classroom in a warren of dismal, odd-shaped rooms
converted from old office space. The kids are former dropouts
from city schools, their prior records showing only failure and
truancy. Yet the hour-long discussion that follows around their
table - probing, passionate, and superbly argued - could rival
classes at the most elite schools in the system.
<P>
This is Jay Pecora's history class at the Chambers Street site
of New York City's Satellite Academy, a hard-pressed public alternative
school for kids who need another chance to prove they can make
it through high school. These students are saving themselves from
failure, and they have the ever-present sense that what they think
and read and do can help.
<P>
Gizelle Thorne, 17, describes the spread of the West African religion
of Yoruba to the Caribbean, Brazil, and the United States and
sparks a spirited conversation about how art and religion adapt
to oppressive circumstances. Natalie Santana outlines the Cuban
origins of Santeria, a hybrid between Catholicism and Yoruba.
Prompted by a classmate's question, Aleshia Gibbons dissects the
term &quot;monotheistic cosmology.&quot; Jay Pecora keeps prodding
the class to go another step, make comparisons, reach for evidence
both from outside research and from their own experiences. At
the break the room is electric with the sense of something gained
far beyond this modest topic - something &quot;less&quot; that
is becoming &quot;more.&quot;
<H5><B>The Power of Revision</B> </H5>

<P>
This unusual 780-student school operates in four autonomous sites
in Manhattan, the Bronx, and Brooklyn, with fewer than 200 students
each. One principal, Alan Dichter, provides leadership to all;
and the separate staffs share a common vision, often collaborating
on curriculum, assessment, and teaching strategies.
<P>
Since it joined the Coalition of Essential School several years
ago, the Chambers Street site, near City Hall in downtown Manhattan,
has pushed steadily toward raising the quality of student work
and demonstrating mastery in concrete ways.
<P>
Teachers coach &quot;Learning to Learn&quot; classes - which develop
key academic skills through reading, writing, discussion, and
cooperative group work on substantive academic topics. And this
year, as they helped students assemble materials for the first
round of graduation portfolios, they came to realize the extraordinary
power the concept of revision holds for these students, in both
schoolwork and life.
<P>
&quot;Selecting portfolio pieces gave us a way to reflect in common
with students on the fact that you can correct your errors,&quot;
says Alan Baratz, the school's coordinator who has taught at Satellite
almost since its beginning in the early 1970's. &quot;That can
mean so many things - not only to our kids but to us as a school.&quot;
<P>
Even the multi-step process of applying to Satellite tests a student's
will to revise the attitudes and habits that have led to previous
failures. 'Everybody here has the same story,' declares student
Dana Jones, &quot;Before, we didn't go to school, - now we do.&quot;
<P>
In the daily &quot;Strategy Group&quot; meeting that brings together
students and their adviser for reflection on personal and academic
progress, several of Daria's peers back her up. &quot;I<B> </B>never
spent, a whole semester in high school since I started,&quot;
says Daisy Jefferson, 19. &quot;Other schools tell you, 'I taught
you that, so if you don't get it, too bad.' Here they want <I>to
know </I>that you know it.&quot; In the astronomy course Mike
Hamburg teaches, Daisy says, 'the work is. hard - you have to
really construct it in order to understand.&quot; (The large scale
model of the solar system that her class created now adorns a
school passageway, flanked by posters reporting on solar nebula
theory and other topics.) With help from the teacher and her peers,
Daisy keeps her grades high enough to serve on the school's governing
council. And she aspires to become a doctor: &quot;I'm just taking
a little more time than I was supposed to!&quot;
<P>
A soft-spoken 18-year-old who is reluctant to give his last name,
Daniel &quot;literally played hooky for two years straight&quot;
before coming here. &quot;My attitude has changed completely,&quot;
he says. &quot;I'm here every day, and I expect to graduate in
June and go on to college.&quot;
<P>
Students agree that teachers' involvement contributes more than
any other factor to their own reversal of fortunes. &quot;You
can't learn in a place where they don't know your name,&quot;
Mack Adessa explains. &quot;I am a motivated student when I feel
it's worth it.&quot; Their academic commitment matters just as
much as the faculty's personal attention, Marion Gonzalez asserts.
&quot;Teachers here have more passion for what they teach,&quot;
she says. &quot;And it rubs off! I never used to write; now I'm
writing all the time, and taking writing classes.&quot;
<H5><B>Fewer Courses, but Longer</B> </H5>

<P>
Students here spend much of their four-period day in classes designed
to support their academic turnaround. New students take a term-long
Orientation class and spend two semesters in the interdisciplinary
Learning to Learn course. Those preparing to graduate meet for
&quot;The Future of You.&quot; Just seven other courses fill out
the school's offerings, their topics varying from cell biology
or human rights to Hamlet or the rain forest. But classes run
long and go deep into the issues.
<P>
In a class called Problem Exploration, Frank Casden coaches students
to use strategies for mathematical thinking. &quot;You don't concentrate
on the answer,&quot; says Chakar Jones, huddling with his classmate
Paul Spivey over the financial details of a sports star's contract.
&quot;You guess and check, or you work backwards, or you find
a pattern or make a chart. I didn't really like math before, but
I like this class. You learn more.&quot;
<H5><B>Another Try for Respect</B> </H5>

<P>
Equally important goals at this school are the habits of respect
and tolerance, support and responsibility, honesty and trust.
Student boards issue binding academic tracts to anyone who regularly
fails to show up on time; certificates reward those with good
records. Training in conflict resolution comes with orientation.
To be here at all, students have to want to succeed. &quot;They
know that things did not work out, and they choose personally
to make another try,&quot; says Baratz. Many of those who stick
it out, he notes, later go into social work for a career - and
it's easy to see why.
<P>
We only had two bad fights last year, and that's way better than
most of the schools I've been in,&quot; says the district security
guard routinely assigned by the school district to police these
premises.  She smiles with satisfaction.  &quot;They call this
a school, but I call it a community.&quot;
<H5><B>Up Toward the Future: Satellite Students' Trajectory</B>
</H5>

<P>
Tracking the success of this alternative school depends on a clear
understanding of its students' profile before and after they choose
to attend. Some indicators:
<P>
<B>Students arrive older. </B>On average, Satellite students are
17.5 years old when they are admitted. Though few arrive with
more than a tenth-grade standing, they can expect to complete
Satellite's graduation portfolio requirements in about two years.
With the school's help many also take on concurrent courses or
internships, either in local community colleges, technical cooperative
programs, or experiential learning programs.
<P>
<B>Students have prior attendance problems. </B>About 50 percent
have actually dropped out of school, and another 20 percent have
been truant (absent more than 21 days in a 90-day term) at their
previous schools. Their &quot;mobility rate,&quot; which combines
transfers, dropouts, and other transient situations, stands at
65 percent, compared to 29 percent city-wide. Chambers Street
site attendance has shown steady improvement since joining the
Coalition, with 82 percent of students present each day, based
on data collected with strict attention to accuracy.
<P>
<B>Students have previous academic failure.</B> On average, students
have earned only one credit (of 14 possible) during the year immediately
before entry, and almost never have passed their classes in the
preceding term. About 200 students of the 780 in Satellite's four
sites graduate each year, which places the school sixth in the
city for percentage of total population graduating. Over half
(54 percent) of Satellite students graduate; another 30 percent
move on to graduation equivalency programs or leave the state.
Those who graduate typically move into post-secondary programs,
including two- and four-year city and state colleges and some
private colleges.
<H3><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools</B>

<P>
<B>Number 21, June 1995</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
