<H1><EM>PERFORMANCE</EM> </H1>

<H3>June, 1995 - No. 22</H3>
<HR>

<H5>Souhegan High School</H5>

<P>
P.O. Box 1152
<P>
452 Boston Post Road
<P>
Amherst, NH 03031
<P>
(603) 673-9940
<P>
Robert Mackin, Principal
<P>
700 students grades 9-12
<P>
56 teachers
<P>
80% go on to college
<P>
District school for 2 rural towns<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>Setting New Norms of Achievement and Respect</B></CODE>
</H2>

<H3><EM>This school's habit of thoughtfulness means more than
merely a creditable academic record. Kids and teachers also commit
to &quot;challenge comfortable limits&quot; in respect, tolerance
and trust. </EM></H3>

<P>
A civilization called Kel sprang into being this term at Souhegan
High School in the small town of Amherst, New Hampshire. The brainchild
of Arthur Bruno - who presented it as his Senior Project to a
spellbound panel of peers, teachers, and visitors - Kel bore all
the hallmarks of a newly discovered ancient society- evidence
of a written language, meticulously, reconstructed maps, even
clay fragments bearing alphabetic runes. &quot;Do you believe
in Kel?&quot; Arthur asked his audience, and unanimously they
did.
<P>
It is typical of the remarkable culture of this three-year-old
Essential school that Arthur's academic mentor, classics teacher
Nancy Baker, also serves as the administrative assistant to principal
Bob Mackin. If there is a mold to be broken, Souhegan will find
a way to break it. And although academically Souhegan students
are already rising well above where they were headed just years
earlier (see sidebar), more striking still<I> </I>is their &quot;respect,
trust, and courage&quot; - which is blazoned on the vision statement
in the entry hall, and which informs every endeavor this school
takes on.
<P>
In the classrooms and hallways of this $12 million building whose
windows reveal the green landscape of rural New Hampshire, students
describe a new sense of agency both academic and personal. 'We
are the indigenous people of Souhegan High School!' declaims junior
Courtney Banghart from her place in the collegial arrangement
of desks in Gary Schnakenberg's Global Studies class. Her joke
refers to the course readings, but the point is real: in 1996
Courtney's class will be the first to graduate after four full
years here.
<H5>Mastering the Material </H5>

<P>
&quot;I feel like we're learning more,&quot; says Matt Babineau.
&quot;Working in groups seemed strange at first, but then it forces
you to feel responsible to the group and that makes it matter
more.&quot; Dan Hogan agrees: 'It seems
<P>
like the goal is not so much the grade now as it is mastering
the material.&quot;
<P>
In many ways, the academic experience at Souhegan is designed
expressly to demonstrate Dan's point. Rather than study algebra
and geometry in sequenced year-long courses, for instance, students
enter on a three-year math program that integrates concepts from
both those subjects. A comparable approach, marks the science
curriculum, which spirals through-life science, physical science,
and chemistry. During their first two years students immerse themselves
in American history and culture; thus grounded, they branch into
the study of other world cultures in the junior year humanities
course.
<P>
Students of all ability levels study in mixed classes, with teachers
providing more time, support, and challenge as necessary. Nine
advanced or college-credit courses are open to any student who
chooses them. And all seniors fulfill their English requirement
via a daily minute interdisciplinary seminar combining extensive
reading and writing with, for example, a focus on the scientific,
social, historical, and political aspects of an environmental
issue.
<H5>Demonstrating a Passion </H5>

<P>
In every instance, the preferred method of following student achievement
at Souhegan is public &quot;exhibition of mastery,&quot; and the
required Senior Project stands as the culminating example of that
practice. In this closely tracked 60-hour &quot;personal learning
experience,&quot; each student independently investigates a special
area of interest with the help of a faculty mentor. The last weeks
of school at Souhegan are a continual celebration of their accomplishments,
as each presents the project to an evaluative panel
<P>
The results can be stunning. Working with Northeastern University
research scientists, seniors Holly Leddy and Lesley Baker in 1993
isolated a mutant gene in a nuisance species of brown algae along
the Massachusetts coast. In Souhegan's lab, says mentor Dan Bisaccio,
'they ran 36 electrophoresis gels, which take 24 hours each, then
spent a week in Boston proving their thesis through statistical
analysis.&quot; Despite the real significance of their work, Bisaccio
notes with pride, &quot;they had the integrity to qualify their
results in their report because their sample wasn't large enough.&quot;
<P>
Other projects reveal a similar authenticity. Anne Small's 1994
experiment with Goeldi's monkeys at the New England Science Center
landed her in Hershey, Pennsylvania to present a scientific paper
at the North American Zoological Conference. In a 1995 project
that far outstripped her previous academic record, Rhonda Ledoux
studied the failure to thrive of a three-year-old relative. Kara
Power presented a study of Martha Graham, complete with a monologue
and performance in that dancer's characteristic style. And Rory
Duffield electrified his audience with a hand-made display and
historical review of medieval chain mail and other armor.
<P>
Students with special needs are folded into Souhegan's classes
with the same expectation that they will stretch the limits of
achievement. Junior Amro Diab has a disability that prevents vocal
speech. But in Edorah Frazer's humanities class he used a language
board to perform the &quot;yes-no&quot; refrain of a call-and-response
poem his class wrote, and he has served as place-kicker for several
football games this year. Todd Phoenix came into Souhegan as a
tenth-grader with a failing record; he just completed a senior
project on the sculpture of Michelangelo and Rodin and will attend
the Rhode Island School of Design next fall. &quot;It was just
a matter of recognizing where his, talents lay and running with
it,&quot; says his adviser Sally Houghton, beaming.
<H5>Setting a Personal Tone </H5>

<P>
The tone of decency that marks this school can be laid in large
part to its advisory structure, which groups ten students and
a staff member for 25 minutes daily of academic and personal support.
Advisory groups also elect the 25 students who join 20 teachers
and parents on a community council that sets policy on most internal
school affairs. Among other moves, the students voted to ' eliminate
class rank, moving to a decile indicator system instead.
<P>
In this small-town environment where everybody knows everybody,
the results of fostering such a culture are perhaps particularly
evident. &quot;I see kids who would <I>never </I>have been leaders
in middle school, and because of what we have to do here they
are so much more confident and capable!' says junior Amy Wheeler.
After a musing moment, she adds proudly, 'I'll bet that if you
put any student here in a situation anywhere in the United States,
that person would run out to be a leader.&quot;
<H5>Stacking Up Success: Souhegan Takes Its Measure</H5>

<P>
<B>SAT scores.</B> Before Souhegan opened in 1991, only 59 percent
of students from the towns it serves took the SATs; their mean
score for math was 473 and for verbal 448. By 1994, the third
year of Souhegan's existence, 83 percent took the college-entrance
tests, and their mean scores jumped to 513 in math and 472 in
verbal-levels well above state and national averages.
<P>
<B>College Acceptance.</B> Among New Hampshire's public high schools
with graduating classes of over 35 students, Souhegan ranked second
only to Hanover High School in the percentage of students accepted
to college.
<P>
<B>Recognition.</B> The school was named New Hampshire's 1994
Secondary School of the Year by a consortium of educators and
businesses giving Excellence in Education awards. And in 1995,
Souhegan principal Robert Mackin received the group's Secondary
School Principal of the Year award.
<P>
<B>Academic Challenge.</B> All students must take three years
of demanding math science courses; the school offers no watered-down
&quot;basic&quot; or &quot;general&quot; math courses. More than
half of Souhegan students are taking Advanced Math by junior year,
and fully 16 percent of seniors take calculus. All students take
at least three years of study in a foreign language, and the school's
156 seniors have signed up for a total of 235 Advanced Placement
or college-credit classes.
<P>
<B>Costs and enrollment.</B> Souhegan spends approximately the
same amount as New Hampshire schools of comparable size - $7,221
per pupil in 1995, not counting the mortgage on its $12 million
building. Enrollment is growing, with a dozen tuition students
enrolled and more on the waiting list.
<H3>PERFORMANCE</H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools</B>

<P>
<B>Number 22, June 1995</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing areas in which significant progress
toward change using the Nine Common Principles.</B> 
