<BODY>

<H1><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H1>

<H3>November, 1995 - No. 24</H3>
<HR>

<H5>Mt. Everett Regional School</H5>

<P>
P.O. Box 219
<P>
Sheffield, MA 01257
<P>
(413) 229-8734
<P>
Glenn Devoti, Principal
<P>
Alice Ramsey, Coordinator
<P>
470 students grades 7-12, 46 staff
<P>
30% free or reduced lunch
<P>
71% college acceptance rate
<P>
5 rural towns in Berkshires<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>A Rural School Takes More Time for Learning</B></CODE>
</H2>

<H3><EM>This school doubled the length of classes so students
could do more serious work in fewer subjects each semester. It
has paid off in higher test scores and college attendance rates.
</EM></H3>

<P>
A Chevy pick-up that runs on solar electricity gleams in the spacious
workshop of Mt. Everett Regional School, the names of local merchants
blazoned on its sides. &quot;The kids had heard about the big
New England race,&quot; says Paul O'Brien, who teaches technology
and applied math here. &quot;So four years ago we began converting
this old thing. Now for two years running we've beat out Ivy League
teams to win the race in our category.&quot; He and his students
went to the capital for a ceremony at the U.S. Department of Energy
- and meanwhile, the school district uses the vehicle for maintenance
tasks around town.
<P>
It's the kind of project - original, hybrid, challenging, practical
- that one comes to expect, visiting the classrooms of this newly
built school nestled near the Housatonic River in the Berkshire
Hills of Massachusetts. At every turn, students of all ages are
making things, exploring places, experimenting with new ideas,
and using their community as a place both to learn and to give
of themselves.
<P>
Each morning at 8:05 in the school's television studio, for example,
seniors Erin Hecker and Gary Soldati anchor the live &quot;Morning
Show,&quot; which broadcasts school news and announcements not
only to every classroom but also to cable TV viewers in five surrounding
towns. 'We've been doing this since eighth grade,&quot; Erin says,
adjusting her mike as junior Jeremy Van Deusen readies the camera
to roll. Kids hustle into their places for the spooky opening
Halloween skit, for the sportscast with videos of last night's
soccer victory, for an interview with a visitor to the school.
The show starts on time, a polished, professional production.
<P>
Because this school enrolls students by choice from many towns,
community-building within the school carries special importance.
In Kathy VanOrman's computer skills class, ninth-grader Jeremy
Turner dashes in with a digital camera, connects it to a terminal,
and pulls up on the screen the faces of<B> </B>twelve classmates
he has<B> </B>just snapped in the halls. 'We're putting together
a freshman<B> </B>yearbook,&quot; he says, &quot;with everyone's<B>
</B>names, faces, birthdays, interests - and what they would do
with a million dollars.&quot;
<H5>Time for True Involvement </H5>

<P>
A million dollars matters a lot in this district, whose voters
sent Mt. Everett's budget back to the drawing boards twice before
deep cuts and a groundswell of parent and student support finally
brought passage. Ever since the school began seriously restructuring
in 1988 under a multiyear Carnegie grant, its bold moves toward
deepening student learning have focused community attention on
the ways Mt. Everett differs from business as usual during the
school day. Joining the Coalition of Essential Schools put the
weight of a national reform movement behind changes already begun.
<P>
Mt. Everett's high school students, for example, take only three
courses per term, but each meets for 99 minutes long enough to
conduct a Socratic seminar, finish a scientific experiment, work
out a complex problem whose answer doesn't come easily. All ninth
graders also cycle through a four-quarter &quot;Tools of Learning&quot;
sequence of research and technology skills, including learning
how to use the library, the Internet, and the other computer resources
increasingly available to them.
<P>
The schedule caused controversy at first, prompting worries that
sequential subjects like math would suffer - and in fact, ninth
graders now take math daily all year to ensure continuity. But
the longer classes have allowed these students to try projects
once made impossible by the dictates of the bell.
<P>
In Bob Gauthier's American Government class, ninth graders sprawled
on the floor are testing out their own board games on issues like
the right to citizenship, or cruel and unusual punishment. One
group argues about why gender classification is deemed acceptable
in certain instances and not others. &quot;These things have been
decided so far in individual cases,' Alexis Batacchi explains.
&quot;It's not in the Constitution.&quot;
<P>
Another of Gauthier's classes does 99 minutes of community service
four times weekly in the local hospital, a nursing home, and a
facility for the exceptionally handicapped, and tutors Mt. Everett's
elementary students, who share the same campus.
<P>
Seventh and eighth graders follow a different schedule, but important
classes are rarely less than an hour in length, and grade-level
teaming allows for sustained projects that cross subject-area
lines. The whole eighth grade, for instance, took canoes down
the Housatonic to look through several disciplinary lenses at
how their own environment changes over time. From the mills of
the Industrial Revolution to pollution and economic problems,
they brought the interconnections of politics, literature, and
science very close to home. The unit culminated with students
taking sides in a formal debate on whether to allow a hydroelectric
plant to locate on the river.
<P>
In a six-week unit on 'theory formation,&quot; seventh graders
learn to examine evidence from historical and scientific sources.
Among other texts, they use actual records from the celebrated
1877 murder trial of a black Sheffield resident. &quot;We use
blood and guts as a way to study forensic evidence and teach kids
scientific facts about blood and fiber identification,&quot; says
teacher Bill Gillooly. &quot;But it's also a way to continue the
theme of power, which we've been exploring all year in other subject
areas.&quot;
<H5>A Common Purpose </H5>

<P>
Students and teachers at Mt. Everett now say that their learning
time is much more valuable than it once was. And as the community
makes more use of the school's expanded buildings, their informal
closer looks at what goes on here have fostered a new sense that
the citizenry agrees. In winter the school stays open late so
senior citizens can walk the halls for exercise. A local Equity
theater company stages its shows here, and runs a drama program
for students as part of the deal. A school day care center serves
staff, students, and residents. And parents, students, and teachers
work together on a Coalition of Essential Schools steering committee.
<P>
&quot;My daughter Chelsea is excited to be applying for a place
on the school council,&quot; says parent and council member Dek
Tillett, who has stopped by to see principal Glenn Devoti, &quot;She's
comfortable with adults. She knows from her experience here that
she can learn something. And she also knows she can make a difference.&quot;
<H5>Steady Improvement Follows Changes </H5>

<P>
From 1990 to 1993 University of Massachusetts researcher Dr. Gretchen
Rossman studied the effects of school restructuring on Mt. Everett's
students, and a researcher from the State University of New York
and Columbia University, Dr. Rose Rudnitski, followed with another
report in 1994. Much of their attention centered on whether Mt.
Everett's new long-block semester schedules improved student achievement
and engagement. In addition, Mt. Everett has documented statistics
on student achievement during the same period. Among the findings:
<UL>
<LI>Grades consistently improved and the number of students on
the honor still increased by as much as 30 percentage points per
class.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Scores on the 1995 California Achievement Tests were well
above national norms. Average SAT verbal scores jumped 43 points
from 1991 to 1994, exceeding the national average by 35 points.
Average American College Testing (ACT) composite scores also went
up, exceeding both the national and the state average.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>College acceptance rates went up from 63 percent to 71 percent.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Students, parents, and teachers agreed that studying three
major subjects in long blocks was better for student learning,
providing more varied and interesting learning opportunities.
Four years after the long blocks were introduced, a large majority
of students said they did not find them boring, and in fact were
going deeper into the subject area.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Teachers reported that they knew their students better, making
it easier to focus on individual students' strengths rather than
their weaknesses.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>Attendance remained stable at around 94 percent.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>The number of students visiting the library jumped dramatically,
decreasing only after computers made access to library materials
possible without leaving the classroom.<BR>

</UL>

<H3>PERFORMANCE </H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Reports from the Coalition of Essential Schools</B>

<P>
<B>Number 24, November 1995</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing Essential Schools that are demonstrating
significant progress toward improved student performance using
the Nine Common Principles.</B> 
<P>
<B>Published regularly by the Coalition of Essential Schools Brown
University, Box 1969 Providence, RI 02912</B> 
<P>
<B>(401) 863-3394</B> 
