<H1><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H1>

<H3>November, 1995  -  No.  25                               
                                                             
                                                             
             </H3>
<HR>

<H5><B>Twin Buttes High School</B></H5>

<P>
P.O. Drawer 680
<P>
Zuni, New Mexico 87327
<P>
(505) 782-4446
<P>
Linda Belarde, Principal
<P>
89 students grades 7-12
<P>
9 teachers
<P>
Alternative school on Zuni Indian reservation<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>Taking Something, Giving Something Back</B></CODE>
</H2>

<H3><EM>Students at this small reservation school work for a purpose--they
know their tribal culture's future depends partly on their involvement
and achievements. </EM></H3>

<P>
Richard Brough's history students were talking, and the scholars
gathered in the Albuquerque Hilton for the annual meeting of the
Society for Applied Anthropology were listening hard. These Zuni
students, from Twin Buttes High School had brought them new perspectives
on how native cultures receive those who come to study and record
their ways. In retelling the story of the 19th century ethnologist
Frank Hamilton Cushing's extended stay at the Zuni pueblo, they
became teachers themselves, taking power and dignity from their
position as the coming generation of tribal leaders.
<P>
Three hours' drive from Albuquerque through the stunning desert
landscape of red rock and mesas, this small alternative school
is helping young people turn their lives and their futures toward
a new vision. Most come to the low cinder-block building that
houses Twin Buttes because they resist the conventional high school
scene in Zuni, a reservation of 10,000 people that boasts the
nation's first Native American school district. They have little
academic success behind them; many already have children of their
own. But by graduation they have become active participants in
their own education, connected in direct and important ways to
their community's well-being.
<H5><B>School Work that Matters</B> </H5>

<P>
Like the American History class that presented Cushing's work
to the anthropological experts, students at this Essential school
come to expect their school work to matter to the outside world.
In the Southwest Studies class led by Craig Birrell and Richard
Brough, they document damage to ancient petroglyphs on nearby
outcroppings for archaeologists' records. By studying, the ruins
of ancient settlements they learn about their Paleo-Indian ancestors,
then teach that history, science, and folklore to Zuni's elementary
school students. They volunteer at the Zuni Museum, and are planning
a guide service for tourists. And they help write and publish
a new local newspaper called the <I>Shiwi Messenger,</I> which
has fast become a major forum for news and public expression.
<P>
&quot;We have so many archaeological and historic sites right
here,' says principal Linda Belarde, who helped start Twin Buttes
in 1983. &quot;Kids can go to the actual spot where Indians made
the first contact with Spaniards; they can climb up the steep
bluff of Dowa Yalanne Mountain, where the Zunis lived for twelve
years during the 17th century Pueblo Revolt.&quot; Learning from
such field experiences brings adventure into academic pursuits
like reading, writing, and analyzing data, she says. One class
travels yearly to the Grand Canyon to compare theories of origin
from myth and other students have won scholarships to Colorado's
prestigious Crow Canyon Field School.
<P>
Using a substantial settlement in a land claim against the government,
the tribe has developed a number of resource management programs,
and many Twin Buttes students now work in the field as interns
&quot;The Zuni Conservation Project uses the latest technology
as well as traditional techniques,' says science teacher Kate
Brown. &quot;It's a very rich environment for my students.&quot;
Students Malcolm Chavez and DeVonna Niiha, for example, helped
develop springs to attract bear and other wildlife. Allison Wallace
tracked coyote and deer, then graphed patterns to help officials
decide which areas to open for hunting.
<P>
To earn the service learning credit Twin Buttes requires for graduation,
other students have cleaned up the graffiti that mars the reservation's
public places, helped the Fish and Game Department restore picnic
areas and trails, worked on the reservation's research and rescue
team, and visited with the elderly in a home health care program.
&quot;I like to hear the old stories,&quot; says Antoinette Escobar,
who at first wanted to drop out of school when she became pregnant
but instead graduated in 1995 as salutatorian of her class.
<P>
After two years of academic foundering, Stephanie Kanteena, 18,
began working with tribal leaders last year to open a teen center.
After a summer spent helping the local museum create traditional
Zuni &quot;waffle gardens,&quot; she says, &quot;School isn't
boring anymore. I'm very happy with the classes I'm taking.&quot;
<H5><B>Dropouts Down, Scores Up</B> </H5>

<P>
Not only are Twin Buttes students learning more and better, but
their enjoyment makes learning a habit they wan to continue after
graduation. Dropping out of high school has been a pervasive problem
on this reservation, where close to half of the students failed
to finish as recently as the 1980's. But since 1991, when Twin
Buttes first began adopting Essential School beliefs, this school's
dropout rate has decreased from 36 to 16 percent. &quot;If we
can get them to the middle of the tenth grade year, we can usually
keep them, says Linda Belarde.
<P>
Indeed, in the last few years students' state achievement test
scores in reading, writing, and math have leapt considerably between
eleventh and twelfth grades. All the school's sophomores pass
the state's reading and writing competency exams, and all its
seniors graduate with a high school diploma (not a &quot;certificate
of attendance&quot;).
<P>
The Essential School principle calling for a &quot;tone of decency&quot;
drives much of the school's emphasis on attendance. &quot;Our
biggest problem is kids who ditch school after showing up for
half a day,&quot; Belarde says. &quot;Obviously, creating programs
that pull and interest them is one solution.&quot; Gang activity
and violence are not problems at the school and although drug
and alcohol abuse is pervasive in the community, Belarde says,
&quot;this year we have had only a few complaints here at school.&quot;
<P>
Students who have babies are encouraged to continue in school,
and 15 young mothers at Twin Buttes bring their infants to the
school's day care center and help with child while they work toward
graduation. &quot;Some of our highest achieving students are teen
parents who are able to stay in school,&quot; observes Belarde.
<P>
The path toward college and career is often unconventional as
well, yet Twin Buttes seems to lay a solid basis for continuing
an education eventually. &quot;Many of our graduates start at
the state university in Gallup and then take some time at home,&quot;
Belarde says. &quot;Later they go to work or start job training,
either in Gallup or in the extension program here at Zuni.&quot;
Twin Buttes's wing of its building adjoins the University of New
Mexico's extension school and construction technology program,
the Zuni Wellness Center, an arts cooperative that grew out of
a Twin Buttes art class, and adult education classes-ample evidence
that there is life after high school.
<P>
Twin Buttes makes a particular effort to form bonds between adults
and young people that transcend the teacher-student role. The
whole school participated, for instance, in a challenge activity
where mostly blindfolded teachers and students traversed a perilous
canyon with only each other as guides. The trip could be seen
as metaphor; these students choose risk and new direction every
day in their education here. And every day, it seems, they also
give something back enriching their lives, and their community,
well beyond graduation.
<H5><B>Quality of Education Brings Awards to Twin Buttes</B> 
</H5>

<UL>
<LI>In its eighth year, the school's award-winning Healthy Children
day care program uses Federal, state, and district funds to help
pregnant teen-agers stay in school. (New Mexico leads the nation
in the percentage of teen births, and this county leads the state.)
Mini-buses transport the young mothers and children to school;
the Women, Infants, and Children (WIC) nutrition program contributes
a healthy start; and young parents and relatives help with day
care, learning home economics skills and sharing the lunch hour
with their youngsters.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>In a self-contained classroom for students with severe physical
and mental impairments, Twin Buttes began an award-winning special
education program to prepare participants for employment. The
program expanded to become a major community resource, including
a sheltered workshop and transition program and Zuni Entrepreneurial
Enterprises, which provides recycling, public transportation,
and food concessions at the local hospital.
</UL>

<UL>
<LI>One student service learning project developed into a greenhouse
now being built on the Twin Buttes grounds. Students designed
the greenhouse and wrote a proposal for its construction; a grant
from the state's Indian Education Center for Excellence provided
help with supplies, materials, and instruction.
</UL>

<P>

<H3><B>PERFORMANCE</B> </H3>

<P>
<B>Progress Report from the Coalition of Essential Schools</B>

<P>
<B>Number 25, November 1995</B> 
<P>
<B>Editor: Kathleen Cushman</B> 
<P>
<B>A continuing series describing Essential Schools that are demonstrating
significant progress toward improved student performance using
the Nine Common Principles. </B>
<P>
<B>Published regularly by the Coalition of Essential Schools,
Brown University, Box 1969, Providence, RI 02912 </B>
<P>
<B>(401) 863-3384</B> 
</BODY>

