<BODY>

<H1>PERFORMANCE </H1>

<H3>December, 1995 - No. 26</H3>
<HR>

<H5>Academy for the Middle Years (AMY - Northwest) </H5>

<P>
7500 Germantown Avenue
<P>
Philadelphia, PA 19119
<P>
(215) 248-6664
<P>
Holly Perry, Principal
<P>
240 students grades 6-8, 18 staff
<P>
70% minority students
<P>
67% free or reduced-price lunch
<P>
Alternative district middle school<HR>

<H2><CODE><B>Making Students Part of Setting Standards</B></CODE>
</H2>

<H3><EM>Students in this urban middle school are readying themselves
to deal thoughtfully and decently with the diverse, impersonal,
and sometimes violent world ahead. </EM></H3>

<P>
Lana Gold's Humanities class at the Academy for the Middle Years
(AMY) starts the morning wired, in the way that only a roomful
of sixth and seventh graders can be. As they pop up and down chattering
from their circle of desks, it's hard to imagine them maintaining
order at all, much less handling the young adult literature on
the blackboard's assignment list. But when their classmate Jentia
Small, 12, takes over as facilitator at a signal from the teacher,
they fall attentively silent. For the next hour, this diverse
group of kids from neighborhoods all over Philadelphia will talk
about what they are experiencing, reading, and writing with a
passion that shows the deep links this Essential school has forged
between students' lives and the world of learning.
<P>
A hush greets one young writer as she reads a description of her
fearsome grandfather, who scowls at her friends and squashes roaches
mercilessly with bare, bunioned feet. Is it all right to be &quot;nasty,&quot;
her classmates debate among themselves, when you're trying to
write about reality? Later, Carmen Williams interrupts to ask
urgently, 'Do souls ever die?&quot;
<P>
These are children who speak casually about life in the urban
danger zone: youngsters shot dead by random gunfire, fragmented
families, addicts on corners. They listen to each other's writing
and give back their questions with utter attention and respect.
And many of them ride school buses an hour and a half each way
to be in a school where that is possible. 'My neighborhood school
is trouble,&quot; Carmen says, to explain the grueling commute.
&quot;Here I have my friends.'
<P>
AMY works hard to establish its tone of decency; students meet
weekly in small groups for social and academic guidance, and disciplinary
suspensions are rare. The Philadelphia Inquirer has cited the
school as one of four middle schools in the city with a nonviolent
atmosphere; daily attendance averages 93 percent.
<P>
AMY has no academic entrance requirements; as a magnet school
in the city's desegregation effort, it admits students by lottery
to reflect the city's racial composition. Started by parents in
the mid-1970s as a public alternatives to neighborhood middle
schools, the school has moved four times in the last decade. The
current location, on a former college campus in the city's residential
northwest Mt. Airy section, is still not secure from reassignment.
<P>
Yet despite frequent upheavals, families, students, and faculty
here remain fiercely attached to their school. Principal Hofly
Perry can only remember one student in eleven years who voluntarily
withdrew, and even in the face of early retirement incentives,
only one teacher position has opened in the last several years.
A vigorous Home and School Association explicitly aims to support
the implementation of Essential School ideas and to offer continual
feedback and support. The president of that group, Linnie Jones,
has sent a son and a granddaughter to AMY.
<H5><B>Preparing for Choices Ahead</B> </H5>

<P>
Jones, in fact, was among a group of students, parents, and alumni
who took part in an unusual ethnographic study of the school over
the last several years. Working with researchers from the University
of Pennsylvania and the nonprofit group Research for Action, they
conducted focus groups and interviews, analyzed transcripts, and
shadowed students through the school day, collecting qualitative
data on how well the school prepared its graduates for what lay
ahead.
<P>
In ninth grade, for example, almost all AMY graduates attend the
high schools of their choice-typically either the smaller, more
demanding academic or performing arts magnet schools, or small
learning communities within the city's comprehensive high schools.
The research project's alumni focus groups, which were balanced
by gender, race, and previous achievement, revealed that students
went on to cope extraordinarily well with the challenges of city
high schools and, eventually, college.
<P>
&quot;They know how to work with peers from many different neighborhoods
and cultures,' says Perry. &quot;They can handle potentially violent
situations in nonviolent ways. They don't like the impersonal
style of a big high school, but they know how to get around it
in a mature way.&quot; One returning graduate told Perry, years
later, that only after she got to college did her AMY education
bear the most fruit. &quot;We help them find their voice,&quot;
observes Lana Gold.
<H5><B>Setting Shared Standards</B> </H5>

<P>
The school's insistence that student voices be heard shows up
equally in the classrooms. &quot;If we let kids into the conversation
about what good work looks like,' says Holly Perry, &quot;they
start to internalize high standards.&quot; AMY keeps track of
student progress using performance rubrics and narrative evaluations,
with results evident in every class.
<P>
In Gene Campher's social studies class, students prepare reports
on what their own lives would be like if they lived in a particular
province of Canada, then create brochures presenting various regions.
But first, they help come up with a rubric that identifies the
qualities of good work from previous projects. By the time they
complete the Canada project, they have assessed their own work
and that of their peers, and the teacher has added his own ratings
and comments. Expectations are specific and concrete, so these
students learn just how their work could improve.
<P>
Science teacher Katie Myles hands back portfolios filled with
a term's work to a class teeming with excitement. Every piece
in the folder has a rubric attached, assessing everything from
written and oral presentation to class behavior and work habits.
'It's worth the extra time when you see the children realize what
it takes to do well,&quot; she says. &quot;They stop believing
you're taking away something they deserve, and start to work for
it.&quot;
<P>
Classes put a high value on thoughtfulness, often using Socratic
seminars and follow-up writing to encourage deeper levels of discourse.
At his computer terminal in Chris O'Neill's class, Anthony Minnick
pecks out his opinion of Ron Mitchell, a Bucks County student
who took his school to court when it objected to his spiky punk
hair style. &quot;Well, he has a right to have his hair,' Anthony
says. &quot;It's freedom of speech; the Constitution says so.&quot;
Still, the school's arguments about safety sway him in the other
direction. He stares at the screen, torn between two points of
view. &quot;I think he has to change the hair,&quot; he finally
says.
<P>
In the small library, media specialist Janet Malloy puts up students'
timelines of their personal histories. A generalist, she often
helps with classroom projects and conducts Socratic seminars with
students. AMY has no &quot;outsiders'; all teachers, including
special education staff, work on teams with around 80 students,
and kids are mixed in vertical age groups that fully include those
with learning differences.
<P>
Around two each afternoon, an eerie silence descends on AMY's
halls, when everyone in the school stops for 35 minutes of sustained
silent reading. The cauldron of energy subsides; something profound
and palpable stirs in the air instead. The next idea, the next
day, the next generation is taking shape; and everyone here has
a part to play in it.
<H5><B>A Sense of Community Shows Academic Results</B> </H5>

<P>
&#183; Attendance holds steady at 93 percent, even though many
students must travel well over an hour to get to school. On one
recent early-release day, attendance was 98 percent.
<P>
&#183; The local press has called AMY one of the city's safest
middle schools, with the lowest incidence of disciplinary referrals
and suspensions.
<P>
&#183; At an average of 22 students, class size is far smaller
than in the typical city school. All of AMY's special education
students are included in regular classrooms, which allows special
Ed teachers to become full partners with the school's teaching
teams, often contributing special expertise in areas like computers
or expressive arts.
<P>
&#183; Since the daily 35-minute Sustained Silent Reading (SSR)
period began in 1994, scores on the Gates-McGinitie Reading Level
Inventory test increased by at least one grade level in 58 percent
of sixth- andseventh-grade students, and over a quarter of those
jumped between two and four grade levels. Thirty-two percent of
eighth-graders' scores went up a grade level, with almost ten
percent of those jumping several levels.
<P>
&#183; On citywide reading tests, AMY students consistently score
better than students in other Philadelphia schools.
<H3>PERFORMANCE </H3>

