<html><head><title>CES: Background: The Coalition Approach to School Change</title></head><body><h1><center>The Coalition Approach to School Change: An Introduction</center></h1>No two good schools are ever quite alike. A good school is the special creation of its own community -- its teachers and students, parents, counselors and administrators. There is no such thing as a distinct, detailed blueprint or model for a fine school. There is no concrete prescription for a good school which can be applied to bring success to any other school. <p>However, good schools do share powerful guiding ideas, principles that are widely accepted even as they take different shapes in practice when people put them to work in their own settings from day to day. It is these shared ideas of what makes good schools that undergirds the Coalition of Essential Schools. The Coaliton is our nation's largest and farthest-reaching school reform effort, and its nine Common Principles serve as guidelines for schools that want to rethink their approach to teaching and learning. Though each Coalition school devises its own individual structures and practices, they share in common the principles they work to apply.<p>The Coalition of Essential Schools was born out of the research of educator and school reform leader Theodore R. Sizer. He distilled the findings of his Study of High Schools (1979-84) into five imperatives for better schools, fleshed out in Sizer's book, Horace's Compromise: The Dilemma of the American High School (Houghton Mifflin, 1984). In 1984, the Coalition was established at Brown University in Providence, Rhode Island, and 12 schools took up the challenge of putting Sizer's ideas into practice to become the first Essential Schools. Drawing on their experiences, Sizer expanded his imperatives for better schools and developed what is now the Coalition's nine Common Principles.<p>Initially, Sizer and his staff worked closely and directly in a mentoring relationship with Coalition member schools to help them navigate the redesign process. The national cry for a better system of education led other schools to explore the Essential School approach until, by 1988, the Coalition's small, university-based staff was reaching out to work with 55 different schools across the country. However, as Coalition membership continued not only to grow, but to diversify across the United States, the Coalition restructured and regionalized its support for schools in the redesign process. <p>Today, Essential School activity in some locales has matured to a level of autonomy. As they witness the successes of others, and as educational reform in general continues to be a national priority, more and more schools are exploring the Coalition. To give these fledglings the support they need, the Coalition is organizing resource centers where experienced practitioners-in-the-field and veteran member schools might work together to support others in their locales.<p>As direct support for Essential Schools becomes regionalized and redistributed among members, the role of the Coalition at Brown is shifting from mentor to facilitator. The work is proceeding alongseveral avenues designed to support the Essential School reform effort in its entirety:<p><dl>	<dd>Explore the concepts about school change and the Coalition's nine Common Principles through research projects which position the Coalition at the fault-line between theory and practice.<p>	<dd>Facilitate reform by focusing effort on those places which show the most promise of serving as both helpmates and examples for others.<p>	<dd>Invest in people who will build the capacity of the Coalition to support school reform via local and regional efforts, particularly through development of the Coalition's corps of practitioners-in-the-field.<p>	<dd>Challenge policymakers to create a climate which favors school change by bringing the work of Essential Schools beyond the classroom and introducing it to members of the larger community.<p>	<dd>Influence the national discourse about school change by continuing to explore the issues of Essential School reform and communicate them via the media and publications which link the Coalition of Essential Schools to its members and to the public.</dl><p><hr><a href = "backgrou.htm">Return to the Background page</a><br></body></html>
