<html><head><title>CES: Membership: General Criteria for Membership</title></head><body bgcolor=#ffffff><hr><h1><center>General  Criteria For Membership</center></h1><p><hr>Inquiries from interested schools are welcome. Memberschools in the Coalition are selected with the followingcriteria in mind:<ol><li><b>Diversity is important</b>:  The Coalition will beenriched by the association of differing schools-urban, suburban and rural; public, independentand parochial; east, west, south and north; smalland large; with a variety of student bodies andcommunities. This diversity will strengthen thevalidity of those aspects of our work whichappear to succeed.<p><li><b>Agreement with the Common Principles</b> of theCoalition must be unequivocally demonstrated by   the faculty of the school. This does not mean thatthese Principles are not changeable over time;indeed, the Coalition schools' experimentationwill surely lead to adaptations. Nor does it meanthat schools have to emphasize all equally.What it does mean, however, is that there is asecure, if simple, common platform upon which ourpartnership rests.<p><li> <b>Moral, professional and financial support</b> is acrucial prerequisite to proceeding with theinevitably difficult work that flows from theCommon Principles. Again, nothing is perfectlysure in this life; governing boards change, moneydries up or becomes available, leaders depart andothers arrive. Yet we seek as firm and specific acommitment from governing authorities as isfeasible and for blocks of years rather than oneyear at a time.<p><li><b>Committed leaders and staffs</b> at each schoolare essential to the success of this endeavor -people interested in the project and, if skeptical,constructively so. Reluctant folk make pooradventurers.<p><li>  <b>The school agrees to share information</b> aboutits work with the Central Staff, otherCoalition schools, and interested visitors.This conversation is vital to our efforts; thereforeit is important to maintain sustained communi-cation. Member schools send the Central Staffinformation about the progress of their Essentialprogram which may include the following: theschool schedule, minutes from meetings whereCoalition matters were discussed, sample lessons,examples of exhibitions of mastery.<p><li>  <b>The school agrees to undergo a self-evaluation</b>every three years, which will include hostinga visiting committee.The school will provide for travel and lodging fora small visiting committee for a few days. Also,the school will allow for members of its own staffto travel to other schools as part of a visitingcommittee. The Central Staff as well as ourmember schools feel that such visits are vital inorder for a meaningful dialogue to take place bothwithin the school, and between the school andthe Central Staff.<p><li>  The school must demonstrate that it hasincluded <b>sufficient funds in its budget</b> for staffdevelopment and planning within the school,evaluation team visits, and travel expensesincurred for participation at Coalitionactivities.The school needs to show that it will be able tofund Coalition activities, particularly thoseexpenses associated with attendance at symposiaand workshops. Such costs will include travel,room, board, and conference fees. Symposia andworkshops are self-supporting. Fees will reflectthe actual costs of developing these conferences.<p></ol>For additional information, please contact:<br>Coalition of Essential Schools<br>Box 1969, Brown University<br>Providence, RI  02912<p><hr><p><a href = "membersh.htm">Return to the Membership page</a><p></body></html>
