<html> <head> <title>CES: Publications: Outside Articles: "ReformingSchools"</title></head><body><hr><h1><center>Reforming Schools: Ted Sizer does HighSchool</center></h1><hr><h3><center>by Doug Riggs<br> in The Rhode Islander Magazine,January 2, 1994<p><i>Special thanks to theProvidence Journal-Bulletin, for its permission toreproduce this article here.</i></center></h3><hr>The scene is a teacher's dream.  A classroom deep within thick,sheltering walls, beyond the reach of bells, intercoms, attendancesheets, and other distractions. Two dozen chairs form a democraticcircle, 23 of them occupied by bright, eager students. <p>Ted Sizer, seated on the 24th, is in his element.<p>"Anyone have any comments on the last two lectures?" he asks.<p>A dozen hands shoot up.  He smiles in anticipation.  Any weariness hemay have felt after a day of administrative chores is banished.<p>Theodore R. Sizer, 61, former dean of the Harvard Graduate School ofEducation, former headmaster of the prestigious Phillips Academy,Andover, former chairman of Brown's education department, leader ofthe foremost national effort to reform our high schools, is about toexercise the greatest privilege he knows He is about to teach.<p>It is something that has always been in his blood -- and remains unalterably on hisschedule, twice a week, despite the demands of his job as chairman ofthe Coalition of Essential Schools, and the even greater demands to come.<p>Nearly 700 public and private high schools across the country have joinedthe Coalition since Sizer founded it, here on the Brown campus, nearly a decadeago.  Each has pledged to leave the safe harbor of teaching-as-usual forthe shoreless sea of Reform, with Sizer as chief navigator.<p>Now he is taking the helm of an even more ambitious effort.  It startedlast October when an anonymous donor put up $5 million to found the National Institute for School Reform, an effort to bridge what Sizercalls "the fault line between theory and practice," with Sizer incharge.<p>Then, three weeks ago, Sizer was at the White House to receive a stunning Christmas present from philanthropist Walter H. Annenberg: Sizer's Institute(immediately renamed the Annenberg Institute) is getting $50 millionto carry on its work, which will include advising Annenberg on how to spendthe remainder of his $500 million "Annenberg Challenge," the largest singlegift even made to American public education.<p>Despite these obvious signs of a growing national here in this classroom,in the basement of the Salomon Center for Teaching on Brown's maincampus, Brown's most illustrious professor of education gets no respectat all.  A lot of affection, but no visible respect.  He loves it.<p><hr>"What if kids reach that point and they haven't been turned on towhatever it is that is going to turn them on?" asks a young woman on hisright, as the others wait their turn.<p>All are student-teachers, most of them graduate students, learning theirprofession by assisting Sizer with his only undergraduate class, Education100.  The young woman with the question is still in high dudgeon over an idea Sizer advanced earlier: that kids be required to go to school onlyuntil they have mastered certain basic skills; from then on, attendancewould be voluntary.<p>"Suppose they reach that level by age fourteen but they have never learnedabout genetics, or, I don't know, nineteenth-century British poetry,"the student-teacher says.  "Are we going to lose the specialists?Are we going to have one big mushy-yucky society with people who know howto read but don't have the beauty of the arts or the complexities of the sciences?"<p>"Who decides which arts are beautiful?" Sizer counters.<p>"Well, obviously that's a problem, but can't we at least--"<p>"No, no, no; don't slide off it.  It's a fundamental problem."<p>"I know that," says the student, her dudgeon sinking rapidly.<p>"You're implying that the <i>state</i>decides that Wordsworth makessense in Fox Point," Sizer says.<p>"No, I'm saying that people will have to be exposed to <i>something</i>--"<p>"My argument is I don't want you to decide for my kid, beyond basicliteracy, what he's going to read," Sizer adds.<p>The student persists: "I'm not saying that I want them necessarily to get[to a certain level], but I want them at least to be <i>exposed</i to--"<p>"I do too!  I want that desperately.  And I think the political process, on issues of this importance, is not the vehicle."<p><hr>Sizer's ideas (which are not necessarily Coalition doctrine, if, indeed,the choice-oriented Coalition can be said to <i>have</i> a doctrine)have been prompting discussion and debate around the country sincethe publication of his first "Horace" book, <i>Horace's Compromise: The Dilemma of the American High School</i> (Houghton Mifflin).<p>That was in 1984, the year George "Big Brother is watching you" Orwellchose (in 1948) as the title for his nightmare vision of a societybased on mind-numbing conformity.<p>The world didn't turn out that way, thanks in part to people likeSizer, but 1984 must have been a pretty numbing year for him anyway.During those 12 months he a) published the book, b) became chairmanof Brown's education department, and c) founded the Coalition ofEssential Schools.<p><i>Horace's Compromise</i> was Sizer's unconventional report on a study of American high schools that he had directed from 1975 to1984.  He spent two of those years visiting 50 schools throughout thecountry, talking with the kids, the teachers, the administrators.  Hisabsorbing and disturbing book is a semi-journalistic, semi-fictionaldistillation of those encounters.<p>Sizer's Horace is a composite figure, a 53-year-old high school Englishteacher, 28-year classroom veteran, "proud, respected, and committedto his practice."  In actuality, he doesn't exist.  In truth, he exists in nearly every high school in America.<p>It is through Horace, and the fictionalized-but-real compromises he mustmake -- with his students, his colleagues, his family, the clock, hisself-respect -- that Sizer reveals, more compellingly than the blizzard of data-laden studies that emerged at about that time, the deepmalaise of the American high school.<p>The book was a resounding call to dismantle our rigid, lock-step model of secondary education in favor of a less-structured, performance-centered model.  "That students differ may be inconvenient," he wrote,"but it is inescapable."<p><i>Horace's Compromise</i> was an immediate hit.<p>"In addition to his roaming-the-halls insights, this book offers [a] far-reaching blueprint for change," wrote Newsweek's reviewer.The Washington Post declared, "The agenda for this decade should be a long-overdue educational renewal.  People like Sizer...deserve a placein the thick of it."<p>Whether that last sentiment was a blessing or a curse is problematic.  Butit turned out to be good prophecy.<p><hr>When he founded the Coalition, Sizer saw it as a modest experiment in school redesign, nothing more.  He and two colleagues signed up a dozedwilling and demographically diverse public and private schools, andset to work trying to nudge them into new and better shapes fromwithin, as Horace would have.<p>Eventually, the "Essential Schools" evolved nine "common principles,"or goals, to which all Coalition schools must pledge allegiance.  Some of the goals sound as warm and fuzzy as most such statements:"The school should focus on helping adolescents learn to use their minds well..."  Others are jarringly specific: "No teacher shouldhave direct responsibility for more than 80 students."<p>Broadly speaking, the principles aim to a) banish the distractionsthat keep many schools from focusing on what happens in class, b) make it possible for teachers to know their students as individuals andteach them accordingly, and c) insist that students actuallylearn before they graduate.  Individually, the principles seem harmlessenough.  Taken together, they spell revolution.<p>They turn high schools upside down, giving far more responsibilityto teachers and students, far less to so-called policy makers.  Theyinsist on mastery of a limited number of subjects, rather than exposure to many.  They insist that students advance not according totime spent or credits earned, but only  after they havedemonstrated their grasp of a subject, by means of an individual"exhibition."<p>They made a lost of people very uncomfortable.<p>But somehow the word got around that exciting things were happeningin those schools; others began knocking at the Coalition's door.By the end of the second year, 1985, the roster had grownt0 31; a year later, to 54.  The experiment had become a movement.<p>Now, as it enters its 10th year, the Coalition's Providence-based staffalone has grown to 45, the budget is $9 million, and there's no endin sight.  Its Fall Forum, in Louisville, attracted 2,200 partisans, who gave Sizer a standing ovation.  And he has written another book:<i>Horace's School: Redesigning the American High School</i> (HoughtonMifflin, 1992).  The movement has become an institution.<p>Even now, however, it is difficult to describe exactly what an"Essential School" is.  Each is pledged to work toward realizing the ninecommon principles.  That often involves jettisoning such traditionalprops as grade levels, 45-minute periods, final exams -- and even teaching, per se (Principle Five urges "coaching" instead).<p>But each school is encouraged to "articulate" the principles in its own wayand at its own pace.  Few have done so completely; some have barelyscratched the surface.  After 10 years, the Coalition of EssentialSchools remains a work in progress.<p><hr>Ted Sizer is seated behind a simple wooden schoolmaster's desk in hisoffice at 1 Davol Square -- the kind of desk Harace might use.  Visitors have been bringing him their problems all morning, including some that have no possiblebearing on the work of the Coalition.  Each person gets his completeattention and apparent respect.  (Family members say he grants the samerespectful attention to little children, whose ideas he solicits as if they possess rare insights -- which he knows they do.)<p>He laughs easily, turning anxiety into rapport.  Often he steers the conversation onto an unexpected path, at the end of which one can glimpsea solution.  But there are no laughs when he describes what is wrongwith American education.  No easy solutions, either.<p>"It produces kids with docile minds.  They are not in he habit ofthinking hard about important things.  And that's a terriblyimportant habit in a democracy.  If the testing schemes give no creditto creativity and thoughtful analysis, just regurgitation, then thesystem is set up to create a mindless citizenry.  And that scares me.<p>"For me, the symbol of it all is the lottery.  The hypocrisy hereis absolutely laughable: We're going to have lotteries to raise moneyfor public education?  Well, lotteries depend on a citizenry thatdoesn't know any math!"<p>High schools, he says, have changed remarkably little since 1900.  "Even in the face of well-intentioned, common-sense criticism, they freezeinto the old ways and hang on for dear life.  And the more they hang on to things that do not stand the challenge of even rudimentarycommon sense, the more they lose their credibility.<p>"It's easier now than it was to talk about ambitious changes withoutbeing written off as a kook and a radical," he acknowledges, but"public confidence in public education continues to erode, fed byendless reports and criticism and finger pointing."<p>Meanwhile, a lot of the conditions that can make public education little morethan a cruel joke are largely beyond the schools' control.<p>"Various kinds of supporting agencies that make growing up tolerableare eroding," Sizer says.  "And, you know, there's gunfire insidethe schools.  There are schools with very hungry children, schools with children with no addresses.  If you don't know if you're going toeat, or if you are going to sleep anywhere that's safe, it takes yourmind off algebra."<p><hr>As the clock reaches 1:45 p.m., Sizer politely but firmly ushers a visitor out and closes the door.  It is time for one last review ofhis lecture notes before his 2:30 class.  Although he gave up thechairmanship of Brown's education department several years ago, his staffers say that nothing -- <i>nothing</i> -- interfereswith his teaching.<p>Shortly after 2 p.m., as he does every Tuesday and Thursday, he leaveshis downtown office to walk the mile or so to campus, alone.  Thewalk helps him to clear his head, he says, and focus on the important task to come.  One imagines him mentally shedding hismasks and titles, one every few steps -- Historian, Dean, Headmaster,Researcher, Author, Reformer, Administrator -- until only one is left, the one that gives meaning to all the others: Teacher.<p>His father was a teacher: art history, at Yale.  Ted was the youngestof six children, and the only boy.<p>"Ted and I grew up in Bethany, Connecticut, during the war, and itwas a magical time," recalls the only sister near Ted's age, AliceWarner, of Lexington, Massachusetts.<p>"The fact that one grows up with deprivations does not necessarilymean one does not have a happy childhood," she adds.  "I think Tedand I had a completely happy childhood.  There was stability --something we don't have anymore."<p>Those were simpler times, both say, dominated by the war.  Their dadand brothers-in-law were all in it.<p>"I daily cut the maps out of the New York Times and tracked themovement of the armies," Sizer says. "To this day, I can identifyWorld War II aircraft by silhouette.  I remember the names of currentlyirrelevant places where battles were fought.<p>"It was for a lot of people -- even very young ones, like I was --a very defining influence.  You didn't go anywhere, between gasrationing and living on a sort of a farm, which my mother kept going -- a very large vegetable garden that grew all the potatoes the whole family ate for a year.  Endless canning of beans...<p>"All of us were routinely read to every night. <i>Routinely.</i>  I just assumed that's what you did.  How many kids are read to every night now?  The hours my mother must have put into the career ofmothering -- amazing."<p>"Right was right and wrong was wrong," adds his sister, "and I don't think either of us ever knew what guilt meant."<p>Ted was an indifferent student, he says, at the private Foote School, then as now closely tied to Yale.  He went on to Yale, where he enrolled in his father's large lecture course under a pseudonym,so his dad wouldn't find out.  ("As I remember, he didn't get a terribly good grade," his sister snitches.)<p>Sizer didn't think seriously teaching until he entered the Army,during the Korean War.  He was barely 21 when the Army told him toteach a bunch of recruits -- mostly Puerto Rican kids from NewYork -- how to become a firing battery for a light howitzer:<p>"That was quite a challenge.  They didn't say, You're too young; they said,Do it.  I learned a lot in the Army: Get the incentives right.  Anddon't give people excuses for not doing things before they are askedto do it: 'I don't care if you're a semi-literate Puerto Rican; you'rea good person.  Pull up your socks and learn how to do a serioussurvey.  So you don't know any mathematics?  Here's the book.  Let'sgo on with it.' It was a good experience."<p>After the war he got his M.A.T. (Master of Arts in Teaching) degreeat Harvard, and wound up in Australia for his first teaching job.  The British-oriented schools there struck him as quite bizarre:<p>"Every boy on Thursday came to school in uniform with his rifle, which was kept at home; they were still fighting the Second World War.  Weassembled outside in our black gowns, and the prefects got eighthundred noisy kids settled down.  Then the captain of the schoolwould come out to the headmaster, tip his cap, and say, 'School is ready,sir!'  And we walked in.  I couldn't believe it!"<p>From that, he learned that schools are mirrors of their cultures,and that "no two good schools are alike, can ever be alike, becausethe important decisions are made right down close to where the kidsare, and all the palaver of headmasters, principals, and superintendentsand politicians is about a minority of the important things at the school."<p>He went back to Harvard, where he got a Ph.D. in the history of education,and stayed on to teach and eventually run the M.A.T. program andbecome dean of the Graduate School of Education -- at age 31.  Nineyears later, feeling detached from the world of schools just ashis own kids were reaching high-school age, he resigned to becomeheadmaster at Phillips Academy, Andover.<p>The old Massachusetts prep school was and is very rich, and so canafford to accept deprived kids on full scholarship.  It was there thatSizer learned the key lesson, the one that prompted him to apply forthe grant that led to the study that led to Horace and the Coalition:<p>"It is possible, if you control enough of the threads of a child's life, to profoundly change the chances that that kid has.  I saw thiswith poor, particularly minority kids.  It's not that you change theirlives; you make it possible for <i>them</i> to change their lives.  Your give them more options.  How that was done fascinated me."<p>Education 100 is a large class, 165 students.  Sizer looks vaguelyill at ease as he stands on the empty stage at the front of Room 101at the Salomon Center, fussing with a recalcitrant microphone.Some teachers enjoy the unchallenged authority and control of a lecturesituation, the chance to perform.  Sizer is not one of them.<p>Today's topic is the clash between the "top-down" school reformers, who advocate greater standardization, centralization, and nationalizationof norms, and the "bottom-up" partisans, who seek what Sizer calls"sub-local" control of the process -- by which he means making asmany decisions as possible at the school or even classroom level, wherethat crucial intersection of student, teacher, and idea takes place.<p>"The question is, Who's going to win?" he concludes. "I would bet on thesub-locals.  I don't sense any grassroots support for national exams ornational testing, or the elaborate progressive bureaucracies necessaryto develop a test.  Who wants another bureaucracy?  If anything, thecountry is tired of bureaucracies, particularly self-righteousbureaucracies that tell them the kids are no damn good."<p>Later, with the graduate students in the basement classroom, hispersonal frustration comes out:<p>"How long before we do something about a mass public-education systemthat turns out a large number of semi-literates?  How long do we haveto wait for common sense to take over?"<p>What about better training of teachers? a student suggests.<p>"We have had fifty years of efforts along those lines: We're going to professionalize teaching; we're going to raise standards; we're goingto have tougher tests, better textbooks, better-paid teachers, bettercollective-bargaining arrangements.  The result is..."<p>There is no need to finish the sentence; everyone in the room knows whatthe result is.  Only an incurable optimist would think he could makea difference -- someone like Ted Sizer.<p>"It would be quite easy for Ted to continue to be chair of the eddepartment at Brown, and be absolutely wonderfully engaged by his students and his writing, and be quite content and happy," saysDon Ernst, the Coalition's director of development, communications,and policy.  "Here's a guy who doesn't need to be taking on all thisstuff, you know?"<p>"All this stuff" includes some vigorous dissent, which comes from twogeneral sources: those who think Coalition-style reforms won't work, and those who fear they will.  Most poignantly, Sizer says, the latter group is led by the students themselves:<p>"Most high-school kids walk in, put the book on the desk, slouch,put the baseball cap on backwards, and say, Entertain me." When school is "no longer broken up into itty-bitty pieces of time inwhich you can fake a lot," and kids have to answer questions, take partin the process, a lot of them don't like it.<p>Some of the teachers don't, either.  Sometimes the reforms call for themto give up the very things they get most satisfaction from, in favor of unfamiliar methods.  And those who embrace reform must endurethe resentment of their colleagues.<p>"There's a whole bunch of criticism," Sizer acknowledges.  He saysthat some call Coalition-style reform "too soft; it leaves too muchdiscretion; the ideas are vaguely stated so people can say, 'Oh, yeah,I'm for that' -- and change nothing."<p>Others say he gives teachers too much authority and responsibility:that unless someone hands them a model to implement, reform won't work.<p>"We'll see," Sizer says.  "I'm prepared to say it won't work in mostcases.  Remember, we're trying to change an institution that has changedremarkably little in a hundred years.<p>"Another criticism is that we ignore the context in which all that takes place: that we are dangerously inattentive to regulation, unioncontracts, funding matters, politics -- all that stuff.<p>"We're going to pay much more attention to the context," he pledges,"but we're going to work very hard not to let that divert usfrom our belief that everything starts and finished with therelationship of teachers, kids, and ideas.  Get that relationshipright; then you know what the policy should be.  Most policy peopledon't address the central problem, which is that the confrontation ofteachers, kids, and ideas is not working."<p>Is the Coalition working?<P>"There's no research; there's no evidence that the kids in the Coalitionschools are doing better than kids anywhere else," complains RobertSlavin, who does his own research on teaching at Johns HopkinsUniversity.  Slavin describes himself as a "friendly critic" of Sizerand the Coalition.<p>By now, Slavin says, someone should have come up with some solid datathat could be used to grade Sizer's effort; after 10 years, the "Incomplete" on the Coalition's report card should be a trifleembarrassing.<p>Sizer and others in the Coalition acknowledge the lack of hard data."This is an area where there's great debate and some disagreement,"says spokesman Don Ernst, "because part of what we argue is thatthe current measures for making these kinds of judgments are inadequatefor the kind of work we're doing."<p>It's a Catch-22: If you believe in letting each Essential School transform itself from within, on its own timetable and in its own style -- and in the use of qualitative rather than quantitative measuresof performance -- you cannot impose the standardized testing and datagathering by which most schools gauge their effectiveness.<p>"Oh, but I think that's nowhere near an adequate response," Slavincounters.  "There's no law that says they have to use standardizedtests; they can use something else.<p>"I'm very, very supportive of the particulars of what Sizer istrying to do," he adds.  "I just wish that he or someone would do a decent study of it."<p>Sizer says that whole issue will be high on the agenda of the new NationalInstitute for School Reform, which is still in the planning stage.But there are crude measures one can use now, Sizer says, ticking them off: "Do the kids show up?  Do they stay through graduation?  Do they get into college?  Do they stay there?"<p>The anecdotal evidence is that Coalition schools do pretty well bythose measures -- some of them spectacularly well.  At violence-riddenThayer High School, in Winchester, New Hampshire, the turnaround wasso startling that someone wrote a book about it, which became the 1992NBC-TV movie <i>A Town Torn Apart.</i>  In 1981, before Thayer became an Essential School, as many of its students dropped out as went on to college -- 10 percent in both categories.  In 1990-91, 62 percentwent on to higher education, and only 1 percent dropped out.<p>But there are no controlled studies, and in several cases the data areclearly suspect.  Providence's Hope High School, like many in the Coalition, developed an Essential School within the "regular" school,and reports statistics for both.  The Essential students do betterin every category.  But, as the critics point out, that means nothing,because the best students tended to volunteer for the program in thefirst place!<p>(Essential Schools-within-schools also produce morale problems.  In onedivided schools, where the best teachers were picked for the new program,those left behind began calling themselves the Non-Essentials.)<p>So there are problems.  The programmatic ones pale beside the overarchingissues of crime, violence, poverty, and a climate of willfulignorance.  "It's a careless society," Sizer says, "quite prepared totalk about what it deserves, quite inattentive to any kind of obligation.  So that's disheartening."<p>So what gives him courage to go on?<p>"There are some schools out there whose kids do well when no oneexpected them to," Sizer says.  "You see that best in schools with a lot of low-income kids.  The schools that have broken through and done a lot of important things at once and are making noticeable changeshave dramatic impacts.  Those are the ones that, you know, just chokeyou up.<p>"You go to graduation ceremonies and walk around and talk to thesechildren, and you say, 'My goodness.  Their lives can be affected,fundamentally affected.'  And you think, 'Well, we have a function;we're not a trivial organization.'"<p>In <i>Horace's Compromise</i>, Sizer wrote: "A new design for school reform.  Will enough people somewhere want it enough to risk it, nurtureit, be honest with it, give it time?"<p>In a place of honor on his office wall there is this response, fromthe class of 1988 at Paschal High School, in Fort Worth, Texas, one ofthe earliest Essential Schools:<p>"We took the risk.  We are richer for it.  Thank you."<p>Horace would have figured that made it all worthwhile.<p></body></html>. 
