<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>THE PULSE OF THE PLANET</TITLE>
<HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="brushed_aluminum.gif">
<CENTER>

<IMG SRC="pulse.gif"
                                HEIGHT=110
                                WIDTH=100
                                BORDER=5
                                ALIGN=LEFT
                                HSPACE=10
                                VSPACE=10
                                ALT="PULSE OF THE PLANET">
<br>
<h1>TERMITE CONTROL TECHNOLOGY</h1>
<br>
Air Date: February 1997
</CENTER>
<HR>
<h2>If you've seen these critters crawling around the boards of your home, you've got termites.  But not to worry--scientists are researching new ways of exterminating these uninvited houseguests.

</h2>
<HR><BR CLEAR=ALL>

<IMG SRC="Feb97.gif"
                                ALIGN=LEFT
                                ALT="Feature Photo">

<!--our monthly sound-->
<a href="Feb97.wav">
<IMG SRC="Ear.gif"
                                ALIGN=LEFT
                                HSPACE=5
                                VSPACE=5
                                ALT="click here for sounds"></a>
<h3>
Click here for the sound of termites in wood, amplified and recorded using a device called an insectoscope.<P>

By doing what they do best--chewing wood--these termites actually help the environment.  Unfortunately, at the same time they also cause quite a bit of aggravation for human homeowners.<P>
 
"Termites do provide a very valuable service in the ecology," says Dr. Vernard Lewis, an entomologist at the University of California in Berkeley.  "If it wasn't for termites, we'd probably be a thousand feet deep in wood.  The problem with termites is if it's our home, worth maybe $300,000 here in California, humans find that discouraging and disgusting.  They want to protect their investment.  And here in California, termites do about $300 million worth of damage every year, about a billion board feet of wood.  Think of a wooden wall about ten feet high and a foot thick along the long axis of California from the Oregon to Mexico border."<P>

Dr. Lewis is currently testing new techniques for exterminating termites.<P>

"I'm evaluating six different drywood termite techniques.  We are looking at two fumigant gases.  We are also looking at thermoerradication using heat.  In that case, you get the temperature up to 120 degrees and hold it for an hour.  At that level, insects will die, they overheat.  Obviously, if you can overheat them, the reverse should be possible.  Liquid nitrogen uses excessive cold;  at about minus twenty, for as few as five minutes, termites will die.<P>

"The electrogun uses electrical shock to kill termites.  Electric shock could be a combination of heat and current passing through the insect.  We are also using microwaves.  There's a certain frequency of microwaves that vibrate water molecules.  Termites, like most life forms, are 80 or 90 percent water.  So in a microwave field, the water molecules in the termites vibrate.  That produces heat, and it overheats the insect, and they die."<P>

In Northern California, Dr. Lewis has set up a small wooden house to test these extermination techniques.  He calls it La Villa Termiti.<P>  

"The first tests have been done with artificial boards.  These are boards that we engineered and we put termites in them.  These boards have three different spaces in there with twenty-five termites each, so that's seventy-five termites.  We treat them, and then open them up and count the number of dead and alive.<P>

"Under that type of testing protocol, the two fumigant gases killed all the insects, and so did the liquid nitrogen.  In the case of the liquid nitrogen, we used a very high dose.  We should probably come back and look at a more realistic dose rate.  Then the heat actually killed 99% of the insects.  The microwaves killed 96%.  And the electrogun brought up the rear at 80%.  We did a second series of tests here with naturally infested boards. It came from someone's roof in Ventura.  And that offers a little more realism."<P>

</H3><P>

<center>

<a href="about.html"><img src="but4.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="more.html"><img src="but6.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="archive.html"><img src="but5.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="index.html"><img src="but7.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<A HREF="mailto:pulse@igc.org"><img src="but8.gif" BORDER=0></A>
</center>

<br clear=all>

</BODY>
</center>


</HTML>


