<H3>Program #1373</H3>

  

<CENTER>MASOALA PENINSULA RAINFOREST -- Saving Habitat</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> Rainforest<P>
We're in the forest of the Masoala peninsula, on the island of Madagascar.  This area is home to some of the most diverse life forms on Earth, yet it's under constant threat of destruction to make room for ever expanding agriculture.  Now, scientists are struggling to find new strategies to win the war for preservation.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

John Veerkamp is the Assistant Director of CARE Madagascar.  He explains to us why the Masoala peninsula is unique among rainforests in the world.<P>

"The peninsula is fairly isolated from the rest of the country, and that has created ecological niches in which you find different species that you dont find anywhere else.  Just an example, we have had a person here from Harvard University who is an ant specialist who discovered ants that he calls prehistoric, that were only known from fossils, and that you find as living ants on Masoala."<P>

Mr. Veerkamp knows that the prospect of discovering new insects isn't enough to convince local villagers to preserve the rainforest, so instead of pleading to their hearts and minds, he's taken a more practical approach.<P>
  
"Our strategy is based on the assumption that people will only respect the environment and will only respect the forest, if they have an economic benefit from it.  So what we have been doing is looking for these economic values that you could extract from this forest, and there are different options that we have started working on."<P> 

"One is butterfly farming, which is a very easy activity, as such, and the only thing you need to do is plant the right host trees next to the forest, butterflies will come lay eggs on the host trees.  You protect the caterpillars from parasites, and once they become pupae, you collect them and you export them."<P>

I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

