<H3>Program #1355</H3>

  

<CENTER>VITAL SIGNS MONITOR -- Medicine</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> Heartbeat<P> 
The days of a cold stethoscope on the chest may soon be over.  Instead, doctors will check your heart rate without even touching your body.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"The next generation of diagnostic devices will measure your vital signs without contacting the individual."<P>

At the Georgia Institute of Technology, scientists are developing a vital signs monitor that uses microwave radiation to measure a person's heart and breathing rates, without actually touching them.  Michael Burrow, a Senior Research Engineer on the project, says that this technology could offer a new way to care for patients whose vital signs can't be monitored by current means.<P>  

"There are many applications for this technology.  One could conceive of this device being in a neo-natalogy unit, to monitor the heart rate and respiration rate of infants, whose skin is very thin.  It's very hard to put electrodes on them.  You could also think of a burn unit, where you don't have access to putting electrodes on an individual."<P>  

Mr. Burrow hopes to expand this technology to measure not only breathing and heart rates, but also blood pressure, temperature, and other vital signs.  The monitor could then lead to new opportunities in home health care.<P>

"I think this technology will be a part of our lives and our homes, where we will be able to monitor our diagnostic information from the home, and that gets transmitted to our physician.  I believe that eventually we will be able to access medical care from our home, and it will eliminate, to a large extent, the amount of time that we have to spend in a doctor's office."<P>

I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

