<H3>Program #1356</H3>

  

<CENTER>SNOWY OWLS WANDER SOUTH</CENTER>

New England and the mid-Atlantic regions of the United States have some unusual visitors this week.  Snowy owls are making their way South.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Snowy Owls<P>

The screech of snowy owls is a sound usually found in the Arctic, but if you live in New England, don't be surprised if you hear it this evening.  These predators spend most of their time on the tundra, eating various rodents.  But it's winter, their prey is dwindling, and the snowy owls are heading for warmer weather to find food.<P>

"Snowy owls basically head South during the wintertime.  They generally come in sometime in November and they leave sometime in April."<P>

Norman Smith is with the Blue Hills Trailside Museum in Massachusetts.  He says that, unlike most birds, snowies don't follow a set migration path.  Instead, these predators merely wander South until they find a place that suits them, often ending up in the Northeastern United States.  If you're lucky enough to see one, snowy owls are indeed a sight to behold.<P> 

"Snowy owls are birds that are basically about 23 inches tall, they have a wing span up to about 5 feet in length, they can weigh up to about six pounds.  The adult males can be immaculately white, with no black markings at all, and the females are basically white with dark barring on their back, their heads, and their chests, also on their wings."<P> 

"They eat a variety of different food items, anywhere from the size of a small mouse to rats, which are preferably their favorite.  They eat a good deal of small birds and waterfowl, and we've actually seen them capture birds as large as a Canada goose, and we actually photographed one capturing a Great Blue Heron, which stands four feet tall.  So they are tremendously powerful birds."<P>

I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

