<H3>Program #1357</H3>

  

<CENTER>SNOWY OWLS WANDER SOUTH -- Airports</CENTER>

If you spent your summers on the wind-swept plains of the Arctic, where would you spend your winters?  How about the windswept runways of a major airport?  Well, that's where some snowy owls are making their home this week.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience/B> Bird-spotting conversation<P>

We're at Logan Airport in Massachusetts, with Norman Smith of the Blue Hills Trailside Museum.  He's talking with a member of the airport's bird patrol about one of it's most unusual winter visitors: the snowy owl.  The owls leave the plains of their Arctic tundra home every winter to find food, and they often end up living in airports in the Northeastern United States.  Why airports?  Well, it may be because the snowies are homesick.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Snowy Owls<P>

"This area is 2400 acres of short mowed grassland, and if the owls, which can fly up to elevations of about 8000 feet, see this as they're flying by, it probably looks more like home than any other area around."<P>

Snowy owls don't necessarily make Logan a regular stopover on their trips.  In fact, the snowies are unusual among birds in that they don't follow any specific migration pattern every year.<P> 

"What I've found out is that the owls don't seem to come back year after year.  Out of 123 snowies that I've banded here, only three have returned."<P>

But the owls that do winter at Logan certainly make themselves at home.<P>

"Snowy owls can be seen virtually just about anywhere at the airport, whether it's on the marshland, or on the grassland of the runway approaches, or sometimes they even sit on the middle of taxiways, or these random signs, or even some of the control towers."<P>

It might not be the Arctic, but with plenty of tasty rodents, Logan Airport will do nicely for the winter.<P>

I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

