<H3>Program #1340</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER VIRUSES</CENTER>

It multiplies endlessly, spreads on contact, and its effects can be devastating.  Cyberspace's version of the plague is the computer virus.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Steve White is a Senior Manager at IBM Research.  He studies computer viruses, and unfortunately he has a new to virus to look at virtually every day.<P> 

"The first computer viruses for IBM compatible computers were first seen in 1987, and they've been increasing in number ever since. There are over 8000 known computer viruses, and they're being created at an average rate of about six a day."<P>

So for whatever reason, someone takes the time and trouble to program a computer virus, and tries to unleash it into cyberspace.  But what sort of threat does it pose?<P>

"A computer virus is a program or a little piece of a program that when it runs, it makes another copy of itself someplace.  Every computer virus changes legitimate programs or documents in ways that you don't intend.  Some are very overt.  They'll trash your hard disk and make you lose all your data.  Others are more subtle, they mostly just spread."<P>

As the world becomes increasingly computerized, the potential danger of a virus also increases.<P>

"So, like a biological virus that makes a lot of copies of itself, a computer virus will infect a legitimate program that you have: a spreadsheet, or an editor.  When you run that spreadsheet or that editor, the virus will make copies of itself in other programs.  Pretty soon, more and more of your programs are infected.  If you give a program to someone else or someone else uses a program from your computer that's infected, they'll become infected.  So it spreads from program to program, computer to computer, country to country."<P>

We'll hear more about computer viruses, and how to prevent them, in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

