<H3>Program #1341</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER VIRUSES -- Cleaning the Net</CENTER>

You download some software from the internet, and unbeknownst to you, it's infected with a computer virus.  When you email the software as an attached document to some of your friends, you're helping to spread the virus around the world.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"This is a computer program that simulates virus spread.  There's a short beep whenever there's a new virus infection."<P>

<B>ambience</B> Simulated Virus Spread<P>

That's a time-lapsed version of how a computer virus spreads.  These days, a virus takes anywhere from several months or a year to span the globe.  But Steve White, a Senior Manager at IBM Research, is thinking about the future.<P>

"We think the computer virus problem is going to get worse in the next few years as more and more people hook up to the net.  As that happens, computer viruses can be transmitted more rapidly, and their population can increase a great deal."<P>

Mr. White has a team of computer programmers working to prevent global virus infection.  When a new computer virus is discovered, these engineers immediately begin analyzing and learning how to control it.<P>

"What these very clever people do is they put the virus on a computer and they look a the bits and bytes of the virus to determine what it does.  They reverse engineer the virus.  And then they'll be able to craft detection and disinfection for that particular virus based on what they see."<P>

The programmers then send their information around the world, so that any further outbreaks can be averted.  But as viruses spread faster and faster, new techniques need to be developed to stop them.  We'll hear more in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

