<HTML><TITLE>1342</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1342</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER VIRUSES -- Safe Email?</CENTER>

Millions of people interact with each other every day on the internet, and they're all vulnerable to computer viruses.  We've all heard about safe sex, but how do we practice safe computer?  Im Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

If you've spent anytime on the internet in a usenet group or any of the on-line communities that share email, you've probably heard some kind of warning about the dreaded Good Times virus.  It's a scenario which demonstrates that people are still largely unaware how computer viruses can be spread.  Steve White is a Senior Manager at IBM Research.<P>

"The Good Times Virus is a hoax that's been circulating around the Internet.  The note that you typically see warns you about this horrible Good Times virus and says 'make sure you warn all your friends.'  So the first thing you do is you send this off to all your friends.  It spreads much the same way that a computer virus does, but it itself is just a note that's spread by silly humans like you and I."<P>

While it's impossible to contract a computer virus simply by sending or reading an email message, there are ways that viruses can be sent on-line.<P>  

"Many email systems can have attached documents. There are now viruses that infect documents.  So I could send you a Microsoft Word document and if you open that Microsoft Word document and it were infected, then you could get a virus that way."<P>

So how's an everyday computer-user supposed to protect themselves from an infection?<P>

"The most important thing that you can do is to get good, reliable anti-virus software and keep it up to date.  New viruses come out all the time, and anti-virus software has to be updated to deal with them.  A second good thing that you can do is to write-protect your diskettes.  Your diskettes have a little black tab on them, when you open up that tab so you can see through it, the computer can't write to that diskette.  If the computer can't write to that diskette, it can't infect that diskette.  It's always important to keep backups of your system, it's the ultimate protection from something going wrong."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

