<H3>Program #1343</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER VIRUSES -- Digital Immunity</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> Simulated Virus Spread<P>
Each beep you're hearing represents a computer somewhere becoming infected with a new virus.  It's a time lapse simulation of how a virus spreads.  The increase of computer viruses around the world has scientists turning to biological models to learn how to control them.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"As more and more people hook up to the net, viruses spread much more quickly.  We're concerned about a day when a virus doesn't take years to get around the world, but minutes."<P>

Steve White is a Senior Manager at IBM Research.  He's using the human body's biological defenses as a guide for eliminating computer viruses.<P>

"We've looked at the immune system in humans and understood how it finds completely new viruses, picks them apart, figures out how to detect them and remove them, and we're crafting what we call an immune system for cyberspace that does just the same thing."<P>

"Here's how we envision that it'll work.  In the middle of the night, a computer in Luxembourg will detect something odd going on and say 'Gee, this might be a virus.'  It'll find the suspicious file or suspicious bit of the system, package it up, send it off over the Internet to secure computers here in our lab at IBM research.  Those computers will take this suspected virus, figure out if it is a virus, and if it is, automatically analyze the program to figure out what it does and how to remove it.  That information will be sent back to Luxembourg, but it will also be sent all over the world.  So if the virus starts to spread from Luxembourg, the cure will already be there to prevent it from spreading widely."<P>

"So over the next year and a half, improvements in the product will lead to a global distributed system that can find and eliminate viruses all over the world automatically."<P>

We'll hear more about computer viruses in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

