<HTML><TITLE>1345</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1345</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIO-ARTIFICIAL KIDNEY</CENTER>

Patients with kidney failure need to spend hours a day attached to a device which filters the toxins from their blood.  But now scientists are researching a way to free patients from this dependency.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Dialysis Machine<P>

We're listening to a dialysis machine, a device which acts as a mechanical kidney.  It's the typical method for treating kidney failure, but as Dr. David Humes, Chairman of the University of Michigan Medical Center explains, dialysis is a far from perfect process.<P>  

"Currently, the treatment with dialysis is life sustaining, but the quality of life is certainly poor.  Patients require 4-6 hours of dialysis treatment at least 3 times a week.  The patient has to get up, get dressed, drive to the center for dialysis, be tethered to a machine that treats and removes the toxins over four to six hours, has to then get off the machine, dress and return home.  That ends up being a full day type of process."<P>

To research an alternate treatment for dialysis, Dr. Humes is growing kidney cells in his lab.<P>

"We have been fortunate to be able to grow kidney cells outside the body in incubators.  Were able to take kidney tissue and expand the important stem cells, or the parental cells, so that from a few thousand cells we can expand, outside the body, the number of cells to billions."<P>

Dr. Humes hopes to use these home-grown cells, combined with a synthetic filter, to create a part organic, part mechanical organ that can be implanted into a person.  If this technology works, it will free patients with kidney failure from their dependence upon the dialysis machine.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

