<HTML><TITLE>1346</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1346</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIO-ARTIFICIAL KIDNEY -- Healthier than Dialysis</CENTER>

In the future, kidney failure might not mean spending fifteen to twenty hours a week on a dialysis machine.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Dialysis Machine<P>

We're at the University of Michigan's Medical Center, listening to the sounds of a dialysis machine.  It filters out toxins from the body, to help replace a patient's failed kidneys.  But as Dr. David Humes, the Chairman of the Center explains, dialysis doesn't do all the work of the kidneys.<P>
 
"What its missing is all those energized type of metabolic processes that the kidneys can produce for the body, not only take away toxins, but also replace important nutrients as well as important types of hormones.  Although its life sustaining, a patient has a worse life expectancy on dialysis than a patient with newly diagnosed lung or prostate cancer.  Patients feel chronically fatigued, they dont have energy, and they many times are unable to return to work."<P>

Dr. Humes is developing an artificial organ that would replace all the functions of a failed kidney.  It combines man-made devices with actual kidney cells grown in a lab.  These cells allow this bio-artificial kidney to not only filter toxins, but also perform the life-sustaining functions that dialysis can not reproduce.<P>  

"The plan is to develop two devices, both of which are important for full replacement of the kidney.  One will be a filter that could be implantable, so that a patient will not be tethered to a machine.  Two, it not only replaces what dialysis does, but adds and optimizes care that dialysis does not provide currently."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

