<HTML><TITLE>1347</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1347</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIO-ARTIFICIAL KIDNEY -- Tissue Engineering</CENTER>

A new alternative to kidney transplants may be on the way.  Instead of removing a healthy kidney from a donor, scientists will just make one in the lab.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. David Humes is the Chairman of the University of Michigan Medical Center.  He's studying a process called tissue engineering.<P>

"Tissue engineering is a burgeoning, developing field combining medical science, and bio-engineering science.  The idea stems from forty years of dialysis technology and the understanding that it has been optimized to a point of almost pure perfection from a synthetic process.  That to have any further improvement, missing pieces had to be added, and those were the biologic, cellular components."<P>

Dr. Humes hopes to use tissue engineering to create artificial organs, by combining man-made materials with actual biological cells grown in the lab.<P>

"What is revolutionizing this approach of tissue engineering is the ability to identify distinguished cells from various body parts or tissues, and grow them up in mass.  For example, your skin cells: part of your skin can be removed, and under the right culture conditions, the skin can replicate and form a new sheet of skin."<P>

"With regards to tissue engineering in general, this may bring an opportunity for tissue replacement and organ replacement for chronic disease such as liver failure, chronic heart failure, chronic kidney failure, and severe burns."<P>

But don't throw away your donor card just yet; it'll be some time before we see bio-artificial organs in human patients.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

