<HTML><TITLE>1348</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1348</H3>

  

<CENTER>LANDFILL GENERATOR -- Powering Up</CENTER>

That stale bread you threw away a few months ago might be powering your television tomorrow.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Gas Compressor<P>

We're listening to a generator that's powered by methane gas coming from the decaying garbage in a landfill.  The gas is collected, and then chemically converted into electricity by a device called a fuel cell.  As Dr. Ronald Spiegel, a Senior Research Engineer for the EPA explains, a single landfill could potentially power an entire neighborhood.<P>

"An ordinary landfill, depending on its size, could generate anywhere from a few kilowatts of power to several megawatts of power.  Were currently using a 200 kilowatt fuel cell at a landfill in Groton, CT.  The 200 kilowatt fuel cell does not use all the potential gas that that landfill can produce, but the electricity from that 200 kilowatt fuel cell can produce enough electricity for 100 homes.  So, if you took that landfill, and you actually utilized all the gas, possibly 500 to 1000 homes could be fueled from the gas from that landfill."<P>

With some careful planning, power can be drawn from a landfill for several years.<P>

"Normally, methane gas can be produced in landfills for twenty years or longer, but that number depends on how hard the gas is being pulled out of the landfill.  So its kind of a balancing act; you dont want to take too much gas from the landfill, but on the other hand you dont want much of the gas to be emitted into the atmosphere either."<P>

The technology used in the landfill generator has other applications as well, and we'll hear more in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

