<HTML><TITLE>1349</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1349</H3>

  

<CENTER>LANDFILL GENERATOR -- Not Just Garbage</CENTER>

A technology which may reinvent our nation's power supply system is currently sitting on a landfill in Connecticut.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Gas Compressor<P> 

We're listening to a generator that creates power from the methane gas emitted from a landfill.  The gas is first cleaned, and then chemically converted into electricity by a device called a fuel cell.  Dr. Ronald Spiegel, a Senior Research Engineer for the EPA, sees this technology being used in any location that has waste methane gas.<P>

"For example, waste water treatment plants have a process called anaerobic digestion where they reduce the sludge to smaller quantities, which in the process also produces waste methane gas. So the clean-up system can be used there to clean that gas up to be used for example, in fuel cells."<P>

Fuel cells easily convert natural gas into electricity.  And, despite their high cost, Dr. Spiegel predicts they'll soon be common sources of energy.<P>

"The fuel cells are relatively new technology; their cost today is probably a factor of two or so more expensive than some other comparable technologies which can generate electricity from gas.  However, the advantage of fuel cells are that they're much more efficient, quiet, and clean. Any place there's natural gas available, fuel cells can be utilized. And so its envisioned in the future that instead of central station power-distribution systems, there could be more widely-disseminated, smaller power distribution systems.  For example, big buildings that basically generate their own electricity from natural gas using fuel cells.  Hospitals, airports, these sort of possibilities."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

