<H3>Program #1350</H3>

  

<CENTER>FISH SCALE FERTILIZER</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> Fish processors voices, bouncing fish<P>
On the coast of Senegal in West Africa, women spend their days processing fish.  Well lately theyre busier than ever, because this staple food of their country is now an agricultural resource.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>FX</B> Olean Latud explaining in Wolof how fish are used<P>

Olean Latud has worked as a fish processor for thirty years.  She is explaining how none of the fish is wasted; even the scales have a purpose.  In years past, farmers would buy the fish waste to use as fertilizer.  But now, scientists are reviving and expanding this practice, in an attempt to improve local agriculture.  Tom Cussack is a professor from Oregon State University, working in Senegal.<P>

"We observed that many of the farmers were coming to purchase these residues.  The farmers obviously believed they were doing some good, and essentially the results show that it can be very effective as a way of increasing yields.  So we designed a small research project to see if this technology could be utilized by many farmers, or under which conditions this could be most effectively used by farmers."<P>

"We don't necessarily try to do something that's very technological, because usually really complicated things cost too much for the normal farmer and require too much of a change in his attitude towards how he does his work.  So this is a relatively small change and something which some farmers are all ready practicing.  So we hope to get quite a good impact from only a small amount of money spent on this research."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for living.<P>

