<H3>Program #1351</H3>

  

<CENTER>FISH SCALE FERTILIZER -- It's Chicken Feed</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> Fish processors singing<P>
Singing as they work to help pass the day, women on the coast of Senegal in West Africa process freshly caught fish.  Now, scientists are using the byproducts of the fish processing to improve the country's economy.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"The objective is to assist the national agricultural research institute here in undertaking good agricultural research.  Mainly in the area of natural resources management, in terms of developing specific technologies that farmers can use."<P>

Tom Cussack is a professor from Oregon State University, working in Senegal.  He and other scientists are trying to utilize the leftovers from fish processing, by encouraging farmers to use them as an agricultural fertilizer.  In only a few years, they have managed to expand the use of fish debris from grain farming, to vegetable growing, and now to a different branch of agriculture. <P> 

"That same fish debris can be used for adding to chicken feed.  It may have a more valuable use for chicken feed."<P>

In the past, the biggest difficulty has been covering the cost of transporting fish scales from the coast of Senegal to the farms in the interior.  But now, chicken producers might offer a solution to that problem.<P>

"If the poultry producers increase the demand for it, and they are more widely dispersed in the country, they may be able to pay for the additional transport costs, and still make a good profit.  And it certainly gives an incentive for local producers of chickens to substitute local product, compared to importing other additives from abroad."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for living.<P>

