<H3>Program #1352</H3>

  

<CENTER>DENIM RECYCLING</CENTER>

The jeans we wear are made of cotton that was once growing in the ground.  That cotton's picked and turned into denim.  But between the denim fabric and a finished item of clothing, there's typically a lot of waste that can't be recycled...until now.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Loom<P>

That's the sound of a loom at a factory in North Carolina.  It creates denim by weaving together thousands of strands of cotton yarn.  As Darlene Ball, the Customer Service Director of Burlington Denim explains, much of the fabric that comes out of the factory ends up being wasted.<P>

"Every time we ship a yard of fabric to someone who cuts and sews and manufactures the jeans, we lose about 10 percent of that yard.  And the reason for that is, when you lay your pattern pieces out, then you cut out your pieces you have little scrap.  That turns out to be about 70 million pounds of waste fabric."<P> 

Instead of sending all that unused denim to a landfill, Burlington's developed a way to recycle the fabric, so that the yarn can be reused.  Though it seems obvious enough, recycling denim isn't as easy as it sounds.<P>

"If we think about the fact that the fabric is woven, it has warp yarns, it has filling yarns, that are interlaced, that tells us that in order to use scrap we must take that apart.  So the process is actually to take large cutters which cut the fabric into smaller pieces, and then pull the small pieces apart, and try to separate the yarns back out again.  Its simply just taking the woven fabric back down to fiber form."<P>

By reusing that fiber, millions of pounds of cotton can be saved every year.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

