<H3>Program #1353</H3>

  

<CENTER>DENIM RECYCLING -- Applications</CENTER>

Soon, we may be sorting our recyclables into glass, paper, plastics, and clothing.  Im Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Loom<P>

We're listening to a loom weaving yarn into fabric at Burlington Denim in North Carolina.  Burlington has developed a process called garnetting, which reverses the work of the loom, and turns denim back into it's original fiber.  As Darlene Ball, the Customer Service Director of the company explains, this cotton can then be recycled for many different applications.<P>

"The first application that we saw and we adopted was a method for turning this into paper.  So in the denim division, all of our paper, our stationery, and envelopes, and business cards, and so forth, are made of recycled denim.  Another company is using it in insulation.  Its been garnetted, taken back to the fiber form, and then has been formed into a thick insulation, which is being sold for housing."<P>

By reusing the cotton fibers, millions of pounds of denim can be rescued from the garbage dump.  And when the yarn is turned into recycled clothing, it also reduces the amount of cotton picked from the fields.<P>

"Another application which we have patented is going through the same process that we do today with 100% new cotton fiber, and you make fabric.  And then from that fabric, our customers can make jeans, or dresses, or skirts, or whatever they may want.  These jeans made of our fabric look exactly like other jeans.  You really would not be able to pick them up and know that they were from the reused or recycled yarn, because they have the same strength and the same characteristics."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

