<H3>Program #1354</H3>

  

<CENTER>VITAL SIGNS MONITOR</CENTER>

The person sitting across the room points a small device at you, and a moment later, they know your vital signs.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

It sounds like a scene from "Star Trek," but it's true.  Ask Michael Burrow, a Senior Research Engineer at Georgia Tech, who's working on the vital signs monitor.  It's a radar-like device that measures a person's heart and breathing rates from hundreds of feet away.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Heartbeat<P>

"The device is a microwave device that sends a signal out and looks for movement of your chest as a result of your heart rate and your respiration.  And as your chest moves, this device records that movement, and provides a recording of your heartbeat as well as of your breathing."<P> 

"It was actually developed for military applications about 10 years ago.  And the idea was to be able to monitor from hundreds of yards away, a individual who's been wounded on the battlefield to determine whether they are still alive and whether you should risk the lives of other individuals to retrieve that individual."<P>

The monitor can also be used away from the battlefield in rescue operations.<P>  

"You could also think of situations in which you've had an earthquake and there's a lot of rubble, and you would like to search for individuals who might be buried in that rubble.  And such a device could actually look through the rubble and look for respiration of an individual who might be trapped."<P>

We'll hear more about the vital signs monitor in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

