<H3>Program #1325</H3>

  

<CENTER>PLANT VACCINES -- Immunizing the World</CENTER>

People in developing countries may soon receive much needed vaccines, in the form of ripe bananas.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Charles Arntzen is the president of the Boyce-Thompson Institute for Plant Research.<P>

"Vaccines are probably the most cost effective health intervention that we know of.  Unfortunately, on a world wide basis, vaccines don't get to all the people that need them, especially children.  Under immunization is a major problem throughout the poor countries of the world where economically disadvantaged children don't get the vaccines that they need."<P>

"Sometimes there is a poor rate of compliance, that is use of vaccines among people, simply because it's inconvenient for them to get to a doctor's office where the vaccines are administered.  If it was possible to find an easier route for distribution of vaccines, I think more people would use them."<P>

To this end, Dr. Arntzen is developing an edible vaccine. He inserts a gene from a virus or bacteria into a plant such as an apple or banana.  The plant then produces a protein which is like a blueprint of that disease.  By eating the fruit, humans ingest this protein and are vaccinated against the illness.<P>

"Our primary focus has has been getting inexpensive vaccines for kids in the developing world, where convenience is going to be a factor.  It's our expectation that we're going to have to have a food crop that can be given to infants, so we've focused on bananas.  Bananas are often times the first food that's given to infants.  My picture of the way bananas would be used would be delivery in something like a baby food bottle.  Where an infant in this country or developing world could simply get a spoonful of this nice banana puree, and get a pharmaceutical at the same time."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

