<H3>Program #1326</H3>

  

<CENTER>AUDITIONER -- Acoustic Predictor</CENTER>

It's now possible to know what the inside of a building will sound like, even before it's beenn constructed.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"Imagine how hard it would be to design the appearance of a building with a blindfold on.  Thats exactly the situation that weve had in the design of acoustics  since the beginning of time.  No one has used their ears to design the acoustics of spaces."<P>

Ken Jacob is Chief Engineer of Acoustic Research at Bose Corporation.  He's developed the Auditioner, a computer program that helps solve the problems of acoustic design.<P>

"In the most basic sense, Auditioner is a scale model for the ears.  In this case, that model exists in the computer.  Imagine yourself crawling inside of that model, sitting down at any seat that you choose, and experiencing sound that is the same as you would experience if that model were actually constructed."<P> 

Building plans are programmed into the Auditioner, taking into account materials which affect acoustics, such as carpeting or tiling.  The computer then uses this information to precisely reproduce how a location inside that structure will sound.  In other words, Auditioner lets you hear the inside of any building in the world, without ever leaving your chair.<P>

"We're gonna start in this church in Framingham, this 500 seat church.  This will sound like the minister were actually on the altar, speaking through a sound system in this church."<P>

<B>FX</B> "Welcome to Plymouth Church.  Or I should say a computer model of Plymouth Church."<P>

We'll hear more about the practical applications of the Auditioner in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

