<H3>Program #1327</H3>

  

<CENTER>AUDITIONER -- Listen Before You Build</CENTER>

The days of bad concert hall and meeting room acoustics may be over, thanks to a new acoustic design system called the Auditioner.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"There are hundreds of buildings that disappoint their designers and disappoint their owners when they finally open, because of the acoustics.  The problem has always been that when the design is finished, is the first time that anyone gets to use their ears, and by then it's too late."<P>

Ken Jacob is Chief Engineer of Acoustic Research at the Bose Corporation.  He's created the Auditioner, a computer system that allows designers to hear what the interior of a structure will sound like, before it's built.  When blueprints for a building are programmed into the system, the Auditioner can audibly reproduce the acoustics of that space.  Engineers can then try out design fixes on computer.<P>

"A good example is this large ballroom where I had to give a lecture to about 300 or 400 people and the problem was that when I was standing on the stage at the podium, there was such a terrible echo from the PA system that it was everything I could do to simply read the outline on the piece of paper in front of me.  And what I realized is that I could very easily fix this problem simply by using Auditioner."<P>

<B>FX</B> "Welcome to the podium.  You're standing beside me and we can both hear the public address system.  Can you imagine how hard it is to give a talk with this horrible echo?"<P>

The Auditioner demonstrates how the acoustics would change in this instance if a different loudspeaker was used and a curtain was added to the back wall.<P>

<B>FX</B> "You can hear that the sound has been dramatically improved.  I no longer have to put up with that horrible echo while I give my talk."<P>

Pulse  of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

