<HTML><TITLE>1328</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1328</H3>

  

<CENTER>FLU DETECTION</CENTER>

If you've ever been sick in bed with flu-like symptoms, chances are it wasnt really the flu at all.  But doctors may soon have a new way of finding out for sure.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"Well most people, when they say that they have the flu, they actually dont really have the flu.  They just have a pretty bad cold."<P>

Dr. Deborah Charych is a Principal Scientist at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.<P>

"The flu means that you actually have an infection by the virus called the influenza virus.  If you really had flu, you'd be so sick, you cant even get out of bed to go to the bathroom.  You feel like you've been knocked over by a truck.  You can imagine a doctor, if there was a drug for flu, would probably prescribe this drug to someone who just had a cold, and it would be ineffective.  So it would be nice for a doctor to have a rapid diagnostic test for the actual case of flu."<P>

<B>ambience</B> Centrifuge<P>

That's the sound of a centrifuge preparing samples for a new test to diagnose the flu virus.  The key to this method of detection is a colored polymer solution.<P> 

"A polymer molecule is simply a bunch of molecules that are linked together.  Similar to the way people standing in a row might link arms.  And it's that polymer that gives the material its color."<P>

Dr. Charych tells us that the flu test uses a blue colored polymer solution. When the influenza virus is introduced to the solution, it binds to the polymer and changes the color.<P>

"When the virus binds, then you have this rippling effect. It now absorbs blue light and reflects red color.  We pick that up as a visible color change from blue to red."<P>

According to Dr. Charych, if doctors are able to diagnose the flu by simply watching a solution change color, they may be able to treat the disease more effectively.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

