<HTML><TITLE>1329</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1329</H3>

  

<CENTER>FLU DETECTION -- Applications</CENTER>

A new method of detecting the flu virus may lead to a new era of health care.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Plate Shaker<P>

That's the sound of a machine shaking up chemical samples at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, where theyre perfecting a simple and easy method of detecting the flu.  As Dr. Deborah Charych, a Principal Scientist at the Laboratory explains, the virus is identified when it changes the color of a solution from blue to pink.<P>

"With the flu test, probably what would happen is you'd walk into the doctor's office, he would take a scraping from the back of your throat or from your nose, dissolve that scraping, and then wait a period of about fifteen minutes and just monitor the color change in the material and if he sees that it changed to pink, that would be a good indication that you had flu."<P>

According to Dr. Charych, this is an improvement over standard flu detecting methods, because it eliminates the potentially deadly time lag before a diagnosis.<P>

"Right now what's done is a throat swab or a nasal swab from a patient is taken and you basically run a cell culture.  And usually that test takes three to five days."<P>

"For certain compromised populations, for example in a nursing home, if there's an outbreak of flu, you could lose a lot of people rather quickly.  So you'd want to be able to know that it is in fact a case of influenza so that you can begin treatment right away and prevent the disease from spreading."<P>

With any luck, this new flu test can lead to easier methods for detecting other diseases.<P>

"Right now we're looking at detecting other bacterial systems.  For example, strep would be one, or chlamydia, or gonorrhea, different sexually transmitted diseases.  Perhaps other viral systems such as HIV virus would be another one that would probably benefit from a rapid diagnostic.  And in some cases it might be desirable to have even a home type of test that might signal whether you should go see a doctor."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

