<HTML><TITLE>1330</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1330</H3>

  

<CENTER>FLU DETECTION -- Beyond the Flu</CENTER>

A new test may make diagnosing the flu easier than ever, and it may also help us to prevent other illnesses.  Im Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Plate Shaker<P>

Were in Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratories, listening to equipment preparing samples for a new test used to identify the flu virus.  When perfected, the test will simplify and speed up detection of influenza.  It works by mixing a tissue sample with a chemical solution.  If the flu virus is present, it will bond with the molecules in the solution, changing its color from blue to pink.  As Dr. Deborah Charych, a Principal Scientist at the Laboratory explains, the test isn't perfect yet.<P>

"Right now we need to have a lot of viruses to bind that material to change the color.  So as a visual test, the sensitivity could be improved.  There might be other organisms or other viruses out there that bind to the same target.  No biological test is going to be perfectly selective for what you're looking at."<P>

But even with the drawbacks, this type of test has other applications.  For one, it may be used to detect when disease causing organisms are trapped in enclosed spaces, the so-called sick-building syndrome.<P>

"It's believed that some cases of sick building syndrome are caused by bacteria or fungi in the air, and it would be nice if you could have some kind of an on-line monitoring system in a room or on a filter that would indicate well the air is getting bad.  So any kind of closed environment life an office environment, or an airplane, or a waiting room of a hospital might be places where you'd want to continuously monitor the air.  It might be useful for just monitoring, you know, the cleanliness of your home for example, if you were interested to make sure there weren't any microbes or airborne organisms in the house that might potentially  cause allergies or disease."<P> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

