<H3>Program #1332</H3>

  

<CENTER>WIRELESS SUBWAY SPEAKERS -- Safety</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> subway station, train stopping<P>
You're riding along on the subway, when the train suddenly grinds to a halt.  You nervously sit awaiting instructions, when the public address system crackles to life with an undecipherable message.<P>

<B>FX</B> Garbled subway message<P>

I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"It's very important to design a new public address system, because of public safety.  PA systems are vital information sources, especially during an emergency.  Conventional PA systems often collapse just at those critical moments."<P>

Dr. Alan Avidan is the Executive Vice President of the MadahCom Corporation.  He's developed a wireless public address system that sends announcements via digital radio signals to strategically placed receivers.  According to Dr. Avidan, this technology greatly improves the clarity of the messages, and increases the system's reliability during an emergency.<P>

"Even if parts of it collapse, the rest of the system continues to operate."<P> 

And the WAVES system can also use a computer to send digital data signals to its receivers.  This data can carry visual information for a lighted sign, which would provide emergency messages to hearing-impaired individuals.<P>

"The data channel's used to display text and animation on visual display signs which can be synchronized with the audio.  It provides a significant quality-of-life improvement to hearing-impaired people.  I can tag a visual message and an audio message and send them with the single flick of a key."<P>

"I think the WAVES product makes our lives safer by providing us reliable, timely, audio and visual information where we need it and when we need it during emergency situations."<P>

<B>FX</B> WAVES Emergency Announcement "There is an emergency situation.  Please leave the station through the South exit."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

