<HTML><TITLE>1333</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1333</H3>

  

<CENTER>AIRCRAFT NOISE REDUCTION</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> Flying jet airplane </P>
We've all heard the roar of a jet engine, but in the future it might not be so loud.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Ian Waitz is the Director of the MIT Aero-Environmental Research Laboratory, where scientists are studying ways to reduce the noise of aircraft engines.<P>

"Airplane noise is something that's felt by more and more people, because more and more people live near airports, and airports are having more and more traffic, so there's more and more overflights.  So, it can impact ability to work, ability to have conversations, ability to sleep at night, which can influence you in a variety of ways."<P>

Aircraft noise is caused by unsteady air flow from the engine's fan.  This unstable air creates a wake, similar to the waves you see behind a boat.  When that reaches our ears, we hear it as noise.  Prof. Waitz wants to quiet the engines by reducing the wake.<P>

"What we do is we take high pressure air from the compressor in the engine, and we pass this air up through the center of this rotating set of hollow fan blades, and then out through the back of these fan blades.  And when we push the air out through the back of these fan blades, that fills in the wake.  And if we can fill in the wake, we can reduce the noise associated with the interaction of that wake.<P>

If this technology works, it will mean a notable improvement in the sound of aircraft.<P>

"Roughly, it might be like the difference between standing very close to a major highway as the cars go by, and then standing many tens of feet back from that highway, in terms of the change in the sound you might see.  So it's a step in the right direction."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

