<HTML><TITLE>1334</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1334</H3>

  

<CENTER>AIRCRAFT NOISE REDUCTION -- Tests</CENTER>

The roar of airplanes may soon be quieted, thanks to tests now being conducted by scientists.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Ian Waitz is the Director of the MIT Aero-Environmental Research Laboratory, where scientists are trying to design a new way to reduce the noise level of jet engines.<P>

"One of the major reductions in aircraft noise which has occurred over the last twenty years has been basically a change in engine design.  Aircraft engine designers with the tools they currently have, have done just about everything that they can do.  And yet, there's continual push from communities to further reduce aircraft noise."<P>

<B>ambience</B> Vacuum pump<P>

We're listening to a vacuum pump preparing a test in Prof. Waitz's research facility.  As he explains, it's used to gather information from a simulated jet engine.<P> 

"What we're looking at here are two large tanks that are connected by a pipe.  And in that pipe are two things.  One is a valve, and the other is a rotating set of fan blades, very similar to what you would see on the front of a jet engine.  In one tank we have a very high-pressure mixture of and argon, and in the other tank we have vacuum.  The way we operate this facility is by spinning up this set of fan blades with a small electric motor, until we reach about 7000 revolutions per minute."<P>

<B>ambience</B> Fan noise test -- blades spinning<P>

"And when we've hit just the right speed, we open the valve, and that allows the air to flow between the two tanks."<P>
  
<B>ambience</B> Fan noise test -- pop of valve opening<P>

"It takes roughly 100 milliseconds for the air to go from the high pressure tank to the low pressure tank.  And in that 100 milliseconds, we can collect a great deal of data that very closely simulates the conditions in the jet engine."<P>

Prof. Waitz can then use this data to find a method of reducing noise in real engines.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

