<HTML><TITLE>1335</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1335</H3>

  

<CENTER>BACTERIAL IDENTIFICATION</CENTER>

Bar codes have become a standard item in the design of grocery packaing.  Now scientists have developed a technology similar to bacteria in order to catalog bacteria.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Riboprinter<P>
 
Youre hearing a machine called a Riboprinter, a kind of a grocery scanner for micro-organisms, which automatically identifies any bacteria sample presented to it.  Dr. A. J. McCardell is a microbiologist with the Qualicon Company.<P>

"The Riboprinter System works by taking bacterial cells, breaking open those cells, very much like cracking an egg, to get at the genetic material.  It cuts the genetic material and produces a genetic fingerprint from the bacterial DNA.  A genetic fingerprint looks very much like a bar code that you would see on a package of food, and it can be used to specifically identify a bacterium."<P>

The genetic fingerprint is stored in the computer's database, so that the Riboprinter will always be able to distinguish that particular organism.  According to Dr. McCardell, this is a significant improvement over previous methods of identifying bacteria.<P>

"The standard way of typing bacteria is to use biochemicals.  Biochemical methods are very slow.  It can take as much as a week or more in order to get a name for a bacterium."<P>

Dr. McCardell says that the Riboprinter classifies organisms not only more quickly, but more precisely.<P>

"Using a genetic method, we are able to actually identify and characterize the bacteria to a much, much finer level than was ever possible before. And it does it in eight hours."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

