<HTML><TITLE>1336</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1336</H3>

  

<CENTER>BACTERIAL IDENTIFICATION -- Cleaner Foods</CENTER>

There's a new way to identify bacteria which may lead to safer foods for everyone.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Riboprinter<P>

That's the sound of the Riboprinter, a computerized device used to identify and catalog bacteria.  It creates a genetic fingerprint, or a kind of bar code for each organism.  The fingerprint is stored in a database so that the bacteria can always be specifically identified.  Dr. A. J. McCardell, a microbiologist at the DuPont Experimental Station, explains one of the applications of the Riboprinter.<P>

"The instrument is being used today in part in the food industry, to track contamination and spoilage issues in their products.  For example, we had a particular customer that had contamination of a final product.  They were able to identify the bacterium in the food with a name.  They found the same kind of bacteria on a worker's hands, as well as in one of the raw materials that went into producing the product."<P>

Now if the bacteria had come from the raw materials, it would mean that the process used to decontaminate the food didn't work.  However, in this instance, by using the Riboprinter, it was discovered that the bacteria actually came from dirty hands after the food had been decontaminated.<P>

"We were able to find an exact genetic match between the patterns of bacteria isolated on the worker's hands and in the final product.  And the pattern found from the raw material was completely different.  Their processing steps in producing the food were working.  It was a lot simpler for them to target specifically new hand washing procedures, mandatory glove wearing procedures, in the final post-processing handling of their product."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

