<H3>Program #1337</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER VOICE SIMULATION</CENTER>

<B>FX</B> Computer arpeggio<P>

That's the voice of a computer singing to you through its own virtual voice box, and although Luciano Pavarotti is in no danger of being replaced here, the computer may help us understand better the mechanics of singing.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

At the University of Iowa, scientists have designed a computerized version of the human speech system.  Dr. Brad Story, an Assistant Research Scientist, used MRI technology to record images of his vocal tract.  These images, combined with mathematical formulas, were then used to create a digital, three dimensional model of his vocal apparatus, with which the computer can then recreate his voice.<P>  

How close does it come?  Well, this is Dr. Story speaking.<P>

<B>FX</B> Recorded Sentence "The blue spot is on the key again."<P>

And this is the sound of the computer simulating his speech with its virtual vocal tract.<P>

<B>FX</B> Simulated Sentence "The blue spot is on the key again."<P>

Dr. Story says that one application of the voice simulator is to study how singers produce certain sounds.<P>

"We've done quite a bit of investigating how the shaping of the vocal tract can enhance different singers voices.  There have long been a lot of methods that voice teachers will tell a student how to get a particular sound.  Like, to make it feel like there's a baseball in the back of your throat or something, that gets them to open up their pharynx.  We're able to go in now and actually open up the pharynx in that part and find out if that, in fact, does enhance the voice."<P>

Dr. Story can test these ideas using the model of his own vocal tract.<P>

"I'm not at all a trained singer, so what you're going to hear is something that I personally can't do, but I can make the computer do it for me.  And what you're going to hear is a little arpeggio, done with the 'ah' vowel."<P>

<B>FX</B> Simulated Arpeggio<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

