<H3>Program #1338</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER VOICE SIMULATION -- Simulated Surgery</CENTER>

How do you predict the effects of surgery on a person's voice?  Well, try using a computer armed with a model of a voice box.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>FX</B> simulated sentences<P>

Thats a computer recreating a human voice. Using mathematical formulas and actual images of a person's vocal tract, scientists have created a three dimensional, digital version of our speech apparatus.  Dr. Brad Story, an Assistant Research Scientist at the University of Iowa, explains how this virtual vocal system can be used.<P>

"The fundamental goal of all of the work we're doing is simply to create a very effective model of the human speech production system, and once we've got to that point, we can begin to do a lot of spin-off applications, one of the most important being that it becomes a very effective research tool, in that we can do a lot of things to a speech production model that we can't do to the human during speech."<P>

"We're hoping to go in and simulate a surgery prior to it being done, and hopefully be able to predict the results.  For example, if someone has one vocal fold that is paralyzed, which is called a unilateral vocal fold paralysis, surgeries are often done now where the vocal fold is bulked up and pushed one side to the other.  And we hope to be able to allow them to simulate that surgery prior to them actually making the cut in the person."<P>

This is a recording of a patient with vocal fold paralysis.<P>

<B>FX</B> Paralyzed vowel sound<P>

And this is the computer, simulating how the patient will sound after surgery.<P>

<B>FX</B> Simulated vowel<P>

Though it still cannot fully predict the outcome of vocal surgery, the computerized speech system may soon be giving patients a better idea of what they'll sound like.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

