<HTML><TITLE>1339</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1339</H3>

  

<CENTER>LANDFILL GENERATOR</CENTER>

If you thought that landfills just took up space, it turns out that they can also be used to produce electricity.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

</B>ambience</B> Gas Compressor<P>

That's the sound of a gas compressor at a landfill in Groton, Connecticut, where the Environmental Protection Agency and Northeast Utilities have put a cap on the landfill to create a prototype of a power generator.  Chuck Trippell, the Project Engineer, explains how it works.<P>

"All landfills produce gas through the decomposition of the garbage.  And the gas either escapes into the atmosphere, or in cases where the landfill is capped, the gas is then collected to be used in the fuel cell."<P>

"A fuel cell is a piece of equipment that takes methane out of natural gas, or in this case landfill gas, which is about fifty percent methane.  It uses that gas to generate electricity through an electrochemical process.  The fuel cell is connected to the utility grid, so the electricity gets used like any other electricity on the grid would get used."<P>

Fuel cells are a nearly pollution-free way of producing electricity.  They also help the environment by reducing the amount of methane emitted from the landfill.  Traditionally, that gas is burned off with a device called a flare.  But flaring off methane into the atmosphere contributes to global warming.  By using that gas to make electricity, the generator reduces the pollution released into the air.<P>

"On a daily basis, approximately 300-400 cubic feet per minute of gas is flared off.  When the fuel cell is in operation, it will use approximately 80 cubic feet per minute of gas.  We're taking that gas and converting it to electricity, so we're saving that pollution that would normally escape into the atmosphere."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

