<HTML><TITLE>1311</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1311</H3>

  

<CENTER>BARRIER PLASTICS - Better Packaging</CENTER>

Soda packaged in plastic bottles will ultimately lose its fizz, as the carbon dioxide gas leaks through the container.  But new kinds of plastic should make a difference.   I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Pump/trap<P>

That's the sounds the sound of a device used to measure how well different kinds of plastic serve as a barrier to gases like carbon dioxide.<P>

"This electro-balance is a very sensitive set of scales that we can use to measure very small changes in the weight of the sample.  From these data we can calculate how much of the gas has dissolved into the plastic, and we can also calculate how rapidly it dissolves into the plastic.  Those two values, for example, how rapidly these gases would permeate through a piece of plastic."<P>

Benny Freeman is an Associate Professor of chemical engineering at North Carolina State University.   He says the plastics he's working with are fundamentally different from the materials used in making soda bottles.<P>

"The molecular structure of the materials we work with, the molecules are much straighter and more elongated than the molecules that are used for the current packaging materials.  So the molecules pack together in much the same way that tooth picks in a box pack together very efficiently.  The plastics we deal with look like molecular toothpicks.  And they align so that all of the molecules are pointing in the same direction.  This very efficient packing markedly reduces the rate of transport of gases across plastics, so it markedly reduces for example, the rate of the loss of carbon dioxide from soda bottles."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

