<HTML><TITLE>1312</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1312</H3>

  

<CENTER>BARRIER PLASTICS - Applications</CENTER>

New kinds of plastics will make better containers and make possible a wide range of new applications.   I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

A polymer is a plastic, and liquid crystal polymers are better at containing gasses and other substances than common plastics.<P>

"Gasoline tanks are made out of plastic bottles."<P>

Benny Freeman is an Associate Professor of chemical engineering at North Carolina State University.<P>  

"Some of these materials could be used to improve the barrier properties of gasoline tanks.  What that does is keep the gasoline in the tank rather than let it escape to the atmosphere and cause a pollution problem."<P>

"They're likely to be used what are called a composite structure.  That is, there will be a very thin layer of these extremely high barrier materials and it will be sandwiched by layers of much less expensive plastics, to bring the cost of the total structure down to a reasonable level, but still give you much better barrier properties than you would get with just the less expensive material alone."<P>

"The military  is looking at these kinds of materials to make all-plastic rockets and missiles, which in addition to having obvious advantages in terms of weight over metal components, it also makes them much more difficult to detect by radar.  A lot of this technology will be applied in space.  NASA all ready uses some of these materials in the breathing system for their next generation of spacesuits."<P>

"We are, I think at the beginning of really understanding where you can start to manipulate structure and actually control properties in these materials.  There's still a lot of uncharted territory in the science of these materials."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

