<HTML><TITLE>1313</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1313</H3>

  

<CENTER>THE SEARCH FOR GAS HYDRATES</CENTER>

Scientists have discovered that abundant pockets of methane gas are buried below the ocean floor.  Now, they are developing new ways to locate and extract that natural gas, using sound.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

William Dillon is a scientist at Wood's Hole Geological Survey, who's researching gas hydrates, crystallized methane gas found beneath the ocean floor.<P>

"A gas hydrate is an ice-like material.  It's a crystalline form of water molecules just like ice, but the crystal structure is held open by the presence of a gas molecule within the structure, generally a methane molecule.  Gas hydrate is found in many places, but most commonly within the deep sea sediments."<P>

A new device to help locate gas hydrates in the ocean's bottom, by first recreating them in the lab.<P>

<B>ambience</B> GHASTLI<P>

"Thats the hydraulic power system going on for an instrument known as GHASTLI--Gas Hydrate and Sediment Test Laboratory Instrument.  The intention of this instrument is to recreate conditions within deep sea sediments where gas hydrates exist.  We inject water and methane, and when conditions are correct, we can form gas hydrate."<P> 

When scientists bounce sound waves off the ocean floor, it gives them  a kind of map or profile of the sediment below.  Now, gas hydrates, which are buried in deep sea sediments, can be located by this method, but first scientists need to identify their acoustic fingerprint.  And that's what Mr. Dillon and his colleagues are trying to do in the laboratory.<P>

We'll hear more about extracting methane from the ocean in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

