<HTML><TITLE>1314</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1314</H3>

  

<CENTER>GAS HYDRATES AND THE ENVIRONMENT</CENTER>

The most abundant source of natural methane gas might be lying deep beneath the ocean floor, and it could be a chief cause of global warming.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> seismic profile

We're on board a research ship in the Atlantic, bouncing sound waves off the ocean floor to create a seismic profile, a kind of acoustic map of the sea bottom.  William Dillon is a scientist at Woods Hole Geological Survey.<P> 

"A seismic profile is created by firing a seismic source, and then listening to the returning echoes.  The rumble is the reflections from the sea floor and from layers beneath the sea floor."<P>

Mr. Dillon uses seismic profiles to locate gas hydrates, which are crystallized molecules of methane gas found at the bottom of the ocean.<P> 

"Gas hydrates are ice-like materials found within ocean floor sediments. They are formed out of methane molecules and water molecules.  The water is frozen into a crystalline state and the methane molecules are held within the water crystal framework."<P>

The undersea methane gas might be one of the hidden causes of global warming.<P>

"Gas hydrates probably have a strong influence on deep sea landslides.  The hydrate actually glues sediment together, and when it breaks down it can cause landslides on the sea floor.  Now, landslides on the sea floor might not sound too for humanity, but sea floor landslides can cause massive release of methane to the atmosphere. Release of methane to the atmosphere will have a contribution to the greenhouse effect.  So the breakdown of gas hydrates on the sea floor can cause a warming of the planet, probably a significant one."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

