<HTML><TITLE>1316</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1316</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER-AIDED DRIVING - The Future of Commuting</CENTER>

You climb into your car after a hard day's of work, turn on the ignition, and then sit back and relax as it drives you home.  It's a scenario that could happen in the not too distant future.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"One of the biggest problems that our nation faces today is the congestion problem on our nations highways.  So a computerized vehicle that can steer itself and also control its own speed would allow you to pack more cars and allow them to travel more quickly because the computer can react more quickly."<P>

<B>ambience</B> RALPH<P>

Dean Pomerleau is a research scientist at the Robotics Institute of Carnegie Mellon University, where they're developing a self-steering car.  It uses a computerized driving system called the Rapidly Adapting Lateral Position Handler, or RALPH, for short.  It monitors lane markings through a video camera to maintain the car's position on the road.  Dr. Pomerleau's next step is to put driving completely in the hands of the vehicle.<P>

"One of the goals of the work we're doing here is to develop these fully automated cars.  That you'd pull onto a potentially special lane of the highway  and hit a button, take your hands and feet off the wheels and the pedals, sit back and read your newspaper while it whisks you to work."<P>

It sounds promising, but there are drawbacks.<P>

"One potential danger of this kind of system is that the driver will become reliant on it and not be attentive to themselves to in this case the driving task.  One of the important attributes that the RALPH system has, is it's ability to estimate its own competence, basically, for driving in a particular situation.  It will tell the driver that is incapable of performing at this point in time."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

