<HTML><TITLE>1317</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1317</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER-AIDED DIVING - RALPH</CENTER>

A new automated system may make driving a lot easier, by taking the job of steering away from the driver.  That system's name is RALPH.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> RALPH<P>

"RALPH stands for Rapidly Adapting Lateral Position Handler."<P>

Dean Pomerleau is a research scientist at the Robotics Institute of Carnegie Mellon University, where they have developed RALPH, one day it may help steer your car.<P>

"We've got a video camera mounted next to the rear view mirror that looks out ahead of the vehicle at the road.  Images from that video camera are processed by a computer in the trunk of the car to determine where the road is ahead and how the vehicle is situated on the road. It tries to find features that are running parallel to the roadway.  So for instance lane markings are nice parallel features that it tries to locate in the image ahead and use the position of those features to estimate the vehicle's location on the roadway."<P>

A prototype of RALPH has all ready been field tested by Dr. Pomerleau.<P>

(p.8, 331) "Over the summer, myself and one of my graduate students took a trip in our test vehicle from Washington DC to San Diego, California.  During the 2850 mile trip, the system, RALPH, was actually in control and steering the vehicle 98.2% of the trip.  We basically just sat back and watched RALPH drive.  Situations where we had to take over were things like stretches of new highway where they hadn't bothered to paint line markings on it yet, or going into the setting sun with the sun shining directly into the camera."<P>

As of now, RALPH only controls a vehicle's steering, but if a speed-control system is developed, RALPH may change the face of commuting forever.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is brought to you by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

