<H3>Program #1318</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIO-DIESEL</CENTER>

If the exhaust from that truck in front of you smells a bit like French fries, you may not be imagining it.  That truck could be running on a type of diesel fuel made from vegetable oil.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Bio-diesel powered truck starts<P>

The vehicle youre hearing is running on bio-diesel fuel.  As Leon Schumacher, an Associate Professor at the University of Missouri explains, bio-diesel is an engine fuel derived the same type of oils used for making French fries.<P>

"The bio-diesel that we're using in the diesel engines is made from soy bean oil. We remove the glycerin from the oil, and by so doing, we have a product that is very similar to petroleum diesel fuel."<P>

"This fuel can be used to power boats, cars, trucks, trains.  It's even been tested in aircraft engines.  So it's got a wide variety of uses and it's very well suited in any application where you would normally operate with petroleum diesel fuel."<P>

Though its seems remarkably innovative, bio-diesel actually first appeared many years ago.<P>

"The very first to power diesel engines with a plant based product was in fact the inventor of the diesel engine: Rudolph Diesel.  He used peanut oil to power the diesel engine in the Paris Exposition when he first introduced the diesel engine. The real difference is that today we're using a product that is very similar to modern petroleum diesel fuel.  And because it is so similar the product requires little if any changes to the fueling system of the engine.  The advantage being you can simply move ahead and use the engine on diesel fuel as well as on the bio-diesel."<P>

We'll hear more about bio-diesel fuel in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

