<HTML><TITLE>1319</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1319</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIO-DIESEL - Environmental Fuel</CENTER>

Soy beans are found in food products from corn chips to tofu.  But now, they may also be found inside your fuel tank.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Bio-diesel Truck<P>

"We have a Dodge pick-up that's been operating for approximately 96,000 miles on a what we call bio-diesel."<P>    

Leon Schumacher is an Associate Professor at the University of Missouri.  His truck is running on a fuel that's made entirely from soy beans.<P>  

"Bio-diesel is actually a product where we take soy bean oil and remove a product called glycerin from it.  And the end result is a fuel that's very similar to diesel fuel and it's operating in a direct-injected diesel engine."<P>

According to Professor Schumacher, an engine runs just as well on the purely organic bio-diesel as it would on traditional petroleum-diesel.  But the bio-diesel out-performs petroleum in other ways.<P>

"Bio-diesel actually facilitates the combustion process and actually reduces many of the undesirable pollutants that are caused by today's fuels."<P>

"Another advantage of the bio-diesel is that its a biodegradable product. For example, a lot of work that the forest service gets caught up in, they have no other option then to use hand tools because certain parts of the area where they are working will not permit them to use any kind of product that if spilled would cause damage to the ecosystem."<P>

Bio-diesel would allow forest workers to use power tools, while minimizing the effects of harmful fuel spills.  We'll hear more about the benefits of bio-diesel in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

