<HTML><TITLE>1320</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1320</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIO-DIESEL - A Sensible Alternative?</CENTER>

Perhaps the most sensible fuel for the world's diesel engines isn't found  buried in the ground, but growing on top of it.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Bio-diesel Tractor<P>

The tractor you're listening to runs on a fuel made from soy beans.  A substance called glycerin is extracted from the soy bean oil, turning the oil into an efficient petroleum substitute.  As Leon Schumacher, a scientist at the University of Missouri explains, this bio-diesel fuel holds in store many benefits for the future.<P>

"The United States consumes approximately 60 billion gallons diesel fuel each year.  When we pull oil reserves out of the ground, we're not able to put that kind of product back into the ground for future generations to remove for their needs."<P>

Bio-diesel fuel solves this problem because, unlike petroleum, the soy beans used to make bio-diesel can be constantly regenerated.<P>

"The product we're using is something that we can grow.  Which indirectly means that we're reserving some of the petroleum product for a future generation."<P>

So why isn't the public already using bio-diesel?<P>

"The only real downside to the product is the cost issue.  The bio-diesel today is being sold for approximately four dollars and fifty cents per gallon.  This, obviously, is much higher than what we're paying for petroleum diesel fuel."<P>

Scientists are now experimenting with bio and petroleum diesel blends, to help lower the cost of the fuel.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

