<H3>Program #1321</H3>

  

<CENTER>ALUMINUM CAR</CENTER>


A new combination of sport and safety can now be achieved in cars, by manufacturing them out of aluminum.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Car racing around street<P>
 
French designers have manufactured a new sports car with an entirely aluminum chassis.  Marcial Hetier is the Chief Engineer of the Renault Spider.<P>

"It's made in aluminum to save weight and to have something more rigid, more stiff.  It's the first time weve built a complete chassis made in aluminum. This process is a very common process for the building industry, but for a car its a new thing."<P>

Aluminum absorbs impacts one and a half times better than the steel generally used in cars.  That translates into improved safety for drivers.<P>

"We have a crash box at the front of the car to absorb all the energy of the crash.   It's completely stiff and protects the passenger of any crash."<P>

But that doesn't mean that the Aluminum car can't be sporty.<P> 

<B>ambience</B> Car racing around street<P>

Because aluminum is such a light weight metal, the Spider performs much better than most sports cars.<P>

"The car accelerates very quickly.  The brakes are fantastic.  This car corners much quicker than any other car in the world. It's completely stable and glued on the road."<P>

To learn more about this and other programs in our series, we'd like to invite you to visit our World Wide Web site.  The address is http://www.pulseplanet.com.  That's www.pulseplanet.com.<P>

