<HTML><TITLE>1322</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1322</H3>

  

<CENTER>SYNTHETIC DIAMONDS</CENTER>

Diamonds have long been considered one of the Earths most precious substances, and now they can be grown in the laboratory.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"Natural diamonds are made at very, very high pressures and heat.  Basically it's a natural occurring process that literally took millennia to form the diamond.  We make diamonds in a couple of minutes here."<P>

James Adair is an Associate Professor of Material Science and Engineering at the University of Florida.  He uses a process called chemical vapor deposition to grow diamonds in a laboratory.  The process begins with tiny diamond fragments called seeds.<P>

<B>ambience<B> heat exchanger<P>
"We take very very fine diamond particles and we make them stick to all kinds of different surfaces on which we wish to lay down diamond.  And then the chemical vapor deposition process grows diamond from those seeds."<P>

Unlike  other methods for making synthetic diamonds, the process that professor Adair uses requires no extraneous equipment or electronics.  But even though these diamonds are easy enough to create, you won't be finding them adorning engagement rings.<P>    

"We're limited to diamond coatings or films on various surfaces.  This particular sample's got a diamond coating on it.  It's about point one thousandths of an inch thick.  It basically looks like a piece of sandpaper."<P>

"Diamond has many more attractive engineering properties actually than aesthetic properties.  When you look at this kind of diamond, hopefully all the romance goes out the window and people will think of it as something that can potentially revolutionize their lives."<P>

We'll hear more about the uses of synthetic diamonds in future programs.  Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

