<HTML><TITLE>1323</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1323</H3>

  

<CENTER>SYNTHETIC DIAMONDS - The Key to Computing</CENTER>

Scientists can now create diamonds in the laboratory.  But they wont be found in jewelry.  These diamonds will end up inside of tomorrow's high speed computers.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

James Adair is an Associate Professor at the University of Florida.  Hes developed a way to create diamonds in the laboratory.  A simple chemical process is used to grow the gems from tiny diamond fragments.  The results are microscopic, but they have important scientific applications.<P>

"Diamond is, of course as you know, one of the hardest materials known to man.  But also it's got the highest thermoconductivity of any material.  What this means is that it transports heat very, very effectively.  You wouldn't want a diamond camping cup, because it would warm up very, very rapidly as a container and so you'd burn your lips."<P>

But the diamonds ability to conduct heat makes them very useful if installed in silicon computer chips.<P>

"For microelectronics, dealing with the heat generated by the circuit is one of the biggest problems.  If the heat builds up too much within a silicon circuit, it can literally melt the silicon.  And it's not going to act as a very good computer brain for you.  Diamond can pull that heat out of the silicon chip, so the circuit can run a little bit cooler."<P>

If a computer chip is kept from heating up, it can be made to perform faster.  And a faster chip can lead to a new breed of computers with enhanced capabilities.<P>

"Based on diamonds, we'll have computers so fast that true voice recognition is possible.  You say 'Computer, I want you to write a program about this topic.'  And so the computer will write the program.  I think it'll be certainly before the end of our lifetimes, much closer than that.  I think diamond will play a big roll."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

