<HTML><TITLE>1324</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1324</H3>

  

<CENTER>PLANT VACCINES</CENTER>

We've all been inoculated against various diseases, and soon, we may be able to receive those same vaccinations by eating a piece of fruit.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Charles Arntzen is President of the Boyce-Thompson Institute for Plant Research.<P>

"In 1992, the Children's Vaccine Initiative put forth a manifesto and called for new technology for worldwide immunization of children against important infectious diseases.  When my colleagues and I read about this, we said 'We've got technology available in the plant sciences which is not being used.  Let's see if it would work.'"<P>

<B>ambience</B> lab<P>
We're in the laboratory at the Boyce-Thompson Institute, where edible vaccines are being developed.  To understand how they work, here's how a typical vaccine does its job:<P>

"Weakened or chemically damaged viruses or bacteria are injected into people.  Our immune system sees them and responds.  Because they've been weakened, they can't cause disease, and so we build up an immunity so the next time we see the real disease causing agent we don't get sick."<P>

The difference with Dr. Arntzen's vaccines is that they're not injected.  They're genetically reproduced in a plant, such as a banana.  You're inoculated by simply eating the fruit.<P>

"We take a gene from a bacterium or a virus that causes human disease.  We're putting the gene into a plant.  In the plant, the gene then causes a protein to be produced, and this protein is something like a fingerprint of the disease causing agent. The plant will start producing it in its edible tissues and we can now feed it and use it as an oral vaccine.  Once our body sees this fingerprint protein, it then causes us to mount an immune response and so we develop a defense mechanism against the entire disease causing agent."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

