<H3>Program #1295</H3>

  

<CENTER>WINDUP RADIO</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> cranking<P>

That's the sound of a wind-up radio - a radio that generates its own power, just by cranking it up. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

We're in Capetown, South Africa, speaking with John Hutchinson, general manager of Baygen Engineering, makers of the Freeplay radio.<P>

"The way that the free play radio works is that you wind it up, it takes sixty turns to give it a full charge.  What it's really doing is winding up a spring.  As the spring unwinds it spins a little generator providing about three volts of energy and it uses that energy to power a radio board.  The radio board is FM, medium wave and short wave and it enables the listener to pick up signals from all over the world, even thousands of miles away."<P>

<B>ambience<B> cranking<P>

"I'm now switching on the radio."<P> 

<B>ambience</B> South African radio (music/talk)<P>

"Not only does the Freeplay radio avoid the need of having to buy batteries, but it's an ecologically friendly radio.  I understand that batteries are the single biggest mercury pollutant on the planet today, and the fact that the Baygen radio doesn't use batteries will obviously have an effect on mercury pollution in the future."<P>

To learn more about this and other programs in our series, we'd like to invite you to visit our world-wide-web site.  The address is http://www.pulseplanet.com.  That's www.pulseplanet.com.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

