<HTML><TITLE>1296</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1296</H3>

  

<CENTER>WINDUP RADIO--The World Tunes In</CENTER>

You're out camping in the wilderness, with a portable radio but no batteries.  Not to worry - a few cranks of the knob on the side of the radio generates enough power to play the radio for thirty minutes at a time. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> cranking<P>

"The concept was really to take communication to people who have never had radio receivers before.  Generally that's been because either there's been no electricity there or he price of batteries in remote regions is so dramatic that it's impossible for somebody to afford them."<P>

John Hutchinson is general manager of Baygen Engineering in Capetown, South Africa, makers of the Freeplay radio.  Just crank it up and it will receive AM, FM, and shortwave signals.<P>

<B>ambience</B> cranking, radio (music/voices)<P>

"I think the importance of the Baygen radio is not restricted to communications in rural South Africa.  It really has a role to play in communications throughout the world.  In fact currently we have one playing in the Amazon jungle, and Amazonian Indians travel enormous distances each day to come and listen to the radio in the evening.  Because it's been the first device of it's kind that's been able to bring continuous listening to that part of the world.  The guys just come in, wind it up, and listen to the Voice of America or the BBC or the voice of Moscow or listen to music from a medium wave station a couple of hundred miles away in the Amazon."<P>

The Freeplay radio is currently distributed in Africa and Europe, and soon will be available in the US.  The Company has plans for making windup flashlights and  windup cellular phones.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

