<HTML><TITLE>1297</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1297</H3>

  

<CENTER>T-RAYS</CENTER>

Between microwave and infrared radiation, there is a range of high frequency radiation called Terahertz, or T-waves.  Scientists are beginning to work with T-Waves to find safe new ways to inspect and analyze materials.  In some applications, they might someday replace X-rays.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Martin Nuss is with Bell Laboratories' Lucent Technologies.<P>

"To generate T-rays, we have to have optics, and very fast laser pulses help us."<P>

The sounds we're listening to are of the T-wave pulses translated to a frequency that humans can hear.  The different sounds indicate that the T-Ray is scanning a different material.<P>

"T-rays can give you a fingerprint of the material or a signature of the material.  Because every material, whether they be gases or liquids or solids, actually have different absorption and dispersion characteristics.  What that means is that tererahertz waves go through the material they get distorted in a very very characteristic way."<P>

"The characteristics of T-Rays in general is that they easily go through most dry non metallic objects, like cardboard, wood, cloth, glass, plastics.  So all of these materials that are used in packaging for instance are almost entirely transparent."<P>

One of the most promising applications of T-Ray technology is package inspection.<P>

"X-rays can also do that but it turns out that X-rays are such high energy, are sometimes a safety hazard.  Terrahertz radiation because it's such a low energy it really is, in the thermal range of the electromagnetic spectrum, it is completely benign as far as we know."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

