<HTML><TITLE>1298</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1298</H3>

  

<CENTER>T-RAYS--A New Look Inside</CENTER>

X-Rays aren't the only form of radiation that enable us to look inside of things.  Terahertz, or T-Rays, have a frequency range between microwaves and infrared radiation, and they offer scientists a new way to inspect, measure and analyze.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Every kind of material absorbs or disperses T-Rays slightly differently, enabling scientists to use this benign form of radiation in a number of different applications.  Martin Nuss is with Bell Laboratories' Lucent Technologies.<P>  

<B>ambience</B> T-Rays

He and his colleagues have designed a scanner which emits a focused beam of T-Rays in rapid pulses.<P>  

"There's a whole class of applications that you can envision for T-ray imaging.  And you can classify in three categories.  One is general quality control.  Density, looking for cracks in packaging, looking for voids in certain materials.  The second class is moisture measurement and water content.  That is very important to a number of industries.  First it's important to the food industry.  Moisture in baked products like cereal an bread and cookies has to be controlled very tightly.  The last application that we envision to be very promising is in gas detection and gas monitoring.  Because when T-rays pass through gases their waveforms get changed in such a characteristic way that we can immediately identify which gas the T-rays passed through and what concentration of gas was present at that time.  So we envision that we can use T-rays for toxic gas monitoring and general environmental sensing."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

