<HTML><TITLE>1299</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1299</H3>

  

<CENTER>EARTHQUAKES -- Bio-Mechanics to the Rescue</CENTER>

In recent years, earthquakes have been responsible for the deaths of thousands of people and have caused billions of dollars worth of damage.  In an effort to design safer, earthquake-proof structures, scientists are looking to biological models.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. George Lee is the director of the National Center for Earthquake Engineering and research, to design to a building that can withstand an earthquake, he's turned to the study of bio-mechanics, which solves engineering problems by studying the models of living systems.<P>

"So we learn form physiology, from the mechanical behavior of a living system.  We actually learn from that and bring that principle into engineering practice, how to design a man-made system that can be more intelligent."<P>

Dr. Lee and his colleagues have designed a device that can be retrofitted into existing structures or installed in new buildings.  It detects the relative motion and power of an earthquake and responds by causing different parts of the structure or absorb the shock, just as the human body would respond to an external push.  We're listening to the sounds of a prototype of the device in motion.<P>

<B>ambience</B> RSD Device<P>
"This particular variable stiffness device for example in real time we can make it totally rigid to behave like a steel bar.  Milliseconds later we can completely relax it.  Now think about yourself.  When you're walking on the deck of a boat and it's shaking, what you do is you just adjust yourself, and one time you might stiffen the muscle in your right leg and relax on the left.  When it goes the other way, you will suddenly stiffen the muscle on your left and relax your right.  So that sudden stiffening and relaxing of the muscle is what this functional switch is doing."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
