<HTML><TITLE>1300</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1300</H3>

  

<CENTER>EARTHQUAKES--Preventing Damage</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> RSM Device<P>

Were listening to the sounds of a prototype device designed to help buildings withstand the force of an earthquake.  Im Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"The system that we have may be described in three components.  The first one is called the sensors, or information gathering devices."<P>

Dr. George Lee is the Director of the National Center for Earthquake Engineering Research.<P>

"The second component of the system is a decision-making unit, which is basically just a computer that takes all the information, analyzes the information, and makes a decision what to do.  If it should decide that the vibrations are too severe, than the decision making device will give orders to these devices that we call them functional switches.  These functional switches will open or adjust this valve, now you hear the clicking sound of the adjustment of the valve, so they can stiffen or dampen the vibrations of the structure."<P>

The ability to stiffen, or cushion, structural supports, together with the sensors or computers, enable this system to respond instantly to the particular motion of an earthquake.<P>

"Earthquake ground motion is really random in nature.  It happens all the time different, but really in general they're very similar.  But the minor details in the motion makes a big difference in terms of how it affects the structural response.  There's always a challenge to better design the structures."<P>

Dr. Lee envisions other applications for this device as well.<P>

"This technology can protect structures from other natural hazards as well, like windstorms or tornadoes.  In addition, it can improve performance on mechanical systems, in automobiles, boats, ships, and so on and so forth."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

