<HTML><TITLE>1301</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1301</H3>

  

<CENTER>FLOATING AIRPORTS</CENTER>
 
For coastal cities, available real estate is often at a premium, particularly for something as large as an airport.  But what if you built an entire airport off shore on a floating platform?  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> ocean waves<P>

Don Innes is chairman of the board of Float, Inc.<P>

"If you as a child have probably taken a glass and turned it upside down in the water.  You pushed the open face down in the water and you've seen that the glass doesn't sink.  Well what is happening in that situation is that you've trapped a bubble of air in the glass, and the glass is pressing back against your hand do to the compression of the air in that bubble.  No matter what you do you will not be able to push it straight down and sink the glass.  Th same principle we use for our platform except we take a lot of these glasses and instead of calling them glasses we call them cylinders and they're cylinders that are twenty feet in diameter, forty feet high, and we complicate the glass analogy by drilling a small hole in the side that lets an air bubble escape from a high pressure cylinder into a lower pressure cylinder.  Therefore evening or averaging out the pressure that is placed on the platform itself.  This has two effects.  It one tends to put less force on the platform, it tends to lift the platform less.  It also seems to have an opposite and equal reaction to the wave itself.  It tends to dampen the wave thatt is trying to lift the platform."<P>

And what would it feel like to be on a floating airport?<P>

"You won't know you're on the platform itself, except during a hurricane, in which case you might sense some movement in the platform."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

