<HTML><TITLE>1302</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1302</H3>

  

<CENTER>FLOATING AIRPORTS--Wave of the Future</CENTER>

The airport of the future might be located on a floating platform. Engineers are studying the possibility of building a floating airport about three miles off the coast of San Diego.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> ocean waves<P>

Don Innes is chairman of the board of Float, Inc.<P>

"Well the idea came from a suggestion made some thirty years ago by the mayor of the city of San Diego to build an extension to naval air stations runways out into the ocean.  This was unacceptable because it would affect the currents and the quality of water off our shore.  Then I thought maybe we should move our whole airport off-shore.  Then instead of connecting it to the land we would float it on the top of the surface so we would not affect the ocean or the sea life that exists out on the platform itself."<P>

"Airports are probably the worst pollution devices that we can create on shore.  They attract a lot of automobiles, they attract a lot of trucks, industry.  They tend to pollute very large regions with noxious fumes from hydrocarbons from these aircraft as well as the automobiles.  By placing one out to sea we get away from the noise pollution because we have no population out there to be affected by the noise.  We are able to distribute the solid pollutants in the air over a natural area that is unoccupied and we have the advantage of having no obstacles in either our take-off or our landing corridor which makes it much safer."<P> 

More on floating airports in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

