<HTML><TITLE>1303</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1303</H3>

  

<CENTER>FLOATING AIRPORTS--A Haven at Sea</CENTER>

A newly designed floating platform may one day make it possible to build airports, oil refineries and stable harbors - in the middle of the ocean.   I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Wave Tank<P>

We're listening to the sounds of a wave tank used to test the platform prototype.  Don Innes is chairman of the board of Float, Inc.<P>

"What you see here is a 1/24 scale replica of the system that we are using for such things as floating airports."<P>

The floating airport will rest on a platform of up to 30.000 cylinders.  The cylinders are all linked together, enabling an air pocket trapped underneath them to collectively dampen the effects of ocean waves - keeping the platform stable.<P>

"The breakthrough is that heretofore all stabilized platforms in the ocean have worked on the principle of avoiding the waves instead of confronting the waves. That's fine and dandy except the only way to access the platform is by helicopter because you can't bring a ship along side because the ship will pound the platform apart or pound the ship apart, one of the two.  And so the access to a platform is a very critical issue, particularly if you are thinking in terms, as we are, of building harbors anywhere in the world that they cannot currently be built, so that we can bring and load ships and cruise ships and water taxis to the area without endangerment to either the cargo or the passengers.  We create with this platform a calm water on the down wave side, so in essence every time we bring a platform in we have created a harbor, a calm harbor."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

