<HTML><TITLE>1304</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1304</H3>

  

<CENTER>CARBON MONOXIDE CATALYST</CENTER>

Hundreds of people die each year from Carbon Monoxide poisoning.  Now a new chemical catalyst has been developed that converts Carbon Monoxide at room temperature into a harmless gas. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"Carbon Monoxide poisoning is really quite common in homes, and what causes it, of course, is some sort of leak that would be a source of carbon monoxide.  A faulty furnace, a faulty fireplace, anyone of a number of things in which you could have incomplete combustion could furnish carbon monoxide."<P>

David Schreyer is a research chemist at NASA's Langley Research Center.<P>

"The reason carbon monoxide kills people is that carbon monoxide has a much stronger affinity for our blood than oxygen does so carbon monoxide tends to tie up the hemoglobin in our blood and we can't get any  oxygen to stick to the blood, so we simply die of a lack of oxygen."<P>

"Right now the typical way that you would try to remove carbon monoxide from the air would be by filtration.  Active carbon and a few other substances will filter carbon monoxide out.  The problem with that is that filters tend to plug up and you don't always know when they plug up and when a filter does plug up it just lets whatever it was filtering come through in great volumes.  So filters fail catastrophically.  The catalyst that NASA has developed doesn't filter carbon monoxide out.  It converts carbon monoxide to carbon dioxide.  Carbon monoxide is toxic, carbon dioxide is not toxic. And since the catalyst is not absorbing the carbon monoxide, it continues to process long after the filter would have been plugged up.<P>

More on the Carbon Monoxide Catalyst in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
