<HTML><TITLE>1305</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1305</H3>

  

<CENTER>CARBON MONOXIDE CATALYST -- Applications</CENTER>

NASA has come with a substance that converts deadly carbon monoxide gas at room temperature into non-toxic carbon dioxide. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"A catalyst is a substance that speeds up a chemical reaction.  Our catalyst speeds up the process of conversion such that it's performed in a fraction of a second."<P>

"The form of our catalyst is a very thin coating on some sort of a support or substrate as we call it.  And that support or substrate can be any one of a number of things.  The great thing about a catalyst is the only thing that matters about it is its surface.  So a catalyst can be incredibly thin and still be very effective."<P>

"One practical application for for the NASA catalyst is simply the removal of carbon monoxide in houses and any occupied buildings to prevent carbon monoxide poisoning.  In a home heating system, you have an air circulation system.  You draw air into the heater, you heat it, then you circulate the air back into the house.  You would insert the catalyst on an appropriate support in the air intake system, and before the air ever got to the heater it would remove any carbon monoxide that was in the air."<P> 

"Another application would be in transportation vehicles like aircraft.  Many times when there is an aircraft fire the people are not killed by the fire, they are killed by carbon monoxide poisoning.  If this fire takes place on the ground and people had face masks containing air catalysts, the people could walk away from the fire and escape the plane and not be burned. This catalyst could also be used by people in a burning hotel to escape, or by firefighters."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

