<HTML><TITLE>1307</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1307</H3>

  

<CENTER>KINETIC TENNIS RACKET--More Pwer, Less Pain</CENTER>

High technology is now routinely used to enhance sports equipment and tennis rackets are no exception. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"For the most part I think tennis technology has evolved from wood products to increasing head sizes as a result of lighter weights, really culminating most recently in graphite rackets with wider cross-sections that have become known as wide-bodies which allow rackets to be stiffer and lighter, which translates into more power."<P>

Kevin Gilbert is president of the ProKennex Company, developers of the Kinetic tennis racket.  The frame of the racket contains chambers partly filled with tiny metal bearings.  The bearings add force to the racket's swing and help dampen vibrations from the impact of the ball.<P>

"We've developed this frame and found out that along with the benefits associated with reducing shock and vibration, that it actually enhances the stability of the frame on off-center shots so that you hit the ball straighter more often.  We've also found out that it actually improves or expands the area of the so-called sweet spot or that area that gives you the best results on the face of the frame."<P>

<B>ambience</B> kinetic matter<P>

"This is actually the lead bearings inside these chambers moving.  Right now, you can hear it.  It's imperceptible during play, but what is making this sound is what allows us to increase the sweet spot, reduce the shock, reduce the vibration and all together enhance the performance of the player."<P>

"The kinetic technology could be applied and incorporated into any sports equipment that is impact oriented.  For instance a baseball bat, a hockey stick, a golf club.  Any sports equipment like that we can appreciably enhance the performance of the equipment and the end user."</P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

