<HTML><TITLE>1308</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1308</H3>

  

<CENTER>SUPERSONIC WING</CENTER>

Imagine flying on a supersonic jet from Los Angeles to Tokyo in under four hours.  Well, NASA is developing a technology that will get you there as fast as the Concorde, for the price of a charter flight.  Im Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

When air is turbulent over the wing of an airplane, the turbulence causes a drag on the wing, which causes the airplane to slow down.  Jeffrey Lavell, a scientist at the High Speed Research Program at NASA, explains how turbulence works.<P>

"Turbulence is when the airflow over a wing separates from the wing at some point along the surface and becomes sort of mixed up with the rest of the air surrounding the wing."<P>

Here's the sound of turbulence.<P>

<B>ambience</B> turbulent air flow<P>

Turbulence also causes the airplane to work harder, and thus burn more fuel.  Mr. Lavell, the manager for the Supersonic Laminar Flow Control Project, is developing a new type of aircraft panel which eliminates turbulence.  The panel, called a glove, is made of titanium and fits over the left wing of an F-16 airplane.<P>

"The panel on the F-16 works by providing some suction from underneath the panel through about twelve million holes.  And the reason we do that is so that we can stabilize the layer of air that's flying over the wing by drawing off just a small portion of the airflow through these very tine holes.  We actually tend to keep the the layer of air stable and keep it from becoming turbulent."<P>

The stable current of air is called laminar airflow, which slides off the wing of the plane rather than causing drag.  Here's the smoother sound of laminar airflow:<P>

<B>ambience</B> laminar airflow<P>

"And if we can make airflow across the wing completely laminar, then what we can do is cut down on the drag and we can save a lot of weight on the airplane and we can save fuel.  And in the end result, we can make tickets a lot cheaper for passengers."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is made possible by DuPont, maker of better things for better living.<P>

