<HTML><TITLE>1309</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1309</H3>

  

<CENTER>SUPERSONIC WING--High Speed Civil Transport</CENTER>

Mention NASA and most people think of expensive research projects with little or no benefits for the average citizen.  But, with their latest attempt to develop affordable supersonic transportation, NASA is proving that not only can they help everyday people, but also that they can also be thrifty.  Im Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

At the Langley research Center, NASA scientists are working in conjunction with leading airplane manufacturers to create a technology for a new type of inexpensive supersonic jet.  The researchers are designing a new type of aircraft wing which will make supersonic travel more efficient.  The wing reduces turbulent air flow, eliminating drag on the plane, and saving fuel.  NASA is testing their technology using computers and a prototype of the wing attached to an F-16 XL fighter jet.  As project manager Jeffrey Lavell explains, this is an extremely cost-effective way of perfecting the technology.<P>

"The main reason were doing the F-16 XL experiment is to validate some computer codes that weve been using for quite some time.  By gathering flight data, we can compare that to what weve predicted with our computer codes and we can adjust our codes.  Its much easier, as you can imagine, to design things with a computer than to build a whole airplane and go flight test it, and then have to come back and make changes."<P>

The end result of this research will be the new supersonic High Speed Civil Transport.<P>

"The High Speed Civil Transport is currently planned for introduction in about the year 2015.  It's an airplane that will fly at about 2.4 times the speed of sound or MACH 2.4.  The High Speed Civil Transport will be larger than the Concorde.  It will carry about three times the amount of passengers, but probably the biggest difference is it will be affordable."<P>

That means NASA's thriftiness will pay off in dollars, and hours.<P>  

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

