<HTML><TITLE>1280</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1280</H3>

  

<CENTER>BODY SHOP</CENTER>


Somewhere between Frankenstein's monster and a department store mannequin lies The Phantom. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> tissue mixing machine<P>

Dr. Peter Olsen is a senior scientist at Pacific Northwest National Laboratory, and he builds body parts called phantoms. We're listening to a machine mixing up the plastics used to make simulated human flesh - what Dr. Olsen calls "tissue equivalent."<P>

"The idea is to simulate the characteristics of human tissues in enough detail and accuracy that we are in effect mimicking the various body tissues of humans."<P>  

Not to worry. Dr. Olsen isn't building creatures - he's helping people who may have been exposed to radiation.  A tiny amount of radioactive material is placed in the synthesized body parts, and then they're used to ensure that the instruments which measure radiation in people are accurate. Dr. Olsen makes everything from phantom limbs to phantom organs, such as lungs.<P> 

"This lung part will eventually contain a uniform or a non-uniform distribution of a very small tiny amount of radiactive material. And then it will go inside an actual body phantom with tissue equivalent overlays, plastics that will mimic adipose fat, etc. And then this whole device, when it's packaged together, will be brought to a whole body counting facility, and it will be used to complete the calibrations. The system is then used for radiological protection for people."<P> 

The people being measured with these instruments would initially include workers in the nuclear industry, or medical technicians who deal with radiation devices.<P>  

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

