<HTML><TITLE>1281</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1281</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIOCERAMICS</CENTER>



Bioceramics - it sounds like a contradiction in terms. But people are full of natural ceramics such as bones and teeth. And now scientists are inventing glasslike materials that could be used inside the human body. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"We're always on the lookout for more compatible materials inside the body. For example,  you can invent ceramics that are much more biocompatible than surgical steel for pins and plates and so forth."<P>  

Alix Clare is an associate professor of glass science at Alfred University in New York. She explains how she makes bioceramic glass.<P>

<B>ambience</B> rollers<P>

"We take powders and take them up to a very very high temperature, and then when they're all molten, we cool them very very quickly between rollers that are cooled in liquid nitrogen. And that way we get thin ribbons of glass coming out the bottom."<P> 

The ribbons of shiny black glass look, feel and even sound metalic.<P> 

<B>ambience</B> clinking<P>

Now, there are a number of ways that bioceramic glass can be used in medicine.<P> 

"Biomedical applications are mainly bone transplants for people, either using the ceramic as a whole or using it as a kind of Hamburger Helper for your natural bone. We can also use ceramics as a kind of treatment device, to either deliver radiation as in radioactive beads put into the body, or we can actually deliver heat, or we can deliver nutrients or drugs."<P> 

More on bioceramics in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

