<HTML><TITLE>1282</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1282</H3>

  

<CENTER>BIOCERAMICS - Destroying Disease with Heat</CENTER>


High temperature is one way to destroy cancerous tissue. The problem is how to apply heat to a tumor without damaging the healthy tissue around it.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Alix Clare is an associate professor of glass science at Alfred University in New York. She's developing a method to deliver heat to a tumor using tiny particles of glass.<P> 

"The materials we make here are called glass ceramics, and that means that they're glasses with little crystals in and those crystals are magnetically susceptible. That means that if I put them in a magnetic field that oscillates backwards and forwards, theyll heat up. (1885) The particular use for these materials is to deliver a local heat source to the body, and the reason that you might want to that is that bad tissue in the body, such as in a cancerous tumor, is destroyed at a lower temperature than healthy tissue is. Therefore, in principal, as long as you can keep the temperture between two windows there, you can actually destroy bad tissue without affecting healthy tissue."<P>  

<B>ambience</B> rollers<P>

To make the glass, Dr. Clare melts down the component materials and pours the liquid over spinning rollers. The cooled pieces of glass would then be ground up into particles about the size of a blood cell, and injected into a tumor.<P>

(1933)  "Then the persons whole body would be put in an oscillating magnetic field, and only the part that contained the glass ceramic would actually heat up, thus destroying the bad part, and not affecting the good part. After the glass has done the work and caused the tumor to decrease, and even go away, then the glass is bioresolvable. And what we mean by that is,  it dissolves harmlessly away in the body, introducing into the body only elements that are there in the first place."<P>  

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

