<HTML><TITLE>1283</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1283</H3>

  

<CENTER>ROBOT THERAPY</CENTER>


In the future, if you get treated by a physical therapist, you might find yourself shaking hands with a robot. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Neville Hogan is a professor of mechanical engineering at MIT. He and his colleagues are testing a prototype robot designed to exercise the arms of a patient disabled by a stroke. First, the patient sits at a table and grasps a handle on the robot's arm.<P>

"It's very much like asking the patient to shake hands with the robot. There's then a visual display provided, and the patient is initially asked to move a cursor on a screen, very much the way that you'd move a mouse in operating a computer program."<P>  

<B>ambience</B> sliding<P>

As the patient slides the robotic arm across the tabletop, the device measures how much force the person is exerting, and it assists the movement when necessary.<P>

"Early in the therapy, the patient is unable to move and so the robot's responsible for the movement. As the patient begins to recover, the responsibility for the movement is actaully shared between the patient and the robot. And then later in the therapy, as the patient begins to recover more fully, the robot does less and less and winds up essentially going along for the ride, simply recording the movement that the patient makes."<P> 

A machine can easily perform this same exercise with the patient many times, and keep precise records of each movement. But researchers are still trying to determine whether the robot-aided therapy really helps the patient.<P>

"If we can prove that it is useful for even a simple movement, then we've got our foot in the door. And if the only weakness was that, well, we can rehabilitate the hand but what about the leg, well, we can go back and make a machine for the leg.  At this stage we're trying to see, does this kind of approach make sense at all."<P>  

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

