<HTML><TITLE>1284</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1284</H3>

  

<CENTER>ROBOTIC THERAPY - Not a Replacement</CENTER>


Recovering from a stroke can require months of physical therapy. Now, researchers are testing a robot that might be able to provide some of that rehabiliation. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Neville Hogan is a professor of mechanical engineering at MIT.<P> 

"Our goal is not to replace human therapists. What we're after instead is to provide tools to assist the clinician, to let the clinician get better use of their time."<P>  

The prototype robot is designed to exercise the arm. The patient sits at a table, grips a handle on the robotic arm, and slides it along a tabletop, following the progress on a computer screen. It looks and sounds a little like a video game.<P> 

<B>ambience</B> music<P>

If the robotic therapy proves useful, Dr. Hogan envisions a clinic of the future where a therapist could work with several patients at a time.<P>

"Each of the patients in the clinic is working individually with a robot, but the clinician is acting more as a supervisor, determining what should be done by the robot with a particular patient. But the therapist doesn't have to do the immediate manual work of actually moving the limbs, and doesn't have to do the work of keeping track of what's going on. The robot by definition has computer attached to it, that's how we get control, and so the robot at minimum provides a very efficient way of recording data and collating it and analyzing the progress of the patient as they recover from a stroke."<P> 

To learn more about this and other programs in our series, we'd like to invite you to visit our World Wide Web site. The address is http://www.pulseplanet.com.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

