<HTML><TITLE>1286</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1286</H3>

  

<CENTER>WRIST PHONE - Better Than Dick Tracy's</CENTER>


What does Dick Tracy do when he needs a little back-up? He calls on the old wrist radio, of course. And soon, you might be talking into your wrist as well. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"People have always, at least since Dick Tracy, envisioned some kind of wrist communicator. But there's a long distance between comic strips and real technology."<P> 

Greg Blonder is a researcher at AT&T Laboratories in New Jersey.  He and his colleagues have built a prototype wrist communicator that uses ordinary cordless phone technology.<P>

<B>ambience</B> wrist communicator call<P>

"The wrist communicator straps to your wrist like any other watch, but unlike most watches it had two wristbands. There's an inner band to hold it onto your wrist at all times, there's an outer band which is actually the handset that unfurls when the phone rings so that you can rotate it and place the speaker, which is at one end of the outer band, in the palm of your hand, and the microphone, which is attached to the joint of the outer and inner band."<P> 

So you bring the palm of your hand up to your ear, and you talk into the microphone on the wristband.  Now, while developing this prototype, the researchers found a few ways to improve on Dick Tracy's design.<P>

"One problem with the Dick Tracy watch is that it's not private. Everyone can hear the conversation, it's a speakerphone on your wrist. So we had to find a way to fold a handset to fit a wristwatch shape. Second of all, it's relatively inconvenient to hold your arm out in front of your body for a half-hour discussion. So we had to find a way so that you could actually rest your arm against your head when you speak. And lastly, it takes a lot of electrical power to make a speakerphone work in a noisy environment. And we wanted to have a wrist communicator that sounded every bit as good as your phone at home."<P> 

The product is still in development, and a cellular version may be available within five years.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

