<HTML><TITLE>1287</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1287</H3>

  

<CENTER>NANOELECTRONICS</CENTER>


The electronics in your VCR or home computer contain tiny components, many times smaller than the thickness of a human hair. But the electronics of the future will be even smaller. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> cryopump<P>

We're in the laboratory of Dr. Udi Meirav at the Weizmann Institute in Rehovot, Israel, where researchers are building some of the world's tiniest microcircuitry. It's a new field called nanoelectronics. Dr. Meirav cites two reasons for making electronics smaller and smaller.<P>

"It's only by making things sufficiently small that you can actually generate a very complex circuit with a lot of information in it.  But perhaps the more dominant motivation at present is speed. The smaller you make the components, in principle, the faster they can operate. And the reason for that is really quite simple, it's a question of how long, how much time it takes for electrical signals to propogate from one part of the circuit to the other.  And the smaller everything is, the less time it takes for these signals to propogate, and the entire calculation process becomes shorter."<P> 

But when you reach this scale of smallness, it isn't just the speed that changes.<P> 
 
"Beyond a certain level of miniaturization, it turns out that the fundamental laws of physics, of electricity, are going to look substantially different than as we have known them.  And that  means that if we continue to miniaturize circuits the way we have done until now, not only will they operate perhaps faster or in a more efficient way, but they will actually operate under completely different principles. And these principles have to be understood and studied thoroughly before we can actually make use of them and continue the process of miniaturization. So the study of physics of extrememly small electronic devices is really laying the foundation for the future of electronics."<P>  

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

