<HTML><TITLE>1288</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1288</H3>

  

<CENTER>NANOELECTRONICS - Ballistc Motion</CENTER>


The search for ever-faster electronic devices is taking microcircuitry to a new level of miniaturization - where electrons go ballistic. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> cryopump<P>

We're in a laboratory at the Weizmann Institute in Rehovot, Israel, where tiny nanoelectric components are manufactured. These semiconductor materials are even smaller than today's microcircuitry, but this degree of miniaturization can change the way electronics work. One fundamental difference has to do with the way that electrons travel through matter.  Senior scientist Dr. Udi Meirav.<P>

"Electrons move through solids in a sort of zig zag pattern.  They dont move in straight lines, they sort of bump into atoms and then keep on going and then bump into another atom. So they form this sort of funny jagged path. It turns out that if you make a device very small, smaller than the typical size of each one of these zig zags, then the entire principle of motion of electrons has a very different nature. Things like the relation between current and voltage, those things cease to work."<P>  

Now that could be good news or bad news for an electrical engineer.<P>

"Its bad news because you really have to rethink the relations between the various currents and voltages in your circuit.  But it could imply very very fast operation of circuits, because as soon as the components become smaller than the typical zig zag path, then electrons are actually moving in a straight line from one end to the other of your device.  This kind of motion is called ballistic motion, and it's a very efficient way of getting across a device. What ballistic motion of electrons gives is an enormous gain in speed of the device. More than you've bargained for in the first place by just making things smaller."<P>  

Understanding the way that ballistic motion works will be essential to reducing the  size of electronic devices in the future.<P> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

</HTML>
