<HTML><TITLE>1289</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1289</H3>

  

<CENTER>NANOELECTRONICS - How Small?</CENTER>


The first computers filled entire rooms. Today, an ordinary laptop is the size of a notebook. Well, how much smaller can electronics get? I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"Already today if you look into a desktop PC, and you open its box, youll find that its essentially empty. There's a tiny chip there, which is about the size of a coin, and that is everything, all the action takes place there.  The rest is just some peripherals which really do some very primitive power handling functions."<P>  

Dr. Udi Meirav is a senior scientist at the Weizmann Institute in Rehovot, Israel. He studies nanoelectronics - structures even smaller than the microelectronics in today's PCs or cell phones. The nanoelectronic components are so tiny they have to be built in a vacuum to make sure they're virtually free of contaminants. The pumps we're listening to are used to maintain the vacuum in the chambers where the devices are put together.<P>

<B>ambience</B> cryopump<P>

Now the smaller the electronic components are, the faster they can operate, at least in theory.  How tiny can you get? Well, Dr. Meirav says the possibilities could be unlimited.<P>

"There have been many predictions in the past as to how small things could be made. And time and again, these predictions have turned out to be wrong. Engineers have found ingenious ways how to continue the process of miniaturization beyond some I would say naive predictions, which said well, you couldn't go beyond this scale because of this or because of that. Clearly, you couldnt make things smaller than a single atom. But anything larger than a single atom, I think would be speculative to say its impossible to reduce anything below that scale."<P>  

To learn more about this and other programs in our series, we'd like to invite you to visit our World Wide Web site. The address is http://www.pulseplanet.com.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

