<HTML><TITLE>1290</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1290</H3>

  

<CENTER>REMOTE SURGERY</CENTER>


Before too long,  surgeons may be able to perform operations on patients located in another hospital - even in another city.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

It's called telesurgery - operations performed via long-distance.  A company in Menlo Park, California has developed a prototype named the Telepresence Surgery System.<P>

<B>ambience</B> control input<P>

The surgeon sits at a workstation that has mechanical arms with the handle ends of surgical instruments attached. There's also a three-dimensional video view of the surgical site. Dr. Ajit Shah, the director of SRI International's Medical Technology Laboratory, explains.<P>

"What I simply do is I sit down at the surgical workstation, and I grasp in my right hand a set of instrument handles that is standard on any set of surgical instruments, and I grab in my left hand a very similar set of instrument handles."<P>  

Positioned over the patient is another set of mechanical arms, and grasped in their hands are the business ends of the instruments - the blades, clamps or whatever. That side of the device is called the slave.<P>

"And now as I start to move my right hand and you look over at the slave side which is in fact positioned over the patient, my right hand makes motions that are in fact exactly recreated by the slave. As I pick up tissue with my right hand at the workstation, the slave picks up tissue in its right hand over the patient. And so when I look in my surgical field, that instrument at the slave side is a simple extension of what I'm holding or perceive to be holding in my right hand. And so as I carry out a range of surgical moves, it's a very natural process. It's intuitive and it literally feels as if I'm holding the instruments in my hand."<P> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

