<HTML><TITLE>1291</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1291</H3>

  

<CENTER>REMOTE SURGERY - Battlefield</CENTER>


Computer technology may one make it possible for doctors to perform operations on soldiers injured in battle, without having to evacuate the soldier to a hospital. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"Soldier goes out. Soldier gets wounded. Medic goes out in the battlefield, and has to try and find that soldier. Once he's found, he's got to try and triage this soldier along with all the other casualties that he has."<P> 

Dr. Ajit Shah is the director of the Medical Technology Laboratory at SRI International in Menlo Park, California.  Usually, he says, a wounded soldier has to wait until he can be transported to a hospital.<P>

"And  that period of time is a very critical period of time for the soldier. He typically can bleed to death or die from the injuries that he's sustained. And what this technology does is, it really changes that. The new scenario is: Soldier goes out in the battlefield. Gets wounded. The medic locates him. And immediately evacuates the crtically wounded soldier 100 yards or a couple of hundred meters to an armored vehicle which contains the Telepresence Surgery System in it."<P> 

Inside the armored vehicle would be an operating table with mechanical arms above it. These arms hold surgical instruments - such as a scalpel.  A safe distance away from the battlefield, a surgeon sits at a computer workstation monitoring the patient on his screen and manipulating the handles of the surgical instruments, which are attached to another set of mechanical arms. He performs the operation via remote control.<P>

"This soldier now can receive definitive medical care because back at a MASH unit, safe behind the battle lines, is a surgeon who's waiting, who's able to transfer his knowledge and his skills through the medic and through the system  to provide care to the wounded soldier."<P> 

Human tests of the Telepresence Surgery System are expected to take place over the next few years.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

