<HTML><TITLE>1292</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1292</H3>

  

<CENTER>DIAGNOSING BONE DISEASE WITH SOUND</CENTER>


A new technology is using sound to diagnose the bone disease osteoporosis. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Andrew Dimaroganas, a professor of mechanical design at Washington University in St. Louis, has developed a device that could offer a better way to test for osteoporosis. He taps on two ordinary china cups to demonstrate how his system works.<P>

"I have two china cups. One has a tiny crack, hairlike crack, barely visible. And then if you hit them, the one that does not have the crack produces a high-pitched sound with a long duration."<P>
 
<B>ambience</B> china cup: high-pitched sound<P>

"And then when we hit the other one that has the hairlike crack, it produces a low-pitched and short duration of sound like..."<P> 

<B>ambience</B> china cup:  dull sound<P>

The bones of a person who has the disease are porous - they have small holes in them. And just as the crack in the china cup dulls its sound, the cavities in the patient's bone dampen a sound that is sent through it.<P>

<B>ambience</B> sweep<P>

A pencil-sized metal stem is placed gently on the patient's skin above the bone to be tested, and this sweep of sound that we're listening to is produced by a computer. Another device, similar to a microphone, measures the sound that's been passed through the bone.<P>

"Now the bone has small cavities because of osteoporosis, and the more cavities we have the more energy they destroy as the sound goes through the bone. Therefore at the point of measurement, the sound that we get has less intensity. And the more cavities we have in the bone, the less intensity remains after passing through the bone."<P>  

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

