<HTML><TITLE>1293</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1293</H3>

  

<CENTER>INJECTABLE HAIR</CENTER>


A new process uses a person's own hair to create an injectable filler that can be used for cosmetic or medical procedures.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

These days, if you want to fill in wrinkles or undergo other cosmetic surgery, the material of choice is collagen - made from cow skin.  A new alternative material is being developed by Cheryl Blanchard, a scientist at the Southwest Research Institute in San Antonio.<P>

"Essentially we start out with a sample of human hair, and that is bleached and cleaned and cut up manually so that it's sort of a free-flowing powder. That material then gets put into a beaker with some type of organic solvent such as acetone, and it gets run through the homogenizer unit for a fairly long period of time until it's ground up into very very small particles."<P>  

<B>ambience</B> homogenizer<P>

"Hair is not an easy material to break down. It has a very high strength, a very high tensile strength. And so it takes quite a bit to break it down into smaller particles, and that turned out to be one of the hardest things for us to figure out how to do. Once the hair is broken down after a significantly long period of time in the homogenizer unit, we take the solution and centrifuge it, and then use the centrifuge to wash and clean the hair, so we'll centrifuge it and then fill the centrifuge tube back up, wash it out and then re-centrifuge it a number of times.  We then take it and dry it out, and then we're ready to re-suspend it in the injectable material, which would probably be a sterile saline, and it's ready for injection."<P>  

According to Dr. Blanchard, the hair-based material has an advantage over collagen -- it appears less likely to be rejected since it comes from a person's own body.  The filler has been tried on people on a limited basis with encouraging results.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

