<HTML><TITLE>1294</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1294</H3>

  

<CENTER>INJECTABLE HAIR - Applications</CENTER>


We typically think of our hair as either decorative or annoying, depending upon where it's growing and how it's behaving. Well now, thanks to a new process, our hair could be turned into something medically useful. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Cheryl Blanchard is a scientist at the Southwest Research Institute in San Antonio, Texas. She uses a person's own hair - which is made of the protein keratin - to create an injectable filler material for cosmetic and medical purposes.<P>

<B>ambience</B> homogenizer<P>
 
"Basically we take the hair, break it down, process it in a piece of equipment called a homogenizer so that it breaks it down into submicrometer-sized particles, or very very small particles. These particles are then sterilized and put back into an injectable carrier material such as sterile saline, and then that mixture is put into a syringe and used to inject for soft tissue augmentation purposes."<P>  

"The practical uses of this injectable material would be to fill in cosmetic defects in someone's face, such as to fill in a wrinkle, to fill in a scar, or to fill in a deficiency where someone wanted mass to be under their skin. There are also some medical applications, such as treating vocal cords that have lost their elasticity, or for treating female urinary incontinence.  There are some other uses for this material that we're beginning to find that are related to wound healing. Since the top layer of our skin is made up primarily of keratin, we've discovered that by taking this keratin-based paste it is very useful in wound healing applications."<P> 

There are other materials in use today for soft tissue augmentation, but the hair -based filler appears to be less likely to dissolve or cause an adverse immune reaction.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

