<HTML><TITLE>1265</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1265</H3>



<CENTER>JOINT REPAIR</CENTER>


When a joint is injured, it's often the cartilage that's least likely to
heal properly.  A new technique is being tried on racehorses that uses cell
transplants to better mend the damage. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the
Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Horse on Treadmill<P>

That's the sound of a  horse being tested on a treadmill to see how well
it's responding to a technique being developed by Dr. Alan Nixon, at
Cornell University's College of Veterinary Medicine. The technique involves
transplanting cartilage cells that will then grow and multiply.<P>

"Cartilage is a peculiar tissue in that once it's damaged, particularly in
an adult, there's a very poor response. As a result of that, we've been
seeking new methods to improve that type of cartilage surface for many
years. And this is by far the best of the techniques that we've evaluated.
We want cells that will produce new cartilage. And if you can improve the
quality of the activity of the cells that you transplant, you'll get a
better quality of cartilage."<P>

To improve the quality of cartilage cells, you grow them in the lab before
the transplant.<P>

"This is a cell-culture procedure where we either take calls from the same
animal or we take cells from another animal that has been destroyed for
other reasons. They provide some donor tissues where we harvest the cells
from the cartilage surfaces. We treat them in the laboratory to get the
numbers increased. And when their numbers are up, then we'll transplant
them. And that pool of new cells essentially helps to provide a much
improved cartilage healing response."<P>

The method seems to be working well with Dr. Nixon's horse patients. And a
similar technique is being tried on people with encouraging results.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

