<HTML><TITLE>1266</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1266</H3>



<CENTER>JOINT REPAIR - Arthritis Prevention</CENTER>


A new technique for repairing cartilage in horses may one day help prevent
some forms of arthritis in humans. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse
of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Alan Nixon is an orthopedic surgeon at the College of Veterinary
Medicine at Cornell University. He's working with a new form of treatment
on injured horses in an effort to help their cartilage heal better.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Horse on Treadmill<P>

That's the sound of a horse being tested on a treadmill,  to help measure
how effective the treatment is.<P>

"New methods of treating knee injuries are important because cartilage
inherently has very poor healing capacity. The nature of the healing
response is usually so bad that many of them develop arthritis. And with
the development of arthritis they become quite lame and there is very
little treatment-wise that can be done to alleviate the lameness."<P>

Dr. Nixon's technique involves taking cartilage cells from a donor animal,
treating them with growth agents to make them more active, and then
transplanting the cells into the injured cartilage.<P>

"Our primary aim in any of these transplantation techniques is to prevent
the development of arthritis. Once the arthritis is set up, there's really
no turning back. It's a one-way street."<P>

There's hope that this technique may eventually be used to prevent some
forms of arthritis in people.<P>

"Whenever you can heal a cartilage defect when it's fresh, before it
becomes arthritis, then you avert the development of arthritis. The
technology   were working on is designed primarily to prevent that
arthritis from developing. By doing that, whether it's for animals or
whether it's for people, we're really improving the quality of people's
lives, the quality of animals' lives. And I think the technology should
carry us through to the point where we can prevent a substantial amount of
the arthritis that is occurring."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

