<HTML><TITLE>1267</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1267</H3>



<CENTER>TIME REVERSAL MIRROR</CENTER>


If you hold an open book up to a mirror, the words are seen written
backwards. Now, imagine what would happen if you could do the same thing
with sound. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, ".tenalP eht fo esluP eht si siht dna ,renzteM miJ m'I"<P>

That's what it sounds like if you play a tape backwards in real time. But
some French scientists have developed a device that reverses sound waves
instantaneously. They call it the Acoustic Time Reversal Mirror. Didier
Casserau works in the engineering school at the University of Paris.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, TRM<P>

"In fact the basic principle of the time reversal mirror is very similar as
reversing a tape. But the problem is much more complex because it's not a
physical tape."<P>

First, an ultrasonic wave is directed at the time-reversal mirror. The
device then reverses the acoustic signals, creating a new wave that goes
back to the initial source.  So unlike that tape we just heard where you
had to play back the entire phrase to hear the first words spoken
backwards,  the time-reversal mirror reverses each acoustical signal at the
moment it occurs. The technology could be used to detects flaws in
metal.<P>

"This technology detects the small defects in the metal by first
illuminating the medium with an initial acoustic beam that moves in the
material. Then the defect generates a reflected wave that moves back in the
direction of the time reversal mirror.  And this allows detection of
defects in the metal. There are some other technologies that use sound to
detect defects in metal, but the advantage of the time reversal mirror is
that it allows detection of smaller defects and it is a more precise
method."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

