<HTML><TITLE>1268</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1268</H3>



<CENTER>TIME REVERSAL MIRROR - Kidney Stones</CENTER>


A new technology  could offer a better way to break up kidney stones. I'm
Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Didier Casserau works in the engineering school at the University of Paris.
He's  developing a device called an Acoustic Time Reserval Mirror. It takes
a sound wave and, just like a mirror does with a visual image, sends back a
signal that reverses the acoustical image of the original source.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, TRM<P>

"The time reversal mirror first observes the sound wave generated by a
source, then it reverses all the electronic signals to generate a new wave
that moves back to what's the initial source location."<P>

One use for the technology could be to detect defects in metal. It may also
be effective as a new treatment for kidney stones.<P>

"The time reversal mirror first illuminates the body,  a wave is created in
the body, and this wave is reflected by the kidney stone. The time reversal
mirror pushes this wave back and concentrates high energy in the
neighborhood of the kidney stone, and this breaks it up."<P>

Ultrasound is already used to break up kidney stones, but the time reversal
mirror technology could have some advantages over current methods.<P>

"At this time the kidney stones can be treated using ultrasound with
devices that generate high energy near the kidney stone, but the problem is
that the patient breathes during operation and thus the kidney stone moves.
The time reversal mirror is better than other technologies,  first because
it is more precise to detect the kidney stone, and second because it can
follow the kidney stone in real time such that all the wave always reaches
the stone."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

