<HTML><TITLE>1269</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1269</H3>



<CENTER>MICROBIAL MATS</CENTER>


Need any help cleaning up contaminated water? Well, consider employing the
services of some blue-green algae and a few other handy microbes.  I'm Jim
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Water Dripping<P>

We're listening to water dripping through a microbial mat, a layered colony
of living microbes that consume contaminants. This mat was grown in Dr.
Judith Bender's research lab at Clark Atlanta University, but the idea
comes from nature.<P>

"Natural microbial mats are mixed microbial ecosystems. They're dominated
by blue-green algae, and they have other kinds of bacteria that naturally
associate with it.  They're found in tidal zones, but actually you can find
them in freshwater areas, too. You can find them in parking lots."<P>

Dr. Bender and her colleagues construct microbial mats using fermented
grass clippings dosed with blue-green algae and whatever other
microorganisms are needed for a particular cleanup job.<P>

"We find these microbial mats in nature. We look at what they do best. We
look at what they do naturally, spontaneously. Basically, we try to
encourage that. By just improving the component microbes we can design them
to do specific jobs. For instance, in constructing mats to take heavy
metals, toxic metals, out of water, we work with integrating certain
bacteria that will produce sulfide. Now the sulfide will precipitate
lead."<P>

That means the lead is separated from the water, and concentrated into a
solid form that can then easily be removed.<P>

"So in that way we've made a special mat to do a special job. And we do
this over and over again for all the different kinds of contaminants that
we have a market for."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

