<HTML><TITLE>1270</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1270</H3>



<CENTER>MICROBIAL MATS - Uses</CENTER>


Microorganisms such as algae and bacteria can be helpful in the effort to
clean up environmental contamination. And they're versatile, too. I'm Jim
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Judith Bender is a professor at Clark Atlanta University. She and her
colleagues grow microbial mats - colonies of microbes that consume
contaminants found in water.

<B>ambience</B>, Water Dripping<P>

They first run water through mats in the lab to determine what contaminants
can be removed.<P>

"We have looked at a number of very toxic organic materials, and the mats
have handled all of them.  Now, included in this array is TNT, explosives,
the propellents that propel rockets. We have looked at oil."<P>

Mats can be designed to remove inorganic materials, too.<P>

"Heavy metals such as lead, cadmium, chromium, iron, toxic metals such as
radionuclides, uranium. The mats handle them very well."<P>

Using microbes to clean up contamination isn't a new idea.  But the mats
have some advantages over other methods of bioremediation.<P>

"You can put them exactly where you want them and for the most part they
stay there. Another advantage is that since they provide their own
essential nutrients, they don't have to be fed to keep them alive. In terms
of cost, this is a great advantage. Then the third issue is disposal. So
when we look at how mats mineralize organics so that they don't have to be
disposed of, in the case of metals, they concentrate the metals in very
small areas so that minimizes the disposal cost, these are real practical
advantages."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

</HTML>



