<HTML><TITLE>1271</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1271</H3>



<CENTER>MICROBIAL MATS - More Than Fish Food</CENTER>


Want to whip up a microbial mat?  Just take some fresh grass clippings,
ferment them, then add a pinch of blue-green algae and other microbes.  I'm
Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Microbial mats are colonies of microorganisms such as algae and bacteria.
In the wild, they exist as natural ecosystems. In the laboratory, the
makeup of the mats can be customized to consume hazardous materials found
in water.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Water Bubbling<P>

Dr. Judith Bender concocts microbial mats in her lab at Clark Atlanta
University.<P>

"We give them some simple minerals on which to grow, and the proper light
and let them do the rest. Now mats are both photosynthetic, that is they
make their own carbohydrates, and nitrogen-fixing, which means they can
make their own protein. So they don't need a lot of feed."<P>

Once the mats are placed in a contaminated area, the microbes get to work
consuming the hazardous materials. Like so many recipes, the one for the
mats was discovered by accident.<P>

"We began the whole project of making blue-green algae mats as a fish feed
project. We were working at that time in the Dominican Republic under a
grant from the Agency for International Development. And the objective was
to make a very low-cost, simple fish feed. And that led us to the grass
clippings, it led us to the blue-green algae, which can make all its
nutrients and pack it in and then the fish eat these nutrients. And it all
worked fine and the fish grew very well, and when we returned to the lab we
found, quite by accident, that these same fish feed mats took out heavy
metals. And then several years later, we discovered that they degraded
oil."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

</HTML>



