<HTML><TITLE>1273</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1273</H3>



<CENTER>SULPHUR LIGHT - Color</CENTER>


One of the limitations of artificial light is that colors don't look quite
the same as they do in sunlight. Well, now a new light allows for a truer
perception of color. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the
Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Light Turning on<P>

We're listening to the sound of a microwave source that's part of a sulphur
light. Michael Ury, the vice president of research and development at
Fusion Lighting in Rockville, Maryland, explains how his company's new
lighting technology works.<P>

"The microwave energy creates an electric field, just as it does in your
home microwave oven, and in a home microwave oven the electric field causes
molecules to vibrate and your food is heated. In this case, the electric
field accelerates electrons which strike molecules of sulphur. They cause
the molecules to be excited, and they emit light. I'd say the light is
closest to sunlight, but it's slightly greenish in color. If you are
inside, your eye adjusts in a matter of seconds. The light appears more
pleasing than fluorescent, because it's truly full color. Is the light more
pleasing than an incandescent source? Well, I think that depends on who's
looking at it. It's a far superior light to work under. You see more
clearly under this light."<P>

Mr. Ury acknowledges that the light isn't right for every circumstance. But
there are applications for which it seems to have a clear advantage.<P>

"Put it this way. If you're out in a parking lot looking for your car at
night, you find that your car has disappeared, because the high pressure
sodium lamp is deficient in the blue and the green, it has a fair amount of
red content. This lamp has all the colors. If we were to light up a parking
lot with this light, you'll find your car, you'll recognize the color."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

