<HTML><TITLE>1274</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1274</H3>



<CENTER>SULPHUR LIGHT - Energy</CENTER>


A new, energy-efficient lamp produces high-powered lighting using sulphur
and microwaves.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

"Twenty-five percent of the energy consumption in this country goes to
power lighting in commercial buildings and residences. An additional five
percent might be used for the air conditioning to cool that lighting. Why
haven't more energy efficient light sources caught on? Well, one of the
reasons is people like the continuous spectrum of an incandescent source.
They sort of like the color."<P>

Michael Ury is the vice president of research and development at Fusion
Lighting in Rockville, Maryland. They've developed a golf-ball size light
bulb, filled with sulphur, that gives off light when it's flooded with
microwaves, the same energy source used in microwave ovens.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Light Turning on<P>

"The sulphur light source today, is as good as the best light source out
there in terms of energy conservation for reasonably good color. It runs at
about 1350 watts consumption, and produces 100 lumens per watt. Compare
that to the 100-watt incadescent bulb, which produces 17 lumens per watt,
and you can see the remarkable advantage in energy efficiency."<P>

In addition to being more powerful than conventional light sources, the
sulphur lamp is expected to last a long time.<P>

"The bulb itself should last at least 60,000 hours. We honestly don't
understand the failure mechanisms. We don't see any failure mechanisms. But
the microwave source, unfortunately, we estimate will last between 15 and
20,000 hours, and it will have to be replaced."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

