<HTML><TITLE>1275</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1275</H3>



<CENTER>ADVANCED SAFETY VEHICLE</CENTER>


Most cars will tell you if you've left your lights on or run out of oil.
Well, the car of the future might be even smarter and safer. I'm Jim
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

An experimental car with 17 new safety features is being developed by the
Toyota Motor Corporation. One of the systems monitors the operator's pulse
and steering, and if it thinks the driver is getting drowsy, the car sounds
a warning.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Drowsy Driver Second Warning<P>

...and vibrates the driver's seat.
Another system uses radar to look up ahead for stationary objects like a
tree or a stopped car. Company spokesperson Frances Champion explains.<P>

"If at a certain distance the radar system realizes that that object is not
moving, it will actually give the driver a warning, saying to either slow
down or to try to divert the car away from the object. At a certain point,
the car will sense that a collision is imminent, and will apply the brakes
regardless of what the driver does, and it will stop the car short of the
barrier."<P>

If the car does hit someone or something, it's designed to minimize
injuries and damage.<P>

"If, by chance, a driver hits a pedestrian on the front of the car, there
is actually a sensor in the bumper which upon impact inflates the airbag on
the hood of the car and cushions the pedestrian's fall to keep them from
hitting the hood as well as the windshield."<P>

Now, the car is strictly experimental at this point, but these features may
be standard equipment someday.<P>

"We have developed these types of experimental vehicles in the past, and
some of the ideas that come out of past vehicles are currently on the road.
For example, airbags, or ABS brake systems."<B>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

