<HTML><TITLE>1276</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1276</H3>



<CENTER>ADVANCED SAFETY VEHICLE - Drowsy Driver</CENTER>

Even the safest vehicle can't protect you if you fall asleep at the wheel -
that is, unless the car itself can wake you up. I'm Jim Metzner, and this
is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

An experimental car is being developed with more than a dozen high-tech
safety features, including one designed to jolt a sleepy driver back to
alertness. Frances Champion is with Toyota Motor Corporation.<P>

"The Drowsy Driver Warning System monitors a car's steering operation as
well as a person's pulse."<P>

The driver wears a wristband with a heartbeat sensor, and another device
monitors the car's steering.<P>

"So for example if a person is driving and their alertness starts to fall,
then the system senses that and alerts the driver with a warning system,
basically telling the driver to pull over, and take a break, get a cup of
coffee."<P>

There's a warning bell<P>
(B>ambience</B>, Bell-1st warning<P>
and a picture of a coffee cup flashes on the dashboard.<P>

"If the driver chooses to ignore that warning system and continues to
drive, the car gives the driver a second warning, and it's an audiovisual
signal<P>
<B>ambience</B>, Beeps - 2nd warning<P>
coupled with a vibrating of the  actual seat.<P>
<B>ambience</B>, Vibration -  2nd warning<P>
So it tries to wake up the driver. If the driver continues on, and decides
to ignore the second warning, the car then comes to a complete stop by
actually applying an electronic braking system."<P>
<B>ambience</B>, Beep, Alarm - Car Stops<P>
When the system applies the brakes, it sounds another alarm, and flashes
the car's hazard lights.<P>

"The premise was that  for a driver to continue driving is actually more
dangerous. For a drowsy driver to keep driving and possibly swerve over to
the other lane, than to have the vehicle completely stop."<P>

The Drowsy Driver Warning System, like other features in the Advanced
Safety Vehicle, is in the prototype stage, with no immediate plans for
commercial use.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

