<HTML><TITLE>1277</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1277</H3>



<CENTER>ADVANCED SAFETY VEHICLE - Too Much Safety?</CENTER>


A new experimental car is loaded with safety systems that can rouse a
sleepy driver, put out a fire or stop the vehicle before it hits a tree.
But is it possible to make a car too self-sufficient? I'm Jim Metzner, and
this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Car Sounds<P>

The Advanced Safety Vehicle, or ASV, is a concept car being developed by
Toyota Motor Corporation. Spokesperson Frances Champion explains where the
idea came from.<P>

"It was originally prompted by the Japanese Ministry of Transport to
enhance the intelligence and the safety of automobiles by fully exploiting
electronic technologies. We developed the ASV based first of all on the
philosophy that safety is the responsibility of the individual, but
realizing that humans do have flaws and that we do make mistakes, Toyota
decided to develop the ASV to try to compensate for those driver
errors."<P>

But if cars get too smart, there's a danger that drivers may become too
complacent.<P>

"There's always a possibility of implementing too many safety features into
a vehicle. Psychologically, if a driver gets into a car and knows that the
car is going to back him or her up 100 percent, there is a possibilty that
they may not be as careful or as cautious when they step into a car. So we
of course want to develop safety features inasmuch as we can, and as
technology allows. However there is also that feature of human psychology
that we have to take into consideration. When is it too many systems in
place, and when is it just the right amount."<P>

The ASV is still experimental, and its safety systems aren't expected to be
in place anytime soon.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

