<HTML><TITLE>1278</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1278</H3>



<CENTER>LEECH RESEARCH</CENTER>


You probably never thought much about how a leech swims - as long as you
can swim faster. Well, some engineers are studying the way that these
wormlike creatures move in the hope that they might one day help solve some
difficult engineering challenges. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of
the Planet.<P>

Dr. Stephen DeWeerth is an assistant professor of electrical and computer
engineering at the Georgia Institute of Technology. He explains why he
picked leeches as the model for his research.<P>

"First of all, there's been a fair amount of study done on the leech's
nervous system. So that makes it good for us. Each of its individual
segments has a set of neurons that are replicated in each segment
basically, and those set of neurons are interconnected in a very regular
way. And that's what causes the wavelike motion that happens when the leech
swims. And so for us that's very nice, that regular structure helps us to
build models of the leech."<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Motor<P>

That's the sound of a motor being used to drive a mechanical model of leech
locomotion. Dr. DeWeerth figures that if he can actually build a model of a
biological system, he's that much closer to understanding how it works.<P>

"Biological systems are wonderful. They solve tasks that we have no idea as
engineers how to solve right now. I mean you can look at the most complex
system like the human visual system or the simplest systems like swimming
in a leech and just wonder, how do these systems do what they do? Certainly
biology can solve some very hard problems and so we're hoping that we can
find some ways that biology is better than engineered systems are right
now."<P>

That knowledge might someday be used to build better robots, or more
natural prosthetic limbs. We'll hear more in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

