<HTML><TITLE>1279</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1279</H3>



<CENTER>LEECH RESEARCH - Applications</CENTER>


The swimming style of the lowly leech is helping engineers learn more about
the mechanics of biological systems, and that information could help them
build better prosthetic limbs. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of
the Planet.<P>

Dr. Stephen DeWeerth is an assistant professor of electrical and computer
engineering at the Georgia Institute of Technology. He and his colleagues
build models that mimic how a leech swims.<P>

<B>ambience</B>, Motor<P>

That's the sound of a motor used to drive one of the mechanical models Dr.
DeWeerth uses in his research. The idea is to learn more about this
relatively simple system of locomotion.<P>

"If we can understand how biological systems work, whether it be the swim
system in the leech or the visual system in a human, whatever. If we can
understand these, we can apply what we've learned to solving hard
engineering problems.  Because obviously, biological systems like a human
hand can do very precise, very careful, very gentle motions, that it's very
hard to get out of a robot, for example. And if we can understand that
control of movement that happens in biological systems, we'll go a long way
to being able to build much better engineered systems."<P>

The research might lead to building better robots, or more useful
artificial limbs.<P>

"If we can understand how the motor system works in a human, we might be
able to build a better prosthetic limb that acts much more like a human
limb and that interfaces to the human nervous system better.  And so even
though right now we're modeling the swimming of a leech, understanding that
motor system will help us understand how a human spinal cord works better
or how a human muscle works better. And all of it will lead to hopefully,
better solutions to the problems."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for
better living.<P>

