<HTML><TITLE>1250</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1250</H3> 

<CENTER>ANTIBIOTIC RESISTANCE</CENTER>

Since the discovery of penicillin, antibiotics have saved countless lives. But some 
of the organisms they kill are becoming resistant. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the 
Pulse of the Planet.<p>


<B>ambience</B> gas chromatograph <p>

That's the sound of a gas chromatograph, a device that's used to help identify 
bacteria. Dr. Clay Walker, a professor of Oral Biology at the University of Florida's 
dental school, works with the chromatograph to study bacteria that have developed 
a resistance to antibiotics. <p>


"Most antibiotics either inhibit bacteria or else they kill the bacteria. When we're speaking of antibiotic resistance it that means the bacteria are not affected by the antibiotic in question." <p> 


So how do bacteria develop a resistance to antibiotics?<p>


"The bacteria acquire resistant DNA elements from other bacteria. We may have the transfer of an individual gene or we may have the transfer of a block of genes so that bacteria acquires resistance not only to the antibiotic in question, but also to other antibiotics as well."  <p>

"Resistance to an antibiotic is coded by one or more genes in the bacteria. Now these genes for resistance can be transferred from one bacterium to another bacterium. It can cross species lines, and there's indication that it can pass from man to animals or animals to man. So, the bacteria don't really care who the host is." <p> 


So if antibiotic resistance can pass between humans and cattle, for example, the 
effects could be far-reaching. We'll hear more in future programs. <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <p>

</HTML>
