<HTML><TITLE>1251</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1251</H3>

  

<CENTER>ANTIBIOTIC RESISTANCE - Interspecies Transfer</CENTER>

As the use of anitibiotics has increased, more and more bacteria have become resistant to the drugs. Now, a researcher in Florida has found evidence that antibiotic resistance can be passed back and forth from people to cattle. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>

<B>ambience</B> cow sounds<p>

Dr. Clay Walker is a professor of Oral Biology at the University of Florida's dental school.<p> 

"We were looking at an organism that's implicated in diseases in the head and neck. And it has a fairly unique gene that makes it resistant to the tetracyclines. Tetracyclines are a broad group of antibiotics that in the past were effective against most bacteria, but aren't any longer because the genes that code for resistance are so widespread."<p> 

The researchers analyzed the gene for resistance to antibiotics, and they started to look for a similar gene found in the bacteria of other organisms. They discovered one -- in the stomach of cattle.<p>

"And we found that this gene from the cattle and this gene in our oral bacteria, 
were very, very  similar. When we see 98, 99 percent similarity, it means that these 
genes are essentially the same."<p> 

The question is, how did the same gene end up in the bacteria found in both people and cows? <p>

"The obvious jump is, did we acquire this gene for bacterial resistance to antibiotics from livestock. We know livestock in feed lots are given antibiotics to 
promote weight gain. And we know they carry alot of bacteria that are reistant to the 
tetracylines. So we could say, we acquired this gene from the bacteria associated with cattle.  Well, the cattle could have acquired it from us. The guy mixing the feed could have sneezed, coughed in the feed, and put some of his bacteria there which the cattle took in and the gene was transferred to the cattle bacteria."<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<p>

</HTML>
