<HTML><TITLE>1252</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1252</H3>

  

<CENTER>ANTIBIOTIC RESISTANCE - Need for new antibiotics</CENTER>

As more bacteria become resistant to antibiotics, the need is growing for new varieties of these drugs.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>

<B>ambience</B> gas chromatograph <p>

That's a gas chromatograph, a device that can help scientists identify bacteria. Dr. 
Clay Walker, a professor of Oral Biology at the University of Florida, is using it to 
study how bacteria transfer the ability to resist antibiotics.<p>

"We refer to it as congregation. Essentially, two bacteria bump together and there is some signal given off and they will exchange DNA." <p>

And with this sharing of information, even more bacteria are able to resist antibiotics. <p>

"I think it's extremely serious. We don't have any new antibiotics in the immediate pipeline. We got rather complacent in the 70s and the 80s, we thought we could treat anything with an antibiotic, and there wasn't an emphasis on pharmaceutical companies to develop new antibiotics, because they're very expensive, it's a long process before they get approved. We're seeing a resurgence of tuberculosis that is very drug resistant. We're seeing a resurgence of bacterial pneumonia, which is also drug resistant. There's a fear that we're going to see more and more serious diseases that are drug resistant, and we won't be able to treat them." <p> 


Another challenge is that as the world's human population becomes increasingly mobile, bacteria have become more mobile, too.<p>


"We can encounter a bacterium somewhere in the world that's resistant to all the antibiotics that we have. It can be transferred to this country, to any other country, and spread very rapidly through the population."<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

