<HTML><TITLE>1253</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1253</H3>

  

<CENTER>WATER CAR</CENTER>


You've heard of gasoline, diesel fuel and ethanol. Well, now get ready for a fuel 
that's half water. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>

<B>ambience</B> diesel engine <p>

That's a diesel engine being tested at A-55, a company in Reno, Nevada. Its fuel is 
a mixture of water and naphtha, a petroleum by-product. Company CEO Rudolph Gunnerman explains.<p>

"Naptha is a distilled product, clear in color, which comes out of raw oil."<p>

Now, normally oil and water don't mix. What makes it happen in this case is Mr. 
Gunnerman's secret formula - a mixing agent that blends the two together. The result is a fuel that can be used in diesel engines or in spark-ignited engines like those found in most cars.<p>

"This fuel can be used by the general public or fleet operators for automobiles which are spark-ignited. It can be used for lawnmowers, it can be used for outboard motor engines, it can be used for weed whackers. That's on the spark-ignited side. It can be used in diesel engines, for highway building equipment, off-road equipment, or if it is trucks, in all sizes and shapes and forms, or if it is railroads, railroad engines are a little bit larger, and it can be used in those. Eventually we probably can use it also in ships." <p>

Mr. Gunnerman has high hopes for the fuel, which he says burns cleaner than most 
existing fuels and is less flammable. <p>

"It will be less expensive than the existing, it will be safer than the existing, and 
it will be more pollution-free than the existing by at least 50 percent."<p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <p>

