<HTML><TITLE>1254</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1254</H3>

  

<CENTER>CONTRABAND DETECTOR</CENTER>

The x-ray machine has long been a commonplace part of airport security. But x-
rays can't detect everything, so researchers are working on a new way to scan for 
contraband. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>

<B>ambience</B> accelerator <p> 

We're listening to a small particle accelerator at MIT that's the basis for an 
experimental scanning system. Richard Lanza, a research scientist in the Nuclear 
Engineering Department, describes how the system works. <p>

(36.02) "Our accelerator produces particles which then hit a target, and the target  
produces these neutral particles, neutrons. They're the constituent of the nucleus 
of atoms, so they're all arounds us.  The neutrons travel into material, and when 
they hit the nucleus of an element such as nitrogen, they will interact with that 
and in that process give off a characteristic wavelength of gamma ray. And it's 
that energy and wavelength which we detect." <p>

The idea is that if you could analyze the elemental makeup of the contents of a 
suitcase or cargo container, you should be able to determine what's inside. <p>

"We're looking for materials that could be explosives, could be contraband, 
could be drugs, could be whatever. And by using this technique, we're able to 
analyze materials without opening up a container." <p>

The technology would enable security systems to detect what x-rays can't. <p>

"X-rays basically as they function now tell you the shape of things. And 
what they can tell you is that there're materials there which stop x-rays.  And 
that might be for example weapons, guns, whatever. And they're much less able 
however to tell you about plastic materials. And unfortunately we live in a world 
where explosives are plastic.  So traditional x-ray techniques can't see the plastic 
at all." <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <p>

