<HTML><TITLE>1255</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1255</H3>

  

<CENTER>CONTRABAND DETECTOR - Analyzing with Radiation</CENTER>

A new kind of scanner uses weapons technology to analyze the compositions of 
different materials.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


<B>ambience</B> accelerator<p>

"This sort  of accelerator was originally designed for the Star Wars program, to be the basis for particle beam weapons. And in fact it's designed specifically to have a very high current, to produce a lot of particles and also to be very compact."  <p>


Richard Lanza is a principal investigator in the Nuclear Engineering Department at MIT.  The accelerator system we're listening to produces a beam of neutrons. The 
neutrons interact with the material being scanned, and that gives off a kind of 
radiation which can be detected and analyzed. That enables researchers to identify 
what elements - such as nitrogen or sulphur - might be present.<p>


"The original design here was primarily for security and contraband detection, but we have looked at other things, any place where you want to make an evaluation of materials sort of in a bulk. Our problem is go out into for example, a mine, or the head of a mine where stuff is coming out and find out what's in there in the field." <p> 

The technology could be used in airport security, in mining and in structural analysis, just to name a few possibilities. But wherever it's used, safety is a prime concern. <p>   


"Any techniques, whether it's x-rays or this technique, which is neutrons, any of these techniques are using radiation, and you have to make sure the radiation levels for the general public are way, way down. That's a primary issue. You have to have the radiation and make it safe, you have to make sure you don't put so much radiation in that you could change the contents of somebody's suitcase, make their suitcase radioactive or something of that sort. So those are all issues that have to be addressed, and that's why making a sensitive detector is so important, because the 
more sensitive it is, the less radiation you have to use."  <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living. <p>

