<HTML><TITLE>1256</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1256</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTERS LEARN LANGUAGE</CENTER>

As smart as computers sometimes seem, they still can't learn what human children learn by age two or three - how to use language. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


<B>ambience</B> computer says "Mama"  <p>

Dr. Eric Brill is an assistant professor in computer science at Johns Hopkins University.  <p>

"The main hurdle that we have to overcome in order to get a computer to interact with us using natural language - human language - is to get that knowledge of language into the computer. And that's what we're working on here. This is a real bottleneck. How do you teach the computer language? It's an amazing problem. Because somehow, all of us as children trivially learned language, when we were very very young. It was not a painful process, presumably. We all did it successfully, and yet we're having real difficulty getting computers to understand language."  <p>

In an effort to help a computer teach itself, Dr. Brill has given a computer about a 
million words of text from the newspaper.<p>

"If you think back to fifth or sixth grade when your grade school teacher asked you 
to diagram sentences and you could be graded on that, we basically do the same thing. 
The computer is given a large set of sentences that have been diagrammed, so to speak, by linguists, by experts in language, who draw the structure of every sentence. They take sentences from the Wall Street Journal and draw the underlying linguistic structure of it and then the computer can use these structures as a basis to try to learn the rules of language."  <p>

And just like grammar school, the computer is graded on how it learns the rules - how 
well it can apply them to new, undiagrammed sentences.  So far, Dr. Brill says it's been about 85 percent accurate. <p>

"To improve the scores we need to do a number of things. The main thing is probably just to give it more data. "<p>


Once the computer has learned the rules of language, the next step will be getting them to actually converse naturally.<p>

<B>ambience</B> computer says "What's happening, dude?"<p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living. <p>

