<HTML><TITLE>1257</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1257</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTERS LEARN LANGUAGE - Natural Communication</CENTER>


If only we could talk to computers in human language instead of having to learn theirs, wouldn't life in cyberspace be simpler? I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


"People have always wanted to have computers understand language. The problem has been that we, as people, although we all know language very well, we don't know what we know. So if you want to sit down in front of a computer and tell it, 'I know language, here's what I know. Let me teach it to you so that you can know it,' that's a very difficult thing to do."  <p>

Dr. Eric Brill is an assistant professor in computer science at Johns Hopkins University. He says the first step in communicating with a computer is to teach it the rules of language. So he's given a computer a million words of text and programmed it to learn those rules by example.<p>


"We'd like to be able to teach computers to learn language for a number of reasons. Mainly because we all speak language very easily. That's the most natural modality for humans. When we interact with people it's natural and pleasant and not stressful because we use language, which we're used to doing. When we interact with computers typically it is stressful and there's a big learning curve on learning how to do that.  And we'd like to overcome that by speaking to computers, hopefully, just like 
we speak to people." <p>

"This means that, first of all, computers could be used by anybody. You don't 
have to be an expert in computers, you don't have to learn a computer language. There 
are no skills that need to be learned. You would just sit down and, for instance, ask the computer, 'I'm trying to find a recipe for baking brownies.' And it would then do the work. And you don't have to be smart to know what the commands you have to give to get this are, you just have to speak in the natural way, just as you would if you were asking your grandmother, let's say, for a recipe for brownies." <p> 


<B>ambience</B> computer says "Here's the recipe."<p>


To learn more about this and other programs in our series, we'd like to invite you to 
visit our World Wide Web site. The address is http://www.pulseplanet.com.<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<p>

