<HTML><TITLE>1258</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1258</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMMUNICATING WITH CHAOS</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> controlled chaos <p>

We're listening to the sounds of controlled chaos. Now, that may seem like a contradiction in terms, but a researcher has shown that controlling chaos is not 
only possible - it could be useful. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the 
Planet.<p>


Chaos in its scientific sense is somewhere between order and anarchy. It's a specific type of behavior that follows complex but often predictable rules.<p>


"In a chaotic system such as the electronic circuit that we have here in the lab, the output of the circuit, its wave form, is very complex naturally."  <p>


Scott Hayes is an electronics engineer at the Army Research Lab in Adelphi, Maryland. He's found a way to influence this chaotic electronic circuit using small nudges of power. Once it's under control, the circuit can be made to carry information.<p>


"What we do is we apply very small current pulses to the circuit in a predetermined way that will influence the behavior to carry a certain message. So, the wave form is very complicated in the first place, and we simply influence it to carry digital information by using very tiny control pulses." <p>


This technique could improve communications technology - such as the equipment 
that transmits this radio broadcast  - by making it simpler and more efficient.<p>


"A typical application would be where you needed a transmitter to generate a digital signal, and the output signal needed to be fairly high in power, instead of using a typical technique of amplifying the signal through several inefficient stages, you could produce the signal in one step by having the transmitter be a chaotic electronic oscillator. One example of a possible application of this could be a fiberoptic transmission system where you have a very simple filter that can remove the noise and boost the signal, and retransmit it." <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

