<HTML><TITLE>1259</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1259</H3>

  
<CENTER>COMMUNICATING WITH CHAOS - The Butterfly Effect</CENTER>

When scientists talk about chaos, they don't mean rush hour traffic or your life on 
Monday morning.  They're describing systems that are complicated - but not random. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <p>

<B>ambience</B> controlled chaos <p>

That's the sound of an electronic circuit at Scott Hayes' laboratory at the Army 
Research Lab in Adelphi, Maryland. A physicist might call the circuit chaotic - but Mr. Hayes has it under control.<p>

"I guess some people would think it is a paradox to think that you can control chaos, but actually it's one of the propeties of chaos that's very important that  makes it easy to control. And that is that any small perturbation, any small tap given to a chaotic system is amplified quickly in time."  <p>

Scientists often explain this property by talking about something they call the 
butterfly effect.<p>

"The butterfly effect is the idea that in a chaotic system, a very small change 
to the system applied at a certain point in time makes the future change in a very 
dramatic way. Something as small as a butterfly flapping its wings now might affect 
the weather system on a global scale six months in the future. <p>

"For example the electronic circuit that I have in my lab is very sensitive to tiny current pulses injected into one of its capacitors, so we can inject these tiny current pulses  and influence the behavior of the system, and that's precisely because it's sensitive to these small perturbations. So one of the properties of chaos, the fact that it's very sensitive to these small perturbations is what makes it in some sense easy to control."  <p>


Why control chaos? Well, a chaotic circuit could lead to better communications 
technology.<p>

"The small control pulses that we apply to the circuit, like the flapping of the 
butterfly's wings have a tiny effect on the behavior at the time that they're done, but in the future they influence the behavior in a dramatic way, and we can cause it to carry a certain sequence of information." <p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<p>

