<H3>Program #1260</H3>

  

<CENTER>ELECTROSTATIC FIELD SENSING - Music</CENTER>


It may one day be possible to control a computer with just a wave of your hand. 
I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <p>


Peter Rogers is a researcher at Hewlett-Packard's lab in Bristol, England. He and 
his colleagues figure that, as computers get smaller, it's going to be harder to use 
a keyboard or a mouse to communicate with them.<p>


"So you have to think of new ways of using what's available to get information into the machines.  And one way is to think about using the space around devices as the control region."  <p>


Mr. Rogers is studying a way to control computers by generating an electric field  
around them. He demonstrates using a musical computer program.<p>


<B>ambience</B> music  <p>

"This is the musical director, which is a demo which allows us to wave our arms in the air and by doing so we can control the tempo that a piece of music is played. We've got two sets of electrodes, and as I move my hands through the field, 
when I cross the midpoint between the electrodes that's when the beat of the next 
bar comes along. And so by doing that we can very naturally alter the tempo of the 
music."  <p> 


"So as I move my hand backwards and forwards, at the moment I'm playing quite slowly, and then I can build up the speed by moving faster, or I can go ridiculously fast, or I can go back to slow. And all I'm doing is just moving my hands backwards and forwards as though you could imagine I just conducted the orchestra in front of me." <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

