<HTML><TITLE>1261</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1261</H3>

  

<CENTER>ELECTROSTATIC FIELD SENSING</CENTER>

If you're working on a computer, be it desktop or laptop, it's pretty easy to control 
with a keyboard or a mouse. But how will you communicate with the computer of the future when it gets even smaller? I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


Peter Rogers works at Hewlett-Packard's research lab in Bristol, England. He's 
developing a technology that creates an electric field in the space around a machine, such as a computer. The user just has to move a hand or finger through that space to control the device. The electric field is generated between two copper plates.<p>


"As the user puts their hand into the region between the two plates, they distort the electric field which is there. They take the current away from the electrodes. And so we measure that loss of signal and use that as our control information." <p>


Mr. Rogers demonstrates how this technology can be used to manipulate information on a palmtop computer.<p>

<B>ambience</B>  swishing of finger over Velcro <p>

"A palmtop is basically a miniaturized PC. In the hinge of the palmtop we've put some electrostatic sensors using exactly the same technology. As I stroke my finger across the Velcro, which is defining where the sensors are, I can then use that to give me page turning in an application."<p>

"What I do is by moving my fingers as though I was actually lifting pages and turning them over as you would with a book, we can control page turning on the screen of the display. So we can see the display flip pages as I just move my hands across the sensor, very much as though I was interacting with a book. And this allows you to quite rapidly flip backwards and forwards through a book and get information much more quickly than you would be able to with just cursor keys."  <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

