<H3>Program #1262</H3>

  

<CENTER>U.S. FIRST - The Robots</CENTER>


An annual contest brings robots together on a playing field to compete in a game of 
skill and strategy. But the real skill comes from the teams that build the robots. 
I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>

Eric Rasmussen is the technical coordinator for U.S. FIRST. Since 1992, the 
organization has run a competition that challenges teams of enginers and students to build robots for a specified task. The 1996 challenge was to get balls into a five-foot high goal. One of the prototype robots for '96 is called the Elf.<p>

<B>ambience</B> Elf <p> 

"This robot was created to pick the large balls up  off the surface of the playing field or the side of the goal, sort of bear hug them and put them into the goal to score a lot of points."<p>

Another robot prototype took a very different approach.<p>

<B>ambience</B> Boomer <p>

"This robot is called the Boomer, mainly for the large boom that extends out the front side of it. It rolls the ball over the top and into the goal, using the boom. It also has a small blue scoop in the front which is used for picking up small balls off the surface of the playing field and then it will transport those to the player on the side of the field who can then literally throw them into the goal." <p>

Dean Kamen is the founder of U.S. FIRST.<p>

"The goal in how we make our rules is to create a headache for the engineers. We want to make sure when they look at the goal and they look at the game, they can come to at least three or four very divergent strategies that are plausible, the goal being that when all the teams show up, their machines are very very different in design and strategy. There is no right answer, there's just room for a lot of imagination."  <p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <p>

