<HTML><TITLE>1263</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1263</H3>

  

<CENTER>U.S. FIRST - The Game</CENTER>

Since 1992, engineers, students and a diverse group of robots have gotten together 
once a year for a little competitive technology. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the 
Pulse of the Planet.<p>

<B>ambience</B> Elf  <p>

That's the Elf, one of the prototype robots for the 1996 U.S. FIRST competition. The 
event challenges teams of engineers and young people to design and build robots to 
perform a specified task. U.S. FIRST founder Dean Kamen explains.<p>

"Each team is supplied literally with a tub full of about 85 pounds of parts which includes motors, gears and servos and radio control equipment, most of which is supplied by all our sponsors. It's a lot of exciting engineering materials, and about a 25-page rule book with a diagram of the field and a set of all the restrictions on how they're allowed to compete." <p> 

In 1996, playing on a hexagon-shaped field, the robots had to move balls of different sizes into a 5-foot-high goal. The robots' task changes every year.<p>

"The first year they played on a field about the size of a boxing ring that was covered with about two inches of slippery unpopped corn, and they had to pick up tennis balls and move them into a goal about two feet square. The second year they had kickballs, and they had to get them into the air and up over a hurdle about a foot high."  <p>

The students and engineers form a partnership in their quest for victory. Usually the students come up with the ideas and leave it to the engineers to make it happen. <p> 

"The students I think really learn a lot about what's possible with engineering and the engineers rediscover how much fun it is to be an engineer and to have the kind of knowledge that allows you to do these kinds of things." <p> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

