<HTML><TITLE>1235</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1235</H3>

 

<CENTER>NATURALLY COLORED COTTON</CENTER>

Think of a cotton field, and you probably picture fluffy white cotton balls. Now 
imagine those cotton fluffs in soft shades of green and reddish brown. I'm Jim 
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


Naturally colored cotton has been around for centuries, but until recently it could 
only be spun by hand. Now, new varieties have been bred that can be machine spun. 
Dianne DeVries Dickerson, a professor at California State University in Fresno, has 
been testing fabric made from the new varieties.<P>


<B>ambience</B> washing machine  <P>
"One of the important features of colored cotton is that when it's laundered it actually becomes darker in color instead of fading like conventional dyed cottons do. So in addition to already being colored, at least for a period of time, the color actually gets darker and darker. The theory is that the lumen, the molecule where the color is present actually becomes more transluscent and so more of the  color is actually seen than prior to the laundering process." <P>


"We have found that about five additional consumer launderings will pretty much 
bring the color all the way out. And then after that it tends to go back to it's little lighter shade, but it's very minimal." <P>


Now don't expect to find electric blue or fire engine red. The natural cotton colors 
are muted and earthy. <P>


"There are shades of brown, everything from a light brown to a reddish brown. The green varies from a yellowish green to a more bluish green. And the green probably changes color most after laundering." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.
