<HTML><TITLE>1236</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1236</H3>

  

<CENTER>NATURALLY COLORED COTTON - Environment</CENTER>


Most cotton plants produce tufts of white or off-white fiber - but some cotton 
grows naturally colored in shades of red and green. These fibers are drawing new 
interest as the raw material for some environmentally friendly fashions.  I'm Jim 
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <p>


Naturally colored cotton has been around for centuries, but until recently the fiber 
was too short to be spun by machine.  Dianne DeVries Dickerson is a professor at 
California State University in Fresno.<p>

"It could be hand spun and it was used by hand weavers and hand spinners, but it wasn't commercially viable. Now the fiber is long enough, the quality has been improved to the point where the staple length is longer and it can be be machine spun."<p>

<B>ambience</B> abrader<p>

That's the sound of an abrasion machine, one of the devices Professor Dickerson is 
using to test colored cotton fabric for durability and other qualities. She explains 
why naturally colored cotton may be a little easier on the earth than other fibers.<p>


"Naturally colored cotton does not have to be dyed. And during the dyeing process there are some toxic chemicals, some heavy metals that are used in setting dyes, that have to be filtered out of the water system before it can be returned to the environment. Also, the dying process uses energy as well as water. So if they 
can eliminate that dyeing step then they have used less energy and they have used 
less water."<p>


Despite those savings, colored cotton garments will cost a just little more than 
other cotton clothing. <p>

"We feel that part of the acceptance of this product and other environmentally  friendly products is to get consumers to think beyond just, 'I like this because of the color and the way it looks.'" <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

