<HTML><TITLE>1237</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1237</H3>

  

<CENTER>MEDICAL HOLOGRAMS</CENTER>


First, there were X-rays, then CAT Scans and MRIs. Now, a new device takes medical imaging into the realm of three dimensions. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


<B>ambience</B> Vox Box<p> 


That's the sound of a new kind of imaging system which is transforming, in this 
instance, CAT scans and MRI pictures of a patient's skull into a 3-D hologram. 
Allan Wolfe is president of Voxel in Laguna Hills, California, makers of a device 
they call the Vox Cam.<p>


"Typically one would make 18 to 35 individual pictures, each being a slice of 
the skull. That data is transmitted to the Vox Cam as a series of electronic 
signals. The Vox Cam takes the first input, which is the very first slice, and makes 
a hologram of it from a particular distance. Also encoded is the distance between 
that slice and the very next slice. Inside the Vox Cam, the projector moves that 
distance and then the second slice is projected, and a hologram is made of that 
second slice and superimposed on the first one. And so on and so on and so on. So 
we now have 35 individual holograms, but they're all on the same piece of film. 
When we reconstruct them, our eye blends them all together and we see the volume 
as it existed in the patient." <p>

Dr. Wolfe says the system gives doctors a kind of x-ray vision.<p>


"When I think about this technology, what it does is convert the doctor into 
Superman because what he sees when he looks at one of these holograms is what 
he would see if he were able to see through the patient. And I know that helps him 
to decide more accurately, more quickly, more definitively what is wrong and what 
to do about it." <p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<p>

