<HTML><TITLE>1238</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1238</H3>

  

<CENTER>MEDICAL HOLOGRAMS - Fused Images</CENTER>


A CAT scan takes clear pictures of bone and an MRI displays images of soft tissue. 
Well, a new device combines scans from both machines into a single, three-
dimensional hologram. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


<B>ambience</B> Vox Box  <p>

"One of the characteristics of these holograms is that even though we can 
see all the detail they are indeed transparent." <p>

Dr. Allan Wolfe is the president of Voxel, developers of an imaging system that 
takes CAT and MRI scans and superimposes them to become a holographic image.<p>


"We can put the one on top of the other now we have a complex image that has both 
the bone and the soft tissue. And we know they're exact because they're the same 
patient, they've been sized the same way and they're very easy to fuse, as we say." <p>


According to Dr. Wolfe, neurosurgeons have found the device useful for diagnosing 
back ailments.<p>


"People who have back problems have problems that may be bony or may be in the spinal cord themselves. It's very hard to make a diagnosis. One of the ways that is sometimes used is a process called a myelagram, where a dye is injected into the spinal canal in order to see the spinal cord more clearly.  That's painful and sometimes dangerous. Doctors working with us have been making a CT exam to see the bone,  MR shows the spinal cord quite nicely and when these are superimposed we get a better picture than we get with a myelagram and it's three-dimensional, so the doctor can decide whether surgery is indicated and if so exactly what needs to be done."<p>

Until now, doctors have had to rely on their training and experience to form a 
mental three-dimensional image from the information on a two-dimensional scan. 
Dr. Wolfe says that this new system takes the guesswork out of that process.<p>

"Because if you're going to contemplate doing surgery inside the brain for example, knowing exactly what you're going to encounter before you get in there is extremely helpful."<p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

