<H3>Program #1239</H3>

<CENTER>MEDICAL HOLOGRAMS - Case Study</CENTER>


A new kind of medical device is using holograph technology to construct transparent, three-dimensional images of a patient's anatomy. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


<B>ambience</B> Vox Box  <p>

That's the sound of a medical imaging system developed by the Voxel Company in Laguna Hills, California. The system takes standard CAT or MRI scans and turns them into holograms. Voxel President Allan Wolfe describes one of his holographic images.<p>


"In this particular case we're looking at the top of the neck and the bottom of the skull of an elderly lady who had disease in her bone and whose neck had become very unstable. There was a great deal of concern that the bone would break, it would sever the spinal cord and she would be paralyzed. It was determined that that had to be made more rigid. The question was, what kind of appliance should be used to create that rigidity, and where should it go.  Well, before the patient was operated on a hologram was made, and one was able to determine precisely what size screw was needed to cause the patient's spine to become more rigid, and precisely where to place it. I'm actually placing it into this hologram right now. And after the surgery had been completed we were able to see another hologram that in fact had the screw in it to confirm that we had made the right intervention. I'm happy to say this was a good result."  <p>


To learn more about this and other programs in our series, we'd like to invite you 
to visit our World Wide Web site. The address is http://www.pulseplanet.com. That's www.pulseplanet.com.<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

