<HTML><TITLE>1240</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1240</H3>

  

<CENTER>DETECTING CANCER WITH LIGHT</CENTER>

A new medical device uses fiberoptics to detect cancer with light. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


<B>ambience</B> clicking shutter <p> 

That's the sound of the shutter on the biomedical spectral analyzer developed by 
Fonet Incorporated. Company president Jan Haerer explains how it works.<p>


"We have a spectrometer, which is a way of separating light into its components, red, green, yellow, etc.  That spectrometer will introduce light from a light source like a light bulb through a fiberoptic. And a fiberoptic is a hair-like fiber of glass. Very, very tiny. We have light that goes into the tissue and then light that is returned. And by studying the colors of light that went in versus the colors that come back, we can determine whether or not we have malignancy in that particular tissue." <p>


Fonet is testing the device to study its accuracy in detecting bladder and colon 
cancer. The fiberoptic procedure is less invasive because no tissue has to be cut 
out. <p>


"If you're not cutting the tissue, then you're not risking bleeding, infection, 
death, metastasis of the cancer, etc." <p>

And the results are available right away - unlike the waiting period patients often 
endure with a biopsy.<p>


"In addition, during surgery, a doctor needs to know, how far do I cut? How far do I have to go in removing a colon, for instance, to know that I have all of the cancer.  One touch with the fiberoptic probe and he would know exactly how much tissue has to be taken." <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>
