<H3>Program #1241</H3>

  

<CENTER>DETECTING CANCER WITH LIGHT - Accuracy</CENTER>


When a doctor suspects cancer, the standard way to confirm the diagnosis is with 
a biopsy. Now researchers are studying a device that may provide the same results 
without surgery. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>

"When you detect cancer now, you surgically remove tissue in question and analyze it. Now that takes time. Often three days, sometimes as long as two weeks, and if you're on the receiving end, you're sitting there waiting for the report to come back, malignant or not. In addition, there are some risks associated with biopsy as with any surgical procedure."<p>


Jan Haerer is the president of Fonet Incorporated in Clearwater, Florida, developers of the biomedical spectral analyzer. <p>

<B>ambience</B> clicking shutter <p>

With the click of a shutter, the device sends light through a fiberoptic probe to the 
suspected tissue. The light that comes back is analyzed to determine if the tissue 
is malignant.  Fonet is testing the device to determine how its accuracy measures 
up against conventional biopsy. <p>


"In the clinical trials we are actually working with patients, people who have consented to help us with the study. The doctor suspects that they may have cancer in the colon or  bladder. And the doctor is there anyway, he's already performing the procedure. Therefore all we're asking is five minutes to shine the light in and do the testing at the same place that this physician would be biopsying. We're comparing the two and comparing the outcomes."<p>


"The problem is that we are forced to measure against conventional biopsy, and unfortunately, 10 to 30 percent of the biopsies are not accurate.  Anything you 
measure is only as good as your ruler, and we don't have a very good ruler." <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

