<H3>Program #1242</H3>

  

<CENTER>INDOOR AIR PURIFIER</CENTER>

Can sick buildings be cured? An engineering professor thinks he's found a way. I'm 
Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <p>


<B>ambience</B> duct system turning on  <p>

We're listening to an experimental duct system in Dr. Yogi Goswami's  lab at the University of Florida in Gainesville.<p>

"The system that we're developing is to clean indoor air, to take care of the sick building syndrome. Sick building syndrome is mostly due to the microorganisms, the mold and mildew and other bacteria that grows in the duct system. In addition, you may have viruses and other bacteria in the air that you would like to clean." <p>

In this test system, an ordinary blower is sending air through a filter that's coated with titanium dioxide, a chemical catalyst that's activated by ultraviolet light. <p>


"Instead of using a regular air filter, we can use a catalytic filter, and that catalytic filter becomes active when this light falls on that filter and when that 
happens, any bacteria, viruses, and other microorganisms that come in contact, they get killed. At the same time, any chemicals that are in the air that are harmful for us, they get destroyed also." <p>

If you have a question about this or any of the other programs in our series, we'd 
like to invite you to visit our World Wide Web site. The address is 
http://www.pulseplanet.com. That's www.pulseplanet.com.<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

