<HTML><TITLE>1243</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1243</H3>

  

<CENTER>INDOOR AIR PURIFIER - Airtight Buildings</CENTER>


Airtight buildings reduce energy bills, but they may not be healthy for the people 
inside. A new technology could help. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the 
Planet.<p>

"In the past, buildings used to be very leaky. And they used to waste a lot of energy, but at least we used to get some fresh air in the buildings. Now with the tight building design, that's not the case. So all of the pollution that we have indoors, that becomes concentrated because we are not getting as much fresh air from outside." <p>

<B>ambience</B> duct system  <p>

Dr. Yogi Goswami, an engineering professor at the University of Florida, is testing 
a system he developed to clean indoor air. Air blows through a filter that's coated 
with a catalyst, and when the catalyst is activated by light, the chemical reaction 
destroys airborne contaminants. Dr. Goswami describes some of the pollutants.<p>

"Volatile organic chemicals that you get from various materials that we use indoors, microorganisms that grow inside the ducts, like mold, mildew, and other bacteria that can grow in the air conditioning systems. Because of the pollution in the indoor air, people feel sick, they don't understand why they're not as productive as they used to be. That is called sick building syndrome." <p>


In addition to providing cleaner indoor air for people to breathe, the technology might help to conserve energy.<p>

"Right now, to clean up the indoor air we need to bring a lot of outdoor air to dilute the indoor air pollution problem. And in this case, if we can clean up that  
air, we won't have to bring that much outdoor air,  which requires a lot of energy 
to condition it again to the indoor conditions." <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

