<HTML><TITLE>1244</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1244</H3>


<CENTER>GUIDED WAVE PROBE</CENTER>

When an airplane ages, it may develop cracks and structural flaws. Scientists are 
looking for ways to find structural defects before they cause an accident. I'm Jim 
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


"Airplanes are made of hundreds of aluminum panels. They're all riveted in place. We all see the rivets as we enter the airplane structure. The airplane skin is probably  up to an eighth inch thick, depending on where it might exist in the structure."<p>


Joseph L. Rose, an engineering professor at Penn State University, is developing 
the guided wave test probe. The probe sends sound waves through the aircraft 
structure, then analyzes the waves to look for flaws, such as those caused by 
corrosion. <p>


"This probe can be used to evaluate fuselage thinning by way of corrosion attack from the inside of the structure. We can take the transducer assembly, place it on the fuselage and by measuring the arrival time of the wave from one transducer to another, come up with a pretty good estimate of the remaining thickness of the structure, which evaluates the corrosion attack." <p>

When the probe finds a flaw, it sounds an alarm.<p>
<B>ambience</B> beeping  <p>

Unlike other ultrasonic probes that only test a small area at a time, this probe can 
test a section that's up to four feet long. And since it's relatively portable, it 
could be used to inspect aircraft quickly in between flights. <p>


"With this new guided wave probe, it's not necessary to schedule complete maintenance for an aircraft. It can be used so quickly that an aircraft, as it comes into the terminal, could have someone within a few minutes take this probe out to a joint,  perhaps something that was repaired some months ago or weeks ago, to get a very quick evaluation on how well it's doing." <p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

