<HTML><TITLE>1245</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1245</H3>

  

<CENTER>GUIDED WAVE PROBE - Aging infrastructure</CENTER>

  
An experimental device that uses sound waves to look for structural flaws could 
be used to help keep aging airplanes in top condition. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is 
the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


Joseph L. Rose is an engineering professor at Penn State University. He and his 
colleagues are developing a portable probe that searches for defects, and sends out 
a warning when it detects a potential problem.<p>


<B>ambience</B> beeping  <p>

"Today with America's aging infrastructure, there's tremendous emphasis being placed on economic efficiency and so on. As a result, we cannot totally replace airplanes. We have to repair and maintain them as well as possible.  It turns out that even though original design lives may call for 20 years, these airplanes can run for 40 years if they're properly maintained. Prior to maintenance, it's critical to carry out a detailed inspection. We have to find out where the problems are occurring, where there's defects, where there's corrosion attack and so on. Fortunately, redundancy in the design of aircraft allows failures of some components to take place without final catastrophic failure, but it's important that we find these early defects."  <p>


The importance of early detection was made clear in 1988, when a 737 lost part of 
its fuselage over Hawaii.<p>


"Because of severe corrosion attack, the entire fuselage and the upper half section of the airplane peeled off. With this incident, many agencies and groups in the United States tried to do something about the safety of the flying public."<p>


With regularly scheduled maintenance and tools like the guided wave probe, airplanes should be flying safely for longer periods of time.<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <p>

