<HTML><TITLE>1246</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1246</H3>

  

<CENTER>GUIDED WAVE PROBE - Other Applications</CENTER>


Technology designed to find defects in airplanes may also be able to detect other 
kinds of structural problems. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <p>


<B>ambience</B> beeping <p>

That's the sound of a guided wave test probe signaling that it's found a flaw - such 
as rust or a crack - in the body of an airplane.  The probe works by sending sound 
waves through large sections of the structure, and then analyzing the waves. Joseph L. Rose is an engineering professor at Penn State University.<p>


"The guided wave test concept can be applied to almost any structure and any material. The problems solved with respect to hardware and software will be slightly different, but the principles are still suitable."<p>


As infrastructure continues to age, the guided wave technology could be used to 
ensure safety in a broad range of applications.<p>


"Safety with aging aircraft and safety with all sorts of other structures. We can use this in the transportation industry for rail, for an ordinary trolley car. We can use guided wave technology for inspection in power plants. Without a doubt, it will improve the quality of our lives by establishing confidence in the the use of older structures. Also the impact with respect to the cost involved with guided wave inspection will be minimal. The amount of money saved by avoiding catastrophic failure will be immense."<p>


To learn more about this and other programs in our series, we'd like to invite you 
to visit our World Wide Web site. The address is http://www.pulseplanet.com. 
That's www.pulseplanet.com.<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

