<HTML><TITLE>1247</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1247</H3>
 

<CENTER>NEW SIREN</CENTER>


If you're driving in your car and you hear this <p>
<B>ambience</B> siren, wail <p>
chances are you'll be looking around trying to figure out where the sound is coming 
from. Well, a different kind of siren with a different kind of sound might make it 
easier to locate. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


"The reason we decided to develop a new siren was that every road user you ever speak to reports the problem that whenever you hear an emergency vehicle siren, you haven't got a clue where it's coming from."<p>


Dr. Deborah Withington is the managing director of Sound Alert Limited in Leeds, 
England. Her research in psychoacoustics shows that our brains simply can't locate  
the sound that comes from existing sirens.<p>


"They just don't operate over the right frequency range, and even in an ideal environment, you'd never be able to tell where those sounds came from, let alone 
driving in a tin box of a car. Current sirens are really hard to localize because they contain very few frequencies, and for our brain to be able to tell the direction of a sound, it needs to listen to a whole range of frequencies. Existng sirens operate over a tiny frequency range, between about 500 Hz and 1.8 KHz. but we can actually hear from 20 Hz up to 20 KHz, a huge range of frequencies." <p>

So Dr. Withington's company has come up with a new kind of siren.<p>
<B>ambience</B> siren, localizer <p>

"The best sound for directionality is to use something called white noise. Now white noise contains all frequencies, all the frequencies that we could hear. Unfortunately, it sounds rather like the static on a radio, and is absolutely useless for alerting people, so there'd be no perceived urgency in the sound and nobody would  
respond to it. So we had to create a sound that had both an alerting response and a 
directional component." <p>

We'll hear more about new sirens in future programs.<p>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<p>

