<HTML><TITLE>1248</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1248</H3>

  

<CENTER>NEW SIREN - Testing</CENTER>

Researchers in England are working on a new type of emergency siren - one that's 
easier for the human ear to localize. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the 
Planet.<p>

Deborah Withington is the managing director of Sound Alert Limited in Leeds, England. She tells us the first step in the research was to determine how well drivers locate the sound of a standard siren.<p>

<B>ambience</B> siren, wail<p>


"We first of all had to test out the existing sirens, using a driving simulator, so people really felt that they were actually driving. It's a real car. They drove along at 40 mph and we played sound from speakers that were hidden from them, so they didn't know where they were, and then they had to respond to where they thought the sound was coming from. We first of all checked out all of the existing ones and found out that they were absolutely useless. And basically when you're trying to tell, is the emergency vehicle in front or behind me, you get that wrong 56 percent of the time. So we had to try and create new sirens."  <p>


<B>ambience</B> siren, localizer <p>

The new siren uses a typical alarm sound interspersed with bursts of white noise, 
which sounds like static. It's the white noise which contains all frequencies 
audible to people, and according to Dr. Withington, it helps our brain to identify 
where the sound is coming from.<p>


"After the laboratory test, obviously we now need to test it in a real environment.  We've arranged to test it in West Yorkshire, that's in the north of England with the ambulance service, and we'll be testing it in central London with the police department."  <p>

Statistics show just how important it is to find a better sound for a siren.<p>


"We know that last year, for example, there were over 1,300 accidents involving ambulances, and that is just in the London area. We haven't got the exact values for the other emergency services, but we're aware that both the police and the fire services have even more accidents than those involving ambulances."  <p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

