<HTML><TITLE>1249</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1249</H3>

  

<CENTER>NEW SIREN - Designer sound</CENTER>


Hundreds of collisions occur each year because drivers have trouble figuring out what direction an ambulance or police car is coming from. Well, researchers in England have custom-designed a new kind of siren that could make emergency vehicles easier to locate. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<p>


Deborah Withington is the managing director of Sound Alert Limited in Leeds, England. She explains how the research got started.<p>

"Well, the idea's certainly been around in my head for at least the last 10 years, noticing that emergency vehicle sirens are not really well designed for the job that they need to do. But it was the presence of the advanced driving simulator at the University of Leeds that really allowed this project to get off the ground." <p>


The simulator has allowed tests that compare standard sirens <p>
<B>ambience</B>siren, yelp <p>
with the company's newly designed sound. <p>
<B>ambience</B> siren, localizer <p> 

It's a high-pitched alarm interspersed with burst of staticky white noise. The 
white noise - which contains all frequencie audible to people - is what according 
to Dr. Withington, helps the ear find the sound.  <p>


"The new sound we've called initially the localizer gives you a lot of information about the sound, it gives you the direction of the sound in addition to having this perceived urgency. Now, the two phases to the sound, the alerting one, the rapidly rising frequency sweeps and then the broad band burst of noise at the end, we've had a lot of difficulty trying to make it so the frequency component was matched such that the car body didn't influence it and distance didn't influence it. The way we've actually done this is by using computers, we've been allowed to sort of paint with sound. It has allowed us to compensate for all sorts of deficits in high-frequency transmission." <p>

An ambulance service in West Yorkshire, in the north of England, has been helping 
the company develop the new siren. <p>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<p>

