<HTML><TITLE>1220</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1220</H3>

  

<CENTER>SOFT TRENCHER</CENTER>


When you think of digging tools, you might imagine a pick or a shovel, or even a backhoe. Well, what about - air? I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Soft Trencher<P>
That's the sound of a soft trencher - a digging machine that uses powerful blasts of air to dig holes without cutting into underground pipes or cables. Richard Nathenson is with Concept Engineering group in Pittsburgh, and he's been helping develop the machine for the Electric Power Research Institute.<P>

"Basically, we use miniature rocket nozzles. If you take compressed air and put it through a properly shaped channel, you will accelerate it to, depending on the pressure, about twice the speed of sound. At that speed the air jet is very energy intensive and capable of penetrating into soil."<P>

The air jets are mounted, along with a vacuum system, onto an extendable boom that the operator maneuvers, much like a conventional grading machine.<P>

"The air jets are basically loosening the material, and the vacuum system is removing it at the same time. This is important because each one really helps the other. The hardest thing for a vacuum to do is actually get material off the surface. That's why your Hoover has brushes. The air jets fluff the material up and make it initially  airborne so the vacuum can then just basically take it and sweep it up into the machine. At the same time, the  vacuum continuously removes material so the air jets always have a fresh surface to work on, so it's really a powerful combination."<P>

According to Mr. Nathenson, the key advantage of the soft trencher is safety. While it's dislodging and removing dirt, it won't damage underground utilities.<P>

"The air jets and the vacuum system are both non contacting. There basically arent any hard edges to do damage."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
