<HTML><TITLE>1221</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1221</H3>

  

<CENTER>SOFT TRENCHER - Digging With Air</CENTER>
                     

<B>ambience</B> Soft Trencher <P> 
We're listening to a new kind of excavating machine that digs with powerful air jets. It may sound tough, but it's gentle on buried utility pipes and cables. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P> 
 
"There's a tremendous need today for a new digging technology in urban and suburban areas." <P>  

Richard Nathenson is with Concept Engineering group in Pittsburgh, and he's been helping to develop the soft trencher for the Electric Power Research Institute.<P> 

"The amount of utilities that are underneath the street if you would open it, for example in downtown Pittsburgh or New York, is astounding. There are many, many accidents having to do with contractors accidentally damaging, rupturing a buried line. These are very serious. There is loss of life and millions of dollars of damage." <P> 

The soft trencher uses compressed air that's traveling at up to twice the speed of sound to blast holes in the ground. At the same time, a vacuum system is getting the dislodged dirt out of the way.<P> 

"The key technology with the air jet is that it's very aggressive at dislodging porous materials, like soil, but is completely  harmless to a solid material like a plastic pipe or even fiberoptic line. Primarily to date it has been used in the utility industry, for digging around pipes or cables. Our company is currently exploring use of this technology in environmental applications, environmental remediation  applications and military applications. For in these instances, material which is buried in the ground, such as drums of waste or even unexploded ordnance also has to be unearthed very carefully." <P> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P> 
