<HTML><TITLE>1222</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1222</H3>

  

<CENTER>DNA DIAGNOSIS</CENTER>

                                  
A computer chip that contains tiny pieces of DNA may offer a new way for doctors to diagnose diseases. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Electrodes Activating Chip <P>
First, a drop of blood is placed on top of the chip and the chip is electronically activated. The blood sample is illuminated with lasers and the image, as seen under a microscope, is picked up by a video camera.<P>
 
"On the computer screen, we can see the formation of some circles that are getting brighter and brighter and brighter over just a matter of seconds." <P> 

Dr. Tina Berger-Nova is the president of Nanogen Incorporated, developers of the chip.  The bright circles she's speaking of show which of the pieces or "probes" of DNA on the chip match the DNA in the blood sample. <P>

"What this tells us is that the patient sample is positive for some specific diseases that we have put a tag or capture probe down on the chip to measure. In this particular example, we have put a probe sample down for strep throat, so this shows you that this patient has a very, very positive sample for strep throat. On  the same computer chip, we have a probe down for a staph infection and that is negative, so we know that the patient sample has a strep infection and doesn't have a staph infection by looking at this result and we are able to then treat them appropriately." <P> 

The more probes on the chip, the more diseases that can be diagnosed at the same time  - with almost instantaneous results. Dr. Nova compares the matching-up process to  a zipper.<P>

"You have half the zipper immobilized and in your patient sample you have the perfect match for that zipper to come together, and so what you're looking for is to see which two  pieces of DNA are a perfect match for one another." <P> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>


