<HTML><TITLE>1223</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1223</H3>

  

<CENTER>DNA DIAGNOSIS - One Drop of Blood</CENTER>



Have you ever had to give up multiple vials of blood because your doctor wanted to run multiple tests? Well, a new diagnostic device would require only a drop of blood to check for many diseases at one time. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Electrodes Activating Chip<P>
We're listening to a machine called an automated programmable electronic matrix. Its key component is a computer chip that actually contains small pieces or probes of DNA. Dr. Tina Berger-Nova, president of Nanogen Incorporated in San Diego, explains how it would work.<P>

"A patient walks into the office and we obtain a drop of blood from that patient, which is a very very small sample compared to what's being done today. We then put that drop of blood on top of our computer chip and we then illuminate that chip with a laser, and then in a matter of seconds to minutes, we're able to determine what the patient has and what the patient does not have in a very, very short period of time."<P>  

Dr. Nova says the chip is a little like a checkerboard, with DNA probes for different diseases in each square.<P> 

"What probes are are small pieces of DNA which are known sequences for a specific disease. The patient sample that you're testing also contains pieces of DNA specific for the disease that they have, and the probes in the patient sample then interact with the probes that are on the computer chip, and we have added a dye that allows you to detect which probes on the chip have bound to the probes that are in the patient sample, and therefore giving you a positive result."  <P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>

