<H3>Program #1224</H3>

  

<CENTER>TOBACCO PROTEIN</CENTER>


With all the talk about what's good or bad for your health, tobacco tends to land predictably in the "bad" category. But instead of smoking or chewing tobacco, what if you drank it? I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Blender, Grinding <P>
"You take green tobacco leaves, you put them into a big blender, basically." <P>

Ray Long is a professor of crop science at North Carolina State University. He's studying the possible beneficial uses of a protein that's relatively easy to extract from tobacco leaves.<P>

"You add water which contains a compound to keep the mush then, once it's ground from turning brown. You simply take the mush and squeeze the juice out of it.  And of course it's a green juice at that point. You have to clarify it, that is you have to get rid of the green color and take the chlorophyl out. And what we have left then is an amber colored liquid,  I call it a beer. If it has protein in it, which we hope that it does, if we've done it properly, you'll have a head on it, just like you will on a beer."  <P>

The liquid is chilled, and the protein crystallizes out of solution.<P> 

"Once the extract has been clarified one can extract from that a protein that is highly nutritious. We think that it would be non-allergenic or at least hypoallergenic, so you'd be able to use it perhaps then for infant formulas. And it has some excellent functional characteristics that allow you to heat set it, gel it, whip it, etc., that would be very useful in manufactured foods. You could add it to soups, you could add it to soft drinks to fortify them nutritionally. So from that standpoint we think it would have a lot of utility." <P>	

A little tobacco juice, anyone?<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
