<HTML><TITLE>1225</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1225</H3>

  

<CENTER>TOBACCO PROTEIN - Uses</CENTER>

 
Is tobacco finally going to get some respect? Scientists have extracted a protein from tobacco leaves that could be used in food products. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

<B>ambience</B> Blender, Grinding <P> 
That's the sound of green tobacco leaves being ground up in a large blender, so that the protein, called fraction one, can be removed. Ray Long is a professor of crop science at North Carolina State University.<P>

"Fraction one protein is probably the most abundant protein in the plant world. Incidentally it's the protein that is responsible for converting sunlight energy into chemical energy in all plants. It constitutes about 30 percent of the total protein in the green tobacco plant. So we're looking to extract fraction one to use it as a food grade protein in manufactured foods." <P>

Dr. Long believes that fraction one protein could be used as a base for infant formula. Some babies are allergic to the milk or soy proteins generally used in formula. <P>

"So we think that perhaps, because fraction one protein is common in all green plants, and so it's present in all green vegetables that we eat, that because of common nature this might be a source of a hypoallergenic infant formula." <P>

Another possibility would be to try to develop a supplement to for kidney dialysis patients. <P>

"Because of the purity of the fraction one and the absence of certain compounds that have to be excreted by the kidneys one could use it as a source of protein supplement for kidney dialysis patients, and that perhaps, you might be able to reduce the  frequency of dialysis by 50 percent." <P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
