<H3>Program #1229</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER CLUBHOUSE</CENTER>
                                 

If children represent humanity's  future and computers the future of technology, it makes sense to get the two together. That's happening in Boston at a place called the Computer Clubhouse. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

"This is a multimedia movie I made that plays out and then at the end it has... it shows a computer screen with the titles of all the other work I've done." <P> 
<B>ambience</B> Music, Kenneth Willis' movie  <P>
"Now that's showing the beginning credits." <P>

Kenneth Willis, from Dorchester, started coming to the Computer Clubhouse about two years ago when he was 12 years old. This multimedia movie he created features such effects as his own face dissolving into colors and a video clips of  famous buildings and statues flashing by. <P>

"At the end of this movie there's a picture of me holding, it's supposed to be the earth. I have to make more... make it look more realistic." <P>

Mitchel Resnick, a professor at MIT's Media Lab, co-founded the Computer Clubhouse with Natalie Rusk, the director of education at the Computer Museum in Boston. <P>

"It's a place we started in order to help inner city kids have an opportunity to investigate the new world of computers. It's partly just to give them access to this new technology. Many of the kids here never had a chance to use computers before. But more than just access is trying to give them a new way of thinking about technology and a new way of thinking about their own learning. We see a lot of the kids here, they're not just using computers to learn a particular skill, but a sort of a new way that they can create things, a new way to express themselves. And I think a lot of them really get engaged with computers, not so much because there's a particular technology that they're learning, but more because it's a new opportunity for them to express themselves in a way they couldn't before." <P> 

