<HTML><TITLE>1230</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1230</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER CLUBHOUSE - Education</CENTER>


Most children today use computers in school. But too often they don't really have a chance to let their imaginations run wild - to use computers as a tool for their own expression. Well, the Computer Clubhouse in Boston is trying to change all that. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

<B>ambience</B> General Clubhouse Background <P>
"I think most important, we're trying to give kids a new sense of themselves as learners. Of being able to create and produce things in a way that they weren't able to before. But it's not just learning skills. It's more learning how to express themselves, and to see themselves as very capable inventors and creators." <P> 

Mitchel Resnick is a professor at MIT's Media Lab. He co-founded the Computer Clubhouse to give economically disadvantaged kids a way to learn about computers by following their own interests. <P>

"As you look around, you'll see on the bulletin boards, we have hanging up examples of lots of previous projects. It's sort of a museum of what's been done. On the computers themselves, we have lots of sample projects. So kids can come in and get a sense of what other people have worked on. They then might start by doing a variation on a theme. Take a look at something that someone else did that they like and do a little variation of it. Then they might make a little bigger variation." <P> 

Before long, the kids are doing projects on their own from scratch. The idea is to give them skills and support, and then let them take it from there. <P>

"We give kids  the tools that enable them to create, design and invent. And we've seen that by giving them those  tools, they learn a tremendous amount. They learn partly computer skills. They also learn mathematical and scientific ideas in the process of designing an invention. They write about their designs and inventions. So they're learning English skills. Most important of all, they're learning to see themselves as creators. And for so many of the possible jobs these kids might grow up into, they need to be able to think of themselves as designers in the world."  <P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living. <P>
