<H3>Program #1231</H3>

  

<CENTER>COMPUTER CLUBHOUSE - A Place to Explore</CENTER>

You may work with  your computer to create a spreadsheet or do word processing, but have you ever tried to use it to record your own music or build a robot? Well, that's all happening at a place in Boston called the Computer Clubhouse. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience</B> General Clubhouse Background <P>
"When kids come in here, they'll work on a wide variety of projects. If you look in one direction, you might see some kids doing some graphics work where they'll make some artistic creation. Others might be animating their creations, making an MTV-like video. We look in another direction, we see some kids work on robotics projects where they're creating robots and controlling them from the computers. Next to them are some kids that are doing more of a scientific experiment. They have some sensors hooked up to the computer, and they're measuring different types of values with those sensors."  <P>

Mitchel Resnick is a professor at MIT's Media Lab. He co-founded the Computer Clubhouse to give inner-city youths free access to the world of computing.<P>

<B>ambience</B> Rap Beat  <P>
"Back in another corner there's a music studio where kids are making some background beat for some rap music that they're creating. And they're using the computer to help create the music and record the music."  <P>

Professor Resnick says that the clubhouse was designed not only to give young people access to computers, but to provide a comfortable place for them to explore their own creativity. <P>

"Too often when people picture a computer lab, they imagine computers sitting in rows and people in front of the computers just staring into the screen. The clubhouse is set up to have a very different feel about it. In the middle of the room there's this funky green table and the computers are scattered around the room in a way that people can work at the computers but also interact with each other."  <P>

