<HTML><TITLE>1232</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1232</H3>

  

<CENTER>TORNADO ALERT</CENTER>

Each year, tornados cause millions of dollars of damage and the loss of lives. Now, scientists in Mississippi have built a  device that warns of the approach of a tornado. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

<B>ambience</B> Tornado <P>
Henry Bass is a physics professor and director of the National Center for Physical Acoustics at the University of Mississippi. He explains how the system identifies the particular roar of a tornado. <P>

"The microphone for the tornado alert system sets outside underneath the eave of the home. The microphone is constantly active and constantly listening for any sounds that are out there. The microprocessor inside the control box is listening for the sound that's fed back from the microphone. But it's looking for signals that have a certain range of frequency, namely, low frequencies that are associated with a tornado." <P>

Now, if it hears the right frequency, and the sound is loud enough, the device then determines whether the sound is getting louder over time. If so, it shifts into a potential alert mode. <P>

"It then continues to listen for the increase in the sound level as a function of time, but the volume has to surpass a second threshhold before the processor will then say, aha, I think I have a tornado, and begin to set off a light on the front of the panel and begin to put out a warning sound..."<P>
<B>ambience</B> Alarm <P>
"...This process continues. The longer the source approaches, the more certain the processor becomes that indeed there is a tornado, and the louder the alarm becomes inside the home."  <P>
<B>ambience</B> Alarm  <P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
