<HTML><TITLE>1233</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1233</H3>

  

<CENTER>TORNADO ALERT - Like a Freight Train</CENTER>

<B>ambience</B> Tornado <P>
The sound of a tornado has been compared to the roar of a freight train gone wild. Now scientists have programmed a microprocessor to listen for that sound and warn people when to take cover.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

Henry Bass, a physics professor at the University of Mississippi and developer of the tornado alert system, describes the sound of an approaching twister. <P>

"Basically what you hear is this fairly low frequency rumble. At first it sounds maybe a little bit  like wind noise through the trees, but it grows in amplitude, and the amplitude increases you begin hear more and more of the rumbling sounds that you would associate with an approaching locomotive. And it gets louder and louder and louder and pretty soon you begin to hear individual trees breaking and other things being thrown up against nearby houses and nearby trees, and it becomes lots of snaps and pops. But underneath all that there's this constant increasing, rumbling and roar that increases in amplitude." <P>

A microphone is placed outside a home equipped with the tornado alert system. It picks up the sound and the device determines if the roar is getting louder. <P>

"The important thing here is that the sound of an approaching tornado will increase with time. Now, down inside of the tornado alert system there is a little computer, and the little computer listens for a sound in the right frequency range that is increasing with time." <P>

If the device hears tornado, it sets off an alarm that gives people 30 to 90 seconds to take cover -- plenty of time, Bass says, if you have a plan. <P>

"It only takes a few minutes. One simply has to think about, where is the safest part of the house to be, get the kids together and say, 'Listen, if I shout tornado, this is where we're going to meet.' " <P> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
