<HTML><TITLE>1234</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1234</H3>

  

<CENTER>TORNADO ALERT - The Discovery</CENTER>
                              

<B>ambience</B> Tornado <P>
This rare recording of an approaching tornado was made in 1974 in Alabama, during a severe tornado outbreak that killed several hundred people.  That same series of tornados spurred University of Missisippi researchers to build a device to warn individuals that a tornado is headed their way. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

Physics professor Henry Bass explains how the idea for the tornado alert system began in 1974. <P>

"A group of us here at the University of Mississippi were talking over coffee, and someone said, if this was a foreign power that had attacked the United States and killed several hundred of our citizens, we would expend billions of dollars in retaliatory action. But since this was an act of God, we were content to essentially do nothing but accept those deaths. And the question was raised, with modern technology, can't we do better? Can't we provide the individual homeowner with some way of having an alarm that will allow them to take shelter to save their lives and to protect themselves from injury?"  <P>

The researchers settled on an acoustic alarm because of a tornado's distinctive sound signature. <P> 

"Our first box, which we built about 1980 was about a half-meter square and cost several thousand dollars. It was only with the advent of microprocessors, with small computer chips that are quite affordable, that this idea actually became feasible. We were able then to squeeze all these large electronic components down into a single chip, and that's what made the process possible." <P> 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better living.<P>
