<HTML><TITLE>1177</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1177</H3>

  

<CENTER>FALL SAFE FLOORS</CENTER>


A new type of floor is designed to cushion the impact of a person's fall. I'm Jim 
Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


"This is the Penn State Safety Floor. Several years ago we took a careful 
look at the needs of the elderly and particularly how mechancial engineering can 
address those needs. And one crucial area of need for the elderly is injury during 
fall." <P>


Don Streit is an Associate Professor of Mechanical Engineering at Penn 
State University. He tells us that the safety floor's cushioning effect is caused by 
a series of columns which buckle under pressure. <P>


"The buckling columns work on the principle, if you could envision taking a 
drinking straw and holding it between your hands and pressing onto the ends of 
that drinking straw. The straw is fairly stiff and it pokes into your hands until you 
put a certain amount of force on, and suddenly that straw buckles and becomes 
soft. That's a similar concept to how the flooring works, in that we have columns 
aligned vertically between two plates. Those columns are fairly stiff when you're 
walking on it, but if someone falls onto the floor, the columns buckle." <P>

"When a person lands on the floor, the columns buckle, they deflect. But the 
columns themselves are elastic, in that they don't permanently deform. So that 
when the load is removed from the floor, the columns return to their original 
shape and the top flooring surface returns to its original shape." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P> 

