<HTML><TITLE>1205</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1205</H3>

  

<CENTER>SKUNK SPRAY REMEDY</CENTER>


<P>
The next time your pet gets sprayed by a skunk, don't despair. A chance discovery 
has led to a simple formula that seems to neutralize that persistant and pervasive 
smell. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


Paul Krebaum  is a materials engineer at Molex Incorporated in Lisle, Illinois. He 
and his colleagues were doing research involving chemical reactions that released 
hydrogen sulfide, a gas with an unpleasant odor. <P>


"We were venting this gas up the hood and were getting 
complaints from other people in the building because they were smelling it. So I 
reasoned that it would be better to destroy this gas rather than simply vent it into 
the atmosphere. So after consulting some chemistry texts I determined that 
alkaline hydrogen peroxide had a good chance of oxidizing hydrogen sulfide to 
innocuous components, and that formula kind of stuck in my mind as a possible 
way of getting rid of skunk smell, which is composed of sulphur based materials." <P>

 

Later, when a friend's cat was sprayed by a skunk, Krebaum suggested a milder 
version of the formula. And it worked. The cat was de-skunked. And now, 

here's the formula. <P>


"The recipe for the deskunking formula is one quart of three-percent 
hydrogen peroxide, one quarter-cup of baking soda, and one teaspoon of liquid soap, 
mixed together shortly before you intend to use it, left on the animal for five to 
10 minutes, and then rinsed off with tap water." <P>


A word of warning: Don't store the mixed formula. It gives off oxygen gas that 
could eventually burst a closed container. <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

