<HTML><TITLE>1206</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1206</H3>

  

<CENTER>GYPSY MOTH PREDATORS</CENTER>



The gypsy moth was first brought to the United States in 1869 under the mistaken 
notion that it could be crossed with a silk worm to produce silk. It turned out to be 
a forest pest with no natural enemies. Well, by introducing some natural 
predators, scientists are hoping to keep the moth population in check. I'm Jim 
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P> 


<B>ambience</B> beetles trying to climb out of trap  <P>

"We're looking at a trap, what we call a calosoma beetle trap. And it has two 
beetles in it."<P>


Paul Schaefer works for the U.S. Department of Agriculture. He has been trapping 
calosoma beetles in a woodlot in eastern Maryland. The calosoma beetle is one of 
about a dozen parasite or predator species that scientists have introduced over the 
years to help control gypsy moths. <P>


"There are some extremely small egg parasites that attack the egg stage of the 
gypsy moth. And they will characteristically take from 20 to 30 percent of the 
eggs, sting them, and thereby killing the caterpillers that would normally hatch 
from them in the spring. There are a number of introduced flies and wasps, both of 
which attack the larval or pupal stages of the gypsy moth. And there are a number 
of other predators that are native including our birds and mammals, both of which 
will consume a portion of the population." <P>


Scientists don't expect these natural enemies to wipe out the gypsy moths, but 
they do hope the predators will control the population. <P>


"And we think by increasing the complex of these natural enemies, that overall we 
can keep populations of gypsy moth under a level where we can accept the damage 
that they cause in a forest such as this." <P>

 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

