<HTML><TITLE>1207</TITLE>

<H3>Program #11207</H3>

  

<CENTER>GYPSY MOTH PREDATORS - Unforseen Results?</CENTER>


Over 100 years ago, gypsy moths were introduced into this country with the idea 
that they might be bred with silkworms to produce silk. They didn't. Instead they 
became a major forest pest. Now, with scienstists looking to introduce other 
insects to control the gypsy moth, what's to prevent other unforseen results? I'm 
Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


<B>ambience</B> woodlot sounds <P>

"Part of my responsibility is to see that newly introduced insects 
have little or no possible detrimental environmental impact." <P>


Paul Schaefer is with the Beneficial Insects Introduction Research Lab in the U.S. 
Department of Agriculture. <P>


"We're dealing with groups of insects that we know have specific needs. Either 
they are predatory on gypsy moths or are parasitic on them, and their whole life 
cycle is dependent upon the gypsy moth. In that kind of a situation, it's difficult to 
imagine how that particular insect can become a problem in itself." <P>


Mr. Schaefer points to the successful introduction of several species of parasites 
used by farmers to control the alfalfa weevil. <P>


"That program was so successful that we are currently in a situation where the 
alfalfa weevil is much less of a problem than it was back in the 1950s, and 
farmers have been relieved of the damages caused by alfalfa weevils. Just the 
introduction of that little parasite which has managed to establish itself and 
perpetuate itself, it becomes a permanent mortality factor for the alfalfa weevil. 
And farmers continue to benefit from that introduction." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

