<HTML><TITLE>1208</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1208</H3>

  

<CENTER>GYPSY MOTH PREDATORS - The Beetle</CENTER>



<B>ambience</B> woodlot sounds <P>

We're in eastern Maryland in a woodlot that's populated by gypsy moths. In an 
effort to control these destructive creatures, scientists have been searching for 
their natural predators. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. The 
calosoma beetle is one such predator. It's a voracious caterpiller hunter. <P>


<B>ambience</B> Schaefer packing beetles  <P>

"I'll put them in a traveling container here, and transport them back to the lab." <P>


Paul Schaefer works for the U.S. Department of Agriculture. He's been trapping 
calosoma beetles in the same woodlot in Maryland, and then taking them back to 
the lab to study them. <P>


"They are about an inch and a quarter long, very active. They're designed to climb 
trees and to consume caterpillers. They use their jaws to grab the caterpiller and 
they'll tear right through the flesh to get at the softer tissues. The beetle itself is 
very much attuned to the life cycle of the gypsy moth. It spends most of the year 
in the ground. In the middle of May it comes out of the ground, begins to search the 
trees for caterpillers, which it feeds on, voraciously. If they find a lot of 
caterpillers, they will go into a reproductive stage where they will produce 
several hundred eggs that they drop into the litter. And quite promptly those eggs 
hatch into larvae of the beetle. These larvae then develop and will attack the pupal 
stage of the gypsy moth. So it's a one-two punch, the adults feeding on the 
caterpillers, the larvae of the beetle feeding on the pupae of the gypsy moth." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

