<HTML><TITLE>1209</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1209</H3>

  

<CENTER>SKUNK SPRAY REMEDY - The Chemistry</CENTER>


Skunks probably think that humans smell awful. We'll never know. But we do know 
that getting sprayed by a skunk is no fun. Now a researcher has discovered a 
simple and effective way to eliminate the stink of a skunk. I'm Jim Metzner and 
this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


Paul Krebaum is a materials engineer, not a veterinarian or an odor expert. He was 
just looking for a way to neutralize the sulphury smell of a gas given off by 
chemical reactions in his lab. He turned to his chemistry books, and reasoned that 
hydrogen peroxide could neutralize the smell by oxidizing the gas. <P>

"The receptors that are in your nose are sensitive to sulphur in its low 
oxidation state, however they are not sensitive to sulphur in its high oxidation 
state." <P>


Krebaum mixed together hydrogen peroxide and a few other household ingredients 
and came up with a formula that deodorized the hydrogen sulfide gas. Now, when a 
friend's cat got skunked, Paul decided to see if the formula could help eliminate 
that sulphury smell as well. And it did. <P>

 

"He had tried all the previous traditional remedies such as tomato juice and things 
like that to no avail. It's my general opinion from hearing people's opinion of 
tomato juice that it simply doesn't work very well at all, whereas this method 
works quite well." <P>


Krebaum said he hasn't found any harmful side effects, and the method does seem 
to hold a cosmetic advantage over tomato juice, the longtime home remedy for 
neutralizing skunk smell. <P>


"We originally thought that perhaps the pet might be bleached and come out white, 
however, people who have tried it have reported that the pet looked essentially 
like it did before the treatment. And it certainly looked much better than tomato 
juice because tomato juice makes them look pink." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for  better 
living. <P>

