<HTML><TITLE>1210</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1210</H3>

  

<CENTER>TOUCHING VIRTUAL REALITY</CENTER>



Computers have long since entered the dimensions of sight and sound, but can 
touch be far behind? I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

<B>ambience</B> flywheel  <P>

"This is a sticky flywheel. And I can spin it with my finger and then try 
and stop it." <P>


Thomas Massie is the founder of Sensable Devices in Cambridge, Massachusetts. 
He's demonstrating the Phantom, a device that lets a person touch virtual objects, 

objects like the flywheel which exist only on a computer screen. <P>


"I can't see it. And it doesn't exist. But I can touch it with my finger. And when I 
touch it, my finger sticks to it. So there's almost like this friction on top of the 
flywheel. And I can impart momentum to the flywheel. I can spin the flywheel 
faster and faster and faster with my finger. If I try and stop the motion, I'll feel 
the inertia that's built up in the wheel - like for instance, right now." <P>


Massie's finger is plugged into a thimble-like opening in the Phantom.<P>


"So what our device actually does is, it measures where your fingertip is in 
relation to these virtual objects. And they might be buttons or bouncing balls. But 
it measures where your finger is, and then it checks to see if your finger is 
intersecting or overlapping with any of these virtual objects. And if it is, the 
computer says, whoops, this shouldn't happen. And it sends a force to your finger 
through the device so that it pushes against you. To give you the pressure that 
you'd feel if there really were an object there." <P>


Three motors in the device provide the force that acts on the user's fingertip. The 
idea is to create an interaction that's less virtual and more realistic.<P>

"If you think about the way we've been using computers, we have the computer 
monitor to see and we have speakers to hear, but we have nothing to feel yet, and 
that's what this is: the beginnings of something that will let you feel." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

