<HTML><TITLE>1211</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1211</H3>

  

<CENTER>TOUCHING VR - Applications</CENTER>



<B>ambience</B> virtual kettle drum <P>

We're listening to the sounds of a virtual musical instrument. It can be touched 
and played - but it only exists inside a computer. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the 
Pulse of the Planet.  A new interface has been designed to give computer users the 
hands-on sensation of actually touching a virtual object. <P>

 

"Computer monitors let us see what's represented inside the 
computer. And speakers let us hear what's inside the computer. We've built a 
device that lets you touch what's inside the computer. You can actually feel the 
models that the computer generates." <P>


Thomas Massie is founder of Sensable Devices in Cambridge, Massachusetts. He's  
demonstrating the computer interface that he calls the Phantom. Plug your finger 
into a thimble-like opening and it simulates, in this case, the sensation of 
touching and playing a virtual musical instrument. And there are plans in the 
works for more practical applications as well. <P>


"One of the most promising applications is to let doctors train on computer 
models instead of real patients or cadavers or animals, for instance. Another 
application would be to let designers actually use their hands when they're using 
computer-aided design programs, instead of just using the keyboard or a mouse. <P>

One of the most interesting applications of the device is being developed at the 
University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill. They have our device connected to an 
atomic force microscope so that they can actually feel particles that are 10 
orders of magnitude smaller than the workspace that you're operating in. They can 
see these particles which are only about 10 atoms wide on the computer monitor. 
Then using our device to control the microscope they can actually even touch and 
push these particles around. That's one of the more wild applications." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for

better living. <P>

