<HTML><TITLE>1212</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1212</H3>

  

<CENTER>TOUCHING VR - Virtual Medicine</CENTER>




Scalpel, scissors, clamp - mouse? A new device is giving doctors a way to perform 
surgery on virtual patients - complete with the sensations of a real surgical 
procedure. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P> 

 

"This one is actually a simulation of a needle biopsy of the brain. So 
I'm taking the path to push the needle into the skull, or through the skull, and into 
the brain. And I can feel each of the layers pop as the needle, the pressure of the 
needle, goes through the membrane."  <P>

 

Thomas Massie is the founder of Sensable Devices in Cambridge, Massachusetts. 
He's demonstrating the Phantom, an apparatus that lets a person touch virtual 
objects. Massie's finger is inside a thimble-like opening in the device, where 
motors and machinery adjust the pressure on his finger to simulate the sensation 
of performing a brain biopsy. <P>  

 

"Now I'm in the tumor, which feels kind of viscous. And I'll extract the needle and 
we can take the sample back to the lab." <P>

 

Of couse, there's no real lab and there's no real patient - just a computer-
generated model.  <P>
 

"Most of our clients intend to use the Phantom to augment these medical 
simulations so that surgeons can practice procedures on virtual patients. And 
when I say virtual patients, I mean a computer-generated patient. Somebody that 
doesn't exist but you can see them on the monitor and you can hear their body 
through the speakers and you can touch their body or cut their body with a scalpel, 
for instance, using our device." <P> 

 

Massie says the device is beginning to be placed in some medical centers, to give 
real doctors a chance to try the simulations. <P>

 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for

better living. <P>

