<HTML><TITLE>1213</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1213</H3>

  

<CENTER>TOUCHING VR - A Full Sensory Experience</CENTER>



If you're visiting virtual reality, you can now reach out and touch virtual objects. 
It's one more step in making computer simulation a full sensory experience. I'm 
Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


 "I thought it would be interesting to program in the way a button 
feels when it clicks." <P>


Thomas Massie's finger is plugged into a device he invented called the Phantom. It 
simulates the sensation of objects, like buttons and switches, even though they 
don't really exist. Massie developed the Phantom as a student in the Artificial 
Intelligence Lab at MIT. <P>


"This is the light button I'm going to click right now. And now I can click one of 
the harder buttons. Now that button feels almost like a light switch, whereas this 
button feels more like a keyboard." <P>


By modeling the physics of the forces going to the user's fingertip, the Phantom 
also helps to reproduce the sound of whatever it is that's being touched. Massie 
says the sound turns out to be a key ingredient in realizing a full sensory 
experience. <P>


"It turns the sound is just a side effect of modeling the physics correctly. So I can 
feel it and hear it at the same time. It turns out when you take two senses and 
give those to the human at the same time, sometimes the effects multiply, rather 
than just adding to the realism. Because I can hear it as well as feel it, it's much 
more real, many times more real, than if I could just hear it or just feel it." <P>


So are we headed towards a brave new world of total computerized simulation? <P>

"I think that virtual reality is nice, but we're never going to be able to do as good 
a job as nature does in providing feedback. And I think a full body suit that 
provides all the sensations you get from a natural environment is at least 100 
years off. <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<P>

