<HTML><TITLE>1214</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1214</H3>

  

<CENTER>WATER DIVINING FROM SPACE</CENTER>



In the driest of deserts, the traces of former rivers may remain beneath the sand. 
And those channels - if they can be found - can point to long-hidden reserves of 
ancient groundwater. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


"The ground water in these places is actually old, we'll call it 
fossil, meaning it's been there for a very long period of time from the geologic 
times when it used to rain there. So when we find the courses of ancient rivers, 
we actually find places where the ground water might be." <P>

 

Farouk El-Baz directs the Center for Remote Sensing at Boston University.<P>


"Long after the river has dried and its source has dried and rains that form the 
water in these rivers have long gone and the environment has changed and dried up, 
the water beneath the surface is still stored and still preserved. It only requires 
us to be intelligent enough to figure out where it might be." <P>


A radar imaging device on board the space shuttle can help detect these ancient 
waterways. The radar penetrates the sand and offers researchers a view of the 
terrain below. <P>


"The radar wave goes through the atmosphere, hits the ground or the water, is 
reflected back and what is recorded on the film on the spacecraft is the echo that 
comes back." <P>


Even in deserts with no surface water and little rain, there may be groundwater 
that can be reached through wells. <P>


"We use the radar images particularly in areas where there is a great deal of sand 
because the radar has the capability of penetrating through the sand cover and 
revealing to us the first solid rock layer beneath the sand. So if we are looking at 
the sand cover of an ancient river, we would be able to see the course of that river 
even though it is covered." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

