<HTML><TITLE>1215</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1215</H3>

  

<CENTER>WATER DIVINING FROM SPACE - The Discovery</CENTER>


A radar imaging device on board the space shuttle is helping researchers to find 
groundwater in some of the driest spots on earth. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the 
Pulse of the Planet.<P>


<B>ambience</B> space shuttle launch<P>

Farouk El-Baz now directs the Center for Remote Sensing at Boston University, but 
he used to work for the space program. In 1981 he asked colleagues at NASA to 
take a radar picture of a part of Egypt's Western Desert. It turned out that the 
radar image taken from space penetrated the sand and produced an image of the 
rock layer underneath.<P>


"Neither they nor I knew that radar would have this ability to penetrate through 
sand and give us a picture of what is beneath the sand. So when the pictures came, 
I began to look at them and I was absolutely stunned at the fact, in this place, that 
I know is absolutely flat and covered by sand and has not rained there at all, maybe 
once every 20 years, it is the driest place on earth and then beneath the sand, 
there are these numerous courses of ancient rivers."<P>


Mr. El-Baz suggested drilling some test wells to see if water from the ancient 
rivers remained underneath the sand.<P>


"Well after well, a great deal of water came through and now, today, there is an 
experimental farm, 10,000 acre experimental farm." <P>


The method has been used successfully in the Sinai, Sudan and other desert 
environments.<P>


"So in every single case, we found water. Most people that live in these desert 
areas, water to them is so critical that it might mean the difference between life 
and death. So, when you go someplace in the middle of a desert and find a new 
source for ground water, then you've done these people a tremendous favor." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<P>

