<HTML><TITLE>1216</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1216</H3>

  

<CENTER>WAVE PUMP</CENTER>


Water, water everywhere - and now, using the pitch and roll of the ocean, there 
may be a way to make sea water drinkable. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse 
of the Planet.<P>


<B>ambience </B> ocean sounds <P>

"The system is called the McCabe Wave Pump Desalination System. It 
is designed to exploit ocean waves by converting their energy into mechanical and 
hydraulic energy and using those energies to produce potable water for remote 
locations throughout the world." <P>


Michael McCormick is a research professor at Johns Hopkins University. He working 
on a wave pump named for Peter McCabe, an Irish civil engineer who thought up the 
idea in the1970s. <P>


"The system consists of three barges. The center barge is held almost motionless 
by a damping plate suspended below it. Attached to this motionless center barge 
are two larger barges which are allowed rotate about their hinges which attach 
them to the center barge. Their rotational motion excites hydraulic pumps which in 
turn draw water up through a fire hose. Those pumps pressurize the water, then 
transport the water to shore and into a desalination system." <P>


The fresh water produced is suitable for human or animal consumption, or for 
agriculture in places where fresh water is in short supply. <P>


"Some of these locations include the over 100,000 inhabited islands throughout 
the world that don't have any natural sources of potable water. There are other 
areas in the third world that don't have natural sources, for example Somalia.  
Somalia has a very long coastline on the Indian Ocean. By using the McCabe Wave 
Pump System, millions of gallons per day of potable water could be supplied to the 
coastal towns." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

