<HTML><TITLE>1217</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1217</H3>

  

<CENTER>WAVE PUMP - Water Power</CENTER>


<B>ambience</B> ocean sounds <P>

Ocean waves have been known to create seasickness, sandy beaches, and surfing. 
Now, engineers are finding a way to harness the ever-present motion  of the ocean 
and turn it into energy. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


"One of the sub-systems that has been devised for the McCabe Wave 
Pump is a system to produce electricity for remote locations." <P>


Michael McCormick, a research professor of civil engineering at Johns Hopkins 
University, is helping to develop the McCabe Wave Pump. It's a system of three 
barges linked together off shore. One barge is held motionless, and the movement 
of the other two is turned into energy through a series of pumps. There's enough 
energy to pump the water to shore, remove the salt, and then some.<P>


"The electricity is actually produced by the high pressure water, so we can have a 
dual system which will produce the electricity and the potable water at the same 
time... To get some idea of the value of this, on Lord Howe Island, which is an 
island off shore of Australia and the energy cost is 45 U.S. cents per kilowatt hour. 
For comparison, in San Diego, which is probably one of the most expensive energy 
areas in the country, they pay 13 cents a kilowatt hour. The McCabe Wave Pump 
should be able to produce electrical energy for 12 cents a kilowatt hour, so the 
saving for these island communities is evident." <P>


McCormick says the system should be able to operate most of the time. <P>


"There will be times when you have dead calms at sea and there will be times 
when the waves are so large that you'll actually have to tow the system to a 
harbor to keep it out of harm's way. For the most part, though, the wave are 
always there." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<P>

