<HTML><TITLE>1218</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1218</H3>

  

<CENTER>FOOD STERILIZATION - Electric</CENTER>


Anyone who's ever scrambled an egg knows how fast heat can change the taste and 
texture of food. Well, a new technology uses intense electric fields instead of heat 
to kill bacteria in liquid food. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. 
Wayne Clark is president of Pure Pulse Technologies.<P>


"The most prevalent method today for pasteurizing foods is heat. 
And heat does cause a lot of changes, chemical changes, in foods and also changes 
the taste. Fresh-squeezed orange juice tastes much better than canned orange 
juice because canned orange juice has been heat treated. This process, which we 
call Cool Pure, is is a way of killing bacteria without affecting the food or its 
taste at all." <P>


<B>ambience</B> cool pure machine  <P>

The process works best with liquids. They're pumped into treatment chambers and 
passed between two electrodes. <P>


"You apply a voltage across, between those electrodes, of about 30,000 volts. And 
those are applied in a few pulses, as the food flows between those electrodes. And 
you basically electrocute the bacteria...  This is absolutely different from what is 
called food irradiation. There's no radiation here. Basically you're using electricity 
to electrocute bacteria. And it makes no change in the food itself. We've done 
extensive tests to show that. Basically what it means is that you can kill the 
bacteria without damaging the food, without changing its taste, or changing its 
chemical or other physical properties." <P>


Along with destroying bacteria that could cause food-borne illness, the process 
also keeps food from spoiling. <P>


"Well, orange juice can go bad in just a couple of days. We've had orange juice that 
we've treated with this technology that has lasted for a month or more. So it's a 
very significant increase in the shelf life." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living.<P>

