<HTML><TITLE>1219</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1219</H3>

  

<CENTER>FOOD STERILIZATION - Light</CENTER>



Ever since Louis Pasteur developed the process that bears his name, heat has been 
the preferred method for killing  bacteria in food. Now, a new method achieves 
similar results using bright light instead. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of 
the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience </B> lamp testing machine <P>

That's the sound of lamps being tested at Pure Pulse Technologies in San Diego. 
The lamps emit white light compressed into very short bursts. <P>


"This is a completely new process that involves the use of pulses of 
very intense light that are very much like sunlight in their characteristics. The 
difference is that the light is about 20,000 times the intensity of sunlight at sea 
level. So it's a very intense flash of light but very brief." <P>


Wayne Clark is president of Pure Pulse. He says the technology kills much of the 
bacteria on the surfaces of food and food packaging. <P>


"The total energy that's involved is very small, but it's compressed into a very 
very short time. It's sort of like if you went to the beach and you got your year's 
supply of tan in less than a second, you'd probably be less than happy, and the 
bacteria are less than happy." <P>


According to Mr. Clark, the process doesn't affect the taste of the food like heat 
treatment does. And it kills microrganisms that can cause food to spoil. <P>


"So there are really two benefits. One benefit is killing pathogenic 
microorganisms, microrganisms that make you sick like E coli and like salmonella. 
And there are just a huge number of illnesses in the U.S. every year from these 
organisms, and a lot of people die. And so one application is to kill those 
microorganisms that make you sick so that you don't have food-borne illness. And 
a side benefit is that consumers benefit by having longer shelf life and improved 
economy in the food supply." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, makers of better things for better 
living. <P>

