<HTML><TITLE>1188</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1188</H3>

  

<CENTER>WHALE BACTERIA</CENTER>


<B>music</B><P>

<B>ambience</B>, Whales, Humpback, Songs<P>

We're listening to the haunting calls of a Humpback,  a member of  the family of 
baleen whales. Scientists are looking at baleen whales to help develop an effective 
way of cleaning up oil spills.  I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet<P>


"We discovered that whales might have microbes that could break down oil spills 
in a very serendipity way. We were working on cows and sheep which are 
ruminants on land. Now ruminants have four stomachs and sheep have microbes in 
it that were  able to break down a plant toxin. From there we then generalized 
other toxins, such as herbicides and pesticides that could be broken down by land 
animals. And then we went and looked at the ruminant of the sea, the baleen 
whales that have three stomachs. And in the first stomach of the baleen whale, we 
were finding microbes that would break down oil spills."<P>


Dr. Morrie Craig is a professor of veterinary medicine at Oregon State University. 
He says that baleen whales can actually use oil as food.<P>


"The oil is broken down by those microbes into short chained hydrocarbons, often 
fatty acids, and then the whale itself utilizes those carbon chains for energy much 
like we would utilize sugar for energy."<P>


The useful bacteria from baleen whale are  anaerobic microbes, that is, they 
survive without oxygen. This can be effective for cleaning up oil when it seeps 
under rocks and into other areas which are not exposed to air.<P>


"The way that you'd apply these microbes is you'd grow them up in a large vat. But, 
they could be poisoned if exposed to air. So they have to be protected from the 
oxygen and then they would just be in fact applied, salted over an area, and if they 
get into an anaerobic, or non-oxygen, area then they could grow up on the oil that 
was there and proliferate." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognise the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

<B>music</B>

