<HTML><TITLE>1189</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1189</H3>

<CENTER>WHALE BACTERIA - Applications</CENTER><P>


<B>music</B>

<B>ambience</B>, Whales, Bowhead<P>

We're listening to the sounds of a Bowhead whale, a species in the baleen family of 
whales. Scientists recently discovered that microbes found inside the stomachs of 
baleen whales may actually be able to break down oil spills, and now they're 
developing a way to incorporate these microbes into current cleanup methods. I'm 
Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


 "In a spill like the Exxon Valdez, you have the oil that ends up on the surface, and 
there you'll have microbes that are able to break it down which come right from 
the ocean themselves and the waves action and you can break down the surface 
components of the oil. When you get underneath the rocks and down into the area 
where there is no oxygen, in those particular places, you need a microbe that can 
live without oxygen and those are anaerobic microbes. And those are the microbes 
that you find in the forestomach of the whale. And it is those type of microbes 
that would be necessary to break down the components of oil underneath the rocks 
and in the anaerobic zones."<P>


Dr. Morrie Craig is a professor of veterinary medicine at Oregon State University. 
He says the whale microbes could be used to help clean up a variety of oil spills.<P>


"You have lots of little cleanups that happen right around the place where you're 
processing oil, where whenever you change a pipe or what have you, 50 gallons or 
100 gallons get spilled. And if they had microbes that could work without oxygen, 
in that particular area would be very helpful. This is where they're trying to put 
the commercial application." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognise the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

