<HTML><TITLE>1188</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1190</H3>


<CENTER>OCEAN DRILLING PROGRAM</CENTER>                           

<B>ambience</B><P> Ocean Drilling Platform (DAT) and ocean sounds (90.6.30-2 
Reeves)<P>

We're listening to the sounds of the machinery aboard a drill ship. Its mission is to 
explore the deep sea bed for clues as to how the earth works. I'm Jim Metzner and 
this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


Reel, cut 2) "We can suspend a drill string up to about 8 kilometers long beneath 
the ship. That's about five miles long. More typically we'll be employing drill 
strings of three or four kilometers, say two, two and a half miles in length, to 
sample these sediments and rocks on the ocean floor." <P>


Dr. Tim Francis is deputy director of the Ocean Drilling Program.<P>


c8) "One picture of the earth's geology is that it's like an orange with a peel on the 
outside. And that peel we call the earth's crust. The earth's crust is only about five 
kilometers thick beneath the oceans, but on land it's something like 30 to 40 
kilometers deep. Once you get beneath this peel of the orange, or the earth's crust, 
you're getting into the mantle rocks of the earth. And they compose a large part of 
the earth's volume. The Ocean Drilling Program has found a few rare places on the 
bottoms of the ocean where these rocks are actually exposed on the ocean floor. 
Normally they are buried at depths which are too deep to be recovered by drilling."<P>

c9) "Among the reasons why it's important to study these deeper rocks which are 
not exposed frequently on the earth's surface is many of the earthquakes which the 
earth experiences are occurring in rocks of this nature. Another reason is it is in 
these rocks where many of the minerals that we recover on the earth's surface for 
economic purposes, find their origin." <P>


We'll hear more about ocean drilling in future programs.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

