<HTML><TITLE>1191</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1191</H3>

  

<CENTER>OCEAN DRILLING PROGRAM - Prospecting on the Ocean Floor</CENTER>



<B>ambience</B> Ocean Sounds<P>

Millions of holes have been dug in the state of Texas alone as prospectors search 
for oil - but in the entire ocean floor, far fewer holes have been drilled. Now, a 
scientific expedition is seeking to mine the sea bed. And while they're not looking 
for oil, what they find may lead to better ways of prospecting for valuable 
minerals on land. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


Reel, cut 5) "The oceans are not like a goldfish bowl, you know, with a watertight 
container holding them. The sea floor is not watertight so you get sea water 
passing into the sea floor and then coming out of it again. And that has a major 
influence on many of the processes happening on the ocean floor, and it also has a 
major influence on the chemistry of the oceans as well."<P> 


Dr. Tim Francis is deputy director of the Ocean Drilling Program. In one recent 
expedition, scientists tunneled into a mound of minerals that was created by an 
undersea hot spring. It's believed that many of today's valuable minerals, such as 
copper and zinc, were created by deep ocean vents such as these.<P>


c6) "As the sea water goes down through the rocks, it leeches out various 
elements from the rocks themselves and it becomes more acid. And then it 
eventually comes up again as it's heated up and becomes more bouyant. It comes up 
and emerges on the sea floor as a hot spring on the sea floor. And when it meets 
the cold sea water on the bottom of the ocean, it discharges its load of minerals in 
solution and produces this mound. So that's a process that's going on all along the 
mid ocean ridges around the world. And it's thought to be the way in which many of 
the minerals which we now mine on land, originated." <P>

c7) "I think the real benefit from studying this mineral-creating process on the 
ocean floor is that it'll help us to understand how these ore deposits are formed on 
land and therefore it'll help us to find them on land. That's where the economic 
return, I think, will come over the next several decades." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>


