<HTML><TITLE>1192</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1192</H3>

     

<CENTER>OCEAN DRILLING PROGRAM - Climate Models</CENTER>


<B>ambience</B>Ocean Drilling Platform (95.11.7) and  ocean sounds (90.6.30-2 Reeves)<P>

The sounds we're listening to were recorded aboard a drilling platform on the deep 
ocean. By tunneling into the ocean floor, scientists are uncovering a geologic 
record of the earth's climate. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


Dr. Tim Francis is deputy director of the Ocean Drilling Program.<P>


Reel, cut 3) "In general, when you're talking about sediments on the ocean floor, 
they tend to be very fine grained and very porous with perhaps 60 to 70 percent of 
their volume is in fact seawater. And many of them are built up from the skeletons 
of plantonic creatures which used to live up in the sea surface. So by going down 
through the sediment column in the sea bed, you are going back through geological 
time. And you can learn an enormous lot about how, for example, the surface 
temperature of the sea and productivity of the sea has varied through time. And if 
you carry out this process in a large number of sites around the world, youcan 
build up a picture of climate change going back through geological time for many 
millions of years." <P>


Dr. Francis says this research could be used to help track global warming and the 
other potential effects of pollution.<P>


c4) "Now, in order to determine what effect these man-made effluents will create, 
one has to construct computer models of climate change, and put in all of these 
parameters that will effect climate, such as carbon dioxide concentration in the 
atmosphere. The problem with this approach is that one has to be able to test 
these computer models and see whether they reflect the way the world works. The 
world's climate is a very complicated system. By obtaining detailed records of 
climate change back through time, we can provide real data of climate change 
which can then be used to allow us to test these computer climate models to see 
whether they are realistic." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>


