<HTML><TITLE>1193</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1193</H3>

<CENTER>CHUNNEL</CENTER>



<B>ambience</B> Train-Channel Tunnel (Reel#2)<P>

Napolean had the idea of sending his troops from France to Britain via a tunnel 
under the English Channel. Well, it took nearly 200 years and over 12 billion 
dollars, but the Channel Tunnel is now a reality. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the 
Pulse of the Planet.<P>


Today it's an army of millions of tourists, commuters and their cars who use the 
Chunnel every year. <P>


(Reel #1)"At the moment, we're standing at the end of one of the loading platforms 
on the Folkestone Terminal. This is where the cars and lorries will load and unload 
from the shuttles."<P> 


Richard Storer is Manager of Buildings and Infrastructure for Eurotunnel, operators 
of the Channel Tunnel, or "Chunnel." He's showing us around the Chunnel terminal in 
England.<P>


"This shuttle train is about half a mile long and weighs up to 2,000 tons."<P> 

"The shuttle trains have been designed to carry vehicles on rail tracks through the 
tunnels. The locomotives are fairly conventional, although they're pretty powerful 
locomotives. The carring wagons for the tourist vehicles, have been designed to 
carry 120 cars or 12 coaches."<P>

"We're now standing in the middle platform where the unloading of the rear section 
takes place and the loading of the front section. The shuttle has arrived about four 
minutes ago and the cars are already coming off through the side loading door, 
from both the bottom and the top decks. The vehicles load at one end and drive 
right the way through to the front of that particular part of the shuttle. So the 
first vehicle on drives all the way through and stops and when the shuttle arrives 
at the destination terminal that vehicle is the first one off."<P>


