<HTML><TITLE>1194</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1194</H3>

  

<CENTER>CHUNNEL - The Technology</CENTER>


<B>ambience</B>Train Station-Channel Tunnel (Reel#2)<P>

The Chunnel, a 31-mile tunnel connecting England and France across the English 
Channel, is an engineering marvel of the 20th century. And today we'll hear about 
some of the technology that made it possible. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse 
of the Planet.<P>


(Reel #1) "First of all, it was very important to make sure that both sides knew 
where the other was down to a millimeter. And so satellites were used to set up a 
survey grid across the Channel to ensure that both teams started from a known 
point. <P>


Richard Storer is Manager of Buildings and Infrastructure for Eurotunnel, builders 
of the Chunnel.<P>


"Computers were used to dictate where the tunnel boring machine should be and 
the information as to where they should be when was programmed into them so a 
guidance system was developed running along the tunnels behind the machines, 
which allowed them to be steered accurately because of course they were going to 
meet in the middle. And it was impossible until they met, and breakthrough 
occurred, to actually survey through the tunnel to check that it was right. I think 
the proof of this system is shown by the fact that when the first machines met, 
they were only a few inches out."<P> 

"The trains use an overhead electric wire system, 25 kilovolts, produced from the 
national grids in both the UK and France. And the power is then transferred to the 
locomotives through an overhead wire collection system. They just propel through 
on standard gauge rails between the U.K. and France." <P>


Mr. Storer also says the chunnel is a smooth ride.<P>


"The track base within the tunnel is a concrete track base. And so there's no 
movement of the tracks as the train goes over, as you get with a conventional 
ballasted track. And so the ride within the tunnel is extremely smooth."<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P> 

