<HTML><TITLE>1195</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1195</H3>

  

<CENTER>CHUNNEL - Safety Concerns</CENTER>


<B>ambience</B>ambience Train-Channel Tunnel (Reel#2)<P>

We're in a British railway station where a shuttle train is embarking on a 31-mile 
trip under the English Channel to France. The Channel Tunnel, or Chunnel, 
transports millions of passengers and their cars along this route every year. And 
as you might imagine, the technology and support systems necessary to keep this 
cargo safe were developed long before the first train made its historic passage 
through the tunnel. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Richard Storer is Manager of Buildings and Infrastructure for Eurotunnel, builders 
of the Chunnel.<P>


(Reel #1)"The tunnel is never going to flood."<P>

"There's a lot of rock above the tunnel before you get to the sea bed - about a 
minimum of 45 meters, a maximum of about 75 meters - and the tunnel is in solid 
rock all the way across. So there is no likelihood of the sea ever coming into the 
tunnel. There are, however, problems of a fire in the tunnel because we're carrying 
internal combustion engine vehicles within an environment where people are also 
mixed with them. Therefore, safety of the passengers and the users has been 
uppermost in the design of the shuttles and the system in which the shuttles 
operate. This must be the only rail tunnel in the world which has a fire main 
running right the way through it with fire hydrants every 125 meters, a service 
tunnel running right the way along the whole length of the system, so that access 
can be obtained every 375 meters by emergency crews if necessary. We have 
smoke and heat and flame detecters, carbon monoxide detecters, which will alert 
the control center if there are any problems within the tunnel itself." <P>


The Chunnel system also has extensive security measures against terrorism, 
including an electronic device that can help detect trace amounts of explosive 
molecules in parts per billion.<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives. <P>


