<HTML><TITLE>1196</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1196</H3>

  

<CENTER>AIRBAGS - Smaller and Better</CENTER>


<B>ambience</B>airbag inflating<P>
                                   

That's a sound most of us hope we never have to hear - the sound of an airbag 
inflating. Airbags have been shown to reduce fatalities in car crashes, and now 
researchers are finding ways of making them smaller, lighter and safer.  I'm Jim 
Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


"A traditional airbag is constructed from two circular pieces of fabric and has a 
circumferential seam, then."<P>


Jim Nelson is a member of the senior technical staff at Sandia National Laboratories in New Mexico.<P>


"Our bag is constructed from one piece of fabric. It starts out as a square pattern and the edges get folded in towards the center.  And  we have linear
seams, then, which run down those edges."<P>

The seams follow the direction of the weave of the fabric, so that the bag is
strong enough even though it's lighter than most current airbags. The custom fabric is similar to material used in making parachutes.<P>


"Parachutes suffer from the same type of problems that airbags do, in that
you want higher performance but you always want to go smaller. Typically if we 
can go in smaller volumes, which for us translates to lighter fabrics, it downsizes 
everything else associated with the system. The tray that it goes into is smaller, 
which means less material, the support structure is smaller. So when you consider 
the airbag system as a whole, this technology probably will end up decreasing the 
cost of the airbag system."<P>


The reduced size also means that the airbags may be used in places where they're 
currently not found.<P>


"We anticipate implementation oif this airbag in other ground transportation 
vehicles such as buses, trains and potentially into planes also."<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of research

and technology in our daily lives.<P>
