<HTML><TITLE>1197</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1197</H3>

  

<CENTER>AIRBAGS - Softer, lighter, faster</CENTER>



When a car crashes, an airbag has to open in milliseconds to keep the occupants 
from slamming into the steering wheel or dashboard. Using fabric technology 
developed for parachutes, researchers have designed an airbag that's smaller, 
smoother, lighter - and faster. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


 "Airbags in the commercials have this soft, billowy unfolding, but in reality 
they're coming out in like three to four thousands of a second."<P>

<B>ambience</B> airbag inflating <P>


Kenneth Gwinn works in solid and structural mechanics at Sandia National

Laboratories in New Mexico.<P>


"Normally an airbag comes out and it inflates very quickly, it hits the passenger a 
little bit, it's called face slap. And our lightweight fabric reduces this phenomenon 
to be really non-existent. The lightness of the fabric relates to a reduction in the 
forces that are put on the person when the airbag inflates. In addition the fabric is 
very smooth and very silky. It reduces greatly the damage to the skin of your face 
during the accident, because the existing fabric is fairly coarse."<P>


The lighter fabric also means that a packed airbag takes up less than half as much 
space, so it can more easily put in other places besides the steering wheel or 
dashboard.<P>


"Because it's smaller you can tuck it into the side of a car easier, you can tuck it 
into the top of a car if you want to do that, you can put it into the rear of the front 
seat so the people in the back seat are now protected. You  can envision a lot of 
places this airbag could  fit."<P>


Researchers expect these airbags to be standard in most cars in the next five or 
six years.<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of research

and technology in our daily lives.<P>

