<HTML><TITLE>1199</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1199</H3>

  

<CENTER>BRIDGE SAFETY - Listening For Cracks</CENTER>

There are nearly 600,000 bridges in the United States and most of them are 35 to 
40 years old. Using high frequency sensors, scientists are monitoring the bridges 
for structural flaws. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


(95.11.12) "The device that we're looking at here is an acoustic emission 
monitoring system. Its purpose is to receive high frequency sounds from materials 
that are undergoing stress. We have sensors which are contact microphones, very 
high frequency, coupled to a piece of steel. And what we're looking for are the 
sounds that are emitted from cracks growing in the steel as the bridge undergoes 
its normal live stresses from traffic."<P>


David Pryne is a research scientist with the Birl Industrial Research Laboratory at 
Northwestern University.<P>


"Acoustic emission monitoring reduces to the problem of extracting the desired 
sounds, in this case the sound of a growing crack, from a background of noises, 
which on the bridge would be the noises generated by the traffic running over the 
bridge. The way we do this is with a very sophisticated form of pattern 
recognition in the computer. We capture these signals and they're digitized and 
analyzed by the computer, and then plotted out on a computer display. The display 
shows us where the sounds are coming from, and we locate the sources and then 
we perform fairly sophisticated pattern recognition on the signals to decide 
whether or not it's coming from an active crack."<P>


<B>ambience</B> acoustic emissions (95.11.12)<P>

These sounds are typically well above the range of human hearing, but we've been 
able to translate them to an audible frequency.<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

