<HTML><TITLE>1200</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1200</H3>

  

<CENTER>ALTERNATIVE LANDFILL CAPS</CENTER>


When a landfill can't take any more trash, it has to be covered so that water 
doesn't seep in and carry contaminants into the soil or groundwater below.  
Researchers are now looking for alternatives to traditional landfill caps. I'm Jim 
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


<B>ambience</B> bulldozers on landfill <P>

At Sandia National Laboratories in New Mexico, scientists are testing traditional 
and alternative landfill caps side-by-side.<P>


"The test plots are 40 feet wide by 300 foot long. The eastern half of each test 
plot will have a sprinkler system installed in it. We can simulate a 100-year 
rainfall event, snow melt in the spring time, whatever."<P>


Steve Dwyer is the principal investigator for the landfill cover demonstration 
project. Most of the alternative caps are designed to perform as well as or better 
than traditional covers even though they're cheaper and easier to build.  Dwyer 
says they could even help protect the environment from landfills that weren't 
properly designed to begin with.<P>


"A lot of the problems are with existing landfills. They don't have the liners below 
them so basically all they're doing is being installed in a hole in the ground. And if 
that's near a groundwater supply, the leachate coming from the landfill will 
eventually get into that water, and could cause some serious problems. There are 
recorded cases of flora and fauna kills, there's been communities that have had to 
switch drinking water supplies, and if you use a better cover, you can help 
alleviate some of those mistakes of the past, and for future covers you can make 
them all that much better."<P>

"Water is becoming scarcer and scarcer and we're wanting to protect our water 
supplies, and the more we can do that the better off we'll be." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

