<HTML><TITLE>1201</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1201</H3>

  

<CENTER>ALTERNATIVE LANDFILL CAPS - The right design for the climate</CENTER>


When a landfill is closed, it has to be covered to keep water out. But different 
climates may call for different kinds of cover. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the 
Pulse of the Planet. <P>


"We're going to have a variety of alternative landfill covers. They're going to be 
designed specifically for dry environments. They'll emphasize materials that are 
readily available to the area, such as basic soils found in the area, sands and 
gravels."<P>


Steve Dwyer is the principal investigator of the alternative landfill cover 
demonstration project at Sandia National Laboratories in New Mexico. Researchers 
are constructing test plots in the dry climate to compare the performance of new 
designs with tradtional landfill caps.<P>


"We're going to install at least three different covers. We will be taking into 
consideration the environment in the dry areas. We're going to encourage 
evaporation by increasing the storage capabilites of the soil layers. We're going to 
discourage erosion by bettering the vegetative covers. We're going to allow the 
soil covers that are installed to work with the basic drier enviroment, and let the 
dry environment do the majority of the work."<P>


Most landfills are covered with a barrier layer of soil that is designed to keep 
water out. The soil is normally saturated, then molded and compacted into a 
uniform layer. But Dwyer says that in arid climates, problems can occur when the 
soil layer dries and loses water volume. <P>

 

"And it's going to shrink and crack.  And those cracks are going to leave avenues 
for water to get down through and into the waste, which really defeats the whole 
purpose. So when you put it in originally, yeah, you've got a really great cover. But 
as it dries, it's not so great a cover any more."<P>


Further testing should show if Sandia's alternative landfill caps will solve that 
problem. <P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of 
research and technology in our daily lives. <P>

