<HTML><TITLE>1202</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1202</H3>

  

<CENTER>ARTIFICIAL MOUTH</CENTER>


There may be no accounting for taste, but scientists have found a way to measure 
flavor - or at least figure out what aromas help create the particular flavor of a 
particular food.  I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


(95.11.16) "We're actually calling this device a retronasal aroma simulator, or 
artificial mouth. Retronasal aroma is actually the aroma that occurs when people 
chew food in their mouth and air that's released from the food in the mouth goes 
up the back passage to the nose."<P>


Deborah Roberts developed the artificial mouth as a doctoral student in the 
Department of Food Science and Technology at Cornell University. It's a hi-tech 
blender designed to simulate the conditions in the human mouth while a person is 
chewing food. First the food items - grapes in this case - are put in the blender.<P>

<B>ambience</B> grapes being poured in, then liquid, then blender going on (95.11.16)<P>


"Then I'll add the artificial saliva then I'll turn on the air flow and start the 
blender."<P>

"The machine isn't actually tasting the food. It's just simulating the mouth 
conditions that affect flavor release. In the device, the flavor compounds are 
released and they're collected on a trap. We actually analyze the volatiles from 
this trap using a machine called a gas chromatograph, that separates the 
molecules. And then we use a human to sniff these molecules and tell us which of 
them has aroma and what the aroma is. And this way we're able to determine what 
the important aroma compounds are in various foods." <P>


By offering a new way to measure the smell component of food, the artificial 
mouth could help chemists determine, for example, what causes the flavor 
difference between high-fat and a low-fat food. <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

