<HTML><TITLE>1203</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1203</H3>

  

<CENTER>ARTIFICIAL MOUTH - Fat-free flavor</CENTER>

Everyone knows that low-fat ice cream just doesn't taste quite the same as the 
high-fat, premium kind. Now a new device called an artificial mouth seeks to 
measure what it is about the aroma of a food like ice cream that contributes to its 
particular flavor. I'm Jim Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


"When someone eats food, there are taste sensations, such as sweet, sour, salty, 
bitter. But there's also something to flavor called aroma, and that's actually the 
smell component of flavor. The molecules that cause the smell component of 
flavor are those volatile molecules which are in the air above food. And these 
molecules have to proceed up the back passage to the nose." <P>

"A good example of the importance of the smell component to the whole flavor of a 
food, is if you pinch your nose when you're eating, this will actually give a large 
decrease in the perceived flavor." <P>


<B>ambience</B> blender<P>

Deborah Roberts developed the artificial mouth - also known as the retronasal 
aroma simulator - in the Department of Food Science and Technology at Cornell 
University.  It's a modified blender that simulates chewing, temperature, air flow 
and salivation - the conditions in the human mouth when a person is eating.<P>

The molecules that form the aroma are released, and then analyzed to determine 
which aroma compounds are important in different foods.<P>


"For instance, fat free foods often don't have the full aroma character and they 
don't have the same taste as the full fat foods. We're looking at skim milk versus 
whole milk. Everyone knows that it's better to drink milk with low fat, but still 
there's a preference for the higher fat milk. So we are analyzing these two 
products in the artificial mouth, to determine the differences and for us to better 
formulate low fat milk." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

