<HTML><TITLE>1204</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1204</H3>

  

<CENTER>ARTIFICIAL MOUTH - Formulating flavor</CENTER>


How can you measure something as subjective as the taste of food? Scientists 
think they've found a way. It's called an artificial mouth. It's an ordinary  blender 
modified to simulate the conditions in a person's mouth while eating. I'm Jim 
Metzner, and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


<B>ambience</B> blender <P> 

That's the sound of the artificial mouth, also known as the retronasal aroma 
simulator. Deborah Roberts developed it as a PhD candidate at the Department of 
Food Science and Technology at Cornell University. The device measures the aroma 
of food, an important component of taste, and offers food chemists a new tool to 
help formulate flavors.<P>


"One of the advantages of this device is that we can analyze any food. We've 
analyzed fresh raspberries, heated raspberries and heated raspberries with cream 
added, and we were able to determine the flavor compounds that caused 
differences between those three products. We've also analyzed other systems that 
show the effect of oil on flavor  release. This is a very important aspect of foods 
that affects their flavors, the oil content, and we've been able to show how oil 
influences the flavor." <P>


The device is sensitive enough to detect the aroma molecules at the trace levels 
found in food. Another application could be in agriculture.<P>


"As breeders try and determine which varieties they want to continue in their 
programs, they need a measure of the flavor of the food. This device can give that 
measure, and it can allow them to choose those varieties which will give in a very 
flavorful product in the end. For instance in the history of breeding apples, the 
sugar-acid ratio has been used for a very long time to select varieties for future 
breeding. But they haven't actually had a measure of flavor, and this is what this 
device could be used for." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont, to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

