<HTML><TITLE>1175</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1175</H3>

  

<CENTER>MAGNETIC FIELD RESEARCH - The Most Powerful Magnet</CENTER>


Scientists are building the most powerful magnet in the world. With it,

they hope to better understand the hidden properties of matter. I'm Jim

Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


<B>ambience</B> Liquifier  <P>

"What you're hearing in the background is the liquifier that is taking

liquid helimum at minus 459 degrees faranheit, over to a cooldown test of

what will be the world's largest research magnet. It'll produce a magnetic

field of a million times the earth's magnetic field." <P>


Dr. Jack Crow is director of the National High Magnetic Field Laboratory.

He says that there are many applications for magnets of this size.<P>


One is the use of magnetism to study new materials: new chemical 
structures, biological structures, As you turn up the magnetic field, it's like turning up the magnefier on a microscope. So as we go to higher and higher fields, we 
can see smaller and smaller objects.<P>

Magnetism is an important part of motors, and we can store energy in large 
magnet systems. There we can build them from small units to enormous units that 
are magnets the size of a football field, and stores 20 million Watts for an hour. 
And that would take care of the city of Tallahassee, for example, that has a total

generating capacity of 400 million Watts. That would supply the power if we

had an interruption, for a few minutes. And that would give stability to it

so we wouldn't have to come home and look at all our digital clocks

blinking at us." <P>


The high powered magnet is scheduled to be up and running by late 1996.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of

research and technology in our daily lives.<P>

