<HTML><TITLE>1176</TITLE>

<H3>Program # 1176</H3>

 

<CENTER>HUMAN GENOME PROJECT -  Common Heritage of Genes</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><P>

<B>ambience</B>,  dawn chorus<P>

Biologists have found genetic evidence to support the idea that all living things 
are indeed connected.  It means that the future may hold in store a whole new 
generation of drugs and other products.  I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of 
the Planet. <P>


J.Craig Venter is director of the Institute for Genomic Research<P>


" I think people are constantly amazed that the human genes are virtually identical 
to the genes of other species. Even at the DNA sequence level genes from humans 
are virtually greater than 90 percent identical to those from rats and mice. We 
have to go down all the way  to bacteria and plants to find really significant 
differences in the gene structure. And when you look at the protein or the amino 
acid level, the similarity is much, much higher. So I think people will begin to see 
from  really seeing the fundamentals of biology that humans are more related 
perhaps to every other species, including pine trees and grass and fish, insects,  
than they ever imagined.  And that maybe will create a different view of humanity 
and even ecology.<P>

Given a common genetic heritage, plants and animals are now seen as potential 
sources for durgs and other useful products.<P>


"There are plants that produce taxol, which is potentially useful for treating 
breast cancer, and there's ways to genetically engineer plants and other organism 
to produce very large amounts of these compounds, which are very difficult to 
synthsize chemically. So in terms of humsn therapeutics, there's no question that 
plants and  other organisms are going to be used in ability to produce new 
pharmaceutical compounds, perhaps cheaper and faster than have been done in the 
past."<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.  <P>

