<HTML><TITLE>1187</TITLE>


<H3>Program #1187</H3>


<CENTER>BRAIN CANCER TREATMENT -  Precision Irradiation</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><P>

<B>ambience</B>, Linear Accelerator  <P>

We're listening to the sounds of a linear accelerator - a device that

produces a high energy beam of radiation. It's the fire power behind a

non-invasive surgical system that can target and destroy a tumor with

pinpoint does of radiation. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the

Planet.<P>

The system is programmed with a computerized map of a patient's brain, and a 
robotic arm guides a radiation beam to the tumor. If the patient's head should move 
even slightly, the computer can track the tumor and keep the beam focused on its 
target.<P>


 "And it basically is just a precision irradiation. And it is

intended for just about any type of brain cancer initially. It is

undergoing FDA trials to prove that it has value in treating brain tumors.

And we've already started to treat tumors outside the brain, having treated

a tumor of the spinal cord. Further in the future we plan

to treat tumors of the prostate, lung, liver, elsewhere in the body." <P>


Dr. John Adler is an associate professor of Neurosurgery at Stanford

University Medical Center. He says that, while successful treatment will

add healthier years to cancer patients lives, it shouldn't be seen as a cure for

the disease.<P>


 "There are limitations to it. It's not a cure for cancer. It can irradicate a tumor 
that a cancer may produce, but it can't eliminate the entire cancer from your 
system. And if for example, a malignant brain tumor of the brain can often send 
little fingers of tumor off into the normal brain. One can't erradicate every finger. 
One may be able to chop off the head of the octopus, but one can't get every little 
tenticle. But we've learned from experience that in many patients there is

value in chopping off the head of the octopus and one lives both better and

longer." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognise the role of

research and technology in our daily lives.<P>

