<HTML><TITLE>1178</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1178</H3>


<CENTER>FALL SAFE FLOORS - The Elderly</CENTER>


<B>music</B><P>

To the elderly, one hard fall can mean the difference between being sctive or 
bedridden. Now, scientists are developing a new type of floor that may help 
prevent such a debilitating accident. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the 
Planet. <P>


<B>ambience</B>, Walking - Stocking Feet on Floor<P>

That's the sound of someone walking across a safety floor.<P>


"It's been shown that people over 60, all people over 60 on average, fall at least 
once a year. Now, by the time you get to 80 years old, this increases exponentially. 
So if we can have an impact on reducing the number of injuries from falls, then I 
think that will not only benefit those who are being prevented from injury, but it 
will also bring down health care costs."<P>


Peter Cavanaugh, a distinguished professor of Locomotion Studies at Penn State 
University is helping to develop the Safety Floor. The floor boards are supported 
underneath by many vertical columns. Like plastic straws, they absorb sudden 
impacts by buckling under pressure - cushioning falls but supporting normal 
walking.<P>


 "Well, the goal of the floor is to install it in places where we can concentrate 
people who are at high risk for falls. We have been studying where people fall at a 
typical nursing home and we have found that most of the falls occur in the 
patient's own rooms So If we can put the flooring in the patients' rooms, then that 
is the area that it will do most good."<P>

"The great benefit of our floor is that it's something that doesn't need any 
compliance by the patient. They don't have to take a pill, they don't have to wear a 
pad. The floor is there if and when they fall." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.  <P>

