<HTML><TITLE>1179</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1179</H3>


<CENTER>ULTRASONIC TOXIC WASTE DESTROYER - How it Works</CENTER><P>


<B>music</B><P>

<B>ambience</B>: Machinery - Ultrasonic Toxic Waste Destroyer<P>

Scientists are developing a machine that can destroy hazardous waste using high-
frequency sound waves. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


We're listening to an ultrasonic toxic waste destroyer. It's pumping contaminated water 
into a chamber that's bombarded with sound waves at frequencies around the upper 
threshold of human hearing.<P>


"These systems or reactors are called ultrasonic irradiation devices and they're 
designed to introduce ultrasound into water and thereby generate gas bubbles that 
collapse violently and generate combustion-like conditions that destroy chemical 
contaminants present in water." <P>


Dr. Michael Hoffman is a professor of Environmental Chemistry at the California 
Institute of Technology. He says the device generates a sound wave with a frequency of 
around15 kilohertz.<P>


"At this level, the sound waves force the formation of bubbles in water, similar to 
opening a carbonated beverage." <P>


The bubbles are allowed to develop to a point at which they become unstable. Then 
another ultrasonic wave is applied.<P>


"And then as a successive sonic wave, ultrasonic wave passes through the bubble, the 
bubble collapses and generates localized high temperatures and pressures. The pressures 
within a gas bubble while it collapses can be as high as 1,000 atmospheres and the 
temperatures as high as about 5,000 degrees Centigrade. For example, the temperature of 
the surface of the sun is about 6,000 degrees Centigrade, so we generate very extreme 
conditions, temperatures and pressures much higher than those encountered during high 
temperature incineration. And we harness these conditions to destroy chemical 
compounds." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

<B>music</B><P>
