<HTML><TITLE>1180</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1180</H3>


<CENTER>ULTRASONIC TOXIC WASTE DESTROYER - Advantages</CENTER>


<B>music</B><P>

<B>ambience</B>:Machinery-Ultrasonic Toxic Waste Destroyer<P>


We're listening to a machine that could provide scientists with a clean and inexpensive 
way to destroy toxic chemicals in water. All it takes is some high-frequency sound. I'm 
Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


The Ultrasonic Toxic Waste Destroyer pumps contaminated water into a chamber where 
it's exposed to high frequency sound waves . The sound energy  causes bubbles to form in 
the water which grow and become unstable and eventually collapse. This produces  
extremely high temperatures and pressures which destroy a wide range of chemical 
compounds in the water .<P>


"Most of the chemical compounds are used in manufacturing. For instance, a major 
chemical contaminant that we can readily destroy is perchloroethylene, which is 
conventional dry-cleaning fluid."<P>


Dr. Michael Hoffman is a professor of Environmental Chemistry at the California 
Institute of Technology. He says by varying the frequencies, the machine can destroy 
many different contaminants.<P>


"In ultrasound, we can harness frequencies over the range of about 16 kilohertz up to 1 
megahertz in frequency and different chemical compounds are destroyed more readily at 
one frequency versus another frequency. So by appropriately applying a particular 
frequency range, we can destroy a very broad range of chemical compounds."<P>


The cost of the components is quite small compared to some other technologies, such as 
high-temperature incineration where the facility may run into the tens of millinos of 
dollars to construct. Ultrasound is quite inexpensive, devices are commonly available and 
capital cost range in the tens of thousands of dollars as opposed to millions of dollars."<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives.<P>

