<HTML><TITLE>1181</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1181</H3>


<CENTER>MONEY RECYCLING</CENTER>


<B>music</B><P>

Ever wonder what happens to paper money when it wears out? Well, like many 
other materials it can end up in a landfill, unless it's recycled. I'm Jim Metzner 
and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


<B>ambience</B>, Machine, Shredder <P>

We're listening to the sound of a machine that's shredding old paper currency.<P>


"This machine will count, verify, as well as destroy the money if need be. What 
happens is the money is placed with the straps on it in the front of the machine, it 
goes through a process where it's verified, and if it needs to be destroyed, it is 
cut into confetti like pieces and shoots up the tube in the back that's green where 
you can actually see it shooting through. It goes into another room in which case 
liquid is added to the material and then formed into a charcoal-like briquette." <P>


Abby Wong is with the Federal Reserve Bank in Los Angeles. They've been working 
with a wide range of companies who see the strong fibers of U.S. paper money as a 
valuable raw material.<P>


"Venders who have been interested in our shredded currency have ranged from 
freeway paneling to roof tiles to fire logs. Currently we are in an effort with a 
vendor where they take our shredded currency briquettes and mix it with a 
concrete slurry. And what the product is is a wood shingle-like roof tile. Other 
vendors that we've worked with for the recycled products would be fire logs. This 
company mixes landfill material, just as ours. And it's a combustible material, 
which works well for environmentally-safe fire logs. Other options have been, 
which interior designers actually like, are insulation panels for buildings because 
the green tint to the money makes a very attractive color in the paneling." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives. <P>

