<HTML><TITLE>1182</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1182</H3>

<CENTER>MONEY RECYCLING - Green Products</CENTER>


<B>music</B><P>

Disposing of money that's been worn out or otherwise rendered unusable can cost a 
lot of money in and of itself. But now the federal government is finding some 
creative ways of putting unfit currency back into circulation. I'm Jim Metzner and 
this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>


<B>ambience</B>, Machinery, Money Recycling Facility <P>


We're at a recycling facility where paper money is being shreadded and, with the 
help of hig-pressure machinery, converted into briquettes.<P>


"The amount of money that is shredded in the Los Angeles branch is approximately 
15 tons per week. That's about a quarter of a million dollars per week. We are one 
of the biggest processers of cash in the United States." <P>


Abby Wong is with the Federal Reserve Bank in Los Angeles.<P>

"Here in Los Angeles branch, it costs us about 100,000 a year to place the 
currency in a landfill. We can save, in operating costs, this 100,000 dollars if we 
actually send it to vendors so that they can recycle this money into usable building 
products someplace else." <P>


The briquettes of shredded money are sent out to a wide range of companies who 
convert the currency into usable products.<P>


"Where you might see the products of shredded currency today, could be in novelty 
items, if you see then inside pens, you might see them inside a little bag sold 
somewhere. We've also seen them inside teddy bears. Typically you're going to see 
them on roofs - wood shingles on roofs, freeway panels will have a little green 
tint, sound panels will also have that green tint. You might see them in a fire log 
in a fireplace... We hope that our recycling efforts will certainly environmentally 
reduce landfills, reduce our operating costs, as well as place products back out on 
the market. That could be fire logs, could be freeway insulation, it could be the 
roof tiles. The money that you've used in your daily lives will get back to you in 
the products that you buy every day on the market." <P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and 
technology in our daily lives. <P>

