<HTML><TITLE>1183</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1183</H3>

<CENTER>SELF-HEATING MEALS</CENTER><P>


<B>music</B><P>

Convenience foods just got a bit more convenient. There's now a new type of

TV dinner that not only cooks in 14 minutes, it doesn't even need an oven.

I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


"So when one opens the box at one end of the carton and slides out the contents, 
they'll see a white foam tray that's holding the heater. That is beneath the food 
entree and there's two other packages in there. One is the utensils and knife and 
pepper fork and salt. And the other's a bag of plain old tap water. And, when one 
rips the water bag open and pours it on the heater, those two ounces meet up with 
the salt that is already in the heater, and that is going to create a liquid that is 
going to corrode the magnesium and iron." <P>


<B>ambience</B>, Sizzling, TV Dinner  <P>

Drew McLandrich is with Zesto Therm, manufacturers of this self-heating meal. He 
says that when the salt water comes into contact with the heater, which is a 
small porous bag of magnesium and iron, it can raise the temperature of the food 
in the container by 100 degrees Faranheit.<P>


"What's going on inside the box right now is the heater is running its course. And 
what's happened is the salt water has found the granuals of magnesium that have 
very fine bits of iron attached to them. So the salt water is fizzing off the little 
granules of iron from the little granules of magnesium, and the heat that's being 
created is being transfered through the thin film of the food tub, into the food 
itself and heating the food."<P>


Mr. McLandrich also says that the magnesium and iron used to heat the food

are safe materials found in our everyday diet.<P>


The food is in a sealed tub with a film membrane atop the tub which is pressed up 
against the heater. And that keeps any of the two things from mixing. But if that 
were to occur, it would not be detrimental." <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of

research and technology in our daily lives.<P>

