<HTML><TITLE>1184</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1184</H3>


<CENTER>SELF-HEATING MEALS - More Than Just a TV Dinner</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><P>

Who ever thought corrosion could be useful? One company is using the

properties of salt water corrosion to cook TV dinners. I'm Jim

Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


<B>ambience</B>, Sizzling, TV Dinner <P>

We're listening to the sounds of a Heater Meal - a packaged food product

that's cooked by pouring salt water onto a porous pouch of a

magnesium and iron alloy. The salt water rigorously corrodes the metals,

raising the temperature of the adjacent food package by 100 degrees

Faranheit. <P>


 "The idea for self heating metallic alloy powders is one that's been around since 
the 1930s. But there have been really no significant uses of the product until the 
Desert Storm conflict that led to the military taking this heating technology and 
adopting it for field use for soldiers to heat a meal ready

to eat." <P>

 Drew McLandrich is with Zesto Therm, manufacturers of the self-heating meal.<P>


"We've made about 65 million heaters for the military in the last half dozen years. 
The Heater Meals product is used by most everybody. Long distance truck drivers 
have been our first and most successful market. And the product's in around 800 
truck stops in 48 states. Additional users would surely be hunters, campers, 
fishermen, boaters, anybody that would like a hot meal anytime anyplace. That 
would include football fans at halftime of a football game, picnickers, people at a 
music concert. So it has a great variety of uses." <P>


And the self-heating technology could be used for more than solid food.<P>

"A beverage for sure could be heated. And we do have prototypes of a

baby bottle warmer, and we're also working on making a portable hot cup of

coffee or a hot cup of tea or cocoa. And we have a product that we may be bringing 
out in the next year or so that a homeowner could use to thaw a frozen pipe, even 
one that the homeowner couldn't actively reach that was frozen back in a wall."<P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of

research and technology in our daily lives.<P>

