<HTML><TITLE>1185</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1185</H3>

<CENTER>BRAIN CANCER TREATMENT</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><P>

Neurosurgeons have a new tool that may allow them to treat brain cancer on

an out-patient basis. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


<B>ambience</B>, Robotic Arm  <P>

That's the sound of a robotic arm that's positioning a

high-powered x-ray. It's part of a new device that destroys brain tumors

with an intense beam of radiation. This type of technology has been

available for some time, but conventional methods require the patient's

head to be surgically attached to a frame in order to keep it still.<P>


The difficulty with this approach is it does in fact involve

putting screws in the patient's head and is painful. In addition, the

technoloy is sufficiently painful that we can only treat the patient one

time. And with very big tumors, a one-time treatment risks injuring the

brain immediately surrounding the tumor." <P>


Dr. John Adler is an associate professor of Neurosurgery at Stanford

University Medical Center.  Using technology originally designed for use in cruise

missles, he's developing a new form of treatment that tracks the subtle 
movements of a person's head, avoiding the use of the frame and the screws. And 
since there are no wounds to heal, the patient may receive several treatments of 
low level radiation as opposed to one large dose.<P>


 "Conventional radiation therapy works by using a much broader beam of

radiation and treating both healthy tissue and malignant tissue.

Conventional radiation relies on the fact that the malignant tissue doesn't

recover from a dose of radiation as well as the healthy tissue. And by

dividing a dose of radiation into several smaller doses, one allows the

healthy tissue to recover, but the malignant tissue doesn't bounce back. I think it 
leads, not only to a better outcome in many of these patients, but also a

far easier way for them to have the operation. <P>


Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of

research and technology in our daily lives.<P>

