<HTML><TITLE>1186</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1186</H3>

  

<CENTER>BRAIN CANCER TREATMENT - Wielding the Cyber Knife</CENTER><P>


<B>music</B><P>

Using technology originally designed for cruise missles, neurosurgeons

can track and destroy brain tumors without breaking the skin. I'm Jim

Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>


<B>ambience</B>, Operating Table <P>

We're listening to the sound of an operating table that's positioning a patient 
underneath a device called the cyber knife. It's a type of x-ray machine that 
surgeons may soon use to treat tumors.<P>


"This is the cyber knife. It consists of a robot which has six different joints that 
can move the radiation source with great flexibility. The radiation source is 
something called a linear accelerator, a device that makes x-rays." <P>


Dr. John Adler is an associate professor of Neurosurgery at Stanford

University Medical Center. He says the precision of the new technology

allows surgeons to point several beams of radiation at a tumor. Surgeons

scan the tumorous portion of the brain and program it into the device. If

the patient moves even slightly, the robot reads its computer-stored map and

keeps the beams focused on the tumor.<P>


"The patient's head is restrained so that their head moves within plus

or minus five millimeters, which almost any cooperative adult can do. And

while the patient's lying there making small little movements, these

movements are registered by the imaging system. And, using what's really

analogous to cruise missle technology, the patient's head is tracked as it

makes small movements. And this tracking capability allows one to keep the

beam, this very intense beam of radiation, focused on the tumor at all

times. And because one knows exactly where the tumor is, one can also shoot at 
the tumor from many different directions. By shooting at it from

many different directions, one concentrates the radiation where all these beams

intersect and we make that point of intersection the same as the tumor." 

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of

research and technology in our daily lives.<P>

