<TITLE>1160</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1160</H3><P>

<CENTER>SPIDER SILK - Milking Spiders</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
<B>ambience,</B> Erector Set motor, Spider Silk Extractor (95.7.21 34:00)<BR>
We're listening to the sounds of a machine that's extracting a strand of silk from a spider. Scientists are now studying ways of putting this unique natural material to work for humans. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

DAT 95.7.21 32:30) "OK, so now the silk is being extracted. It's coming out at two centimeters a second here. The drag line silk is this beautiful golden color. This spider is sitting here oblivious to the fact that it's being silked. You can see that the machine is winding up a spool of spider fibers or spider thread."<P>

Lynn Jelinsky (gel-IN-skee) is director of Cornell's Center for Advanced Technology.<P>

8:00) "What we're really interested in is making very high performance materials, for example parachutes, seat belts. And the reason is that the spider silk has properties that no synthetic material can capture. It gives a little bit and then it stiffens as you stretch it. You can think about, have you ever seen a spider doing a bungee jump? No. The spider drops nice and smoothly, whereas, if it were a conventional elastomer, the spider would bungee up and down and that doesn't happen."<P>

Although it seems the spiders don't mind being "silked," the process is rather time consuming. Jelinski is exploring the idea of mass producing the spider silk chemicals by growing them in genetically engineered plants or other organisms.<P>

24:00) "The advantage of producing it in some other organism is that you don't have to deal with the spiders. It's very time consuming to take these spiders down and pull the silk out at the right rate. We would be much better if we could plant an entire field of tobacco, let's say, and have that be busy making acres and acres of high performance material. And that's really our dream."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.  <BR>
