<TITLE>1161</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1161</H3><P>

<CENTER>SPIDER SILK - Uses</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
Nature is providing scientists with a blueprint for creating high-performance materials. Take, for example, the amazing properties of spider silk... I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet. <P>

<B>ambience,</B> Erector Set Helicopter, Spider Silk Extractor (95.7.21 34:00)
We're listening to the sounds of a machine that's slowly extracting a strand of silk from a spider.<P>

DAT 95.7.21 4:00) "We're entering an exciting new time in material science. There is an emerging new field called biomolecular materials and what that is is gleaning from nature ideas to make new polymers and that's what we're doing with the spider silk."<P>

Lynn Jelinsky (gel-IN-skee) is director of Cornell University's Center for Advanced Technology. She's studying the golden orb-weaving spider, whose silk is as strong as steel, yet flexible enough to be stretched to ten times its original length.<P>

17:00) "The uses for spider silk are really only limited by your imagination. You can immediately think of big quantity uses - for example, seat belts where you'd like it to give just a little bit and then you'd like it to stiffen before your head went through that windshield. Also, parachutes are another opportunity, but we shouldn't overlook the possible applications in biomedical devices. there are biodegradable polymers. They could be used for ultrafine sutures, for example, in surgery."<P>

25:00) "It may turn out that this is just not an economically viable way to go. However, I think in the long run, this field of biomolecular materials is givigng us insight that we never had before, and out of it will come new materials, whether they're spider made, plant made or man made is hard to tell, but certainly by looking at the spider, it's giving us new insight into how to make synthetic polymers."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
