<TITLE>1162</TITLE>


<H3>Program #1162</H3><P>

<CENTER>ANIMAL WASTE PRODUCTS</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
A poultry farm with 100,000 chickens can produce ten tons of manure every day. Now, scientists are developing a machine which can convert that waste into natural gas and other useful products. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience,</B> Shaker (95.7.20A 105M)<BR>
We're in a laboratory listening to the sounds of an incubator. It's growing a special type of bacteria that will be used in the thermophilic anaerobic digester (THER-mo-fill-ick  ANN-air-oh-bick..).<P>

140) "In the absense of air, there's a group of bacteria that can break down organic matter, in this case the manure, and convert it into very small molecules, which is methane and carbon dioxide. And methane is natural gas. So we thought that may be a way to manage the waste and at the same time produce something valuable."<P>

Dr. Jason Shih (SHEE) is a professor at North Carolina State University's Department of Poultry Science. He says the machine works by heating the waste to around 115 degrees Faranheit. Special bacteria then convert the waste into three phases.<P>

192) "One is a gas phase, which is a biogas or methane gas, which you can use as a fuel. Liquid phase is the waste water coming out of the digester. The waste water has a high nutrient content. We studied that and found that it can be utilized as a source of nutrient to support fish growth. Then the third phase is sludge, which sounds dirty stuff, but we can convert it into what we call a solid byproduct. And of course there's some protein in it and some vitamin in it. They all can be a good nutrient source for growing chicken or any other animals."<P>

Dr. Shih says that, in theory, a farm with 50,000 chickens could supply enough fuel to provide electricity for about 200 homes. <P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognise the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<P>
