<TITLE>1164</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1164</H3><P>

<CENTER>SOLAR CHIPS - Applications</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
In the future, buildings, railroad ties and virtually any other structure that's exposed to light may be used as a solar collector. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience,</B> Mortar and Pestle (95.8.24A 109M - cut #2, mono)<BR>
We're listening to the sounds of a mortar and pestle grinding chunks of silicon into small grains. This powder will be added to a cement mixture and formed into a flat sheet that'll conduct electricity like a solar panel.<P>

348) "Solar panels now are mostly used to power satellites in space where there is no power grid to hook onto. Our purpose is to make something that can supply the general energy needs of the world population here on earth."<P>

Dr. James Van Vechten (VECK-ten) is a professor of electric and computer engineering at Oregon State University. He says one of the first applications of the material will be attaching them to roofing shingles.<P>

367) "Normally the roofing shingles are outdoors and when the sun is up, it shines on them. These would be connected together in series as the shingles are normally laid on the roof, so that they would produce tens of amps of current at fifty volts, which is the legal maximum for a unprotected voltage outdoors."<P>

Dr. Van Vechten imagines these solar collectors could be attached to everything from railroad ties to office buildings. And they might even make their way indoors.<P>

460) "There's a considerable waste of energy in taking the 120 volts AC that comes out of the wall and converting it down to three volt DC, which is what a modern computer or many other modern electronic devices run on. With the solar cells, they naturally produce DC at low voltages. It would be quite easy, for example, to have the solar cells on the case in normal room lighting, convert the room lighting into the power supply for the computer itself."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
