<TITLE>1166</TITLE>
<H3>Program #1166</H3><P>

<CENTER>ANIMAL WASTE PRODUCTS - Chicken Feed</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
<B>ambience,</B> Chickens, Muscoot Farm (91.9.2-1 87N)<BR>
For over 15 years, scientists have been researching ways to manage the vast amount of feathers and other waste produced as a biproduct of chicken farming.  What's all this work amounted to?... Well, for one thing, Chicken feed.  I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Jason Shih (SHEE) is a professor at North Carolina State University's Department of Poultry Science. He's been developing a machine that uses bacteria to break down animal waste into carbon dioxide and methane - or natural gas. One day, a dead chicken accidentally ended up in the digester, and that lead to a curious discovery.<P>

250) "And then we opened up the digester after a few days - the chicken also disappeared. And we'd like to find out why."<P>

It turns out that a particular strain of bacteria used in Dr. Shih's system was hearty enough to break down even the toughest of proteins.<P>

"Chicken feather, which is made of protein called 'keratin,' a very tough protein, it's not digestible by our intestinal tract. Apparantly, the digester that we were operating seems to be able to digest the feathers. So we spent two or three years, and we finally found the bacteria."<P>

The bacteria produce an enzyme that can convert keratin and other tough proteins into amino acids. The resulting product can be used as a low-cost, nutritional protein source for chicken and other livestock feed. Now that's more than chicken feed when you think of how many chicken feathers are out there.<P>

352) "In the United States, we produce about one million tons of chicken feathers every year. If we can convert that chicken feather to make it become a digestible protein, we think we can generating about 400 million US dollars a year for the market, based on the protein value."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognise the role of research and technology in our daily lives<BR>
<B>music</B>

</HTML>
</DOC>
