<HTML>
<TITLE>1167</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1167</H3><P>

<CENTER>CONTRACEPTIVE VACCINE</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
In the past, vaccines have helped prevent everything from the Measles to Polio - and now, a new vaccine may prevent pregnancy. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

ambience, Shaker, Laboratory (95.8.20A 15o - STEREO)
We're listening to the sounds of a laboratory shaker. It's being used to analyze blood samples taken from baboons who've been vaccinated against sperm. Dr. Erwin Goldberg, professor of Biochemistry at Northwestern University, is developing the contraceptive vaccine. Its active ingredient is a unique protein found only in sperm. Injecting it directly into the female's bloodstream causes an immune response.<P>

103) "This stimulates the immune system to produce antibodies against a foreign substance. Sperm contain components that are not present in the female. These are recognized as foreign very much the same way that bacteria are recognized as foreign, and an immune response to this foreign material is mounted, and will then have the protective effect."<P>

179) "We're testing this vaccine in a group of female baboons. These animals now are being mated, and we're determining over a period of several menstrual cycles of the baboons, how long they're protected against pregnancy. So far, in our first study we achieved an efficacy level of between 75 and 80 percent protection against pregnancy in the female baboons."<P>

They're also testing the vaccine to see how long its effects last.
164) "In the case of the birth control vaccine that we're working on, we have done studies to demonstrate that it is reversible, that the effect wears off after approximately eight to twelve months."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<P>
<B>music</B><P>

</HTML>
