<H3>Program #1169</H3><P>

<CENTER>HUMAN GENOME PROJECT - Diagnosing Disease</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
<B>ambience,</B>  pipetting machine (DAT 95.5.1  45:30)<BR>
Scientists from all over the world are currently mapping the human genome - the collection of 60,000 or so genes packaged in the units that we call chromosomes.  Their efforts are already having a profound effect on how we diagnose disease.  I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

We're listening to the sounds of a pipetting machine - used to prepare samples in human genome research.  With us is J. Craig Venter, director of the Institute for Genomic Research.<P>

DAT 95.5.1 7:25)  "There's about 5,000 genetic diseases that are due to defects in single genes. And so we're leading an effort right now to take the genes that we've discovered, to get them placed back on the physical maps of the chromosomes so that we can very rapidly get a list of all the genes there to find which is the gene that causes that disease. We were involved in a collaboration with Burt Vogelstein at Johns Hopkins University where we discovered three new genes that are involved in the cause of colon cancer. And so from a period of time of discovering those genes in our database to the actual publication showing that these were the cause of this kind of colon cancer was about three months time. That's in contrast to the previous studies. For example, it took a decade and well over $100 million to find the gene in the tip of chromosome four which is actually responsible for Huntington's Disease. So by having all this information in a much shorter period of time, and being able to localize it back to the chromosomes, it's going to speed up our discovery of the cause of thousands of genetic diseases. And that's going to lead to early diagnostics, which with things like cancer, could be very valuable because if you can detect it early, there are treatments such as surgery to deal with it."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
<B>music</B><P>

</HTML>
