<TITLE>1170</TITLE>

<B>Program #1170</B><P>

<CENTER>HUMAN GENOME PROJECT - Knowing the Future of Disease</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
As scientists learn more about the causes of heredity illnesses, they're able to better predict at an early age individuals who will be at risk later in life.  This glimpse into the future may well advance the cause of medicne, but how will it effect the lives of those diagnosed?  I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

J. Craig Venter is director of the Institute for Genomic Research.<P>

(DAT 95.5.1  p4/5)  "Right now what we can do with Huntington's Disease and other genetic diseases is we can diagnose those at the earliest possible stage of human life and predict that that individual will come down with Huntington's Disease somewhere in their third or fourth decade of life. But we can't do anything about it right now. We can predict the future, but we can't alter the future. That's why it's critical that there is public education - that people understand these discoveries, understand the implications for their own lives. We have a problem with people who are afraid to have the test for Huntington's Disease or some of these other diseases because if they have them and it's a positive test, they could lose their life insurance or their health insurance. They could even lose their employment because with the insurance industry, they view it as they're no longer part of the shared risk, they're a known entity that they're going to come down with this disease. So we're going to have an increasing situation, unless we can get some laws changed, of genetic discrimination. People, because they know what's going to happen sometime, maybe forty years in the future, they're going to be discriminated against now. So I think there's a lot of serious implication with any new information, there's good and there's bad news. But as any information moves forward, it's going to have a tremendous positive impact on society and health care."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
<B>music</B><P>


