<H3>Program #1171</H3>

<CENTER>TEXTILE RESEARCH - Pyro-Man</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
A fire fighter's nightmare is walking into a building where the temperature is so hot that an entire room can burst into flame.  I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

In order to develop new clothing that can withstand that kind of heat, scientists have enlisted the help of new sort of mannequin - Pyro-Man.<P>

<B>ambience,</B> Fire Burst (95.8.22A 406M) - mono<BR>
That's the sound of a burst of flame engulfing Pyro-Man.<P>

323) "What we have is a system that allows us to surround the mannequin with a cylinder of flames that would simulate this condition that a fire fighter might face."<P>

Dr. Roger Barker is a professor of textile materials science at North Carolina State University.<P>

377) "Typically, we would expose Pyro-Man to a flashover condition. That's an emergency condition that would be faced perhaps by a fire fighter who would walk into a room where the surfaces in that room and the gases in that room would have reached a condition where they would be spontaneously engulfing the room in flames. So it's a fairly high thermal exposure."<P>

470) "In the case of Pyro-Man, what we have are heat flux sensors which measure the thermal energy on the surface of Pyro-Man. And we have 122 of those distributed over the surface of the mannequin. And they take the reading of thermal energy or intesity of the thermal energy. And that output is analyzed and, we're able to predict a level of protection that would be provided by a test garment in terms of the degree of second degree burn, third degree burn, total body burn, and also where on the torso that burn is going to occur. And you can see how valuable that would be to us in terms of designing the protective garment or the protective material."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
<B>music</B><P>



