<TITLE>1172</TITLE>

<H3>Program #1172</H3><P>

<CENTER>TEXTILE RESEARCH- Fireproof Clothing</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
<B>ambience,</B> Fire Engines (SF 43A 660/B 258-279)<BR>
The latest fashion in fire fighting these days is a uniform that can withstand extreme bursts of flame, simultaneously, it lets the body cool itself off by releasing heat through the garment. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Roger Barker is director of the Thermal Protection Laboratory at North Carolina State University's College of Textiles. Their research is helping manufacturers develop better fire protective clothing.<P>

133) "Our role is to understand how the fiber may be spun into yarn and may be woven into fabric to increase its performance - the ability of the fabric to insulate against a high thermal exposure. At the same time, can we design a material so it is also able to allow moisture vapor to pass through it, because that's a big part of the way the body cools itself off - through the evaporation of sweat."<P>

This kind of research has helped develop many protective garments, such as a fire fighter's coat.<P>

206) "The coat typically consists of three layers of fabrics: The outer shell fabric that provides a level of fire resistance. Right immediately under that there's a layer called a moisture barrier. That's there to keep water from coming in and getting the fire fighter wet. And then there's a third layer that's called a thermal liner. And generally that's there to add another level of thermal insulation. And so all these three fabric systems have to function together. And some of the choices that have to made are very technical about how to make these choices and the synergy that can exist between these three different fabric materials."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
<B>music</B><P>



</HTML>
