<TITLE>1173</TITLE>

<B>Program #1173</B><P>

<CENTER>TEXTILE RESEARCH - Coppelius</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
Textile scientists now have a new tool for designing more comfortable clothing - a mannequin that sweats. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

Dr. Roger Barker is a professor of textile materials science at North Carolina State University. He's introducing us to Coppelius (koh-PEEL-ee-us).<P>

"He is a mannequin that actually sweats by virtue of the fact that we deliver moisture to simulated sweat glands distributed over his body. There's 187 of these tubes that are connected to sweat pores, but the difference between Coppelius, our sweating robot, and a human being is that we can control the rate of sweating and we can always have the same rate of sweating - we can do this reproducibly. So we can dress Coppelius out in a test garment and measure the heat loss, come up with an engineering measurement of that. He is suspended on a very sensitive balance, so all the while we can measure the change in the weight of the mannequin and that's an indication of how much moisture is being held and trapped inside the clothing."<P>

Coppelius is being used to measure how body heat dissipates through fabrics in climate conditions as diverse as a frozen tundra or a steamy rainforest.<P>

429) "Coppelius's skin is really a membrane that takes the moisture that comes to the pore and spreads it out, just like it would if you were sweating and your skin was getting increasingly wetter and wetter. So he's going to be very useful to us in studying clothing comfort for all sorts of things from skiwear to protective clothing. Chemical protective suits, for example, is one area where we're very interested in the heat burden that would be imposed, and Coppelius is going to help us study that."<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
<B>music</B>



</HTML>
</DOC>
