<HTML>

<TITLE>1174</TITLE>

<B>Program #1174</B><P>

<CENTER>MAGNETIC FIELD RESEARCH</CENTER><P>

<B>music</B><BR>
For most people, magnets are what they use to hang things on the refrigerator door with. But to many scientists, they're useful tools for developing new materials and processes. I'm Jim Metzner and this is the Pulse of the Planet.<P>

<B>ambience,</B> Cooling Pipes (95.9.3A 72M)<BR>
We're standing near the cooling system for a high powered magnet at the National High Magnetic Field Laboratory. Dr. Jack Crow is the Lab's director.<P>

60) "What we're listening to here is the water rushing through. This is extremely pure water, rushing through to cool the very large magnets."<P>

Dr. Crow says that high powered magnets like these have already been used for many applications - for example, the Magnetic Resonance Imagers available at many hospitals. They work by exposing the human body to a magnetic field, causing the nuclei of individual atoms to rotate.<P>

334) "And then from that, if we shine a signal in, a radio frequency signal, it disturbs that frequency of rotation and then it send a signal back because of that, which we convert into an image inside your body totally non-invasively. And we can do that in other materials also."<P>

High powered magnets are being used to manipulate atoms in the manufacture of new materials.<P>

360) "We have some experiments running on right now looking at the processing of new materials in magnetic fields. And that's processing polymers or plastics. And that's using the magnetic field to line up the little molecules in plastics and we make the plastics much stronger. That means we can make the plastic bottle thinner. We can make it so it degrades faster in a trash dump."<P>

Techniques like this can also be used to develop more efficient semiconductor chips which would, in turn, bring us faster computers.<P>

Pulse of the Planet is presented by DuPont to recognize the role of research and technology in our daily lives.<BR>
<B>music</B>



</HTML>
