<LI><A NAME=ToC_702 HREF="#Header_702" >Step 4. Coding CGI Programs with S-HTTP (Optional)</A>
<LI><A NAME=ToC_703 HREF="#Header_703" >Step 5. Using S-HTTP</A>
</MENU><P>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="HDRSHTTPOV" HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC_614">Overview of S-HTTP security</A></H2>
<P>
<P>
S-HTTP is a security-enhanced variant of HTTP proposed by
Enterprise Integration Technologies (EIT).
It is a message-based protocol that allows you to choose the
security specifications you want for each transaction between
a client and a server.
<P>
With S-HTTP, you can specify
a wide variety of cryptographic options (CRYPTOPTS)
for each hypertext link
in an HTML document that uses the HTTP protocol.
Hypertext links are defined in the anchor coding.
<P>
In the anchor coding,
you specify the CRYPTOPTS that
tell the client the appropriate security for the document
referenced in the anchor.
For your server, you can choose
whether you want communications to be:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Encrypted
<LI>Signed
<LI>Both encrypted and signed
</UL>
<P>
You also specify CRYPTOPTS in protection setups
and, optionally, in ACL files.
Protection setups protect one or more files in one or more
directories based on URLs.
ACL files limit access to one or more files in a directory.
<P>
The CRYPTOPTS in protection setups and ACL files
enforce the security as the document is served.
You should code these CRYPTOPTS because:
<UL>
<P><LI>The server does not know what CRYPTOPTS were specified
in the anchor coding.
The server only knows what CRYPTOPTS the client is using and
what CRYPTOPTS the client is capable of using based on what the
client sends in its request for the document.
<P><LI>All vendors'
clients may not handle the CRYPTOPTS in an anchor the same way.
</UL>
Therefore, the only way you can ensure the server enforces the security
you want is to code CRYPTOPTS in protection setups and,
optionally, in ACL files.
<P>
The CRYPTOPTS you specify for a document
in an anchor must be consistent with the CRYPTOPTS
you specify in protection setups and ACL files.
If they are not, the server won't serve the document
even if the client has complied with the CRYPTOPTS
specified in the anchor.
Again, the server does not know what was coded in the
anchor.
It uses what you've coded in protection setups and, optionally,
in ACL files to determine how to serve the document.
<P>
Because you can specify different CRYPTOPTS for different
anchors, a client and the server must
negotiate the CRYPTOPTS for each anchor individually.
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Header_615">A scenario</A></H3>
Suppose you create a welcome (or home) page for your
clients using HTTP protocol (transport mode).
Within your welcome page, you specify some anchors
that use S-HTTP.
<P>
You code CRYPTOPTS in each S-HTTP anchor to tell the client
the appropriate security for the document
referenced in the anchor.
<P>
For each document referenced in an S-HTTP anchor, you
code protection setups and ACL files to ensure that the security
you want is enforced when the document is served.
<P>
When a user at a client specifies the URL for your welcome
page, the server serves the welcome page.
<OL>
<P><LI>A user clicks on an S-HTTP anchor on your welcome page.
<P><LI>The client reads the anchor and compares its own CRYPTOPTS
with the CRYPTOPTS specified in the anchor.
<P><LI>If the client cannot comply with the CRYPTOPTS
specified in the anchor, the negotiation fails.
The request for the document will not be sent to the server.
<P>
If the client can comply with the CRYPTOPTS
specified in the anchor, it sends the server its CRYPTOPTS
in a header along with a request for the document.
<P><LI>The server receives the client's request.
<P><LI>The server compares the client's CRYPTOPTS
first with the CRYPTOPTS specified in
its protection setups and then with the CRYPTOPTS specified in
its ACL files.
<P><LI>If the CRYPTOPTS for either
the protection setups or the ACL files are not
consistent with the client's
CRYPTOPTS, the negotiation fails.
The server sends an error message to the client and
doesn't serve the document.
<P>
If the CRYPTOPTS for protection setups
and ACL files are consistent with the client's CRYPTOPTS,
the server serves the document.
</OL>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Header_616">Implementation summary</A></H3>
<P>
To implement S-HTTP, you:
<OL>
<P><LI>Set up S-HTTP security using configuration forms
<P><LI>Code your HTML document for S-HTTP
<P><LI>Code your protection setups and, optionally, ACL files for S-HTTP
<P><LI>Optionally, code CGI programs that use S-HTTP
</OL>
<P>
As you implement S-HTTP, keep in mind that:
<UL>
<P><LI>The CRYPTOPTS in an anchor tell the client the appropriate
security for the document referenced in the anchor.
<P><LI>The CRYPTOPTS in protection setups and ACL files enforce the
security as the document is served.
</UL>
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="Header_617" HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC_617">Step 1. Setting up S-HTTP</A></H2>
<P>
To implement security you need to specify the port you'll use for
secure communications.
<P>
Also, the server must have a
public-private key pair and a certificate.
<P>
The server uses its private key to sign messages to clients.
The server sends its public key to clients so that they
can encrypt messages to the server, which the server decrypts
with its private key.
<P>
To send its public key to clients, the server needs a certificate.
The certificate contains the server's public key, the Distinguished
Name associated with the server's certificate, the serial number
of the certificate, and the expiration date of the certificate.
<P>
A certificate is issued by a certification authority (CA),
who verifies that you are who you say you are.
<P>
To conduct commercial business on the Internet, you would
use a CA, such as VeriSign, Inc.,
who is widely known by clients and servers.
<P>
For a private Web network within your own company, university,
or group, you could, with your Internet Connection Secure Server, be
your own CA.
What you need to do to become a CA and how to process
certificates for this server and other clients and servers is
described in 
<A HREF="icswg012.html#HDROWNCA">"Acting as a certification authority for a private Web network"</A>.
<P>
For S-HTTP, clients also need a public-private key pair and
a certificate.
For Secure WebExplorer, clients can use KeyManager to create their key pair
and request their certificate.
<P>
Use the following Configuration and Administration forms
to set up S-HTTP security for the server:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Security Configuration form to specify the port that will be
used for S-HTTP and how you will use security server-side includes
in your HTML documents
<LI>Create Key and Request Certificate form to create the server's
public-private key pair and certificate request
<LI>Receive Certificate form to receive the server's certificate
into a key ring so that the server can use it for secure communications
</UL>
To access these forms:
<OL>
<P><LI>Go to the front page of your server and
click Configuration and Administration
Forms.
<P><LI>You are prompted for your user name and password.
Type them in and click <B>OK</B>.
<P><LI>The Configuration and Administration forms page appears.
Page down until you find the topic Security.
To access any security form listed, click its name.
</OL>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Header_618">Fill in Security Configuration form</A></H3>
<P>
Use the Security Configuration form
to specify some of the security
information needed for the server.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_619">1. Specify connection options</A></H4>
<P>
Use the first part of the <B>Security Configuration</B>
form to specify your connection for S-HTTP.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b01.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b01 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
For S-HTTP:
<UL>
<P><LI>Make sure the box to allow HTTP and S-HTTP connections is checked.
This causes the default port number you specified on the Basic form
to be used for HTTP and S-HTTP connections.
<P><LI>The box to allow SSL connections can also be checked
if you want to use SSL security too.
</UL>
<P>
All transport methods can be implemented on the server at the
same time.
However, you cannot use S-HTTP and SSL simultaneously for the same
document.
<P>
To learn more about when you might want to use SSL or S-HTTP,
see 
<A HREF="icswg009.html#HDRPCKSEC">"Why use one security protocol instead of the other?"</A>.
How to implement and use SSL is described in 
<A HREF="icswg010.html#HDRSSL">"Using Secure Sockets Layer (SSL)"</A>.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_620">2. Process your request</A></H4>
<P>
Check your form and make sure you entered each item correctly.
Click <B>Apply</B> to process the form.
<P>
You receive a Confirmation that the form was successfully processed.
You can make changes to other Configuration and Administration forms.
However, when you are ready for the changes you've made to
this form to take effect, you must stop the server and then
start it again.  The server will not pick up your changes if your only
restart it.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="HDRDTUSSI">3. Decide whether to use server-side includes</A></H4>
<P>
For S-HTTP, as we'll see later, you need to
send clients the server's certificate and Distinguished Name if you
want clients to encrypt messages to the server or to verify
the server's signature.
There are two ways of supplying the server's
certificate and Distinguished
Name in an HTML document or a CGI program:
<UL>
<P><LI>Put the certificate or Distinguished Name directly into
the HTML document or CGI program.
<P><LI>Use a server-side include. A <B><I>server-side include</I></B>
is coding you specify in
an HTML document that tells the server to get the
certificate or Distinguished Name and send it to the client.
</UL>
<P>
It's easier to code a server-side include than to put
a certificate or Distinguished Name directly into a document
or CGI program.
However, server-side includes take more processing time,
which affects the server's performance and slows down response time
for clients.
<P>
Use the <B>Basic</B> form to choose how you
want to implement server-side includes.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b08.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b08 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
Choose one:
<UL>
<P><LI><B>Disable server-side includes</B>:  Choose
this option if you don't want to use server-side includes.
<P><LI><B>Enable server-side includes for CGI scripts
only</B>:  Choose this option if you want to use server-side includes
in CGI programs only.
<P>
If you choose this option,
the server checks the output of each CGI program
it processes for server-side includes.
The server does not check HTML documents
for server-side includes.
<P><LI><B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files
only</B>:  Choose this
option if you want to use server-side includes in HTML documents only.
<P>
If you choose this option, the server checks each HTML document
it processes for server-side includes.
<P>
However, you can further limit the HTML documents the server checks
for server-side includes and improve performance.
Specify a unique file extension, such as .shtml,
for <B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files with extension</B>.
Use the unique file extension for your
HTML documents that have server-side includes.
<P>
When you choose
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files only</B> and
specify the file extension, the server checks only those HTML
documents with the extension you specified for server-side includes.
<P>
The server does not check the output of CGI  programs
for server-side includes.
<P><LI><B>Enable server-side includes for both CGI scripts and
HTML files</B>:  Choose
this option if you want to use server-side includes in HTML
documents and CGI programs.
<P>
If you choose this option, the server checks each HTML document and
the output of each
CGI program it processes for server-side includes.
<P>
However, you can further limit the HTML documents the server checks
for server-side includes and improve performance.
Specify a unique file extension, such as .shtml,
for <B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files with
extension</B>.
Use the unique file extension for your
HTML documents that have server-side includes.
<P>
When you choose
<B>Enable server-side includes for both CGI scripts
and HTML files</B> and
specify the file extension, the server checks the output of
each CGI program, but only checks those HTML documents
with the extension you specified for server-side includes.
<P>
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_622">4. Process your request</A></H4>
<P>
Check your form and make sure you entered each item correctly.
Click <B>Apply</B> to process the form.
<P>
You receive a Confirmation that the form was successfully processed.
You can make changes to other Configuration and Administration forms.
However, when you are ready for the changes you've made to
this form to take effect, you must stop the server and then start it
again.  The server will not pick up your changes if you only restart it.
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Header_623">Fill in Create Key and Request Certificate form</A></H3>
<P>
These instructions tell you how to use this form to do one of
the following:
<UL>
<P><LI>Create a key pair and request a certificate for the server
from VeriSign.
<P><LI>Create a key pair and request a certificate for the server
from a CA other than VeriSign.
The other CA could be some other outside CA.
Or, someone within your organization could act as a CA for
a private Web network;
for example, you might act as your own CA and the CA for
others in your group.
If you are acting as a CA, you
need to follow the instructions in
<A HREF="icswg012.html#HDROWNCA">"Acting as a certification authority for a private Web network"</A>.
The chapter tells how to become a CA and
how to process certificate requests.
</UL>
<P>
To create the server's public-private key pair and request a
certificate, use:
<UL>
<P><LI>Create Key and Request Certificate form to choose your CA
<P><LI>One of the following forms, depending on the CA you choose,
to create the server's keys and request
its certificate:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>VeriSign Low Assurance Certificate
<LI>VeriSign Secure Server Certificate
<LI>Other Certificate
</UL>
</UL>
<P><B>Note: </B>For S-HTTP, the server must have a public-private key pair
and a certificate.
However, if you have already implemented SSL for this server and
want to use the same keys and certificate for S-HTTP, you're ready
to go to 
<A HREF="#HDRHTMLDOC">"Step 2. Coding an HTML document for S-HTTP"</A>.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_624">1. Choose a CA</A></H4>
<P>
Use the Create Key and Request Certificate form to specify
the CA from whom you want to obtain a certificate.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b02.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b02 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
VeriSign is a widely known CA.
Choose one:
<UL>
<P><LI><B>VeriSign (Low Assurance Certificate)</B>:
The level of proof required to get a low assurance
certificate is less than for a secure server certificate.
You might want to get a low assurance certificate to do a beta test
of security with your clients
or for some other non-commercial purpose.
<P><LI><B>VeriSign (Secure Server Certificate)</B>: To
conduct commercial
business on the Internet, you want a secure server certificate.
The level of proof required to get a secure server certificate is
higher than for a low assurance certificate.
<P><LI><B>Other</B>:  This is any other CA.
For example, for a private Web network, your organization
could choose to act as its own CA.
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_625">2. Process your request</A></H4>
<P>
Click <B>Apply</B> to process this part of the Create Key
and Request Certificate form.
<P>
Another part of the Create Key and Request Certificate
form appears, depending on which CA you choose:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>VeriSign Low Assurance Certificate
<LI>VeriSign Secure Server Certificate
<LI>Other Certificate
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_626">3. Create public-private key pair</A></H4>
<P>
Use <B>Create Key</B> to create a key pair.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0o09.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0o09 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_627">Specify key name</A></H5>
<P>
Specify a meaningful, unique name to identify the key pair.
The <B><I>key name</I></B> is the label that identifies
the key pair and certificate in the key ring.
You may use non-alphanumeric characters in key names; however,
keep in mind that some platforms have special uses for
some of these characters.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_628">Specify key ring</A></H5>
<P>
Specify the fully qualified path and file name for the key ring file.
A <B><I>key ring</I></B> is a file where the server keeps one or more
key pairs and certificates.
If you specify a file that doesn't exist, the
server creates the file for you.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_629">Specify the size of the key pair</A></H5>
<P>
Specify the size of the key pair in bits after considering these
factors:
<UL>
<P><LI>The more bits you specify for
the key pair, the more secure your communications.
<P><LI>The more bits you specify, the more processing time required
for encryption and decryption.
<P><LI>With export versions of the server,
you can create a key pair up to 512 bits.
With U.S.-Canadian versions, you can create a larger key pair; however,
if you want clients outside the United States to encrypt messages
to the server,
U.S. export rules require that the key pair be no larger
than 512 bits.
If you want clients outside the United States only to verify your
server's signature or sign messages,
the key pair can be larger than 512 bits.
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_630">4. Specify key ring password</A></H4>
<P>
Use this part of the form to specify the password that protects
the key ring.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b03.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b03 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
The password is important because it protects the server's
private key.
The server's private key is the only key that
can decrypt messages encrypted
with the server's public key.
Also, the server signs documents with its private key.
<P>
The security of the server's private key depends
upon this password.
Here are some commonly accepted rules for specifying passwords:
<UL>
<P><LI>Make the password at least six characters.
<P><LI>Make sure the password doesn't spell a word.
<P><LI>Make sure the password doesn't consist of publicly
obtainable information about
you; for example, the initials and birth date for you, your spouse,
or children.
<P><LI>Include at least two, nonconsecutive numbers in the password.
</UL>
<P>
Type the password twice to ensure that you have typed
it correctly.
<P>
If you must record the password, make sure it is stored in a
well-secured place.
<P>
The key ring password must be specified when the server is started.
Check <B>Automatic login</B> if you want the server to stash
the password and specify it for you whenever the server is started.
<P>
Stashing your password is less secure so
it's generally a good practice not to stash it.
However, there may be cases where you need to stash the password;
for example, if you have a remote server and you want it to
automatically restart after a power failure.
<P>
Next, to request the server's certificate, fill in the rest of the
form.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_631">5. Specify Distinguished Name</A></H4>
<P>
Specify the Distinguished Name you want associated with the server's
certificate and used to identify the server's public key.
In it's simplest form, a Distinguished Name is someone's
name.
<P>
As we'll see later, you need to specify the Distinguished Name
in an anchor if you want a client to encrypt messages.
<P>
The information you provide for Distinguished Name depends upon
whether you want a:
<UL>
<P><LI>VeriSign Low Assurance Certificate.
See 
<A HREF="#HDRDNLOW">"Specify Distinguished Name for low assurance certificate"</A>.
<P><LI>VeriSign Secure Server Certificate or Other Certificate.
See 
<A HREF="#HDRDNHIGH">"Specify Distinguished Name for secure server or other certificate"</A>.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="HDRDNLOW">Specify Distinguished Name for low assurance certificate</A></H5>
<P>
For this certificate, the Distinguished Name is
the full name of the user for whom the certificate is being requested.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b04.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b04 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
For <B>User's full name</B>, specify the user's full name and make
sure it is unique.
For example, if you request more than one certificate for Mary Ann
Jones, you might specify Mary Ann Jones1 for the first
request and Mary Ann Jones2 for the second request.
<P>
<B>User's e-mail address</B>
should contain the user's address
where you want VeriSign to mail the certificate.
<P>
Next, you need to provide mailing information, as described in
<A HREF="#HDRMAILTO">"6. Specify mailing option"</A>.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="HDRDNHIGH">Specify Distinguished Name for secure server or other certificate</A></H5>
<P>
For these certificates, the Distinguished Name is the server name
and the location of the server.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b11.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b11 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P><B>Note: </B>The text for Distinguished Name will vary,
depending on whether you're
on the VeriSign secure server or the other certificate form.
Also, the User's e-mail address field, which is on the
other certificate form, is not on the VeriSign
secure server certificate form.
<P>
You may use non-alphanumeric characters in Distinguished Name; however,
keep in mind that some platforms have special uses for
some of these characters.
Provide the following information for Distinguished Name:
<UL>
<P><LI>Server Name:  The X.500 common name of the server.
Usually, it is the TCP/IP fully qualified host name; for example,
www.ibm.com.
For a VeriSign secure server certificate request, it must be the fully
qualified host name.
<P><LI>Organizational Unit: Optionally, the organizational unit.
For example, you might specify the division of your company.
<P><LI>Organization:  The name of your organization, such as
the name of your company.
For a secure server certificate, if you already have an account
with VeriSign, the name in this field should match the name on
that account.
<P><LI>Locality/City: Optionally, the city or locality where your
server resides.
<P><LI>State/Province:  The state or province where the server resides.
You must specify at least <B>three</B> characters.
<P><LI>Postal Code:  The postal code or zip code where the server resides.
<P><LI>Country:  The two-character country code for the
country in which the server resides.
</UL>
On the other certificate form, <B>User's e-mail address</B>
should contain the user's address where
you want the CA to mail the certificate.
If you're requesting this server's certificate, which you plan to
process as a CA, leave this field blank.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="HDRMAILTO">6. Specify mailing option</A></H4>
<P>
The mailing option depends on the kind of certificate being requested:
<UL>
<P><LI>For a VeriSign low assurance certificate,
see 
<A HREF="#HDRMAILL">"Mailing option for low assurance certificate"</A>.
<P><LI>For a VeriSign secure server certificate,
see 
<A HREF="#HDRMAILH">"Mailing option for secure server certificate"</A>.
<P><LI>For an Other certificate,
see 
<A HREF="#HDRMAILO">"Mailing option for other certificate"</A>.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="HDRMAILL">Mailing option for low assurance certificate</A></H5>
<P>
A VeriSign low assurance certificate request must be electronically
mailed to VeriSign.
If you are behind a firewall, verify with your system administrator
what you need to do to electronically mail this request.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b06.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b06 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
Go to 
<A HREF="#HDRCOPY">"7. Save copy of certificate request"</A> for a description of what you need to do next.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="HDRMAILH">Mailing option for secure server certificate</A></H5>
<P>
There is no mailing option on the form for a VeriSign secure server
certificate.
A secure server certificate request must be saved in a file
and manually mailed to VeriSign.
The VeriSign home page,
<B>http://www.verisign.com/ibm</B>,
has instructions on what you need to provide in order
to obtain a secure server certificate from VeriSign.
Some e-mail programs may alter files and should not be used
to send a certificate request.
For example, some programs may pad the lines of a certificate
request with blanks and invalidate it.
Also, if you are behind a firewall, verify with your system administrator
what you need to do to electronically mail this request.
<P>
Go to 
<A HREF="#HDRCOPY">"7. Save copy of certificate request"</A> for a description of what you need to do
next.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="HDRMAILO">Mailing option for other certificate</A></H5>
<P>
For an Other certificate, you need to consult with your CA
to determine how to mail the certificate request.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0b07.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0b07 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
After consulting with your CA, choose one:
<UL>
<P><LI><B>Mail to</B>:  Choose this option and enter
the electronic address of your CA
if you want to electronically mail the certificate request.
If you are behind a firewall, verify with your system administrator
what you need to do to electronically mail this request.
<P><LI><B>Don't mail</B>:  Choose this option if
you plan to act as your own CA for this server's certificate
or if you don't want to electronically mail the certificate
request to another CA at this time.
You can manually mail the certificate request later; however,
some e-mail programs may alter files and should not be used
to send a certificate request.
For example, some programs may pad the lines of a certificate
request with blanks and invalidate it.
Also, if you are behind a firewall, verify with your system administrator
what you need to do to electronically mail this request.
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="HDRCOPY">7. Save copy of certificate request</A></H4>
<P>
It's a good idea to save the certificate request in a
file.
If you're requesting a VeriSign secure server certificate,
you must save the request to file and manually mail it later.
If you're acting as your own CA for this server's certificate,
you also must save the certificate request in a file.
(After you complete this form, you can
use the instructions in 
<A HREF="icswg012.html#HDROWNCA">"Acting as a certification authority for a private Web network"</A> to become
a CA and to process this server's certificate.)
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0o10.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0o10 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
<P><B>Note: </B>The text on this form
for Save Copy will vary, depending on whether you're on the
VeriSign low assurance, VeriSign secure server, or Other certificate
form.
<P>
Specify a unique fully qualified path and file name
for the file where you want to keep the certificate request.
If you specify a file that doesn't exist, the server creates the
file for you.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_639">8. Process your request</A></H4>
<P>
Check your form and make sure you entered each item correctly.
Click <B>Apply</B> to process the form.
You receive a Confirmation that the form was successfully processed.
<P>
The server:
<UL>
<P><LI>Stores the key pair in an encrypted format on the key ring and
adds the default trusted roots that are shipped with the product
to the key ring.
<P><LI>If you specified <B>Automatic login</B>,
encrypts the key ring password and puts it in a file
that has the same name as the key ring file,
except the extension is .sth.
<P><LI>Creates the certificate request and stores it in the file
you specified and:
<UL>
<P><LI>For a low assurance certificate, the certificate request is
electronically mailed to VeriSign.
<P><LI>For a secure server certificate, you have to manually mail
the certificate request to VeriSign.
Go to the VeriSign home page,
<B>http://www.verisign.com/ibm</B>,
for instructions on what you need to provide in order
to obtain a secure server certificate from VeriSign.
<P><LI>For an other certificate, if you're acting as your own CA
for this server's certificate,
you need to process the certificate request.
Go to 
<A HREF="icswg012.html#HDROWNCA">"Acting as a certification authority for a private Web network"</A> for instructions on how to
become a CA and for how to process this server's certificate.
For any other CA, follow its instructions.
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
The CA processes your certificate request.
When the CA is satisfied that you have met all of its requirements,
it electronically mails a certificate to you.
Next, you need to receive the server's certificate.
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Header_640">Fill in Receive Certificate Form</A></H3>
<P>
Use the Receive Certificate form to receive
into the key ring the certificate
electronically mailed to you by your CA.
<P><BR>
<B><BR><IMG SRC="icsl0o11.gif" ALT="* Figure icsl0o11 not displayed."><BR></B><BR>
<P>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_641">1. Specify Receive Certificate information</A></H4>
<P>
Before filling in this form, use your e-mail program to
receive the certificate into a unique file.
Some e-mail programs may alter files and should not be used to
receive certificates.
For example, some programs pad the lines of the certificate
with trailing blanks, which invalidates it.
<P>
Provide:
<UL>
<P><LI><B>Name of file containing certificate</B>:  The
fully qualified path and file name of the
file that contains the certificate.
<P><LI><B>Key ring</B>:  The fully qualified path and
file name of the key ring you specified on the
Create Key and Request Certificate form for the certificate
you are receiving.
<P><LI><B>Key ring password</B>:  The password you specified on the
Create Key and Request Certificate form for the
certificate you are receiving.
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_642">2. Process your request</A></H4>
<P>
Check your form and make sure you entered each item correctly.
Click <B>Apply</B> to process the form.
<P>
You receive a Confirmation that the form was successfully processed.
<P>
The server stores the certificate in the key ring.
It is referenced in the key ring with the
<B>key name</B> you specified on the Create Key
and Request Certificate form.
<P>
After you receive your Confirmation for the Receive
Certificate form,
you can make changes to other Configuration and Administration forms.
However, when you are ready for the changes you've made to
any security forms to take effect, you must stop the server and then
start it again.  The server will not pick up your changes if you
only restart it.
<P>
When you start the server, you will be prompted for
the key ring password unless you stashed it
by selecting <B>Automatic login</B> on the Create Key and
Request Certificate form.
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="HDRHTMLDOC" HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC_643">Step 2. Coding an HTML document for S-HTTP</A></H2>
<P>
In this step, we're going to see how to include S-HTTP coding
in your HTML document.
<P>
You need to include security coding in your HTML
document to provide a client with the server's S-HTTP security
specifications.
You use the security coding in your HTML document to:
<UL>
<P><LI>Supply a client with the server's certificate.
You include this coding in the header of an HTML
document.
<P><LI>Supply a client with the security specifications for a
document referenced in an anchor:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Notification of S-HTTP security.
<LI>Optionally,
the Distinguished Name associated with the server's certificate.
<LI>Optionally, CRYPTOPTS.
However, as we'll discuss later, you should always specify the
security you want for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements.
It is the CRYPTOPTS header that specifies
whether messages should be signed,
encrypted, or both signed and encrypted.
</UL>
</UL>
Now let's see how to code S-HTTP security specifications
in the header and anchors of your HTML document.
<P>
<H3><A NAME="HDRCERTS">Code S-HTTP security in the header of your HTML document</A></H3>
<P>
To set up security, you used the Configuration and
Administration forms.
You used the Create Key and Request Certificate form
to create the server's public/private key pair and request
the server's certificate from a CA.
After the CA sent you the server's certificate, you
used the Receive Certificate form
to receive the certificate into the server's key ring.
<P>
For clients to communicate with the server, they need the:
<UL>
<P><LI>Certificate of the CA who issued the server's certificate.
The CA certificate must be designated as a trusted root.
<P><LI>Server's certificate,
which contains the server's public key,
the Distinguished Name associated with the certificate,
and the signature of the CA who issued the certificate.
The certificate may also contain other information such as its
serial number and the date it expires.
The client will use the server's public key to encrypt messages
to the server and verify the server's signature.
</UL>
<P>
You give the server's certificate to clients by coding one
of the following in the header of your HTML document.
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>CERTS tag followed by the certificate
<LI>Certificate server-side include, coding that tells the server
to get the certificate and send it to the client
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_645">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<P>
It's easier to code a server-side include than to put
a certificate directly into your document.
However, server-side includes take more processing time, which affects
the server's performance and slows down response time for
clients.
<P>
To use server-side includes, you need to choose
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files only</B> or
<B>Enable server-side includes for both CGI scripts and
HTML files</B> on the Basic form.
You can also limit the documents the server checks
if you use a unique file extension to identify documents with
server-side includes and specify it for
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files with extension</B>.
Then, the server checks only the HTML documents with the file extension
you specified.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_646">CERTS tag</A></H4>
<P>
Use a CERTS tag when you want to include the server's
certificate directly in
your HTML document.
It's a good practice to code your CERTS tag as part of the HTML header.
You can have several CERTS tags in your header.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_647">Format</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;CERTS FMT=<VAR>format</VAR>&gt;<VAR>certificate</VAR>
&lt;/CERTS&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<VAR>format</VAR> is the presentation format of the certificate and can
be:
<DL>
<P><DT>PKCS-7
<DD>Public Key Cryptography Standard 7,
developed by RSA Data Security, Inc., and others.
The presentation format is a PKCS-7 signed Data message with
no content and no signer.
<P><DT>PEM
<DD>Internet Privacy-Enhanced Mail standard.
The presentation format is
a comma-separated list of base64-encoded X.509 certificates.
</DL>
<P>
<VAR>certificate</VAR> is the actual certificate in the server's
key ring.
<P>
One way to get the certificate directly into your
HTML document is to
serve a document with server-side includes for
the certificate and the Distinguished Name associated with the
certificate.
View the HTML for the document you served.
Then, cut and paste the certificate into your HTML document.
You would also cut and paste the DN into your HTML document as
described later.
If you use the Internet Connection Secure Server, the <VAR>format</VAR> of the certificate will
be PKCS-7 (FMT=PKCS-7).
<P>
How to code server-side includes for your
HTML document is also described later.
For now, here's an example of coding you might use for the
document that would be served so that you could
cut and paste the certificate and
Distinguished Name directly into your HTML document:
<PRE>
&lt;head&gt; &lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;!--#certs name=""--&gt;
&lt;!--#dn=""--&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
This example shows double quotes with
no key name specified for certs name or dn.
You can specify a server-side include for a
certificate or DN with double quotes and
no key name when
you want to use the first certificate in the server's key ring.
<P>
Here's an example of how a certificate might look.
The certificate is armored or base 64 encoded.
When the certificate is no longer armored, it
is actually a PKCS-7 signed data message that contains a
certificate.
It is necessary to armor the certificate because it is
a binary message.
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;CERTS FMT=pkcs-7&gt;
MIAGCSqGSIb3DQEHAqCAMIACAQExADCABgkqhkiG9w0BBwEAAKCAMIIBsjCCATwC
BCAhT3gwDQYJKoZIhvcNAQECBQAwPjELMAkGA1UEBhMCVVMxGDAWBgNVBAoTD0lC
TSBDb3Jwb3JhdGlvbjEVMBMGA1UEAxMMQW5uZSBPbnltb3VzMBoXCzk1MDcxNjE1
MzFaFws5NjA3MTUxNTMxWjBrMQswCQYDVQQGEwJVUzEMMAoGA1UECBMDV0lTMRAw
DgYDVQQHEwdSYWxlaWdoMQwwCgYDVQQKEwNJQk0xFjAUBgNVBAsTDURhdGEgU2Vj
dXJpdHkxFjAUBgNVBAMTDVNhbXBsZSBTZXJ2ZXIwXDANBgkqhkiG9w0BAQEFAANL
ADBIAkEAnzH6RUM/DJN6IWPYlwnXsZsaMFNtoq1XEqpa9qeP7cGKtSKpIvrzDeRC
+zPB369dEZ3zbHeIiICNGn0a7k2XWQIDAQABMA0GCSqGSIb3DQEBAgUAA2EAfXLS
yGfaF8dhm9c4PWZm2FRojly0mx+vgt4+v66SDu78mMWNeCTGNakP1vXk3zbYDauO
P6ktTGyBF27FhoauRIoPBTEkddtb3CmCbXMFWau0a1Az37eBPvjb0tpigqldAAAx
gAAAAAAAAAAA
&lt;/CERTS&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_648">Server-side include for a certificate</A></H4>
<P>
Use a server-side include for a certificate when you want to refer to the
certificate in your HTML document and have the server get the
certificate and send it to a client.
It's a good practice to code the server-side include
as part of the HTML header.
You can have several server-side includes for certificates
in your header.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_649">Format</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;!--#certs name="<VAR>key name</VAR>"--&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<VAR>key name</VAR> is the <B>key name</B> you provided
on the Create Key and Request Certificate
form for the server's key pair.
In the server's key ring,
key name is the label used to reference the certificate.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_650">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<UL>
<P><LI>You can only use a server-side include if you chose
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files only</B>
or <B>Enable server-side includes for both CGI scripts and
HTML files</B> on the Basic form.
If you also specified a file extension for
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files with extension</B>,
the file extension for this document must
match the file extension you specified on the Basic form.
<P><LI>You can specify certs name with double quotes and without
<VAR>key name</VAR>
if you want the client to use the first certificate
in the server's key ring.
If you want to use another certificate in the key ring, you must
specify <VAR>key name.</VAR>
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_651">Example</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;!--#certs name="jheist"--&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Header_652">Code S-HTTP security in the anchors of your HTML document</A></H3>
<P>
You code the security specifications you want a client to follow as
part of the anchor for a document.
You can use different security specifications for each anchor.
<P>
Following is the format and an example
of an anchor with no security specifications:
<P>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_653">Format</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="http://<VAR>destination</VAR>"&gt;
<VAR>link text</VAR>&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
For the document (<VAR>link text</VAR>) referenced in this anchor,
there is no security coding.
<B>http://</B> indicates the normal transport method.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_654">Example</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="http://www.joker.com/planned_crimes/schedule.html"&gt;
Heists Schedule&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
The security specifications you can code in an HTML anchor include:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Transport method for S-HTTP.
<LI>Optionally, the Distinguished Name associated with
the server's certificate.
<LI>Optionally, CRYPTOPTS.
However, as we'll discuss later, you should always specify the
security you want for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements.
It is the CRYPTOPTS header
that specifies whether messages should be signed,
encrypted, or both signed and encrypted.
</UL>
<P>
Following is the format and an example
of an anchor with security specifications:
<P>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_655">Format</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://<VAR>destination</VAR>"
DN="<VAR>dn or server-side include for dn</VAR>"
CRYPTOPTS="<VAR>CRYPTOPTS</VAR>"&gt;
<VAR>link text</VAR>&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
For the document (<VAR>link text</VAR>) referenced in this anchor:
<UL>
<P><LI><B>shttp://</B> indicates S-HTTP security.
<P><LI>DN is the Distinguished Name of the certificate
and public key that the server wants the client to use.
<P><LI>CRYPTOPTS are the cryptographic options that tell the
client the appropriate security for the document referenced
in the anchor.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_656">Example</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://www.joker.com/planned_crimes/schedule.html"
DN="CN=Joker, OU=Security, O=&quot;Joker Crimes, Inc.&quot;&#44; L=Raleigh, ST=NC, C=US"
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements: recv-required=sign"&gt;
Heists Schedule&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
Now let's see how to include each of these
security specifications in
an HTML anchor.
<P>
<H3><A NAME="Header_657">Specify S-HTTP transport mode</A></H3>
<P>
To tell clients that this document is protected by S-HTTP security
specifications, you need to specify <B>shttp://</B> as your
transport mode.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_658">Format</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://<VAR>destination</VAR>"&gt;
<VAR>link text</VAR>&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_659">Example</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://www.joker.com/planned_crimes/schedule.html"&gt;
Heists Schedule&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
In this example, neither DN nor CRYPTOPTS are specified.
After interpreting this anchor,
a Secure WebExplorer
signs the request for the document.
<P>
If an anchor contains a Distinguished Name and no CRYPTOPTS,
a Secure WebExplorer encrypts but does not sign.
<P>
The clients of other vendors might interpret an anchor
with no CRYPTOPTS differently.
Therefore:
<UL>
<P><LI>Always require the CRYPTOPTS you want.
<P><LI>Always refuse the CRYPTOPTS you don't want.
<P><LI>Accept the defaults for CRYPTOPTS only when it doesn't matter
what CRYPTOPTS are used.
</UL>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="HDRDNANCH">Specify the Distinguished Name of the server's certificate</A></H3>
<P>
If you want the client to encrypt messages, you must
specify the Distinguished Name of the certificate you
want the client to use.
<P>
You provide the Distinguished Name by coding one of the following
in the anchor of your HTML document:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>DN tag followed by the Distinguished Name
<LI>DN tag followed by a server-side include for a DN,
coding which tells the
server to get the Distinguished Name and send it to the client
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_661">Important Coding Considerations</A></H5>
<P>
It's easier to code a server-side include than to put
a Distinguished Name directly into your document.
However, server-side includes take more processing time,
which affects the server's performance and slows down response time for
clients.
<P>
To use server-side includes, you need to choose
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files only</B> or
<B>Enable server-side includes for both CGI scripts and
HTML files</B>
on the Basic form.
You can also limit the documents the server checks
if you use a unique file extension to identify documents with
server-side includes and specify it for
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files with extension</B>.
Then, the server checks only the HTML documents with the file extension
you specified.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_662">Specify the Distinguished Name for the DN tag</A></H4>
<P>
The Distinguished Name you specify in your anchor should match the
Distinguished Name you gave when you filled in the
Create Key and Request Certificate form.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_663">Format</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://<VAR>destination</VAR>"
DN="CN=<VAR>Name,</VAR> OU=<VAR>Unit</VAR>, O=<VAR>Organization</VAR>, C=<VAR>City</VAR>, ST=<VAR>State/Province</VAR>, C=<VAR>Country</VAR>"&gt;
<VAR>link text</VAR>&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<VAR>Name, Unit, Organization, City, State/Province,</VAR> and
<VAR>Country</VAR> match the information you gave for Distinguished
Name on the Create Key and Request Certificate form.
<P>
One way to get the server's DN directly into your
HTML document is to
serve a document with server-side includes for
the certificate and the Distinguished Name associated with the
certificate.
View the HTML for the document you served.
Then, cut and paste the Distinguished Name
into your HTML document.
(You would also cut and paste the certificate as described earlier.)
<P>
How to do server-side includes for the
Distinguished Name are described next.
For now, here's an example of coding you might use for the
document that would be served so that you could
cut and paste the certificate and
Distinguished Name directly into your HTML document:
<PRE>
&lt;head&gt; &lt;/head&gt;
&lt;body&gt;
&lt;!--#certs name=""--&gt;
&lt;!--#dn=""--&gt;
&lt;/body&gt;
</PRE>
This example shows double quotes with
no key name specified for certs name or dn.
You can specify a server-side include for a certificate or DN
with double quotes and no key name when you want to use the first
certificate in the server's key ring.
<P>
Here's an example of how the Distinguished Name
would look in your HTML document
after you've cut and pasted it in.
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://www.joker.com/planned_crimes/schedule.html"
DN="CN=Joker, OU=Security, O=&quot;Joker Crimes, Inc.&quot;&#44; L=Raleigh, ST=NC, C=US"&gt;
Heists Schedule&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_664">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<UL>
<P><LI>All of a Distinguished Name must be on the same line.
However, you can put DN= on one line and the Distinguished Name on
the next line.
For example:
<PRE>
DN=
"CN=Joker, OU=Security, O=&quot;Joker Crimes, Inc.&quot;&#44; L=Raleigh, ST=NC, C=US"
</PRE>
<P><LI>If a phrase, such as Joker Crimes, Inc., in your DN specification
contains a comma, enclose it in double quotes as shown in the previous
example.
Make sure the comma that is the separator between O= and L=
is outside the closing double quote as shown in the previous example.
Here is how the HTML coding would look:
<P>
<PRE>
DN=
"CN=Joker, OU=Security, O=&sdq.;Joker Crimes, Inc.&sdq.;, L=Raleigh, ST=NC, C=US"
</PRE>
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_665">Specify a server-side include for a DN tag</A></H4>
<P>
The format of a server-side include for a DN is similar to the format of
a server-side include for a certificate.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_666">Format</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://<VAR>destination</VAR>"
DN= &lt;!--#dn name="key name</VAR>"--&gt;&gt;
<VAR>link text</VAR>&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<VAR>key name</VAR> is the <B>key name</B> you provided
on the Create Key and Request Certificate
form for the server's key pair.
In the server's key ring,
key name is the label used to reference the certificate.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_667">Important coding consideration</A></H5>
<UL>
<P><LI>You can only use a server-side include if you chose
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files only</B>
or <B>Enable server-side includes for both CGI scripts and
HTML files</B> on the Basic form.
If you also specified a file extension for
<B>Enable server-side includes for HTML files with extension</B>,
the file extension for this document must
match the file extension you specified on the Basic form.
<P>
If you don't specify server-side includes on the Basic
form or if the file extension of your HTML document with
server-side includes doesn't match the file extension you
specified on the Basic form, clients will display
parts of the anchor coding, instead of the correct text for
the link.
If you need to turn server-side includes on,
you can use the Basic form or the imbeds directive.
<P><LI>You can specify dn name with double quotes and without
<VAR>key name</VAR>
if you want the client to use the first certificate in the
server's key ring.
If you want to use another certificate in the key ring, you must
specify <VAR>key name</VAR>.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_668">Example</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
&lt;a href="shttp://www.joker.com/planned_crimes/schedule.html"
DN= &lt;!--#dn name="jheist"--&gt;&gt;
Heists Schedule&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
<P>
<H3><A NAME="HDRCOS">Specify CRYPTOPTS</A></H3>
CRYPTOPTS are the cornerstones of your HTML anchor security
specifications.
You specify CRYPTOPTS to tell a client
the appropriate security for
the document referenced in an anchor.
<P>
An example of a CRYPTOPTS header is:
<P>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements: orig-required=sign;recv-required=encrypt,sign"
</PRE>
<P>
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>The server will send the client signed
responses for the document referenced in
this anchor.
<LI>The server will require that the client encrypt and sign
requests for the document referenced in this anchor.
</UL>
<P>
Next, let's look at the format of a CRYPTOPTS.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_670">Format of a CRYPTOPTS header</A></H4>
<P>
The format of a CRYPTOPTS header is:
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="<VAR>CryptoptsHeader</VAR>: <VAR>origmode</VAR>=<VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>;<VAR>recvmode</VAR>=<VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>"
</PRE>
<UL>
<P><LI><VAR>CryptoptsHeader</VAR>
describes the kind of CRYPTOPTS being specified.
These are the <VAR>CryptoptsHeaders</VAR> you can specify:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>SHTTP-Privacy-Domains
<LI>SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements
<LI>SHTTP-Certificate-Types
<LI>SHTTP-Key-Exchange-Algorithms
<LI>SHTTP-Signature-Algorithms
<LI>SHTTP-Message-Digest-Algorithms
<LI>SHTTP-Symmetric-Content-Algorithms
</UL>
Each header and what it means is described later.
<P><LI><VAR>origmode</VAR>
is the mode the server uses to send
responses to a client.
There are three <VAR>origmodes</VAR> that you can specify for each
<VAR>CryptoptsHeader</VAR>:
<UL>
<P><LI><VAR>orig-optional</VAR>:  The server can send responses using
the specified <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR> if the client requires it.
<P><LI><VAR>orig-required</VAR>:  The server sends all responses
using the specified <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>.
<P><LI><VAR>orig-refused</VAR>:  The server does not send
any responses using the specified <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>.
</UL>
<P><LI><VAR>recvmode</VAR>
is the mode the server uses to accept
requests from a client.
There are three <VAR>recvmodes</VAR> that you can specify for each
<VAR>CryptoptsHeader</VAR>:
<UL>
<P><LI><VAR>recv-optional</VAR>:  The server can accept requests from a
client with the specified <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>, but the server does
not require that the client make requests using this <VAR>recvmode</VAR>.
<P><LI><VAR>recv-required</VAR>:  The server accepts only requests
from a client when the client uses the specified
<VAR>HeaderOption</VAR> for the
request.
<P><LI><VAR>recv-refused</VAR>:  The server does not accept
any requests from the client when the requests are made with the
specified <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>.
</UL>
<P><LI><VAR>HeaderOption</VAR> is
the CRYPTOPTS <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR> that
the server is using for this cryptographic header.
The <VAR>HeaderOptions</VAR> are described later
when each CRYPTOPTS header is explained.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_671">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<UL>
<P><LI>The general rules for coding CRYPTOPTS in anchors are:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Specify required for <VAR>HeaderOptions</VAR> you want
<LI>Specify refused for <VAR>HeaderOptions</VAR>
you don't want
<LI>Accept optional, the default, only
when it doesn't matter which <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>
is used.
</UL>
Later, each CRYPTOPTS header is discussed in detail, including
whether to explicitly specify the header or accept the header's default.
<P><LI>If <VAR>origmode</VAR>
is coded in an anchor, it will not be handled in the
same way by all vendors' clients.
Some clients may ignore <VAR>origmode</VAR> in the anchor because it
describes how the server sends responses.
However, a Secure WebExplorer will process <VAR>origmode</VAR> and determine if it can
comply with the CRYPTOPTS the server will use in its
response.
If not, the negotiation fails at this point.
Otherwise, the negotiation doesn't fail until the client sends
the server a request for the document.
<P><LI>All of a CRYPTOPTS header must be on the same line.
You can put CRYPTOPTS= on a line by itself.
However, you must put each CRYPTOPTS header on its own line.
For example:
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS=
"SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements: orig-required=sign,encrypt;recv-required=sign,encrypt;
SHTTP-Privacy-Domains: orig-required=PKCS-7;recv-required=PKCS-7"
</PRE>
<P><LI>There is another way to specify CRYPTOPTS in your document.
You can specify a set of CRYPTOPTS in the header of your HTML
and give them a name.
Then in your anchor coding, you can use the name of the CRYPTOPTS.
Use this method to save time if you plan to specify the same set
of CRYPTOPTS for more than one anchor.
For example:
<PRE>
&lt;head&gt;
&lt;!--#certs name="jheist"--&gt;
&lt;CRYPTOPTS NAME="heistsch"&gt;
SHTTP-Privacy-Domains: orig-required=PKCS-7;recv-required=PKCS-7;
SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements: orig-required=sign,encrypt;recv-required=sign,encrypt
&lt;/CRYPTOPTS&gt;
&lt;/head&gt;
<P>
<VAR>body of document</VAR>
<P>
&lt;a href="shttp://www.joker.com/planned_crimes/schedule.html"
DN="CN=Joker, OU=Security, O=&quot;Joker Crimes, Inc.&quot;&#44; L=Raleigh, ST=NC, C=US"
CRYPTOPTS="heistsch"&gt;
Heists Schedule&lt;/a&gt;
</PRE>
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_672">Defaults</A></H4>
<P>
There are defaults for each CRYPTOPTS header.
When you specify <B>shttp://</B> transport mode in an anchor,
the server uses the default CRYPTOPTS for any header
not specified in your anchor coding.
In most cases, the defaults are fine and are recommended.
<P>
There are two CRYPTOPTS you need to ensure are coded
to provide the security you want:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements because it specifies
the security you want:  encrypt, sign, or
both encrypt and sign
<LI>SHTTP-Symmetric-Content-Algorithms if you need
very strong encryption algorithms
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_673">SHTTP-Privacy-Domains</A></H4>
<P>
Use this header to specify the format used for an encrypted
message.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_674">Header options</A></H5>
<P>
You can specify one of the following <VAR>HeaderOptions</VAR>:
<DL>
<P><DT>PKCS-7
<DD>Public Key Cryptography Standard 7,
developed by RSA Data Security, Inc. and others.
<P><DT>PEM
<DD>Internet Privacy-Enhanced Mail standard.
PEMs are always signed.
</DL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_675">Default CRYPTOPTS</A></H5>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Privacy-Domains: orig-optional=PKCS-7,PEM;recv-optional=PKCS-7,PEM"
</PRE>
<P>
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>The server can send the client messages encrypted with PKCS-7
or PEM if the client requires it.
<LI>The server can accept messages from the client
encrypted with PKCS-7 or PEM, but the server does not
require that the client send messages encrypted with PKCS-7 or PEM.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_676">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<UL>
<P><LI>In most cases, you want to accept the default
value for this header.
Consider the following before choosing PKCS-7 or PEM:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>PKCS-7 is more flexible than PEM.
<LI>If you want clients outside the United States to encrypt messages
to you, they must use PKCS-7.
Also, U.S. export rules require that clients outside the United
States use RC2-CBC with a key range of 40-2 as the algorithm
to encrypt the content of the PKCS-7 message.
</UL>
<P><LI>Messages encrypted with PEM are always signed.
Make sure the options you choose for this header are consistent with
the options you choose for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements.
For example,
if you specify orig-required=PEM or recv-required=PEM for this header,
do not specify orig-refused=sign or recv-refused=sign for
SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements.
<P><LI>If you want a client to encrypt requests to the server,
you need to make sure you have coded a DN for this anchor.
See 
<A HREF="#HDRDNANCH">"Specify the Distinguished Name of the server's certificate"</A> for more information on how to code DN.
Also, make sure you have sent the server's certificate to the client by
coding the CERTS tag or a server-side include in the
header of this HTML document.
See 
<A HREF="#HDRCERTS">"Code S-HTTP security in the header of your HTML document"</A> for more information on how to code the CERTS
tag or a server-side include.
<P><LI>If you want to encrypt the server's messages to a client
or have the server verify a client's signature, you
need to have the client's certificate.
Many secure clients, including the
Secure WebExplorer, automatically send their
certificates to a server.
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_677">SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements</A></H4>
<P>
Use this header to specify that the server encrypts, signs, or
both encrypts and signs messages and that a client encrypts,
signs, or both encrypts and signs messages.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_678">Header options</A></H5>
<P>
You can specify one or both of the following <VAR>HeaderOptions</VAR>:
<DL>
<P><DT>encrypt
<DD>The message will be encrypted.
<P><DT>sign
<DD>The message will be signed.
</DL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_679">Default CRYPTOPTS</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS=
"SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements: orig-optional=encrypt,sign;recv-optional=encrypt,sign"
</PRE>
<P>
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>The server can send the client messages encrypted, signed, or
both encrypted and signed, if the client requires it.
<LI>The server can accept messages from the client encrypted, signed,
or both encrypted or signed, but the server does not
require that the client encrypt or sign messages.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_680">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<UL>
<P><LI>Do not accept the defaults.
Be sure to specify the security you want for this header:
<UL>
<P><LI>If you want the client to encrypt and not to sign:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Send the server's certificate and make sure the anchor
contains the Distinguished Name.
<LI>Make sure you code the CRYPTOPTS that tells the client
it must encrypt and must not sign:
recv-required=encrypt and recv-refused=sign.
</UL>
<P><LI>If you want the client to sign and not to encrypt:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Make sure the anchor
does not contain the Distinguished Name.
<LI>Make sure you code the CRYPTOPTS that tell the client
it must sign and must not encrypt:
recv-required=sign and recv-refused=encrypt.
</UL>
<P><LI>If you want the client to encrypt and sign:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>Send the server's certificate and make sure the anchor
contains the Distinguished Name.
<LI>Make sure you code the CRYPTOPTS that tell the client
it must sign and encrypt:  recv-required=encrypt,sign.
</UL>
</UL>
<P><LI>Be careful when you use
Graphic Interchange Format images
(GIFs) that contain confidential information
in documents protected by CRYPTOPTS.
Each GIF is requested individually.
Because you cannot code CRYPTOPTS on image tags,
there are no CRYPTOPTS and no DN; the defaults
are used.
When there are no CRYPTOPTS and no DN, a
Secure WebExplorer client will sign a request for a GIF.
The Internet Connection Secure Server will encrypt the GIF.
Other vendors' products may not handle the defaults in the same
way.
Be sure to code CRYPTOPTS in protection setups,
ACL files, or both to enforce the security you want.
<P><LI>Make sure the options you choose for this header are consistent with
the options you choose for SHTTP-Privacy-Domains.
For example,
do not specify orig-refused=sign or recv-refused=sign for this header
if you specify orig-required=PEM or recv-required=PEM for
SHTTP-Privacy-Domains.
Messages using PEM as the encrypted format are always signed.
<P><LI>What you specify for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements in an anchor must
be consistent with what you specify for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements in
protection setups and ACL files.
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_681">SHTTP-Certificate-Types</A></H4>
<P>
Use this header to specify certificate formats.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_682">Header options</A></H5>
<P>
There is currently only one <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>:
<DL>
<P><DT>X.509
<DD>ISO standard format.
</DL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_683">Default CRYPTOPTS</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Certificate-Types: orig-optional=X.509;recv-optional=X.509"
</PRE>
<P>
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>The server can send the client certificate type X.509.
<LI>The server can accept from the client certificate type X.509.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_684">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<P>
Accept the header defaults.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_685">SHTTP-Key-Exchange-Algorithms</A></H4>
<P>
Use this algorithm to exchange keys.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_686">Header options</A></H5>
<P>
There is currently only one <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>:
<DL>
<P><DT>RSA
<DD>Exchange key algorithm from RSA Data Security, Inc.
</DL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_687">Default CRYPTOPTS</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Key-Exchange-Algorithms: orig-optional=RSA;recv-optional=RSA"
</PRE>
<P>
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>The server can use the RSA algorithm to exchange keys.
<LI>The server can accept the RSA algorithm to exchange keys
from a client.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_688">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<P>
Accept the header defaults.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_689">SHTTP-Signature-Algorithms</A></H4>
<P>
Use this algorithm to digitally sign a message.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_690">Header options</A></H5>
<P>
There is currently only one <VAR>HeaderOption</VAR>:
<DL>
<P><DT>RSA
<DD>Digital signature algorithm from RSA Data Security, Inc.
</DL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_691">Default CRYPTOPTS</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Signature-Algorithms: orig-optional=RSA;recv-optional=RSA"
</PRE>
<P>
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>The server can use the RSA algorithm to sign messages.
<LI>The server can accept messages from a client that are signed
with the RSA algorithm.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_692">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<P>
Accept the header defaults.
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_693">SHTTP-Message-Digest-Algorithms</A></H4>
<P>
Use this header to specify the algorithm that will be used to
compute a message digest.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_694">Header options</A></H5>
<P>
You can specify one of the following <VAR>HeaderOptions</VAR>:
<DL>
<P><DT>MD2
<DD>An algorithm for computing a message digest.
<P><DT>MD5
<DD>An algorithm for computing a message digest.
</DL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_695">Default CRYPTOPTS</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Message-Digest-Algorithms: orig-optional=MD2,MD5;
  recv-optional=MD2,MD5"
</PRE>
<P><P><B>Note: </B>Each CRYPTOPTS header should be coded on one line.
The default is shown on more than one line because of formatting.
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client that the server can use the MD2 or MD5
algorithm to compute a message digest.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_696">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<UL>
<P><LI>Accept the header defaults.
<P><LI>The server uses one of these algorithms to compute
a message digest if you
specified that the client is required to sign
(recv-required=sign for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements).
</UL>
<P>
<H4><A NAME="Header_697">SHTTP-Symmetric-Content-Algorithms</A></H4>
<P>
Use this header to specify the algorithm that will be used to
encrypt the content of a PKCS-7 message.
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_698">Header options</A></H5>
<P>
You can specify one of the following <VAR>HeaderOptions</VAR>:
<DL>
<P><DT>DES-CBC
<DD>An algorithm for encrypting the content of a message.
<P><DT>RC2-CBC
<DD>An algorithm for encrypting the content of a message.
</DL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_699">Default CRYPTOPTS</A></H5>
<P>
<PRE>
CRYPTOPTS="SHTTP-Symmetric-Content-Algorithms: orig-optional=DES-CBC,RC2-CBC;
  recv-optional=DES-CBC,RC2-CBC"
</PRE>
<P><P><B>Note: </B>Each CRYPTOPTS header should be coded on one line.
The default is shown on more than one line because of formatting.
This CRYPTOPTS tells a client:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>The server can use the DES-CBC or RC2-CBC
algorithm to encrypt the content of a message.
<LI>The server can accept from a client a message encrypted
using the DES-CBC or RC2-CBC algorithm.
</UL>
<P>
<H5><A NAME="Header_700">Important coding considerations</A></H5>
<P>
Before accepting the defaults for this header, consider the following:
<UL>
<P><LI>One of these algorithms is used to encrypt a message if PKCS-7
format is used for SHTTP-Privacy-Domains.
If you want clients outside the United States to encrypt messages to
you, U.S. export rules require that they use PKCS-7 format
for SHTTP-Privacy-Domains and the RC2-CBC algorithm for
SHTTP-Symmetric-Content-Algorithms.
<P><LI>You can also specify a key size for RC2-CBC:
<PRE>
RC2-CBC&#91;<VAR>key size</VAR>&#93;
</PRE>
<P>
<VAR>key size</VAR> can be:
<UL COMPACT>
<LI>A range.  The maximum range is 128-2 for U.S and 40-2 for export.
For example:
<PRE>
RC2-CBC&#91;40-2&#93;
</PRE>
<LI>A single number.  The single number can be from 2 through
128 for U.S.-Canadian and from 2 through 40 for export.
For example:
<PRE>
RC2-CBC&#91;40&#93;
</PRE>
<LI>40, which is the default
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
The greater the key size, the stronger the encryption.
You might want to specify a range to allow negotiation of the
strongest encryption.
However,
if the server is an export version or if some clients are outside
the U.S., you need to
require the RC2-CBC algorithm with a key range of 40-2.
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="Header_701" HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC_701">Step 3. Coding CRYPTOPTS in protection setups and ACL files</A></H2>
<P>
You use
protection setups to protect one or more files in one or more
directories based on URLs.
You use ACL files to limit access to one or more
files in a directory.
<P>
You can code CRYPTOPTS for protection setups and, optionally, for
ACL files.
These CRYPTOPTS are very important.
Remember:
<UL>
<P><LI>The server does not know what CRYPTOPTS were specified
in the anchor coding.
The server only knows what CRYPTOPTS the client is using and
what CRYPTOPTS the client is capable of using based on what the
client sends in its request for the document.
<P><LI>All vendors'
clients may not handle the CRYPTOPTS in an anchor the same way.
</UL>
Therefore, the only way you can ensure the server enforces the security
you want is to code CRYPTOPTS in protection setups and,
optionally, in ACL files.
<P>
Instructions on how to code protection setups and ACL files begin
at 
<A HREF="icswg008.html#HDRACTPROT">"Step 1. Activating protection"</A>.
<P>
You need to make sure the CRYPTOPTS you code for protection setups
and ACL files are consistent with the CRYPTOPTS you code for
the document referenced in an anchor.
If they are not, the server won't serve the document
even if the client has complied with the CRYPTOPTS
specified in the anchor.
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="Header_702" HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC_702">Step 4. Coding CGI Programs with S-HTTP (Optional)</A></H2>
<P>
You can write CGI programs with S-HTTP security.
<HR>
<H2><A NAME="Header_703" HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC_703">Step 5. Using S-HTTP</A></H2>
<P>
You're ready to use S-HTTP.
Before implementing it widely, you should test the S-HTTP
coding in your document to make sure you're getting the
security you want and need.
<P>
To test security, go to a browser and type the URL for
the HTML document with S-HTTP coding.
Click the anchors that have S-HTTP coding.
When the server serves the document,
check what security is being used.
For Secure WebExplorer, this information
is in the server certificate dialogue.
Select <B>Security</B>
from the menu bar, then click <B>Client
certificate</B> and then <B>Server certificate</B>.
<P>
After you've completed this testing,
look at the server's log files for errors.
<P>
When you're satisfied that you're getting the security you want,
you're ready to use S-HTTP.
<P>
If you want to set up a proxy server, see
<A HREF="icswg003.html#HDRPROXY">"Running your server as a caching proxy"</A> for information on how to set up your server
as a proxy.
<P>
Secure WebExplorer clients can issue a URL using <B>shttp://</B> as
the transport mode.
Since there are no CRYPTOPTS and no DN, an Internet Connection Secure Server will
sign its response.
Other vendors' servers may not support clients issuing a URL
with the <B>shttp://</B> transport mode.
<P><HR><B>&#91; <A HREF="#Top_Of_Page">Top of Page</A> &#124; <A HREF="icswg010.html">Previous Page</A> &#124; <A HREF="icswg012.html">Next Page</A> &#124; <A HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC">Table of Contents</A> &#93;</B>
<A NAME=Bot_Of_Page>&nbsp;</A>
