<H1><A NAME="HDRSHTNEG" HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC_749">Appendix B. S-HTTP negotiation</A></H1>
<P>
<A HREF="icswg011.html#HDRSHTTP">"Using Secure HTTP"</A> describes how to set up and use S-HTTP.
It provides an overview of S-HTTP, including how security
for a transaction is negotiated.
It also describes how to specify the cryptographic options
(CRYPTOPTS) that can be used for a transaction.
This chapter assumes you understand how S-HTTP works, especially
how CRYPTOPTS are specified.
<P>
The chapter summarizes how Internet Connection Secure Server and Secure WebExplorer negotiate.
<P>
S-HTTP is a message-based protocol that allows different CRYPTOPTS
for each transaction.
There are two negotiations for each transaction.
The first negotiation takes place when a user
clicks on an anchor that uses <B>shttp</B>
protocol mode.
If that negotiation is successful, the client sends a request
to the server, and another negotiation takes place between the
client and server.
This negotiation must be successful for the server to serve the
document.
<P>
For each of these negotiations, each CRYPTOPTS is negotiated
individually for both send and receive.
For example, for the SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements header, sign
would be negotiated for send and receive and encrypt would
be negotiated for send and receive.
<P>
If a CRYPTOPTS is not specified, the defaults are used.
<P>
In general, for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements, the default for both
Secure WebExplorer and Internet Connection Secure Server is to encrypt.
However, for the client to encrypt, it must have the server's DN;
for the server to encrypt, it must have the client's certificate.
<P>
If the client does not have the server's DN or if the server does not
have the client's certificate and no CRYPTOPTS are specified, then
the client or server will sign.
<P>
On the other hand, if the client does not have the server's DN or
the server does not have the client's certificate, if some
CRYPTOPTS are specified, and if
the SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements header is not specified, then
the negotiation fails.
Although the default is to encrypt, the client cannot encrypt if it
does not have the server's DN, and the server cannot encrypt if it
does not have the client's certificate.
If the SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements header
is specified, it will override this
default behavior.
<P>
Following is a table that shows how the CRYPTOPTS are negotiated
if the client is Secure WebExplorer or the server is Internet Connection Secure Server.
<P>
For the negotiation that occurs when the user clicks on the anchor, one
side of the matrix represents the client's CRYPTOPTS
and the other
side represents the CRYPTOPTS coded in the anchor.
<P>
For the negotiation that occurs when the client requests the document
from the server, one side of the matrix represents the client's
CRYPTOPTS (the result of the anchor negotiation)
and the other side of the matrix represents the CRYPTOPTS
coded in the server's protection setups, ACL files, or both.
If CRYPTOPTS are coded in both the protection setups and the ACL files,
the CRYPTOPTS in the protection setups are negotiated first and then
the CRYPTOPTS in ACL files.
If either of these negotiations fail, the document will not be served.
<P>
<BR>
<PRE><TT>
+==================+==================+==================+==================+
| &nbsp;                | Required         | Optional         | Refused          |
+==================+==================+==================+==================+
| <B>Required</B>         | YES              | YES              | FAIL             |
+------------------+------------------+------------------+------------------+
| <B>Optional</B>         | YES              | COULD            | NO               |
+------------------+------------------+------------------+------------------+
| <B>Refused</B>          | FAIL             | NO               | NO               |
+------------------+------------------+------------------+------------------+
</TT></PRE><P>
In this table:
<UL>
<P><LI>YES means that the CRYPTOPTS will be used.
<P><LI>NO means that the CRYPTOPTS will not be used.
<P><LI>FAIL means the CRYPTOPTS conflict, and the negotiation
will fail.
The document will not be requested or served.
If the document is not served, the server will send an error
message to the client.
<P><LI>COULD means that the CRYPTOPTS could be used.
However, as described later, you should require what you want,
refuse what you don't want, and accept optional (the default) only
if it doesn't matter how the CRYPTOPTS header is handled.
</UL>
<P>
After each CRYPTOPTS has been negotiated for both send and receive,
the client or server checks the resulting CRYPTOPTS to ensure they
are consistent and not contradictory.
(For example, if PEM is required for SHTTP-Privacy-Domains and
sign is refused for SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements, then the
CRYPTOPTS are contradictory because messages encrypted with PEM are
always signed.)
If the CRYPTOPTS are contradictory, then the negotiation fails.
If the CRYPTOPTS are not contradictory, then the negotiation succeeds,
and the client will send the request for the document or the server
will serve the document.
<P>
Other vendors' products may not handle negotiation the same way as
Internet Connection Secure Server and Secure WebExplorer.
That is why it is very important that you:
<UL>
<P><LI>Require the CRYPTOPTS that you want and refuse the CRYPTOPTS you
don't want.
Accept optional, or the default, only for a CRYPTOPTS
if it doesn't matter how the CRYPTOPTS is negotiated.
This is particularly important for the SHTTP-Privacy-Enhancements header.
<P><LI>Specify CRYPTOPTS on the server in protection setups, ACL files,
or both.
The server does not know what CRYPTOPTS were coded in an anchor.
The server only knows what CRYPTOPTS the client is using and is
capable of using, based on what the client sends in its request.
Therefore, you should use the CRYPTOPTS in protection setups and
ACL files to ensure that the server serves documents with the security
you want.
</UL>
<P><HR><B>&#91; <A HREF="#Top_Of_Page">Top of Page</A> &#124; <A HREF="icswg014.html">Previous Page</A> &#124; <A HREF="icswg016.html">Next Page</A> &#124; <A HREF="icswgmst.html#ToC">Table of Contents</A> &#93;</B>
<A NAME=Bot_Of_Page>&nbsp;</A>
</BODY></HTML>

</DOC>
